<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8923 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-GE-SUCCESSION-HNS &LR;      09-20 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GE-SUCCESSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLED POWER SYSTEMS DIVISION AT GE IS NOW A SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ Five years ago, Robert Nardelli took over
GE's troubled Power Systems Division in this upstate city.
</P>
<P>
   Power Systems had a profit of $700 million on sales of $6.4
billion. But the outlook for the division was anything but
optimistic. The market for turbines and generators was stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Schenectady's economy is still hurting, but Nardelli's division
is a success story in a company that has been remarkable in its own
right for growth and profitability.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the division is expected to post profits of $1.7
billion on sales of $9.7 billion. Nardelli is talked about as a
possible successor to GE Chairman Jack Welch, one of the most
admired businessmen in the world. Welch is scheduled to retire at
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nardelli turned the Power Systems business practically on its
head. ``You can either be victimized or be very proactive in
shaping the market,'' Nardelli said in a wide-ranging interview at
the division's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Like Welch, his mentor, Nardelli is excited about business. He
gets animated when he recites numbers and talks about the
power-generating industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers speak for the whole strategy,'' Nardelli said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he's on the short list to succeed Welch. Nardelli,
51, is said to be in the running alongside Jeffrey R. Immelt,
43-year-old head of GE's medical systems business, and W. James
Mcnerney Jr., 50, head of the aircraft-engine business. Nardelli is
considered a dark horse candidate largely because of his age. Welch
is said to favor someone closer to his age when he took over 18
years ago at 45.
</P>
<P>
   Nardelli, who lives in a $1.4 million home in Colonie, won't say
much about the succession issue, but few who know him doubt his
competitive nature and ambition.
</P>
<P>
   When Nardelli came to Power Systems, its business was almost
exclusively turbines and generators for the utility industry. Now,
Power Systems has lots more pieces of equipment it can sell. As a
result, it has developed a lucrative global service business to
operate the equipment for its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shape the market, instead of the market shaping us,''
Nardelli said. Stock analysts who follow GE practically rave about
the unit's performance now that it's a $9.7 billion business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doing astro-phenomenonally well,'' said Nicholas Heymann
an analyst at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Nardelli is ``extremely successful,'' said Kent Newcomb, analyst
at A.G. Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Nardelli's strategy was to cut hundreds of jobs over his
years here. He had a reputation for toughness at his previous job
as president and chief executive officer of GE Transportation
Systems in Erie, Pa., which makes locomotives. He revived that
business in part by cutting jobs and outsourcing work.
</P>
<P>
   Nardelli faced a dismal U.S. market for utilities when he came
here. Utilities in the United States weren't buying much new
equipment, Nardelli recalled. Energy deregulation was still on the
horizon, and the utilities were stalling their buying decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The utility executives didn't really know how much or what kinds
of equipment they'd need, and they didn't want to make the wrong
purchasing decisions and be stuck with costs later.
</P>
<P>
   Nardelli didn't know the energy business then, but in his 10th
posting in a GE job he'd learned the drill. Go in and assess the
situation and see what needs to be changed. Communicate those
changes and take action.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, we were pretty focused on gear,'' Nardelli said. The
company sold gas turbines for customers who use natural gas as an
energy source, and steam turbines for customers who rely on coal,
oil or nuclear power. That was it _ a turbine to match your fuel
source to help turn your fuel into energy.
</P>
<P>
   Not much thought was given, he said, to finding out what else
the customer might want in additional products, services or
consulting. It was: ``Yep, here's your order.'' And that posture
made the company too vulnerable to economic ups and downs, he said,
both in business sectors and in geographic markets.
</P>
<P>
   So he added other products to GE's toolbox _ often by buying
other companies, entering into joint ventures or distributions
agreement. The company made more than 30 acquisitions and embarked
on a course that created a global empire. It bought one company in
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   GE Power Systems headquarters is still in Schenectady, but its
business interests are served from many countries.
</P>
<P>
   So even as Power Systems has grown, Schenectady hasn't regained
many of the jobs lost in firings earlier in the decade. Power
Systems' local employment was as high as 7,700 in early 1995. After
3,400 jobs were eliminated, some 4,300 people now work for Power
Systems locally, among the overall GE work force of 9,000 in this
region.
</P>
<P>
   But customers and shareholders seem to be gaining.
</P>
<P>
   Now GE can sell turbines up and down a range of sizes to meet
the needs of the biggest industrial customers to smaller business
sites. Cities grappling with temporary power shortages or rock
concert promoters planning huge events can rent portable energy
sources for short-term use. Soon, homeowners will be able to get
dishwasher-size fuel cells made by local Plug Power to create all
the electricity a home needs.
</P>
<P>
   And Power Systems is now locking customers into long-term
service contracts, generating an additional profit stream.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment sales tend to create service sales, and then service
sales generate more equipment sales _ and so the cycle goes on,
Nardelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Heymann said, service is higher profit. Building
hardware is not where the big profits are in the market, he said.
Across the corporation, in fact, GE is pumping service sectors for
new sources of income, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Power Systems was in the midst of this transformation, the
U.S. energy market bounced back in the last couple of years. Energy
deregulation became a reality, and utility companies became clearer
on what they needed to buy. And they got more eager to buy too, by
1998, as hot weather and brownouts created more demand for power.
</P>
<P>
   Now things are smoking, Heymann said. Power Systems has plenty
of orders to carry it into 2002, he said, and is far ahead of
competitors Westinghouse, Mitsubishi, Siemens and Alstom.
</P>
<P>
   Power Systems, he said, also is doing well implementing GE's
productivity improvement program, called Six Sigma. That's an
initiative that spans the corporation, and is intended to help
employees cut waste and steer customer requests into GE products
and services.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not all of Nardelli's decisions were popular as they came
along, especially among residents of the region. Some work was
outsourced, for example, to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Nardelli defends that decision by saying that GE risked losing
some customer business if it didn't outsource, and instead, waited
to gear up U.S. supplies and facilities.
</P>
<P>
   GE officials said the same logic works looking at a recent
string of global acquisitions in the gas-turbine business. The gas
turbine business is up, as more global customers select cleaner,
more efficient natural gas over other fuels. Gas turbines are made
in North Carolina and Europe, not in Schenectady, which focuses on
steam turbines.
</P>
<P>
   Still, an upsurge in gas turbine orders can indirectly prompt
orders for generators made in Schenectady, GE pointed out, as well
as boosting the health of the overall business.
</P>
<P>
   Service operations, though, were headquartered in Atlanta, not
Schenectady. That decision meant the relocation of 350 jobs from
Schenectady to Atlanta. The new service business needed a brand-new
environment, Nardelli said, and Atlanta offered more convenient
flight routes to international markets. The decision, Nardelli
said, ``wasn't so much for my people as for our customers. You've
got to make sure the customer doesn't find it so difficult to visit
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
