<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8943 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-PULP-MILLS-HNS &LR;      09-20 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULP-MILLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULP AND PAPER INDUSTRY, ONCE BOOMING, IS NOW IN PERIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TICONDEROGA, N.Y. _ The public schools in Ticonderoga are only
five miles from the massive International Paper mill that churns
out copier paper and supports the local economy, but teachers and
administrators last year used paper made in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper executives weren't surprised when they found
out. ``It could just as easily have been Indonesia,'' noted Donna
Wadsworth, spokeswoman for the IP mill in Ticonderoga.
</P>
<P>
   Once a booming industry that helped define New York's North
Country, the pulp and paper industry is in peril. Even as the
region begins to enjoy what some label an economic recovery, the
outlook for workers making paper and pulp is bleak.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 positions have been cut or are being eliminated at the
International Paper plants in Ticonderoga and Corinth, reducing the
combined work force to around 1,170. And 300 workers in St.
Lawrence County will soon lose their jobs making glossy, coated
paper unless a new owner is found for the mill in Newton Falls.
</P>
<P>
   But all the blame can't be placed on Indonesia, Brazil and the
global economy because managers and executives have missed
opportunities that could have put the industry on a different
course.
</P>
<P>
   Blame a manufacturing mindset more geared to production than
profitability, some say, or a slowness among some companies to
shift into new product lines. Analysts also say that instead of
attempting to specialize in niche markets, domestic paper companies
tried to compete with developing countries on volume.
</P>
<P>
   The industry isn't dead yet, but to save it, major resuscitation
efforts must start now, these analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The paper industry has been in decline for most of this decade:
Paper jobs numbered more than 40,000 in New York in 1990. Now,
thousands more of the 32,000 or so paper-related jobs remaining in
New York _ comprising about 3.5 percent of the state's
manufacturing work force _ are threatened.
</P>
<P>
   New York's economy _ even part of its ecosystem _ relies far
more heavily on the health of the paper industry than industry
employment numbers alone reveal, paper's promoters said.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the situation, start with the jobs themselves.
Working in a pulp or paper mill isn't glamorous. It's hot and humid
and noisy near the assembly lines of machines that squeeze vast
amounts of water from pulp to produce giant rolls of dry paper.
</P>
<P>
   But the people who run the paper machines, work in the business
offices, package the finished goods and drive the forklifts in the
warehouses are earning solid middle-class incomes at union jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Many mill workers earn $50,000 to $60,000 a year with a high
school education, said Kevin King, executive vice president of the
Empire State Forest Products Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best money in the area,'' agreed Jim Jenkins, who
works at IP's Hudson River Mill in Corinth. His wife, Angela, also
works at the mill, which has concentrated on making coated, glossy
papers.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, only professionals and employees of Niagara Mohawk
Power Corp. can match the $14- to $19-an-hour earnings the mill
provides them, said Jenkins, a father of two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared, not just for our mill but for our children,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the loss of paper-mill jobs in places like Corinth or
Ticonderoga can be even more devastating than the seepage of
manufacturing jobs from cities such as Schenectady and Troy.
</P>
<P>
   The July unemployment rate in Essex County was 5.7 percent,
compared with 3.3 percent and 3.8 percent, respectively, in
Schenectady and Rensselaer counties. Smaller industrial cities in
the area at least have more than one source of manufacturing
employment, even if the overall number of industry jobs is
declining.
</P>
<P>
   Paper mills are a different creature _ often the only source of
manufacturing jobs in the remote river towns they inhabit. In the
early days of the industry, a century or more ago, King said, it
made sense for the paper companies to put mills in spots that were
isolated: up in the woods and along the rivers and lakes that could
provide the enormous amounts of water needed in the pulp mixing.
</P>
<P>
   The paper industry has come a long way in operating
environmentally cleaner mills, helping to erase a dated image of
mill towns as grubby places, said Ticonderoga town Supervisor Mike
Connery.
</P>
<P>
   But not many industries fit in the wilderness. Manufacturers of
other goods don't have any economic incentive to put big plants in
places like northern Saratoga, Essex, or Warren County, King noted.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that new warehouse jobs are moving into Saratoga
County, from Ace Hardware and Target Department stores, Jenkins
noted, but they pay more like $7 to $10 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Paper mill jobs, once lost, probably can't be replaced, at least
in this generation, experts say, making the spread of rural poverty
a real threat in upstate communities where paper has been king.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs outside the mills are affected, too. International Paper
estimates that each mill job creates enough economic activity to
support five other jobs in the community.
</P>
<P>
   More financial pressure on paper and forest products companies
could also prompt them to sell off large tracts of forest land,
rather than holding the property for selective cutting and having
to pay property taxes and other carrying costs, noted Hugh Canham,
an expert in forest economics at the State University of New York's
College of Environmental Science and Forestry at Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should be a regional concern,'' said Canham.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
