NYT-09-20-99 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8948 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCKINNON-COX     09-20 1789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCKINNON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mark McKinnon contemplates spending money earned from creating
Bush's TV ads
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In his basement offices, Mark McKinnon is
wrapping up work on the answer to the most perplexing question of
the presidential campaign: How can George W. Bush possibly spend
the giant buckets o' cash he is collecting for his White House bid?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, as it is to too many questions about
turn-of-the-century America, is television.
</P>
<P>
   And McKinnon _ former lead singer for Lazlo Frink and the Odd
Sofa Review featuring the Lazlettes, former short-term jailbird,
former media guru for big-name Democrats _ is the man making the TV
ads that will mold Bush's national persona as well as consume much
of his political cash. So far, that is $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   For McKinnon, 44, spending the Bush money is the latest stop in
a magical mystery tour that has taken him from music to politics to
swearing off politics to media man for the front-running
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my political flame was completely burned out, but he
reignited the pilot,'' McKinnon said of Bush. ``I genuinely believe
in him, and that was a hard thing for me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the just-north-of-downtown basement offices of his Maverick
Media, which exists for the sole purpose of making TV ads for the
Bush campaign, McKinnon has a firm grip on the ups and downs of his
job.
</P>
<P>
   Up: He's working for a front-running candidate with gobs of
money and a winning way.
</P>
<P>
   Down: Up frequently foreshadows down. ``One thing I'm worried
about is we've got nowhere to go but down, and the TV is going to
go up and we could go down, and everybody is going to say it's
because of the TV,'' McKinnon said. ``There is no way we are going
to put TV up and the numbers are going to go up. They can't go any
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of following Bush around with a 30-year-old Bell
and Howell film camera, McKinnon has almost all the shots he needs
(though the campaign recently staged a phony speech in downtown
Austin for a more controlled atmosphere). Most of the ads _
including responses to anticipated attacks _ are in the can. A
schedule, carrying through the primary season, has been set, though
McKinnon would not reveal it.
</P>
<P>
   It's all kind of amazing to McKinnon, whose financial rewards
from the campaign will begin to flow when the ad buys begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, if you would have told me I'd be making
commercials for a Republican I'd have been in shock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a converted Republican,'' said
McKinnon, who never worked for a GOP candidate before the Bush 1998
gubernatorial campaign. ``I'm a Bush man.''
</P>
<P>
   The long, strange trip
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon has navigated a peculiar path to the Bush camp. Born in
Colorado, he ran away from home just before his senior year in high
school to get to Nashville, Tenn., and Kris Kristofferson, who had
been impressed by a band fronted by McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kristofferson sort of put up with me, and I just hung out with
him and hung out at the studio and wrote songs,'' McKinnon said.
``Then I decided I was going to spend the rest of my life trying to
be Bob Dylan or Kris Kristofferson.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon later returned to Denver and completed high school
before heading back to Nashville to pursue the musical dream,
complete with dishwashing for dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote a bunch of songs. I had songs cut by, like, the Miss
Mississippi 1964 beauty queen. It entered and left the charts at
160,'' he said. ``There was a song that Elvis was going to cut and
then he died the next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Music brought McKinnon to Texas when he won a songwriting
contest at the 1975 Kerrville Folk Festival. A year later, he moved
to Austin and lived off gigs at a variety of now-defunct venues.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, his intellectual clock ticking, McKinnon decided to
check out the local big state university. He enrolled at the
University of Texas and became editor of The Daily Texan.
</P>
<P>
   When prosecutors looked for Iranian students who had disrupted a
campus speech by a Shah ally, they asked McKinnon to turn over
unpublished photos. He refused, and spent a day in jail until the
case moved forward without the photos.
</P>
<P>
   Apropos for McKinnon's long, strange trip, the prosecutor who
had him jailed is now a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see him and wave at him all the time across the street,''
McKinnon said. ``I bet he still doesn't know why he has a flat tire
every morning.''
</P>
<P>
   With a UT education, if not a degree, under his belt, McKinnon
moved on to politics.
</P>
<P>
   The first stop was a house that served as headquarters for
then-Texas state Sen. Lloyd Doggett's 1984 U.S. Senate race.
Inside, McKinnon encountered some folks heading for the big time.
Cajun James Carville was the campaign manager and Paul Begala was a
top hand. Both later hit the big time after signing on with
then-Arkansas governor Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the rascal like a wayward stepchild,'' Begala said of
McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
   Begala believes Bush may be McKinnon's little red sports car.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a friend, I think maybe it's a bit of a mid-life crisis,''
he said of McKinnon's current job.
</P>
<P>
   For McKinnon, the Doggett campaign led to a stint as a press
aide to Democratic Texas Gov. Mark White and a string of Democratic
candidates, including Louisiana Gov. Buddy Roemer and Texas Gov.
Ann Richards.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1987 Roemer win, McKinnon moved to New York to work
with political media mogul David Sawyer's firm. He returned to
Austin in 1990 and became communications director for Richards' bid
for the Democratic gubernatorial nomination. He left after Richards
won the primary, moving on to 17 other clients he had across the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, McKinnon, whose operation was folded in with Public
Strategies, an Austin-based consulting firm, was very good at what
he did and very unhappy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd learned how to manipulate the system, and I used all the
tricks of the trade to help elect my candidates,'' he wrote in
Texas Monthly. ``There's a bottom line to political consulting:
winning. Nothing else matters.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon went corporate, concentrating his talents on Public
Strategies' non-political clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life was good,'' he said of not dealing with candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The seduction of Mark McKinnon
</P>
<P>
   Life was so good that McKinnon was doing things like dining with
his Public Strategies cronies and Bush in the fall of 1997. From
afar, McKinnon was intrigued by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a Republican governor who was for things instead of
against everything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, McKinnon headed to the dinner ``prepared not to
like him.'' He failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disarmed almost instantaneously by his humanity, by his
integrity. I expected to meet a great politician. I just was
unprepared to meet such a great human being,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, McKinnon was approached to do the ads for Bush's
1998 re-election campaign. His coming-out party came at the GOP
state convention in June 1998. McKinnon strolled into the Tarrant
County Convention Center, surveyed the crowd and joked about
needing a flak jacket.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush bio-video he prepared was warmly received. The best
reaction came to a scene, shot during a Bush fishing trip, in which
the governor doffs his cap after catching a big one and then puts
the fish, instead of the cap, on his head.
</P>
<P>
   In that simple image of a governor acting goofy, according to
McKinnon admirers, is evidence of his talent. Begala says McKinnon
makes ads that connect on a personal level.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands politics is an affair of the heart,'' Begala
said of his buddy on the other side. ``If you grab them by the
heart, their head will follow. Voting is a powerful act of
self-definition. It can't be devoid of intellectual content, but it
goes to something more important. It goes to emotion and values.
Mark is comfortable speaking that language. That's why he is so
comfortable with Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   But Begala sees a potential point of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has surprised me with his caution, his timidity. He is
playing not to lose. A classic front-runner,'' Begala said. ``Mark
is a throw-deep kind of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, McKinnon helped concoct ads for U.S. Sen. Bob Krueger's
longshot effort to hold the seat to which he had been appointed by
Richards. Krueger threw deep. The Shakespearean scholar donned dark
sunglasses and a leather jacket and poked fun at his own dull image
by appearing on an ad saying, ``Was it Shakespeare who said, `Hasta
la vista, baby?'''
</P>
<P>
   The ad got a lot of attention. Republican Kay Bailey Hutchison
got the Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, undefeated as a GOP adman, McKinnon is content being in a
place he never expected to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Character and independence are really much more important to
me than ideological purity,'' he said. ``Because those who are most
ideologically pure are most often hostage to those interests.''
</P>
<P>
   He proceeds with the heartfelt wishes of his old friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he fires him,'' Begala said of Bush. ``If there is
anything I can do I'd be happy to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The big gig
</P>
<P>
   The Bush ad campaign for the primary season is mostly in the can
and ready to run. McKinnon said it is long on Bush and short on
production gimmicks. Thanks to who he is and where he's from, Bush
doesn't have to spend much time introducing himself; he can quickly
move to his message, McKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that where he is going is more important than where
he has been, and that's what people want to hear about,'' McKinnon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though there is a schedule in place, changes could be forced by
well-heeled GOP foe Steve Forbes, who Bush officials expect to come
out early with a full-frontal TV assault on the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has reminded voters that Bush's unsuccessful 1995 attempt
to cut property taxes included a long list of proposed tax hikes. A
Bush ad featuring the candidate and defending the failed tax plan
is ready to air on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, McKinnon said, voters will see relatively simple ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people when they make political ads try to add
filters like logos and voice-overs. A lot of layers of things to
distract or influence viewers,'' he said. ``We try to take filters
away, particularly with Governor Bush because he is so good
completely unfiltered, one on one.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon said he's striving for a documentary feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a lot of ribbons and bows,'' he said. ``The only way I can
really screw this up is if I forget to put film in the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
