<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAND-TRANSPLANT PATIENT SHOW SIGNS OF PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ky., N.J.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year after he received a new right hand and forearm in a
transplant operation in France, Clint Hallam of Australia has
gained a sufficient grip to ride a motorcycle and even write with a
pen, his doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   After the experimental transplant was performed on Sept. 23,
1998, many doctors predicted failure, saying a body would reject
the combination of skin and dozens of muscles, tendons, nerves and
blood vessels in the donor arm. They added that even if the foreign
tissue was accepted, Hallam's brain could not power nerves that had
been severed in a prison accident 14 years earlier, and the new arm
would be a useless stump.
</P>
<P>
   But substantial nerve regeneration has occurred, more is
expected in the months ahead, and Hallam, 49, has not experienced a
serious rejection reaction, said Dr. Earl Owen, the hand surgeon in
Sydney, Australia, who headed the international team that performed
the transplant in Lyons, France.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam's new hand has about 25 percent of normal grip strength
and the pinch grip between his index finger and thumb is good, Owen
said in a telephone interview last week, during a visit to Lyons to
review Hallam's progress in the last year. Hallam could not be
reached for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   If he continues to do well, the operation will prove to be the
world's first successful hand transplant.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Dr. Warren C. Breidenbach's team in Louisville, Ky.,
performed the first hand transplant in the United States, on
Matthew David Scott of Absecon, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Scott can bend his fingers and hand to grasp and release
objects, and can open doors, drive a car, and pick up and hold his
children, a spokeswoman for the Louisville team said. And he can
detect hot, cold and other sensations in much of his new left hand.
But the spokeswoman said he had ``reached a plateau in the function
and range of motion at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott has had three rejection episodes that were controlled by
drugs. He is expected to return to Louisville in about three months
for monitoring tests and possible surgery to loosen tendons to gain
more function and mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's experimental surgery in France, for which a team of
doctors was assembled from four countries and the patient flew
halfway around the world, was an effort with few rivals in the
annals of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam underwent extensive psychological testing in Australia
and France. But Owen's team was embarrassed to learn only at the
time of the transplant that Hallam had lost his hand and forearm in
a circular saw accident while in prison in New Zealand, and not in
a logging accident, as he told the doctors earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The postoperative care and rehabilitation have strained
relations between the doctors and Hallam, who travels frequently
and skips appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam now lives in Perth, Australia, and has not followed the
team's recommended schedule of exercise, rehabilitation, and blood
tests and skin biopsies to monitor rejection, Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he does go for physical therapy, Hallam suffered a
setback, his doctors believe, when he skipped supervised therapy
sessions while he traveled in Europe and the United States for
weeks instead of returning directly to Australia for such care.
</P>
<P>
   Communication between Hallam and the doctors is often by fax and
e-mail, and ``it is impossible to tell where the faxes originate
from,'' Owen said. For example, Hallam recently sent e-mail
messages to two members of the transplant team informing them that
he was considering a job with ``a charity organization'' in Las
Vegas, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Owen said he had been unable to reach Hallam to ask him to
``meet for a major follow-up'' when three members of the team from
France and Italy were in Sydney for a scientific meeting in late
August.
</P>
<P>
   In mapping the areas where a patient has feeling, doctors often
insure objectivity by blindfolding and misleading him, saying, for
example, that they are going to apply a light touch when they stick
a pin into a hand. In Hallam's case, the doctors also put a curtain
in front of him because, as Owen has said, ``We do not believe this
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors used such objective measures in Hallam's recent
checkups, the last in Perth on Sept. 14, when a skin biopsy showed
no evidence of rejection and confirmation of an improved range of
hand movements, Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   The new hand has settled into a normal position instead of being
bent with respect to the wrist. Muscles powered by the ulnar nerve,
which is in the hand below the pinky finger, are starting to
function. For example, Hallam could weakly move his little finger
outwardly.
</P>
<P>
   Sensation reached his fingertips at eight months and has
improved since. Standard tests of nerve function show that he can
detect a doctor touching his hand and exerting pressure on it, and
can discriminate hot and cold sensations in all fingers and thumb.
But the degree of sensory feeling in the digits varies.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam has stopped taking steroids and now takes two
anti-rejection drugs. A serious rejection reaction can occur at any
time after any transplant. The immune suppression resulting from
the anti-rejection therapy and mild diabetes leaves Hallam at
increased risk of infection.
</P>
<P>
   Owen's team plans to do four more hand transplants. No suitable
donors became available during Owen's current weeklong visit to
Lyons, but a number of potential donors were available while he was
at home in Australia, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
