<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8980 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BREAST-FEEDING-2T     09-20 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BREAST-FEEDING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONING THE `DEADLINE' FOR WEANING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Ill., Fla., N.C.)   (af)  
 By RANDI HUTTER EPSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Martha, my 3-year-old daughter, is a drinker. She
craves breast milk and she just won't quit. On the other hand, her
twin brother as well as her older brother weaned themselves at 10
months.
</P>
<P>
   I never intended to nurse a toddler. Martha and I have tried
cold turkey. We didn't do well. The plan was to endure the
withdrawals (in other words, let her scream) until she learned to
enjoy a breast-milk-free life. That was suitable for the privacy of
our own home, but it didn't work in restaurants or other public
places.
</P>
<P>
   As my feeble attempts to wean failed, I began to wonder why
weaning mattered so much. I wondered whether there was any medical
evidence to support the popular deadline, six months to a year.
</P>
<P>
   And what I discovered from interviews with specialists and a
review of the medical research on breast-feeding was that though
Martha and I may be an oddity on the Upper West Side of Manhattan,
in the world at large we are the norm. The global average is about
three years.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, data extrapolated from nonhuman primates suggest
that humans might be wise to nurse their young for several years,
said Katherine A. Dettwyler, an associate professor of anthropology
and nutrition at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dettwyler has investigated chimpanzees, gorillas, seals,
moose and other large animals. She related certain milestones, like
gestation period, full-grown size and age at sexual maturity, to
the age of weaning. She concluded that a more natural age for
weaning in humans would be somewhere between 2.5 and 7 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the world, there are lots of cultures where people
nurse three, four or five years on average,'' added Dr. Dettwyler,
co-editor of ``Breast-Feeding: Biocultural Perspectives'' (Aldine
de Gruyter, 1995). ``All cultures have various ideas about how
short is too short and how long is too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dettwyler is now examining the consequences of long-term
nursing in a group of 1,429 American children. One category
includes three children who nursed until they were 9 or 10, and
another includes seven children who nursed until they were 8 or 9.
The study is in its early stages, she said.
</P>
<P>
   I had assumed most pediatricians encouraged women to stop
nursing within a year. Not so. Dr. Lawrence M. Gartner, a professor
emeritus at the University of Chicago and chairman of the American
Academy of Pediatrics' task force on breast-feeding, said, ``There
is no contraindication to extending breast-feeding and no evidence
that it causes psychological harm.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy recommends that women breast-feed for at least one
year or longer; ideally, Gartner said, babies should get breast
milk exclusively for the first six months.
</P>
<P>
   He reassured me that there was nothing wrong with Martha. ``The
impression a number of us have from seeing a large number of
children breast-feed for two or three years is that, if anything,
they are more self-confident and can handle crowds and people
well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the 1950s, Niles Newton, a research psychologist at
Northwestern University, studied a group of children who were
breast-fed at least three years. ``Her hypothesis was that if you
nursed a child more than one year, you would tie that baby to your
apron strings,'' explained Ruth Lawrence, a professor of pediatrics
and obstetrics at the University of Rochester and author of
``Breast-Feeding: A Guide for the Medical Profession'' (C.V. Mosby,
1999).
</P>
<P>
   But Newton found quite the opposite. Nursing toddlers blossomed
into children who were more assertive, advanced physically and
mentally, and more at ease in social situations compared with those
who had weaned earlier.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy to weed out objective findings from wishful
thinking by researchers who are promoting breast-feeding. Still,
Gartner suspects breast-feeding provides some toddlers a sense of a
security with their mothers. ``It's important that children feel
safe and secure,'' he said, ``and they will choose different routes
to feel this way. That is why the recommendations from the academy
are very open-ended.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A baby sucking at the nipple triggers a flurry of chemical
messages from breast to brain. The two main hormones sent from the
brain are prolactin, which helps to make milk, and oxytocin, which
helps to release it.
</P>
<P>
   When prolactin soars, ovarian hormones like estrogen plummet.
That is why women who nurse newborns usually do not menstruate or
become pregnant. They may also feel the other uncomfortable effects
of a lack of estrogen _ vaginal dryness and a decreased sense of
well-being.
</P>
<P>
   But the longer a woman nurses, the less her prolactin spikes and
the more likely her other hormones bounce back to normal. That
means that a mother who is nursing a baby has a very different
hormonal response from one who is nursing a toddler. And that means
that my prolactin still rises a bit as Martha latches on, but it
does not soar the way it used to.
</P>
<P>
   What has intrigued me is whether prolactin causes any other
chemical reactions in my body. The hormone was named in 1922 when
investigators believed its sole role was synthesizing milk. But now
they suspect it is much more versatile.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary evidence suggests that prolactin fortifies the
immune system, helps to regulate water and salt, and may influence
behavior, said Marc E. Freeman of the department of biological
sciences at Florida State University.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman's studies on rats have demonstrated that mother rodents
deprived of prolactin ignore their young, while those satiated with
the hormone build nests, nurse and gather their scampering
offspring. And there are hints, he said, that oxytocin has similar
effects but not quite as intense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a big leap to predict human maternal behavior from
a pride of rats. Some scientists say the animal studies prove that
prolactin and oxytocin induce a sense of relaxation in mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Others studying the same data believe the hormones promote a
hypervigilant state that can make some women irritable.
</P>
<P>
   The potential links to irritability are probably why some
doctors suspect that for some women, nursing increases the risk of
postpartum depression. But there is no scientific evidence to prove
the connection.
</P>
<P>
   As any mother can vouch, it is virtually impossible to know what
part of an emotional response is hormonal. And some women may be
more sensitive to hormonal changes during delivery and
breast-feeding than others, said Dr. Diana Dell, assistant
professor of psychiatry, obstetrics and gynecology at Duke
University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to make blanket statements about the way one
hormone will affect well-being, or whether breast-feeding is
guaranteed to relax or stress a woman.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I know that I relaxed when I nursed my newborns. It
was a peaceful time to stare into the eyes of my tiny babies and
dream about them romping around as young children. But a toddler
latching onto the breast for a few minutes to appease crankiness is
quite different.
</P>
<P>
   There is no bonding. It is more like a quick fix to stop a
tantrum. Maybe for other mothers the experience is different.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing I do know is that my prolactin has subsided enough
to kick my ovaries back into gear. I became pregnant while nursing.
My new maternal state has made me think more seriously about
weaning Martha in time to start nursing a newborn again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
