<HEADER>
A8986 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ANGINA-SURGERY-NY     09-20 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ANGINA-SURGERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNIQUE RELIEVES ANGINA, BUT WHY? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., Pa., N.Y., Calif., Fla.)   (af)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is, quite simply, a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers treated 182 people with angina, the agonizing and
debilitating pain that is often a precursor to a heart attack, with
a laser that drills holes in the walls of their heart muscles. Half
of the patients got better, even though they had not responded to
standard treatments for angina. And a year after the laser surgery,
many who had been in pain even when resting could walk for blocks
without discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   The results, reported in the Sept. 11 issue of The Lancet, the
British medical journal, were surprising _ all the more so because
the researchers admit they have no idea why the surgery seems to
have worked.
</P>
<P>
   Angina occurs when the heart muscle receives less blood than it
needs, and scientists thought the laser treatment might improve
blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original idea was to vaporize a channel through the heart
muscle to the cavity so that blood within the cavity could seep
directly into the muscle, as it does in reptiles, without having to
detour through the arteries,'' said an author of the study, Dr.
James W. Jones, chairman of the department of surgery at the
University of Missouri, who performed 42 of the surgeries reported
in The Lancet.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we measured no increase in blood flow,'' he went on.
``It's a paradox. The surgery relieved the angina, but did not
improve the underlying conditions that cause it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Previous work had claimed benefits for the laser therapy, known
as transmyocardial revascularization and intended for people who
cannot undergo treatments like bypass surgery or angioplasty to
clear their arteries. But many researchers had been skeptical of
those claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many earlier reports were more like testimonials than careful,
comparative studies,'' said Dr. Timothy Gardner, chief of
cardiothoracic surgery at the University of Pennsylvania, who was
not involved in the Lancet study. ``This is the first study using
scientific methods to show clinical benefits.'' Gardner is chairman
of the American Heart Association's council on cardiac, thoracic
and vascular surgery. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, the findings should be viewed with caution.
``This study had only a 12-month follow-up,'' he said. Ischemic
heart disease, the kind that results from reduced blood flow and is
often preceded by angina, is a chronic condition that progresses
slowly. ``We won't know for another 12 months whether the results
are a transient phenomenon or not,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 182 patients in the Lancet study, recruited at 16 medical
centers, had been taking maximum doses of at least two anti-angina
drugs and had high scores on a common measurement of angina pain.
Patients were randomly assigned either to continued medication for
their angina or to laser surgery in addition to the medication. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A small incision to the chest gave the surgeons access to the
surface of the heart. A laser was applied to make 15 to 30 small
holes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A year later, patients who underwent laser surgery could
exercise an average of 65 seconds longer on the treadmill than they
could before the operation; the medication-only group had
deteriorated and could exercise 46 seconds less. The pain of angina
was reduced substantially for about half the laser-treated group,
as against one in seven in the medication-only group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the laser surgery did not improve blood flow, why did the
patients improve? Some researchers speculate that the lasers
destroyed the nerve fibers that transmit the pain. Others think
that the laser created microinjuries to the heart that somehow, in
healing, led to the growth of blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that this type of response is not specific for
lasers,'' said a co-author of the study, Dr. Daniel Burkhoff, an
associate professor of medicine at Columbia University. ``It
probably reflects a general response to any kind of microinjury
that in turn incites this inflammatory and healing response.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers say many different factors may be at work.
``It is naive to believe a single mechanism is responsible for the
reduction in angina,'' said Dr. Peter Whittaker, a researcher at
the Heart Institute at Good Samaritan Hospital in Los Angeles, who
has performed animal studies using ultraviolet lasers rather than
the infrared laser used in the Lancet study. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of laser surgery for intractable angina will
be done through a catheter, a thin plastic tube that can be eased
through an artery in the leg, Burkhoff said. ``Instead of making an
incision through the chest wall, we'll push the tube through and
deliver the energy of the laser through the catheter, with no major
incision or general anesthetic necessary.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, patients treated by the lasers say they are still
doing well, One of Jones' patients, Jack Harren of West Palm Beach,
Fla., who had the treatment two years ago, has returned to his life
as a sea captain and professional diver, although he is considering
giving up the diving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the surgery I got angina just going up the stairs,'' he
said, ``and medication was all they could do for me'' after two
bypasses 10 years apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to take three to four nitroglycerin tables a day,'' he
said. ``Now I take that many a year.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such results are encouraging to researchers, even if they do not
fully understand what is going on. ``It's no trivial matter to
eliminate these severe, debilitating chest pains in patients who
often can't walk across a room,'' Whittaker said. ``Yes, we don't
know the mechanism, but on the other hand, it seems to work. If we
can get such good results when we don't have a clue, just think how
amazing it is going to be when we do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8989 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SPINE-ART-2TAKES-     09-20 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PEOPLE PARALYZED WITH SPINAL CORD INJURIES ARE GAINING
MOBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, N.Y., Calif., Canada)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Left to its own devices, the human spinal cord cannot memorize a
Beethoven sonata, solve a quadratic equation or conjugate a Russian
verb. No spinal cord, detached from its neighboring brain, will
ever win a spelling bee or appear as a featured contestant on
Jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   But neither is the spinal cord _ the length of nerve fibers,
neural machinery and blood vessels that constitutes the southern
extension of the central nervous system _ as much of a dullard as
scientists have long believed. An increasing number of studies
demonstrate that far from being a passive conduit, slavishly
ferrying information to and from the brain, or a repository of
unchanging reflexes, the spinal cord has its own contribution to
make.
</P>
<P>
   Spinal cord neurons, researchers are finding, are capable of
learning in simple ways, and show changes in response to
environmental cues that many investigators interpret as a form of
memory. Intriguingly, these abilities remain even when the spinal
cord is cut off from the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spinal cord,'' said Dr. James Grau, a professor of
psychology at Texas A&AMP;M University who studies spinal cord
learning, ``is a lot smarter than you think.''
</P>
<P>
   The conception of the spinal cord as an active partner in
learning comes from a convergence of work in a variety of
scientific disciplines, including physiology, behavioral
neuroscience, psychology and physical therapy. Knowledge gained
from animal studies of spinal cord learning is already helping some
patients with debilitating spinal cord injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Bernd Pagell, for example, a German schoolteacher paralyzed from
the waist down as a result of a car accident in 1989, has gained
new mobility and now walks with a walker, thanks to a novel therapy
that grew out of work on spinal cord learning in animals.
</P>
<P>
   New understanding of the spinal cord's abilities is also helping
researchers study the biological underpinnings of learning and
memory and offering clues to the understanding and treatment of
chronic pain.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have championed the spinal cord's cause over the past
century have had something of an uphill battle. Philosophers and
theologians of the 18th and 19th century drew a strict distinction
between the lofty brain, considered the seat of the soul, and the
lowly spinal cord, capable only of reflexive behaviors. Learning,
in their view, required consciousness, the exclusive province of
the brain.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, work with patients with spinal cord injuries
indicated that the cord retained some flexibility in functioning
after cortical connections were damaged or severed. And researchers
periodically offered evidence suggesting that in animals the spinal
cord could be conditioned to respond to cues, much as Pavlov's dogs
were led to salivate at the sound of a tone. But such studies were
often criticized or ignored.
</P>
<P>
   That many scientists are now giving the spinal cord more credit
is a result, in part, of sophisticated new technologies for
examining the brain at work, and significant advances in
neuroscientific research. These developments have shown that the
nervous system is much more flexible and responsive to the
environment than anyone thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now clear from a lot of areas that the whole nervous
system changes continually in response to development, to learning,
to trauma,'' said Dr. Jonathan Wolpaw, chief of the laboratory of
nervous system disorders at the Wadsworth Center of the New York
State Department of Health. ``There is plasticity and the capacity
for change throughout the central nervous system, and that includes
the spinal cord.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the same structures and chemical processes that seem to
underlie learning and memory in the brain are present in the lower
nervous system as well, scientists point out. NMDA receptors, for
example, molecules that receive signals from other cells and are
thought to be important in memory formation in the brain, are also
active in the spinal cord. And NMDA receptors trigger the same
neurochemical changes in spinal cord neurons as in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Blocking the action of NMDA receptors in the spinal cord appears
to interfere with simple learning, according to studies by Dr.
Russell Durkovic, a professor of neuroscience and physiology at the
State University of New York in Syracuse and by Grau and a
colleague, Dr. Robin Joynes, now at the University of California at
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In studies by Grau and Joynes, for example, rats whose spinal
cords have been transected in the middle region _ cutting off
communication to the brain and leaving the animals unable to move
their hind legs voluntarily _ learn to keep one leg raised to avoid
a shock, just as normal animals do. But when the injured rats are
given a drug that blocks NMDA receptors, they are no longer able to
learn the response.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, even learning that starts in the brain changes the
structure and function of the spinal cord, researchers are finding.
Wolpaw and his colleagues, for example, have shown that training
monkeys and rats to alter the size of a simple reflex _ a tendon
jerk _ produces lasting changes, both anatomical and physiological,
in the spinal cord itself, and the changes persist when connections
to the brain are severed.
</P>
<P>
   The same appears true in humans, Wolpaw said, and may explain
why training takes so long for athletes and, in particular, ballet
dancers, who execute finely tuned movements with their legs. Such
skills, he said, ``involve changes at many levels in the nervous
system, including the spinal cord, and many of these changes occur
gradually.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hope of understanding more about pain perception,
researchers are studying changes in spinal cord neurons that
transmit pain messages to the brain. By recording electrical
activity from pain neurons in the spinal gray matter, Dr. William
D. Willis, of the University of Texas Medical Branch in Galveston,
and his colleagues have shown that these nerve cells respond
intensely not only to sensory signals from an injury site, but also
to messages from sensory receptors in adjacent uninjured areas.
</P>
<P>
   These hyperactive responses last for some time, Willis said,
suggesting that the spinal cord neurons have been sensitized, a
process that looks a lot like short-term memory. ``These neurons
have learned something, just as much as neurons in other higher-up
systems have,'' Willis said.
</P>
<P>
   In people who suffer from chronic pain after an injury or
illness, he said, the new patterns established in the spinal cord
may for some reason persist long after damaged tissue has healed,
as the neurons continue to send distressed, but now inaccurate,
reports to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is in the treatment of spinal cord injury patients, however,
that the new wave of research is already paying off. An estimated
250,000 Americans live with spinal cord injuries, according to
national support groups. For some, the novel therapy used by Pagell
may offer increased mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Pagell, 52, a high school teacher, said he was driving his car
early one morning in 1989 when he fell asleep ``for one second.''
The ensuing accident left him mostly paralyzed from the waist down,
except for limited movement in his left leg and sensation in both
legs.
</P>
<P>
   He considers himself lucky, because he did not have to give up
his job, as many patients with spinal cord injuries do. ``I like to
work with young people,'' Pagell said.
</P>
<P>
   But he was also fortunate in another way: About six years after
his accident, he became a participant in an experimental program
directed by Dr. Anton Wernig, a professor of physiology at the
University of Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   At Wernig's clinic, near Karlsruhe, Pagell was strapped into a
harness and, with a specially trained physical therapist helping to
position his legs, began to take steps on a motorized treadmill,
gripping the bars on either side with his hands. Before starting
the three-month program, he was confined to a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   But as the weeks passed, he was able to walk increasing
distances on the treadmill, and at the end of the training he had
greater movement and could use a walker, an ability he retains
today, four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Wernig's technique was based on animal studies conducted in the
1980s by two researchers, Dr. V. Reggie Edgerton, a professor of
physiological science at the University of California at Los
Angeles, and Dr. Serge Rossignol at the University of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists had long known that the spinal cord contains groups
of neurons that, when chemically activated, generate rhythmic
flexing and extension of the legs in an alternating pattern. But no
one thought that adult animals with longstanding spinal cord
injuries could be taught to activate these pattern generators.
</P>
<P>
   The learning of locomotor skills, it was believed, could not
occur without the participation of the cerebellum, the area of the
brain involved in coordinating motor movements.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA and Montreal researchers proved otherwise. Designing a
special training program in which experimenters provided animals
with partial body support, they trained cats whose spinal cords had
been severed in the middle region to step on a treadmill. After
three to six months of daily sessions, the researchers found, the
animals were able to walk, correctly positioning their hind legs
and readily adjusting to the speed of the machine.
</P>
<P>
   What was occurring, the researchers theorized, was a type of
activity-dependent learning: practicing a specific series of
movements provided sensory information that somehow re-educated the
spinal cord. But most experts were skeptical about whether such
recovery was possible in humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just been this strong underlying viewpoint that the
human nervous system is unique and special, and that the brain was
essential for everything,'' Edgerton said.
</P>
<P>
   Wernig's success in Germany, however, is changing many people's
minds. In one of his studies, for example, 44 German patients with
chronic spinal cord injuries were trained on the treadmill for 10
to 12 weeks. At the beginning of the study, only 6 could walk with
a rollator or walker; the rest were confined to wheelchairs. But at
the end of the training program, 38 patients could walk unassisted,
using a walker or canes.
</P>
<P>
   Wernig's work is stirring great interest in the United States,
not only for the potential it has to increase mobility for some
patients but also because scientists hope the training might
eventually be combined with transplants of spinal tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Research on spinal cord regeneration is still in its infancy,
but experts say one obstacle is that when nerve tissue is
transplanted, neural connections are unlikely to reattach in the
right places. If the spinal cord could be retrained, however, using
the locomotor therapy, it might improve the chances for success of
such surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Locomotor training of the type developed by Wernig is not yet
widely available in this country, although clinical trials are
about to begin in five American cities. And researchers caution
that the therapy is not suitable for every patient with a spinal
cord injury, that not everyone is helped by it and that the
benefits vary widely from person to person.
</P>
<P>
   They stress that it also involves far more than just getting on
a treadmill. ``It's not enough to have a treadmill and a harness
and suspension, and you hang the patient there and tell him `Now
go!,''' Wernig said. ``You have to apply certain rules.''
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible for the studies, participants must have
``incomplete'' injuries, in which connections with the brain have
not been completely destroyed. Experts believe that such patients
are more likely to benefit from the training.
</P>
<P>
   But in an effort to find out more about learning in human spinal
cords, Dr. Susan Harkema at UCLA is also using the therapy with
``complete'' injury patients like Tony Scott, who was walking his
dog in downtown Los Angeles one Friday afternoon last April when a
palm tree fell on him, virtually severing his spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old patient, who began the training last month,
reports to the clinic three times a week. He undergoes a vigorous
stretching routine, then is hoisted onto the treadmill, where he
works for about an hour and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who jogged regularly and played basketball before his
injury, may or may not be helped by the locomotor therapy. But he
said: ``To see myself up and breaking a sweat is very good
psychologically. To be confined to this wheelchair is eating me
alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
