<HEADLINE>
`GOT MILK' AD MAY HAVE HALTED DECLINE IN CONSUMPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After using the ``Got Milk?'' slogan for six
years, the milk industry says 9 of every 10 consumers recognize the
advertising message.
</P>
<P>
   That finding comes from a new study by the Berkeley-based
California Milk Processor Board, a group of business people who
receive milk from dairy producers, put it in cartons and bottles
and send it to retailers.
</P>
<P>
   The question has been posed in 31 television commercials and on
countless outdoor advertising posters. ``It probably is the most
recognized ad line right now,'' said Jeff Goodby, co-chairman and
creative director of Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners, which produced
the ads.
</P>
<P>
   But here are the statistics that mean even more in advertising:
Per capita milk consumption in California was 29 gallons in 1980,
and by 1993 it had fallen to 23 gallons. After that year, when the
ad campaign began, the decline was halted and sales have remained
fairly steady, ranging between 21 and 23 gallons per person each
year, said Jeff Manning, executive director of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Manning calculates that had the consumption decline continued at
its rate in the 1980s and early 1990s, sales would have fallen by
85 million gallons annually in California. At $3 a gallon, that's a
$255 million yearly loss that, Manning argues, is prevented by
spending $23 million on the Goodby, Silverstein advertising budget.
</P>
<P>
   Manning says the slogan is ``short, and it's memorable. ... More
important, it's a question. Think how different this would look if
everything said, `Get Milk!' It's a non-combative, open-ended
question that does not attack anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``What right does an advertiser have to tell you want to do?''
asked Manning. He has taken the campaign nationwide via licensing
deals with the dairy industry and has struck deals to place the
``Got Milk?'' trademark on more than 40 products, from kitchenware
and clothing to Barbie dolls and Hot Wheels.
</P>
<P>
   He has also signed marketing deals with partners including
Nestle, Nabisco, Pillsbury, General Mills, Kellogg, Quaker Oats,
Keebler and Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Another licensing agreement, with the national Milk Processor
Education Program, joins the ``Got Milk?'' tag line with another ad
campaign by Bozell Worldwide Inc., creators of the ``milk
mustache'' print ads.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, ``Got Milk?'' is on virtually every piece of paper
connected to the dairy industry, and it's part of American culture,
said Manning.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the milk board and the Girl Scouts of
the San Francisco Bay area is a good example of ``Got Milk?''
synergy: Images of Bay Area Junior Girl Scouts and Girl Scout
cookies have been used in cross-promotional billboard and bus stop
shelter advertising since 1997 and appear during the cookie-selling
period in March.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion is duplicated nationwide in similar partnerships
between Girl Scout councils and dairy associations _ but always
features the Bay area scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Importantly, said Manning, the Girl Scouts _ wearing ``Got
Milk?'' buttons _ sell more cookies in March than Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the ``Got Milk?'' spots turn on people who suffer the
agony of milk deprivation, often when eating foods that are married
to milk, such as Oreo cookies, Trix cereal or chocolate cake.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in ``Aaron Burr,'' the host of a radio contest
randomly calls an Alexander Hamilton specialist and asks him, ``Who
shot Alexander Hamilton in that famous duel?'' Unfortunately, the
Hamilton scholar _ he even has the bullet from the duel among his
Hamiltonian paraphernalia _ has stuffed his mouth with a peanut
butter sandwich and is fresh out of milk. His correct response is
unintelligible. There goes the $10,000 prize.
</P>
<P>
   If the message of the campaign is grounded in a simple human
truth _ that a cupcake without milk is no way to live _ this is by
any measure a sophisticated collection of 31 individual 60- or
30-second television mini-dramas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate advertising that talks down to people or over-sells,''
said Goodby. ``I think `Got Milk?' treats you like an equal. It
assumes you are intelligent. It assumes that you have a sense of
humor that is pretty well-developed. Ninety-nine percent of
advertising is pretty insulting, I think, and hopefully we keep
that thing to a minimum here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got Milk?'' has won 130 awards including the Clio and Cannes
International Advertising Festival awards. The slogan has helped
propel Goodby, Silverstein, which in 1993 was a relatively small
San Francisco ad agency, into prominence.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it had fewer than 100 employees and under $100 million in
billings. Today it bills $500 million and has 280 employees
stretching the seams of its own six-story building here on
California Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
