<TEXT>
<P>
   LEVEL THE PAYING FIELD FOR ATHLETES
</P>
<P>
   WHEN LAWS AREN'T FAIR
</P>
<P>
   WHY WEN HO LEE MATTERS
</P>
<P>
   MULTIMEDIA PROJECT SPOTLIGHTS U.S. LATINOS
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAM JEFFERSON: PUSHING AGAINST THE ODDS IN LOUISIANA
</P>
<P>
   These articles, described below, are available this week to
clients of NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE, available exclusively from The
New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   NEW AMERICA NEW SERVICE is a special wire service dedicated to
stories that reflect our nation's varied social and ethnic makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Having attended UNITY '99, we understand the needs of editors
across the nation who are on the hunt for topnotch multicultural
material for their publications.
</P>
<P>
   --- New America News Service is the answer.---
</P>
<P>
   For more information about NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE _ or to see
the articles in their entirety _ please contact sales
representative Ana Pena by phone, (212) 499-3333, or fax, (212)
499-3382.
</P>
<P>
   Receive the service for 30 days FOR FREE -- NO STRINGS ATTACHED!
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown:
</P>
<P>
   WHY WEN HO LEE MATTERS. Wen Ho Lee, a physicist, was fired last
March from the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico after
20 years on the job. Wen Ho Lee isn't a celebrity, writes columnist
Amy Wu. So why should we care? Why does Lee's saga dominate the
headlines of international newspapers? And why did his story play a
role in the cooling of Sino-U.S. relations in May? Because the
Chinese-American scientist was fired for possibly leaking
information to the Chinese government. At the heart of the
controversy is whether or not FBI agents focused on Lee because of
his ethnicity. Wu, a new contributor to New America News Service,
explains how the controversy has affected her personally, and how
it affects most Asian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   LEVEL THE PAYING FIELD FOR ATHLETES. Columnist Bill Maxwell
believes that those who run big-time college football need to come
clean about the corruption in the institution and the abuse of
young men who play. ``Fine-tuned, chiseled, testosterone-soaked and
egocentric, these young men are not STUDENT-athletes,'' he writes.
``They are ATHLETE-students.'' The corruption in the game was
brought to the public's attention in July when it was reported that
William ``Tank'' Black, an NFL Players Association agent, had been
caught giving cash and cars to football standouts at various
universities _ a standard operating procedure among many agents.
Maxwell's solution: ``The National Collegiate Athletic Association
needs to establish a uniform system to pay ATHLETE-students what
they deserve. If nothing is done, the system will continue to
corrupt players and their universities.''
</P>
<P>
   MULTIMEDIA PROJECT SPOTLIGHTS U.S. LATINOS. The brainchild of
actor Edward James Olmos, ``Americanos: Latino Life in the United
States'' began as a book project and quickly expanded to include a
traveling photo exhibition, an HBO documentary and even a CD of
related music. Under the direction of Olmos and Lea Ybarra,
executive director of the Institute for Academic Advancement of
Youth at Baltimore's Johns Hopkins University, 31 photographers _
mostly Latinos _ spread out across the country last year to capture
the essence of what it means to be Hispanic in this country. Writer
Ana Radelat reports on this historic project in this feature
article from Hispanic magazine.
</P>
<P>
   PUSHING AGAINST THE ODDS IN LOUISIANA. Rep. William Jefferson
(D-La.) hopes to become the first black governor in Louisiana's
history. He grew up in Louisiana's East Carroll Parish, one of the
poorest places in America. At age 7, he started picking cotton for
$3 a day. Despite his parents' humble earnings, all 10 Jefferson
children attended college. Bill Jefferson went to Southern
University and then Harvard Law School, and later established what
became the largest black law firm in the South. He was elected to
three terms in the Louisiana State Senate, and is now in his fifth
term as a congressman representing New Orleans. On Oct. 23, he will
be on the ballot as an underdog gubernatorial candidate, hoping to
unseat GOP incumbent Gov. Mike Foster. ``If I were to (become
governor), I think the message would be there's a chance for
opportunity everywhere,'' Jefferson says. A profile from Hispanic
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN LAWS AREN'T FAIR. This week, columnist Juan Gonzalez tells
the story of Jose Garcia, a 68-year-old Cuban immigrant who
succumbed to a heart attack on Aug. 22 in the state prison in Green
Haven, N.Y. Garcia had worked for most of his life as a waiter, was
married to the same woman for 41 years and put his son and daughter
through Catholic schools. But a decade ago, Jose Garcia made a
foolish mistake: He agreed to become a lookout for a drug gang on
his block _ a gang busted by the cops in 1989. Although already
very sick with a heart condition. Garcia refused to accept a plea
in exchange for a four-year sentence. Gang leaders had sent word
that if he sang they would go after his family. He received 15
years to life under the harsh mandatory-sentencing requirements of
the Rockefeller drug laws in New York State. Garcia's story, as
told by Gonzalez, leads readers to ponder the severity of such laws
_ and whether exceptions should sometimes be made.
</P>
