<HEADLINE>
MEN'S FASHIONS `MORE SARTORIAL' THIS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The line between men's and women's apparel is so fuzzy this fall
it almost demands corrective lenses.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion trend followers of both sexes will be wearing clothes a
little closer to the body, courtesy of stretchy fabrics, bias cuts
and geometric silhouettes _ rectangular and triangular to boxy.
</P>
<P>
   Fur, leather and fuzzy fabrics bridge the gender gap along with
blunt-toed shoes, turtlenecks and flat-front pants.
</P>
<P>
   When Donna Karan introduced her DKNY line for fall, models were
dressed for icy weather in off-white pants, hooded jackets and
coats. It wasn't until midshow that some in the audience figured
out both men and women were walking the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Among all these gender-neutral styles, however, there are some
things that distinguish fall '99 menswear.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jensen, director of men's apparel for Mario's in downtown
Seattle, says there's a ``more sartorial'' look to menswear this
year _ a look he translates as ``Italian does English.''
</P>
<P>
   Jensen says Neapolitan clothing is currently hot _ a
British-gentleman kind of style borrowed from the English.
Traditional British fabrics are part of the picture: faint
windowpane patterns, pinstripes, muted Prince-of-Wales plaids.
</P>
<P>
   For years, menswear has been influenced by Italian designer
Giorgio Armani _ a look distinguished by longer jackets, lowered
armholes and big shoulders. Menswear trends are still coming out of
Italy, but the looks have been sleeked-down with higher armholes
and shorter three-button suit jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Even casual apparel is exhibiting less bulk. Cargo pants are
omnipresent, but they're not as baggy.
</P>
<P>
   Layering is still key to casuals, but even T-shirts contain
spandex for a trim fit, and fleece vests are sans bulk.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Trinidad, spokesman for The Fashion Association (a
non-profit trade organization in New York that monitors fashion and
lifestyle trends), says men's clothes are looking different because
they're being designed for a more fashion-conscious consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are much more comfortable with being fashionable,'' he
says. ``They're seeking out apparel that's not only functional
(but) enhances their appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   And according to Trinidad, gym workouts have become mainstream,
especially for men 20 to 40. All that exercise leads to bigger
shoulders, smaller waists.
</P>
<P>
   These men are key customers to contemporary menswear designers
such as Calvin Klein or Kenneth Cole, Trinidad says.
</P>
<P>
   But not everything is Italian/British inspired. Designer Tommy
Hilfiger presented the sleek look with an all American twist:
clothing inspired by leather-clad bikers.
</P>
<P>
   As Diane Sustendahl, a New York fashion authority, puts it,
``Men aren't spending all that time in the gym so they can hide in
L.L. Bean bags ... lumberjack looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask menswear experts to suggest five items that will update a
wardrobe, and they don't even pause before reeling off:
</P>
<P>
   _ Leather jacket _ One that's squared-off at the hem. Make sure
it's boxy or rectangular in silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   _ Something with a hood _ It can be on a sweater or jacket.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vest _ Options abound here. Choose a colorful fleece (extra
points if it's orange with plenty of zippers), a sleeveless
sweater, or a multipocket version favored by photographers and
fly-fishermen. Think of it as a layering item.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flat-front pants _ Forget about pleats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turtleneck sweaters _ ``They show you know what's really going
on,'' says Mark Jensen of Mario's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
