 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Sept. 21. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ASSEMBLY (United Nations) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan
sounded a warning to a frequently paralyzed Security Council on
Monday, saying that it must act faster and more effectively to meet
the challenge of a world engulfed in civil wars that quickly
descend into the slaughter of helpless civilian populations.
Speaking to the General Assembly the day before President Clinton
is scheduled to address world leaders here, Annan did not single
out the United States, the Security Council's most powerful member,
or any other major nation, but his unusually strong criticism of
the council's initial failures to deal with genocide in Rwanda and
1994 and to agree on responding to Serbian atrocities in Kosovo
over the last year pointed obliquely at American policy decisions.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-RDP (Dili, East Timor) _ The vanguard of an international
peacekeeping force staked its claim to this silent and broken town
on Monday, watched warily by clusters of refugees, sullen
Indonesian troops, and small, angry groups of irregular militias.
There was no resistance but no welcome for the peacekeepers, who
arrived with all the firepower and high technology of modern war.
There was no peace to keep; East Timor's tiny capital is a dead
city _ burned, looted, evacuated. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INQUIRY (Moscow) _ Developments in the Russia-Bank of New
York corruption investigation.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-CAROLINAS (Tarboro, N.C.) _ There are 10,000 people in
shelters in North Carolina and two thousand of them are being
housed in a high school gymnasium here where there is no running
water. Most of the people are from tiny village of Princeville,
population 2,000. Princeville was the first town in America
chartered by feed slaves and now is completely underwater. Not even
rooftops can be seen from helicopters overhead and there is no way
in or out by road. Signs of devastation are everywhere in North
Carolina. But even more rain is expected Monday night and this may
worsen flooding on eastern North Carolina rivers. At least 23
people were confirmed dead after 20 inches of rain inundated North
Carolina's coastal plain. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NY (Undated) _ Aftermath of the storm in the New York
region: For many, today was the first day of work since the storm
turned their lives upside down. By David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-POLICE (Trenton, N.J.) _ From wires: After months of
bureaucratic delay, Gov. Christie Whitman on Monday announced the
appointment of a veteran FBI agent and administrator as her choice
to be the new superintendent of the New Jersey State Police.
Whitman scheduled an afternoon news conference to make the
announcement. The appointment of Carson Dunbar, 47, of Ramsey, must
now be submitted to the state Senate for confirmation. By David
Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-LABOR-ASSESS (Undated) _ The agreement reached last week
between the United Automobile Workers union and DaimlerChrysler
includes some of the best raises obtained in a union contract in
years. Despite the pact's unusual generosity, neither economists,
auto executives nor industry experts are warning of disaster on the
inflation front or to the industry's competitiveness. A news
analysis by Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-ORBITER (Undated) _ The Mars Climate Orbiter arrives at
Mars and undergoes the first of many braking maneuvers that will
leave it in orbit around the red planet to begin an extensive study
of Martian weather and geology. The orbiter will also serve as a
communications relay for the Mars Polar Lander, which will arrive
in December. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPINE (Undated) _ The human spinal cord _ the length of
nerve fibers, neural machinery and blood vessels that constitutes
the southern extension of the central nervous system _ is not as
much of a dullard as scientists have long believed. New studies
demonstrate that far from being a passive conduit, slavishly
ferrying information to and from the brain, or a repository of
unchanging reflexes, the spinal cord has its own contribution to
make. Spinal cord neurons, researchers are finding, are capable of
learning in simple ways, and show changes in response to
environmental cues that many investigators interpret as a form of
memory. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
