<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGIC SHOOTINGS CALL FOR SYMPATHY, ACTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush did what he should have done
upon learning of the tragic shootings at the Wedgwood Baptist
Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Up to a point, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He scrubbed an out-of-state presidential campaign trip and came
home to offer sympathy to the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   His comments, essentially the same he has made in response to
previous episodes of senseless violence, didn't sound very
presidential. But they were doubtlessly heartfelt and honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no law _ I wish we could pass it. I would sign it _
that says people will love one another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Bush once again was unable to offer any hope
that government can do much to prevent the type of tragedy that has
occurred in several states with alarming frequency this year.
</P>
<P>
   He may be right. How do you stop someone who is deranged enough
and determined enough to wreak carnage that he is willing _ maybe
even eager _ to die in the process?
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments certainly made more sense than those offered by
a spokesman for Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, one of his longshot
opponents for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we made clear that anybody who used a gun in crime would be
severely punished ... that is what we need to be doing,'' the Hatch
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   His statement was absurd. It had absolutely no bearing on Larry
Gene Ashbrook, who shot himself to death after walking into the
Fort Worth church service and shooting 14 other people, seven
fatally.
</P>
<P>
   Or on recent random, well-publicized shootings that killed other
people in Colorado, Georgia and California.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of being punished was the last thing on those shooters'
tortured minds.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook, had he survived, could have been prosecuted for
capital murder in a state that has executed more convicted killers
than any other government in the Free World. But that possibility
didn't stop him from shooting up a church.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Hatch, Bush and other Republicans at one time or
another have made similar statements in the long-running debate
over gun control, but the Texas governor wasn't so simplistic on
his Fort Worth trip.
</P>
<P>
   The gun-control issue, never far removed from presidential
politics, is revived every time there is a multiple shooting that
attracts national attention.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, the
Democratic candidates, favor more gun control, while Republican
candidates generally oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, as the Republican front-runner, receives a large share of
the attention on this issue, as he does on most other issues. And
his record is strongly supportive of gun-ownership rights.
</P>
<P>
   During his first year as governor, he signed the law allowing
Texans to legally carry handguns, a measure that his Democratic
predecessor, Ann Richards, had played a key role in defeating two
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has embraced some gun-control proposals, including
raising the minimum age for purchasing a handgun from 18 to 21 and
closing a loophole in federal law that allows people to buy guns at
gun shows without submitting to a criminal background check.
</P>
<P>
   But, so far, they have been little more than an afterthought in
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some Texas legislators tried to pass a state law requiring
criminal background checks for gun show purchases. Bush said he
supported it when questioned by a reporter in the wake of the high
school shootings in Littleton, Colo., last spring. But he never
told any legislators that he supported the bill, and a House
committee killed it.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook purchased one of the handguns he used in Fort Worth at
a gun show. But he didn't have a felony record, and his purchase
may not have been blocked by a criminal background check anyway.
</P>
<P>
   More gun-control laws won't stop people who are bent on
destruction from obtaining firearms. But the random, multiple
shootings are still the exception. Of more potential danger to most
Americans are the less-dramatic, everyday murderers, robbers and
rapists who still have all-too-easy access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   Although people realize that no amount of laws is going to keep
all firearms out of the wrong hands, they can stand some
reassurance that government is doing everything it can to address
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   As the front-runner for his party's presidential nomination,
Bush has a forum from which to actively promote the reasonable gun
restrictions that he passively supports.
</P>
<P>
   Offering sympathy in the wake of a tragedy is fine, and people
appreciate it. But they also expect their leaders to be leaders,
even on hot-button issues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
