<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9035 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PRAIRIE-2TAKES-NY     09-20 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PRAIRIE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN IOWA, RESTITCHING THE TORN FABRIC OF THE PRAIRIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(af) 
 By SAM HOOPER SAMUELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ecologists call them ``prairie remnants.''
</P>
<P>
   They are forgotten snippets of land along roadsides. Corners of
farm fields steep enough or wet enough to have escaped the plow.
The rough of an occasional midwestern golf course.
</P>
<P>
   These are the few remaining pockets of the American prairie,
once a vast sea of grasses, sedges, and flowering plants that
spanned three time zones.
</P>
<P>
   As habitats go, these prairie remnants do a poor job of
sustaining the diversity of life that a large, continuous stretch
of prairie once could. Plant populations have become isolated from
one another, turning a once-robust gene pool into a series of
shallow gene puddles.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated species die out in some remnants, leaving only a few
species in the mix. Large, nomadic creatures like buffalo and elk
lack the expanses of grazing land they need. The fact remains that
one of the defining features of prairie is vastness.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the aptly named town of Prairie City, Iowa, 20 miles
east of Des Moines, vastness is making a comeback. So are buffalo,
elk, and a variety of plant species.
</P>
<P>
   Prairie City is the location of the Neal Smith National Wildlife
Refuge, a project of the United States Fish and Wildlife Service,
and at about 5,000 acres, the scene of one of the most ambitious
and unlikely efforts to restore a prairie ever tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1991, when we surveyed this area, it was a farmed
landscape,'' said Pauline Drobney, a biologist who works at the
refuge. ``There was no significance ecologically to this place. It
was just a big chunk of land available to start a refuge on.''
</P>
<P>
   The land, 3,600 acres at the time, was owned by Iowa Light and
Power, which had planned to use it for a nuclear power plant. When
that plan was abandoned, the acreage went on the market. Neal
Smith, who was then a congressman representing Prairie City,
managed to guide to passage legislation that called for the federal
government to acquire the land and create a refuge, at an initial
cost of about $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   An acquisition boundary was drawn that encompassed a total of
8,654 acres. To date, 5,000 acres have been acquired at market
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Drobney was hired at first as a consultant to survey the
land, then later as refuge biologist in charge of transforming this
sizable parcel from farmland back to prairie.
</P>
<P>
   The first hurdle was to find seeds. A mature prairie contains
150 to 200 species of plants, all of which have local variants.
Seeds are scarce, and when commercially available can cost as much
as $75 an ounce for the rarer species.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about 10 pounds of live seeds to replant one acre of
prairie. Hoping to gather seeds from authentic local sources, Ms.
Drobney consulted the Iowa Department of Natural Resources, which
maintains a database that includes prairie remnants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had records of eight remnants in the southern 40 percent
of Iowa,'' Ms. Drobney said. ``With that bad news, we decided to
get out there and find them ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Drobney hired five people, who for two and a half months
traversed 38 Iowa counties in search of remnants and seeds. The
search yielded about 2,000 remnants of native prairie and savanna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them were very tiny,'' Ms. Drobney said. ``Others were
300 acres or more. You take bits of this gene pool and bits of that
gene pool, you bring these together, and then you have the genetic
exchange, that gene flow that's possible once again on at least
this piece of the landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   After eight years of restoration, the genes are indeed flowing
again in Prairie City. Over time, the refuge has had to rely less
and less on seeds from outside sources, instead harvesting its own
seeds for replanting. Over the last two years, 20,000 pounds of
seeds have been gathered.
</P>
<P>
   Where once uniform rows of corn and soybeans were grown, Ms.
Drobney now takes visitors wading, with difficulty, through prairie
grasses up to 12 feet high, trudging through Canada wild rye, big
bluestem, little bluestem, nut sedge and Indian grass.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere the eye lands, there is some different plant, spider,
snake, inchworm or bird. Plants of many heights and colors form the
mottled landscape of a healthy prairie. A pair of sand hill cranes
was spotted on the refuge in July of 1997. Indiana bats, a
federally endangered species, hang from the oaks. Short-eared owls,
once common in Iowa but now on the state's threatened and
endangered species list, find shelter on the ground under the tall
grasses.
</P>
<P>
   And there are buffalo. A herd of 42, including 10 calves born
last spring, graze on a 750-acre enclosure within the refuge.
Buffalo do not just need prairies; prairies need buffalo, too.
Their grazing action keeps tree seedlings like dogwoods from
growing up and turning the prairie into scrublands. This year, the
buffalo were joined by nine elk brought in from outside Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   With buffalo come tourists. Some might argue that the point of a
refuge is to protect plants and animals from the intrusion of
people, but Ms. Drobney considers Homo sapiens as important a
species as any on the prairie landscape.
</P>
<P>
   There are purely practical reasons for this. The refuge has far
to go. The original plan included a staff of 36; because of stiff
competition for federal financing, the refuge operates with a staff
of 12. The bulk of the planting, monitoring and seed gathering is
done by volunteers. There would be little public support without
public access.
</P>
<P>
   On a more philosophical level, Ms. Drobney explains, education
is part of the refuge's mission. Last year the center saw 50,000
visitors, including 18,000 schoolchildren, who can lose themselves
in a prairie maze, built to resemble gopher tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo and elk are what environmentalists call the
``charismatic macrofauna'' of the habitat, the animals that the
public will support and visit. To achieve true diversity, equal
attention must be paid to the ``enigmatic microfauna.'' Ants,
earthworms and butterflies are also the subject of much work at the
refuge.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is the regal fritillary, a prairie butterfly
resembling a monarch but with a purple tint and large white spots
on its hind wings. In the words of Diane Debinski, an assistant
professor of animal ecology at Iowa State University, regals are
like canaries in a mine shaft: If they can survive, it is an
excellent indicator of high-quality prairie habitat. And like the
buffalo, regals do not do well on isolated patches of prairie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing a lot of research about the regal
fritillary's behavior at the edge of prairie,'' said Dr. Debinski,
who leads the regal fritillary project at the refuge. ``They really
don't like to leave a prairie. When they hit a cornfield, they
generally turn around and go back into the prairie.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, when their habitat is cut up into small pieces,
they do not thrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been studying these butterflies since 1994,'' Dr.
Debinski said. ``We looked for them across Iowa in 52 prairies, and
we only found them in 11 prairies. Only 5 of those 11 had
populations over 50 individuals. So they're really not doing well
in Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters for these little creatures, their larvae
are finicky eaters. There are only four species of plants they will
eat, and the only one indigenous to Iowa is the blue prairie
violet, another species that is on the decline.
</P>
<P>
   At the refuge, Dr. Debinski is working to re-establish a
population of blue prairie violets. Next year, she will release
regal fritillaries over the violets, hoping they will breed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most inspiring project for Iowa that I've seen
since I've been here,'' Dr. Debinski said about the refuge. ``The
scale of it is so immense. It gives us hope that the prairie could
become a functioning ecosystem in this area again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
