<SLUG> BC-TV-GANGS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEEKING SOLUTIONS': SUCCESSES IN THE WAR ON CRIME AND HATRED
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hedrick Smith delivers two and a half hours of good tidings
Wednesday night. Wherever he goes, from Washington, D.C., to Kansas
City to the North Side of Chicago, from a penitentiary in Oregon to
churches in South Carolina to a school in Southern California, he
finds individuals, groups and entire communities working
successfully to battle crime and hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeking Solutions'' begins in Washington at Benning Terrace, a
public housing project with a bad reputation. At night residents
used to lock themselves in their apartments while bullets flew on
the streets. Eight young men were killed in eight months. Finally,
in 1991, the murder of a 12-year-old on his way home from school
roused the neighborhood to action against feuding drug gangs.
</P>
<P>
   A few residents, joined in the Alliance of Concerned Men, went
out proselytizing among gang members. Their credentials were their
own criminal records, which carried credibility on the streets.
Smith reports how in cooperation with a community organizer,
Housing Authority officials and the police, the volunteers
succeeded in brokering a truce that gave the former troublemakers
incentives to improve their neighborhood and train for real jobs.
As they worked together to scrub away the graffiti that marred
their homes, one gang member said it was as though they ``took the
past away.'' The bullets stopped flying.
</P>
<P>
   In another example of community action, neighborhood leaders in
the Blue Hills section of Kansas City joined with the police in
shutting down drug houses and other centers of criminal activity
and fixing up abandoned homes. The crime rate has gone down
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago and in San Clemente, Calif., students are being
taught to live together amicably and resist the lures of crime and
the poison of group antagonism. Smith is persuaded that youngsters
can learn tolerance and can benefit from the experience of others,
even the inmates of the Oregon State Penitentiary who now mentor
teen-agers who seem headed for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran reporter that he is, Smith is careful to note that the
success stories are never entirely successful. Crime has not been
abolished in Chicago or Washington, and pockets of racial
intolerance survive in South Carolina even after a jury awarded
$37.8 million to a rural black church in a decision against some Ku
Klux Klanners. A Washington youth, a father of eight, says, ``I'm
still where I'm at,'' and he fears that when ``my kids get older,
they're going to be right there, stuck just like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet these neighborhoods have changed for the better. What they
have in common by this account is their residents' steady
commitment to improve their lives. Their resolve comes through in
Smith's discussions with parents, teachers and officials around the
country. ``Seeking Solutions'' preaches that where there is a will,
determined folks can find the way.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `Seeking Solutions: With Hedrick Smith'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Wednesday at 8 p.m. ET (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Hedrick Smith, correspondent and executive producer; David
Murdock, Marc Shaffer and Ariadne Allan, producers; Sandra Udy,
production manager/coordinating producer. A production of Hedrick
Smith Productions in association with South Carolina Educational
Television.
</P>
</TEXT>
