<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Sept. 21, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A cold front will sweep to the East Coast on Tuesday with
showers followed by cooler winds. In the Northeast, clouds will
persist all day, but the rain will be intermittent and mainly
during the afternoon near the shoreline. More heavy rain is likely
along the Southeast Coast as tropical moisture streams north ahead
of Harvey. Sections of the eastern Carolinas could receive over 3
inches of rain, aggravating the cleanup from Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Harvey may strengthen to near hurricane force
before it moves into central Florida. Near and just south of the
storm center, tides will average 3 to 6 feet above normal. Squalls
will bring wind gusts to gale force well inland. The heaviest rain
should fall along and northeast of the storm track. Isolated
tornadoes are also possible near the point of landfall which should
be within 40 miles of Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   The leading edge of much cooler air will push to the Gulf Coast.
Clouds will persist in much of Texas with showers likely along the
coast and in the western panhandle. Moisture from decaying
hurricane Hillary in the eastern Pacific will flow into the
Southwest helping to produce showers in sections of Arizona and
parts of southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Very cool air will cover a large portion of the nation from the
central Plains to western New England. Sprawling high pressure in
the Middle West will sponsor sunny skies and a milder afternoon. A
surge of warmer air should reach the Upper Plains Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest will stay bright and quite warm, but ocean clouds
will seep into the coastal valleys of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Autumn By The Bay
</P>
<P>
   Autumn's arrival signals waning warmth in most of the nation,
but in San Francisco, late September is typically the warmest time
of year. In mid-summer, the city by the bay is often cooled by
breezes from the 60-degree ocean water. With the jet stream far to
the north, weather systems are weak, so local winds are the primary
meteorological influence. In early fall, the jet stream shifts
south, steering lows and highs into the Pacific Northwest.
Clockwise flow around high pressure areas brings brisk winds from
the east, which temporarily push the maritime air out to sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
