<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-NEWSPAPER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL WILL PUBLISH WEEKLY TABLOID, ONLINE UPDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ILENE LELCHUK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco State University's longtime
student newspaper, the Golden Gater, is going the way of the
typewriter _ obsolescent.
</P>
<P>
   In a city considered the nation's center for online publishing,
the university's journalism department is making some high-tech
changes to an old publishing tradition to prepare students for the
so-called new media.
</P>
<P>
   Next fall the Gater, currently published twice a week, will
merge with the campus' magazine into a new weekly tabloid called
``Golden Gate Xpress'' and a parallel online version. The online
publication will be updated with breaking news three or four times
a week, said acting department Chairman Austin Long-Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of experience our students need to become
more competitive in the journalism field,'' Long-Scott said. ``More
and more news is online. The (Internet) is becoming the first place
many of our students go for information.''
</P>
<P>
   The move is an expansion of the university's popular journalism
elective, ``Introduction to Online Journalism,'' which has a
waiting list of students trying to get in.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Scott believes San Francisco State is one of the first
colleges to focus on online publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The university's move is welcomed by companies in San
Francisco's Multimedia Gulch that are looking for new talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great idea. It's clear that job opportunities
of the future, of the present for that matter, are online,'' said
David Talbot, founder of Salon.com, an online magazine based in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Salon is just one of many online publications launched from San
Francisco. The explosion also includes CNET's News.com, Wired and
Mother Jones online versions, and Women.com.
</P>
<P>
   Major print newspapers, whose numbers are dwindling nationwide,
also have launched their own online versions.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this means the death of the printed newspaper, local
media experts say, which is why San Francisco State will publish a
weekly news magazine, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do is expand the ways in which news is
presented by our publications,'' Long-Scott said. ``We are trying
to do more of that, not less.''
</P>
<P>
   About 80 students a semester will work on Golden Gate Xpress and
the online version, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gater is an old tradition in San Francisco student
publishing and was a starting point for many who are now
journalists in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a shame,'' said one of them, Gater alumnus and Examiner
copy editor Geoff Link. ``The Gater was a great paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad the Journalism Department has taken such an
elitist attitude about journalism. The online audience for news
does not include most of the people in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Link, the paper's editor in 1964-65, remembers when the Gater
was a 9,000-circulation daily that managed to cover news beyond the
campus' borders.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, the Gater sent a reporter to Selma, Ala.,
and he and another Gater editor went to Mississippi and covered the
Freedom Summer civil rights campaign in 1964, and the Gater was the
first in the Bay Area to write about the 1963 protests at San
Francisco's Mel's Drive-In for its allegedly discriminatory hiring
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the best civil rights coverage in the city,'' said
Link.
</P>
<P>
   The name ``Gater'' first appeared on a campus publication in
1931, according to university archivist Helene Whitson. The
journalism department then used the name for the campus newspaper
in 1959, she said.
</P>
<P>
   During the student strike of 1968, the Associated Students took
over the Gater from the journalism department. Soon after, the
journalism department created the Phoenix as an alternative paper.
</P>
<P>
   Financial failings and lack of interest killed the Gater in
1972. From 1974-78, students formed another paper called Zenger's
to take its place, but in 1979 it was renamed the Golden Gater.
</P>
<P>
   The Gater and Phoenix, both run by the journalism department,
competed until they combined around 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very sad about (losing the Gater),'' said retired
journalism advisor Jerry Werthimer, who worked with student
journalists from 1960 to 1995. ``I think it's got a great
tradition. And the campus deserves a first-rate paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the university's publishing changes are a sign of the times,
said Ben Bagdikian, former dean of the University of California at
Berkeley graduate journalism school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural thing for students interested in journalism to
be trained to do what obviously is going to be done in the
professional publications,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
