A9069 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-CUBAN-VANVAN-KANSAS-K     09-20 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-VANVAN-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN BAND LOS VAN VAN IN U.S. FOR ENTERTAINMENT PURPOSES ONLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LISETTE GARCIA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Los Van Van _ Cuba's greatest dance band
under communist leader Fidel Castro _ will be in Kansas this week,
celebrating 30 years of innovative sound and the debut of its first
American album.
</P>
<P>
   The band's tour and album ``Llego Van Van'' _ which translates
``Van Van has arrived'' _ sidesteps tricky U.S.-Cuba trade
relations, whose history dates to President John F. Kennedy's
blockade on goods and services from the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just grateful to be here,'' said the group's musical
director Juan Formell in a phone interview with The Star. ``The
U.S. is the pinnacle of success.''
</P>
<P>
   The group is slated to play its salsa-funk fusion Tuesday night
at Liberty Hall in Lawrence, kan.
</P>
<P>
   Although Van Van has performed on U.S. soil for several years,
this anniversary series is the first time the group's music will be
sold under an American label: Havana Caliente of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Formell said another difference is that the 15-piece ensemble
will earn a cut of profits from the sale of recordings and tickets
in the United States. The musicians formerly were considered
24-hour employees of the socialist state and earned a fixed salary
until Castro recently loosened the reins on artists, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Loopholes like this avert U.S. sanctions and ruffle some
government officials and anti-Castro Cuban exile groups.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami this month, community pressure forced the postponement
of the band's scheduled Oct. 9 concert. The concert has been
rescheduled for Oct. 11, pending an audit of Van Van's tour
finances. If concert records show that the band is sharing in U.S.
profits, a violation of the members' visas, Miami Mayor Joe Carollo
said he will cancel the show again.
</P>
<P>
   The Van Van controversy wasn't the only one last week involving
a Cuban band. Two members of another popular group, Sintesis,
requested political asylum Thursday at the office of U.S. Rep.
Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, a Florida Democrat, while enroute to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Formell told The Star that interpreting Van Van's visit as
anything more than entertainment is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Castro rhetoric, reported in his nation's official daily, holds
that sold-out U.S. performances by Cuban artists are political
conquests in ``enemy Yankee territory'' and that ``culture is a
weapon of the revolution.'' Formell flatly refutes these slogans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that,'' Formell said. ``Art is art and a
universal act. Either you do it right, it transcends and you rise.
Or it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuba has increasingly depended on money from tourism and the
arts to support his regime, since losing its subsidy from the
fallen Soviet Union in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Blaming the U.S. embargo for Cuba's marked demise in the last
decade is simply a device, Formell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a marketing tool. Cuba is not even ranked among the
world's 10 poorest countries,'' Formell said. ``If it sells, so be
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He cites the recent example of ``Buena Vista Social Club,'' an
independent film hit in which Ry Cooder dusts off forgotten Cuban
troubadours and parades them at a Carnegie Hall recital in New
York. Formell said: ``All's fair in love and sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't allow myself to be used that way. But I might if I
was a has-been, trying to make ends meet on a measly retirement
check each month.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbarito Torres, Van Van's special guest tonight, was featured
in ``Buena Vista,'' jamming in Jimi Hendrix-fashion on the laud, an
ancient mandolinlike instrument.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame them,'' Formell said. ``It's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Formell doesn't care who sits at the helm of one
country or another, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, I listen to Beethoven and I don't care who wasduring that period,'' Formell said. ``People should just listen to
me for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
