<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9075 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MARS-ORBITER-ART-     09-20 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-ORBITER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACECRAFT NEAR MARS FOR 2ND WAVE OF FRUGAL MISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two American spacecraft are approaching Mars, the second wave of
economy-class robotic orbiting and landing parties in an ambitious
revival of exploration of the red planet.
</P>
<P>
   One spacecraft, scheduled for arrival on Thursday, is to orbit
the planet and study its atmosphere, prospect for water and
generally observe weather through the seasons of a full Martian
year (687 days). The second craft is on course for a landing on
Dec. 3 at the edge of the south polar ice cap, where the terrain is
thought to hold a layered record of the planet's climate history.
</P>
<P>
   Mission officials at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena,
Calif., said Monday that both spacecraft, Mars Climate Orbiter and
Mars Polar Lander, are in excellent condition and ready for their
arrival. Last week, the orbiter fired thruster jets to fine-tune
its aim on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Though relatively modest in cost and scope, the missions are
integral steps in a long-term strategy of sending small spacecraft
to Mars at each 26-month opportunity when the orbital relationship
is right. Orbiters, landers, roving surface vehicles, balloons and
miniaturized airplanes _ at all times over the next decade or more
there should be a robotic presence on and over Mars. Their
objectives are to map the entire planet and its resources and scout
out clues to conditions there in an earlier, more temperate epoch.
</P>
<P>
   Eventual objectives are to return samples of rock and soil,
perhaps by 2008, and someday send astronauts for a long visit.
Behind this methodical approach is the enduring question of whether
life ever emerged on Mars and left some fossil traces, and whether
it still exists in some moist recesses of this cold, arid world.
</P>
<P>
   This is a far cry from the fictional travels to Mars that once
fired the human imagination. In the marvelous tales of Edgar Rice
Burroughs, also creator of Tarzan, the gentleman-adventurer John
Carter simply closed his eyes and wished himself all the way to
Mars (Barsoom in the novels), where he found spired cities,
eight-legged beasts of burden and, not least, the beautiful Dejah
Thoris, the princess he wooed and won.
</P>
<P>
   Real-life exploration of Mars has proved to be tame stuff by
potboiler standards. Long after the Martians of legend vanished,
two spacecraft landed there in 1976 in search not of a princess but
of the merest trace of microbial life in the red dust. Finding
nothing, and under tighter budget limits, scientists have turned to
the even more plodding operations of today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to do a whole lot more with less,'' said Dr. Sam
Thurman, flight operations manager of the current missions. ``The
public and Congress have told us, `Space is neat, but it's got to
be done at less than a billion dollars a pop.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was the price tag on the Mars Observer spacecraft, which
failed just before reaching the planet in 1992. The failure was
particularly devastating because the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration had put all its eggs in one basket, and was left
with nothing. The Viking life-seeking missions in 1976, though
operational successes, cost more than $2 billion, a figure no
longer acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, as a result of NASA orders to develop ``cheaper,
better, faster'' science missions, the complete cost of the present
Climate Orbiter and Polar Lander missions has been kept to $327.5
million, Thurman said. This represents a further paring of
expenditures over the first two missions in the current program.
The Pathfinder spacecraft, which landed with its little Sojourner
rover two years ago, cost $270 million. Another $300 million went
for the orbiting companion, Global Surveyor.
</P>
<P>
   Global Surveyor is still going strong, returning the most
detailed pictures ever for mapping the planet. The pictures of
widespread water erosion and magnetic data showing that in an early
period the planet churned with internal heat have further
encouraged planetary geologists in their view that ancient Mars was
a more Earthlike place, with abundant water, and could have
supported the beginnings of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to understand the history of that planet from a
biological perspective,'' Dr. Charles Elachi, director of the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory's space and earth-science programs, said in
an interview with Sky &AMP; Telescope magazine. He has been in charge
of developing the current Mars exploration strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to answer some of the life and climate questions,
the orbiter is equipped to examine the temperatures, dust and
clouds in the planet's atmosphere, composed mainly of carbon
dioxide, and especially look for water vapor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very important part of trying to understand Mars'
climate,'' said Dr. Richard W. Zurek, the chief mission scientist.
``We want to learn how water gets into the atmosphere, where it
comes from and where it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Launched last December, the 1,387-pound Climate Orbiter is
approaching the northern half of Mars. A 16-minute firing of the
craft's main rocket should slow it down to enter a wide-ranging
elliptical orbit. The spacecraft will loop around Mars once every
14 hours, at first dipping in no closer than 130 miles from the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Then the craft will be maneuvered to a closest approach of 60
miles to use friction from the upper atmosphere to bring its orbit
down to a low circular course. This technique, known as
aerobraking, was first demonstrated by Mars Pathfinder in 1997. Its
advantage is economic: The reduction in the amount of fuel needed
for rocket braking means the spacecraft weighs less and could be
launched on its journey by a smaller, less expensive rocket.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of November, the spacecraft should be settled in a
262-mile-high orbit and ready to support the Polar Lander's planned
90-day operations on the surface. During that time, the orbiter is
to serve as a communications satellite, relaying radio
transmissions between the lander and Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,270-pound Polar Lander, 3.5 feet tall and 12 feet wide, is
targeted to touch down on a broad, gently rolling plain near the
south pole. Specifically, the landing site is a rectangular area
125 miles long and 12 miles wide, at 76 degrees south latitude, 195
degrees west longitude.
</P>
<P>
   At landing time, it will be the end of spring in the planet's
southern hemisphere. The site will be in 24-hour daylight, critical
to operations of the solar-powered craft's systems. The thick polar
ice cap, in seasonal retreat, will be farther south. But drilling
into the frozen surface, the spacecraft should be able to
investigate subterranean water ice and the details of the layers of
dust and ice deposited there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this layered terrain is a record of climate change
on Mars,'' Zurek said. ``In a sense, digging into the surface will
be like reading tree rings or layers in an ice core.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ronald Greeley of Arizona State University, a member of the
lander science team, said a study of the thickness and geometry of
the polar layered terrain should test ``some of our ideas of how
the layers relate to the planet's climate history'' over millions
of years.
</P>
<P>
   The lander's 6.5-foot-long digging arm will probably take two
days to scoop up soil samples and deliver them to an oven. Gases
from the heated samples will be analyzed for any evidence of water
vapor, among other things. Then the lander's cameras and other
instruments are expected to collect data on atmospheric conditions
and weather patterns. A microphone is designed to capture the
sounds of Mars, perhaps the whistling of winds on the robot arm's
digging operation.
</P>
<P>
   To supplement some of its own explorations, the lander is
supposed to release two projectiles about 10 minutes before
touchdown. These probes are to crash at 400 mph and bury themselves
beneath the surface, where they will draw soil samples for heating
and another search for vaporized water ice.
</P>
<P>
   By March, when the lander's operations should be ending in the
approaching polar darkness, the Climate Orbiter is scheduled to
begin its own primary mission. One of its two science instruments
is an infrared radiometer for measuring temperatures, dust, water
vapor and clouds in the atmosphere from the surface to an altitude
of 50 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The orbiter also carries a color imaging system, combining
digital wide-angle and medium-angle cameras, developed by Dr.
Michael Malin of Malin Space Science Systems in San Diego. The
wide-angle camera will be used for daily global pictures of the
Martian atmosphere and surface. The medium-angle instrument should
provide more detailed pictures of surface changes related to
weather and seasonal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Because temperatures on the planet rarely rise above freezing,
most water there is probably stored in the ground, chemically and
physically bound to the soil or as ice. This may be especially true
in the polar regions. Wherever water is, the orbiter's mission is
to investigate its distribution and search for possible surface and
subsurface reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Climate Orbiter cruises toward its encounter, all is
quiet for flight controllers. Their simulations are completed. All
instructions for maneuvers have been radioed to the spacecraft's
computers. And Polar Lander, with another two and a half months to
go before its arrival, is essentially flying on autopilot.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, the controllers will be busy operating two vehicles
at once, and the Global Surveyor as well. As another concession to
the budget crunch, said Thurman, the flight operations manager, the
ground support team has been trimmed to 80 people. Seven years ago,
Mars Observer had a team of more than 200. And in the 1970s, the
Vikings had 500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 1726EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
