<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9077 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-COMMEN     09-20 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE MUST ACCOUNT FOR ALL THE SHEEP, EVEN THE LOST ONES
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Also moving as STAPLES-COLUMN in ``k'' commentary category) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The little boy is no more than 7 or 8. He's
telling me that his sister was shot the night before in the same
way one might declare the day of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours earlier, his sister had been one of the 14
people hit by bullets sprayed into a Wednesday-night church service
in Fort Worth by a man who would then turn the gun on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people, mostly teen-agers, were killed. The little boy's
sister, though, was one of the lucky ones. She managed to cheat
death.
</P>
<P>
   And now, with my body folded into a little blue chair in front
of my daughter's third-grade class, I simply wanted to forget his
words.
</P>
<P>
   But I couldn't. Even in the midst of reading to the class ``The
Elephant Prince,'' an old Nordic tale about the power of love, the
little boy's voice echoed in my head like thunder.
</P>
<P>
   Job's age-old question posed in the Old Testament when he was
confronted by his friends Eliphaz, Bildad and Zophar was my own:
``But where shall wisdom be found? And where is the place for
understanding?''
</P>
<P>
   Not even a book, my great invincible companion, the one that all
of my life allowed me to travel the world without ever leaving the
room, could bring me peace. Indeed, it may as well have never been
written. The only words hanging onto me now belonged to the little
boy. They owned me, because they reminded me of how closely related
we all are.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know his sister, but I was face to face with a little
boy my daughter, Asha, knew as David. Before the day would end, I
would learn that another child's sister, Cassandra Griffin, was
familiar to me as well. She played clarinet in the North Crowley
High School band, as did my niece, Jana. And I'd cheered for her
when she played basketball with Jana.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Cassie,'' as her friends called her, was one of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   And now, even with a book in my hand, the world seemed so small
and no amount of words, not even ones that evoke the powerful
message that love conquers all, could choke the terrifying pain in
my throat.
</P>
<P>
   No, I needed answers. I needed to be able to explain to my
daughters why the world isn't safe anymore. Not front yards. Not
school. Not even church.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Job asked: ``But where shall wisdom be found? And where
is the place for understanding?''
</P>
<P>
   The grim irony in this tragedy, perhaps, is that for many of us,
that place is often the church.
</P>
<P>
   What we tend to forget, however, is that even the church isn't
perfect, if for no other reason than we _ human beings _ make up
its members.
</P>
<P>
   There's a song my church choir likes to sing that says whatever
one needs, it can be found in the house of God. It's a true saying.
There is love there. Peace. And joy. Whatever you need.
</P>
<P>
   But church can be a dark and lonely place, too. There, you can
also find bigotry and hatred, the kind 47-year-old Larry Ashbrook,
the gunman, brought with him last week to Wedgwood Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help but wonder if this was the kind of place
Ashbrook found when he visited church; if that's why he drove
nearly 20 miles from his home in Forest Hill, a Fort Worth suburb,
before stopping in Wedgwood to unload his rage.
</P>
<P>
   That is as much an indictment against the church as it is a plea
for it to live up to its most basic principle, to love one another,
to treat others as we would have them treat us.
</P>
<P>
   Three times, Jesus told Peter if you love me, feed my sheep. And
he said this also: Insofar as you have done it unto the least of
these, you have done it unto me.
</P>
<P>
   People are always in great danger when they know what they
should do and refuse to act. And so you have to wonder if our
failure to keep God's first commandment has brought the church to
the dangerous place we find ourselves in today.
</P>
<P>
   News stories quoted neighbors as saying Ashbrook was a loner who
never talked to anyone. Wednesday night, he did a lot of talking,
spouting obscenities and demeaning worshippers' beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder what might have happened had people responded
before it got to that; if they had put aside their preconceived
notions and told him that God can replace even lost dreams.
</P>
<P>
   When the King learns in ``The Elephant Prince'' that his
daughter is sad, he declares that whoever can climb the hill and
bring her happiness will win her hand in marriage and rule half the
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   God promises his kingdom to us if we accept his son as lord and
master of our lives. But it doesn't stop there. He said, if you
love me, feed my sheep.
</P>
<P>
   We may never be able to fully explain Wednesday night's tragedy
to our children. We may never find an answer to the violence
destroying them. But we will all have to give an account for those
moments when we had the opportunity to love, to do the right thing,
and chose not to.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Send E-mail to gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9078 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     09-20 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE MUST ACCOUNT FOR ALL THE SHEEP, EVEN THE LOST ONES
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Also moving as CHURCHSHOOTING-COMMENTARY in ``a'' general
news category) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
