<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO A TAX CUT, LET'S ACT LIKE A SMART FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress, take heed: Accept the veto. This is not the time for a
fat tax cut financed by borrowing from the future. Not if we're
serious about shoring up the Social Security trust fund for future
retirees. Not if we really want quality education for all of
America's children. Not if we're sincere about filling in the
glaring gaps in our health-care system.
</P>
<P>
   Not if we meant it when we said we're ready to turn over a new
leaf with the new millennium, stop running deficits and begin
making payments on the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly not if the big beneficiaries of this tax gift are
to be people like Bill Gates and the other instant billionaires
that our soaring prosperity has spawned. Not if it's a tax cut for
those who need one the least.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders of the House and Senate announced at the
beginning of the August recess that they were going to the people
with their plan for a $792 billion tax cut. They were going to
build up such a crescendo of public demand that President Clinton
would be bombarded with letters, petitions and phone calls to
convince him that America's millions want nothing else so much as a
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   From all accounts, the effort backfired. People said they'd
rather pay off at least some of our debts first. Cut the interest
payments that are eating our lunch. Replace inadequate school
buildings and hire more teachers so our kids have fewer in their
classrooms and get more attention. These, according to all the
polls, are the American peoples' priorities. Not a whopping tax
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Now a group of Senate Republicans is arguing that we can do all
these things and also have a hefty tax cut simply by tapping into
predicted future budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Where would they start? Well, they say, the first thing _ just
for this year, mind you _ would be to borrow from next year's
Social Security surplus. It would only be temporary, see, and then
when things got better we could ...
</P>
<P>
   Where've we heard that before?
</P>
<P>
   They'd call it an ``advance funding plan,'' says Sen. Arlen
Specter of Pennsylvania, member of the Senate Appropriations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this wouldn't amount to yet another smoke-and-mirrors
gimmick, Specter replied that ``the real reality is how smoky is
the smoke and how reflective are the mirrors.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's pretty clear, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   What's clear is that if they have to resort to this kind of game
to justify a huge tax cut, we don't need the tax cut _ least of all
one at just this time.
</P>
<P>
   What makes sense is using a portion of the taxes that come in
during this unprecentedly prosperous year to retire some of the
debt we've been building up, so that it won't continue to mount and
drag us down in future years.
</P>
<P>
   It's Joseph's age-old advice to the pharaoh. Set something aside
in the seven years of plenty. There may be years of need ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It makes good sense for the Treasury, at President Clinton's
direction, to pay off and buy up as much as possible of the old,
high-interest-rate debt that's dragging us down.
</P>
<P>
   Families have done this over the years. When interest rates are
low, as they are now, it's a great time to retire old debt, by
refinancing if necessary, to lower the interest payments. But,
first and foremost, pay off as much debt as we can when we have
extra money, and sock some away for the kids' education.
</P>
<P>
   America's families have had to learn, among other things, the
ruinous cost of letting big debts accumulate to drain away precious
dollars in monthly interest payments. America, at its best, is
nothing less than one big, extended family.
</P>
<P>
   Once, years ago when I was mayor of Weatherford, Texas (which
was then a town of maybe 12,000), we came to the end of a very good
fiscal year. We'd done some good things _ built parks and paved
some streets, bought a small lake and modernized our waste-water
disposal system _ and still had some money left over.
</P>
<P>
   Our wise old city attorney, George McCall, pointed out that we
still had some old, unpaid bonds that were financed many years
earlier at outrageously high interest rates. Some were costing us
almost 5 percent a year! While others (George smiled benignly) had
been negotiated at rates as low as 1.75 percent!
</P>
<P>
   What we did was to use our surplus to buy up and retire as much
as possible of the highest-interest debt. We didn't worry so much
about the 1.75 percent bonds _ just kept paying on them.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury officials believe they could use a portion of our
expected surplus each year for such a selective buyback to trim the
total public debt from today's $3.6 trillion to less than $2
trillion in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   That would be like a $125 billion-a-year gift to American
taxpayers. It would cut at least that much from the present drag of
approximately $300 billion in carrying charges that we're obliged
to ante up to bondholders every year.
</P>
<P>
   Those interest charges come out first, remember, leaving that
much less for schools, roads, health, public safety, national
defense _ all those positive things that contribute to our
individual and collective wellbeing.
</P>
<P>
   These are things that a prudent family might do with an
unexpected surplus.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright &LR; tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
