<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9084 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX     09-20 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING TOWARD A CITY THAT'S SAFER FROM GUN VIOLENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JACK Z. SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In October of last year, Fort Worth businessman Lee Bass called
Joel Glenn, the security chief for the Bass Companies, into his
office.
</P>
<P>
   Bass had heard about a program called Project Exile in Richmond,
Va., in which federal and local law enforcement officials were
combining forces to crack down on gun crimes. The idea was to focus
prosecution in federal courts, which were less clogged than state
courts and provided substantially longer prison time for
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Bass wanted to know what Glenn thought of the concept. Their
conversation led to talks with civic leaders and law enforcement
officials about launching a similar project here. That talk will
become reality on Sept. 29, when the launching of Safe City USA,
modeled after Richmond's strongly successful Project Exile, will be
announced in downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The Safe City program won't guarantee that there won't be future
tragedies like Wednesday night's carnage at Wedgwood Baptist Church
in southwest Fort Worth, in which a deranged loner named Larry Gene
Ashbrook killed seven people and wounded seven others in a
horrifying shooting spree that culminated with his suicide.
</P>
<P>
   However, if Safe City works as well as Richmond's Project Exile,
it likely will result in declines in gun-related crimes, including
murder and armed robbery. And the program won't require passage of
any new laws or any new local tax expenditures, according to its
backers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the year that Project Exile was just getting launched
in Richmond, the Virginia city recorded 140 homicides. Last year,
the number dropped to 94. And in the first eight months of this
year, the city has had only 47 homicides, compared with 67 for the
same period in 1998. Project Exile is given much of the credit for
that decline.
</P>
<P>
   Safe City will be somewhat different from any law enforcement
project ever seen here.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a public-private partnership in which donations from
businesses, foundations and individuals will pay the full cost of
several hundred thousand dollars for a ``media blitz'' designed to
publicize the program and intimidate gun-toting criminals.
Everything from billboards to 30-second TV spots will be employed
to spread the message that ``Gun Crime Means Hard Time.'' A similar
media focus accompanied Project Exile in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   The steering committee for Safe City includes Fort Worth Mayor
Kenneth Barr, Police Chief Thomas Windham, U.S. Attorney Paul
Coggins, Tarrant County District Attorney Tim Curry, the Bass
Companies' Glenn, and Patsy Thomas, executive director of the Crime
Prevention Resource Center, who will coordinate the program.
</P>
<P>
   Under Coggins' direction, the program will utilize resources of
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the FBI, the Drug
Enforcement Administration and the U.S. Secret Service in support
of Fort Worth police.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Terri Moore, who has a wealth of
experience as a federal and state prosecutor, says the prospect of
working in the Safe City program is ``absolutely exciting'' because
of the potential to reduce gun violence and save lives.
</P>
<P>
   If a suspect is caught carrying a gun in the commission of a
crime and the case goes through the state court system, ``this guy
is probably going to be back on the street in a couple of hours''
after posting bail, ``and his case probably won't be heard for a
year or longer,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the suspect goes through the federal system, he will be
immediately jailed and likely denied bail, and his case probably
will be handled within 70 days, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said stiffer federal laws mean that a person who gets a
10-year prison sentence will likely serve nine years or more behind
bars. But a 10-year sentence from a state court may result in only
two years behind bars, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Safe City, prosecutors are expected to utilize the federal
Gun Control Act of 1968. That law says it is illegal for felons,
fugitives from justice and others with a blighted status to possess
or sell a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   The boosters of Richmond's Project Exile program range from
President Clinton to the National Rifle Association, which has
touted stronger enforcement of existing gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   I think the Safe City program probably will prove a success. But
it will be difficult for the program to match Richmond's in terms
of the percentages of decline in violent gun-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Fort Worth already has achieved a dramatic
reduction in crime. While Richmond had 140 homicides in 1997, Fort
Worth had only 64 last year, compared with a record 202 in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Safe City looks like a program that will have a
clearly beneficial effect. And in the wake of last week's
nightmarish church shootings, we ought to be looking for every
effective weapon against gun-related violence that we can find.
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Z. Smith is an editorial writer and columnist for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. He can be reached at (817) 390-7724 or
jzsmith &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
