r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-20 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE STILL DON'T NEED HATE-CRIME LAWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a fair question: If last week's murders at a Fort Worth
church were a result of the killer's loathing for Christians in
general or Baptists in particular, should the shooting spree be
labeled a hate crime?
</P>
<P>
   The question has come up frequently in the days since Larry Gene
Ashbrook walked into Wedgwood Baptist Church and shot 14 people,
killing seven and wounding seven before committing suicide. We may
never know precisely what motivated the attack, but there is
considerable evidence that he had an ax to grind where religion was
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   If Ashbrook gunned down churchgoers for no reason except that
they were engaged in the practice of religion, then the shootings
should qualify as a hate crime under any conceivable definition of
the term. But let's face it: The hate-crime laws that are so
popular nowadays are not being adopted for the benefit of Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   The laws have been prompted by violence against groups and
individuals that have historically been targets of violent bigotry:
racial minorities, Jews, homosexuals, women. ...
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream Christian religious organizations simply aren't
thought of as victims of oppression in this country _ or they
weren't before Wednesday. Larry Ashbrook may have changed all that.
</P>
<P>
   A hate-crime bill failed to make its way through the Texas
Legislature this year, in part because of disagreements about which
groups should be designated for protection. If the legislation is
reconsidered in the next legislative session, the debate will
undoubtedly extend to the question of how specific the law ought to
be in its protection of religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   The argument could go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   And so could the argument about the entire concept of hate-crime
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable that groups whose members are too often
targets of violence would favor laws that specifically prohibit
such violence. But there is no act of violence against a human
being that isn't already illegal _ and that doesn't subject the
perpetrator to severe penalties.
</P>
<P>
   One of the vicious bigots who dragged Texas resident James Byrd
Jr. to his death in 1998 has already been convicted. Another has
been convicted but not yet sentenced as of Monday. Would that
killer's eventual lethal injection be any more deadly if he had
been convicted under a hate-crime law?
</P>
<P>
   And if Ashbrook hadn't taken his own life after shooting 14
churchgoers, would Texas need a hate-crime law to prosecute him for
a mass murder that may have been motivated by his apparent enmity
for Christians?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. Capital murder is capital murder, no matter what
the motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many laws passed by legislative bodies in this country,
hate-crime laws are totally unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, on issue after issue, politicians pass laws for
no reason except to placate some individual or interest group that
can deliver votes or campaign contributions. Hate-crime laws are
not adopted to prevent or punish hate crimes; they are adopted for
the gratification of the groups that believe that they are
potential targets for hate.
</P>
<P>
   There's no disputing that we have put laws on the books for
flimsier reasons. But it's high time that we put a stop to the
practice of adopting redundant laws that serve no purpose except to
make somebody feel good.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush was criticized during the legislative
session for not going to bat for the hate-crime proposal, but his
position was perfectly reasonable. If the Legislature had sent him
a bill, he would have studied it and made a decision as to whether
it filled a void in Texas law enforcement or merely duplicated laws
that were already on the books.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way of knowing, of course, but I'm guessing that Bush
would have found the bill to be unnecessary and refused to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   We don't need a hate-crime law to prosecute the killers of James
Byrd Jr., and we wouldn't have needed a hate-crime law to prosecute
Larry Gene Ashbrook.
</P>
<P>
   We just plain don't need a hate-crime law.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
