<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9092 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE21-CO     09-20 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pick an insurance plan to keep you covered
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feel like gambling?
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of employers nationwide will be sending out
stacks of packets filled with pamphlets, brochures, charts and
forms in triplicate in the coming weeks. It's time for open
enrollment at larger companies, with workers rolling the dice on
what kind of health care they're going to get in Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Employees could learn through their packets how to guarantee
well-child care for their babies, brand-name drugs for chronic
conditions and physical therapy in the event of an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most workers spend less time examining plans than they spend
ordering a pizza _ the result of being overwhelmed and confused
about what each plan covers. And although employers and insurers
have gotten smarter at explaining health benefits, most workers
still see that folder as a Big Mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found many of them never even read it,'' said David Settle
of Southern Co., which has more than 30,000 employees and recently
revamped its open enrollment package to include quick-comparison
charts of options.
</P>
<P>
   So what should you consider when picking a plan that will
provide _ and pay for _ the health care you need?
</P>
<P>
   Rule No. 1: Don't pick a plan on the basis of how much is going
to be taken out of your check each week. In recent years, health
plans have been raising their premiums to cover rising expenses. In
response, employers have raised the amount their workers pay in
deductibles and co-payments, and reduced the number of services
covered. So if you go with what looks like the most economical
plan, you might get a shock when you actually receive a medical
bill. ``What might appear to be the cheapest plan might not be the
most cost-effective plan,'' said Dr. Wayne Hoffman, vice president
of medical management at Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Rule No. 2: Determine your health care patterns. Write down the
doctor and hospital visits you had this year and how the health
plan you picked worked out. Did your claims get paid promptly? Did
your doctors treat you with respect? Was it easy getting the
medications you needed? Decide whether you dealt with annoyances or
serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration: Are you making any life changes in the
coming year? Planning to get married? Will your new spouse need any
kind of treatment _ for diabetes, for example _ you haven't needed
in the past? Thinking about having children? You may want to
compare different plans' coverage of prenatal care. If you're
getting divorced _ and have children _ you will have to pick a plan
that covers their health care regardless of where they are living.
The same is also true for college students.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors to consider:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More companies are offering domestic partner health benefits,
so unmarried couples should investigate what might be available to
them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parents with chronically ill children should study each plan's
track record with that disease. For example, if you have a son with
asthma, you should check how well the plan educates its members and
whether it is willing to pay for the special medication and
equipment _ such as an inhaler _ needed for your child to be well.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure the network of the plan you pick includes the
doctors and hospitals you expect to use. You can also see if the
plan is accredited with the National Committee for Quality
Assurance (www.ncqa.org), which provides survey information about
patient satisfaction, doctor satisfaction and quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Take a special look at prescription drug benefits. As more
medications swamp the market, insurers are ratcheting down what
they will cover, requiring that patients either pick from a certain
list of approved medications, known as a formulary, or pay more to
get drugs that aren't on the list. If you know you need a certain
brand-name medication, call the plan's customer service office to
find out whether that drug is covered. (And if you can't get
through on customer service lines, that is a sign of what you can
expect in the future.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you might want to call your doctors and ask them about
the plans you are considering. They probably know the hassle factor
of each of the plans and may be able to help you decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one-size-fits-all with health plans,'' said Arthur
Levin, director of the Center for Medical Consumers, a New York
nonprofit advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   So open that packet and uncap the ballpoint pen. This year, when
the health care game is over, the winner should be you.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Consitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
