<HEADER>
A9094 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-PROSTATE-CANCER21-COX     09-20 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-CANCER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What you should know about: Prostate cancer
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prostate cancer is the most common cancer in American men, and
the second deadliest behind lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But chances of survival are high _ if it is diagnosed early.
Tumors generally grow slowly on the prostate, a walnut-size gland
under the bladder and in front of the rectum. The prostate
surrounds the urethra, the tube through which urine flows.
</P>
<P>
   HOW IT'S DETECTED
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Digital rectal examination.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Prostate-specific antigen (PSA) blood test.
</P>
<P>
   WHO SHOULD BE SCREENED
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  All men 50 years and older should get annual PSA tests and
digital rectal exams.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Men at high risk for prostate cancer, including those with
family history of prostate cancer and African-American men, may
want to consider starting screenings at 40.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HAPPENS
</P>
<P>
   DURING SCREENING
</P>
<P>
   Digital rectal exam
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The patient bends over, and the physician inserts a gloved
index finger into the patient's rectum. The bent position allows
the doctor to feel for bumps or nodules on the prostate through the
rectal wall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The procedure only takes seconds and is easily tolerated, says
Dr. Fray Marshall, chairman of the urology department at Emory
University School of Medicine (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About one in two detectable prostate bumps prove cancerous.
However, prostate cancer isn't always detectable via DRE.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The exam also can detect enlarged prostates, which are common
in older men, but aren't necessarily cancerous.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate-specific antigen test (PSA)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Requires drawing blood.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The test can't specifically diagnose cancer but can indicate
whether something may be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The test looks for antigens, molecules capable of stimulating
an immune response. Prostate-specific antigens are released only by
the prostate gland.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A higher than normal PSA level can reflect anything from an
infection to prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High PSA levels warrant a closer look by a urologist.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO GET SCREENED
</P>
<P>
   Several metro hospitals and clinics are offering free PSA tests
and rectal exams during the next two weeks. Call the American
Cancer Society at 1-800-227-2345 or look up the Web site at
www.cancer.org.
</P>
<P>
   _Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
