<HEADER>
A9099 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSSTAND21-COX     09-20 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First lady wins over Esquire writer
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a quest for the real Hillary Rodham Clinton, Atlanta writer
Tom Junod hits the campaign trail with the first lady for an
insightful and irreverent profile in Esquire ($3). Junod examines
the myth and reality of the woman some consider to be the most
polarizing political wife since Marie Antoinette. ``The most
interesting fact about Hillary,'' Junod writes, ``is that so many
men absolutely hate her and that their hatred is not so much
political as sexual. Under the guise of political discontent, men
say things about Hillary they would never say about other women.''
Junod's assessment of the woman who would be senator? She has
pretty eyes, sexy lips and a wicked laugh, and, yes, Junod says,
``I would vote for her in a New York minute.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Teen scene: Teenagers have had such an impact on culture in
the last half of the century that it's hard to imagine a time when
they didn't exist. Actually, says Thomas Hine in American Heritage
($4.95), teenagers did not emerge as a defined group until the
Great Depression. Before then, they were simply young people who
went to work on farms or were sent into factories and mines to help
support their families. After World War II, Hine says, young people
became teenagers ``because we had nothing better for them to do. We
began seeing them not as productive but as gullible consumers. We
defined maturity primarily in terms of being permitted adult vices,
and then were surprised when teenagers drank, smoked, or had
promiscuous sex.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New on the rack: Finally, Architectural Digest has published a
slick magazine for car buffs that can be displayed on coffee
tables. The debut issue of Architectural Digest Motoring ($4)
features a cover shot of Kevin Costner with his 1966 Mustang, an
essay by John Updike, and a consumer article on collectible autos.
Says editor-in-chief Paige Rense: ``Our cars reveal our individual
triumphs, as well as our yearnings; in them we find a concentrated
form of design that is capable of transporting us emotionally even
as it transports us literally.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The newsweeklies: For a while, it looked as if the geeks were
going to inherit the earth. Now, Time ($3.50) reports, the
engineers who ruled Silicon Valley have been replaced by business
school graduates who are taking over what the engineers started.
... In a Newsweek ($3.50) cover story, scientists discuss new
research that suggests that health patterns are determined in the
womb, and that diabetes, obesity, cancer and heart attacks are not
necessarily the result of bad genes. A sidebar explains things
women can do, from preconception care to diet and exercise, to give
babies their best start.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  No pizazz: The New Yorker's ($3) Joe Klein examines the
presidential campaign so far and finds it sorely lacking in style.
That's right, style. There's plenty of substance, Klein writes, but
that's not what the public wants. ``There isn't much fun anymore in
politics,'' agrees former White House speechwriter Peggy Noonan.
``The prissy and the pious and the cautious have taken over.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Picture perfect: In a collector's edition, Life ($3.99)
presents the photographs that remain frozen in our minds, from the
picture of Jack Ruby shooting Lee Harvey Oswald in Dallas to the
images of the Berlin Wall being torn down. One section is devoted
to celebrities such as Elizabeth Taylor and Sally Quinn, who
explain their most memorable photographs of the century. Quinn's is
the picture of a naked Vietnamese girl fleeing a napalm attack.
``When people who had been for the war saw this picture, they
thought, `Oh my God, what are we doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Soccer star Brandi Chastain reveals almost all
(again) for Gear ($3.50) in an interview with Candace Bushnell.
Chastain defends her controversial sports bra exposure at the end
of the Women's World Cup championship match. ... Entertainment
Weekly ($3.95) continues its series on a century of pop culture
with the 100 greatest moments in movies over the past 50 years.
It's no surprise that ``The Godfather'' is No 1.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
