<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERWATER-HOCKEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIANS DIVES INTO UNDERWATER HOCKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Minnesota transplant Dov Cohen was invited
to play hockey with some new friends here, his first thought was to
grab his skates. When the friend said forget the skates, bring the
fins, he figured the game was a ``crazy California thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to try it,'' says Cohen, 32, a scientist from Livermore,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   It took about three dives beneath the surface of the pool for
Cohen to turn this odd new game into a passion, and not much longer
to learn that underwater hockey is played worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Although the obscure sport was started 50 years ago by English
divers looking for something to do in the off-season, San
Francisco's club started just this past summer, with players
ranging from plumbers to management consultants whose ages run from
30 to 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing when compared to any other sport,'' says Andy
Dean, 42, of Santa Rosa, who gave up basketball and football to
play water hockey three years ago. ``The fact that you have to do
something athletic while holding your breath, there's an extra
level to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The game that started in England as ``octopush'' involves six
players who don fins, masks and snorkels and dive for brightly
colored pucks at the bottom of the pool. Using only a 10-inch-long
sawed-off hockey stick, they swim to the puck, then compete to push
it to the end of the pool and, with luck, into a trough for a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the players' time is spent with their faces in the
water, and much of the time they are holding their breath.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they get bonked in the head with a fin or knocked with
a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this could be the friendliest sport on Earth. There are
few rules. Fouls are called on the honor system _ usually by the
people who made them. After all, it's not easy to see under water,
and there are no referees for local games.
</P>
<P>
   When a goal is made, almost nobody cheers, high-fives or dances
in the end zone. They're still treading water. In fact, at the end
of the game, often nobody is quite sure of the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no score because nobody cares,'' says Caroline Harris,
39, a member of San Francisco's team who got lured into the sport
15 years ago in her native England. ``And if it were one-sided we
would switch around the players to make it even.''
</P>
<P>
   At a recent game, the players look _ from above the water at
least _ like disorganized dolphins having a romp. As colorful fins
and Speedos dart under and over the water in quiet splashes, it
quickly becomes evident when the puck is spotted.
</P>
<P>
   The swimmers swarm around it in what resembles a shark feeding
frenzy. They do this _ alternately holding then gasping breath _
for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Although the game is admittedly tough to follow from the
sidelines, for players the rules are simple. They can't use their
free hand, they can't block another player and they can't shoot the
puck behind the goal. Positions are determined by individual teams,
although there are generally six to a side _ three offense and
three defense. They line up at each end of the pool until someone
shouts, ``Sticks up!'' and then ``Go!''
</P>
<P>
   This sport has some obvious attractions for young and old.
</P>
<P>
   Oceanographer Sean Avent, 28, says he's lost up to 2 pounds in
one game. But he notes that because the game is played in water, he
has little chance of injuring himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no gravity to hurt yourself, so you won't blow a knee
or hurt your bones,'' he said. ``It's very rigorous exercise and
very exhausting. And the great thing about it is you don't realize
you're getting tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Anderson, 70, a retired social worker and veteran diver
from Santa Rosa, has played the game for 27 years. While he can't
get the puck into action as quickly as he'd like, his aim is sharp.
Then there's Cohen, the newcomer who took up the sport two years
ago and couldn't score a goal until last year.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's no surprise that a game invented by divers _ who
live or die by the buddy system _ encourages such noncompetitive
camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good group of people,'' says Cohen. ``The nature of
the sport is very cooperative. They have to watch out for one
another so they're very conscientious.''
</P>
<P>
   He says veteran players always seem happy to show neophytes the
ropes, and are forgiving of the many inevitable errors that happen
in the first year of playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all a little bit crazy,'' says Avent. ``We get along
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
