<P>
   BUSH-MCKINNON _ AUSTIN, Texas _ In his basement offices, Mark
McKinnon is wrapping up work on the answer to the most perplexing
question of the presidential campaign: How can George W. Bush
possibly spend the giant buckets o' cash he is collecting for his
White House bid? The answer, as it is to too many questions about
turn-of-the-century America, is television. And McKinnon _ former
lead singer for Lazlo Frink and the Odd Sofa Review featuring the
Lazlettes, former short-term jailbird, former media guru for
big-name Democrats _ is the man making the TV ads that will mold
Bush's national persona as well as consume much of his political
cash. So far, that is $50 million. For McKinnon, 44, spending the
Bush money is the latest stop in a magical mystery tour that has
taken him from music to politics to swearing off politics to media
man for the front-running presidential candidate. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
