<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-RECYCLABLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S RECYCLING BIN BRIMS WITH STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS .MDNM/
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody knows that Heather Locklear will flex her conniving
muscle on ``Spin City'' this season, fresh from the dead-and-gone
``Melrose Place.'' (And, before that, the late ``T.J. Hooker'' and
the departed ``Dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   That Locklear. What a survivor. Or, to be more precise, a
recyclable _ one of those stars who keep turning up time and again
in different seasons on different shows in different roles.
</P>
<P>
   And this season is full of them.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably well aware of the spinoff stars: David Boreanaz
(''Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' to ``Angel'') Jennifer Love Hewitt
(''Party of Five'' to ``Time of Your Life''), and Countess Vaughn
(''Moesha'' to ``The Parkers'').
</P>
<P>
   But did you know that ``Snoops'' star Paula Marshall has been
recycled from ``The Wonder Years'' to ``Spin City'' to ``Chicago
Sons'' and last season's ``Cupid''? Or that ``Get Real's'' Debrah
Farentino has bounced from ``Equal Justice'' to ``Earth 2,''
``Hooperman,'' ``McBride and Groom'' and ``EZ Streets?''
</P>
<P>
   Others just hop on other ships as theirs are sinking: Nancy
Travis was ``Almost Perfect,'' so she's back in the CBS comedy
``Work With Me.'' Moira Kelly exited ``To Have &AMP; To Hold'' for
NBC's ``The West Wing''; ``Homicide's'' Richard Belzer bolted with
his conspiracy theories to NBC's ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims
Unit''; Rob Estes latched onto NBC's ``Suddenly Susan'' after
``Melrose Place,'' and Maura Tierney bolted from NBC's
``NewsRadio'' to NBC's ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   You could say Sharon Lawrence found a home on CBS' ``Ladies
Man'' after visiting ``NYPD Blue'' just as Jessie L. Martin found
``Law &AMP; Order'' after too many episodes with that scatterbrained
``Ally McBeal.'' Jason Behr got firm footing on ``Roswell'' after
kicking about on ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   And how about the veterans? Betty White (''Mary Tyler Moore,''
``Golden Girls'') is making trouble in CBS' ``Ladies Man,'' Rue
McClanahan (''Golden Girls'') is making trouble on the WB's ``Safe
Harbor,'' and Buddy Hackett (''The Jackie Gleason Show,''
``Stanley'') is making trouble on Fox's ``Action.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Alda (''MASH'') will drop in on ``ER,'' Tyne Daly (''Cagney
&AMP; Lacey,'' ``Christy'') is a regular on ``Judging Amy'' and David
Ogden Stiers (''MASH'') and Swoosie Kurtz (''Sisters'') are,
surprise, a snobby rich couple on CBS' ``Love &AMP; Money.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Michael Michelle. ``Central Park West'' was
short-lived. ``New York Undercover'' sank two seasons after she got
there; ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' died one season after she
was brought on as a detective.
</P>
<P>
   Just where has she been recycled? ``ER.'' Don't worry. The No. 1
rated series is considered the Titanic of television.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
