r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     09-20 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MEDIA'S EYES WERE WIDE SHUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The release of  &UR; Stanley Kubrick &LR; 's final movie, ``Eyes Wide
Shut,'' became an event, says the latest Brill's Content, because
of the machinations of  &UR; Pat Kingsley &LR; , an entertainment publicist
who makes it her business to be professionally conniving.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsley's strategy was to pretend that the movie was
extraordinarily sexy, a fabrication that worked only because she
prevented people who were writing about it from seeing it
beforehand. The film's stars were on the cover of Bazaar, Vogue,
Esquire, Good Housekeeping, US, Rolling Stone and Time. Rolling
Stone called it the ``summer's sexiest movie''; Vogue writer  &UR; John &LR; 
 &UR; Powers &LR;  described its ``erotic audacity'' without ever having seen
it.
</P>
<P>
   Once the movie opened, the audience decided how steamy it was. A
month after its premiere, says the magazine, it had taken in $53.5
million; ``The Blair Witch Project'' had earned twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsley tried to dissuade reporter  &UR; Katherine Rosman &LR;  from
writing the story _ ``Let it go. Let it die'' _ and then said
mediocre attendance figures were neither her fault nor the actors'.
``That's the movie's fault,'' she said. ``Dead men have no
publicists,'' observes Rosman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BODILY FUNCTIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Anti-Aging Network is going to ``launch internationally''
next month, says founder  &UR; Elysa Henley &LR; , but it won't be available
locally. This will be disappointing news to those who hoped to
watch continuous shows on such topics as ``Celebrity Youth
Secrets,'' ``Beauty/Body Makeovers'' and ``Financial Fitness.'' As
the Web site for the network advises, ``Grow younger through TV.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Because October is National Breast Cancer Awareness Month, the
authors of ``Speak the Language of Healing: Living With Breast
Cancer Without Going to War'' (Conari; $14.95) have started a
``Stupidest Thing That Someone Ever Said to Me About My Cancer''
contest. Winner gets a pair of earmuffs (to keep out stupid
comments), a pendant and her  &LR; their  &LR; entry posted on the book's Web
page, www.speakhealing.com. Entries can be e-mailed to
stroupkl &LR; aol.com or sent to Stupidest Things, 1424 Hillside Ave.,
Nashville, TN 37203.
</P>
<P>
   _ AromaBand.com is selling bracelets infused with scents for
energy, serenity, passion, &LR;  and clarity, allowing the lucky
consumer to sniff away any time of day or night. The list of stars
wearing this $3.50 product is said to include  &UR; Sara Rue &LR;  and
 &UR; Charisma Carpenter &LR; , and if you don't know who they are, you
probably don't want a smelly bracelet anyway.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bayer has stopped putting cotton in the top of its aspirin
bottles. The original purpose of the packing material was to keep
pills from breaking. It has been unnecessary since the '80s when,
through the miracle of science, the company started coating the
pills with a substance that prevented breakage.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Business School professor of marketing  &UR; Al Silk &LR;  told
the Wall Street Journal that the move may be a mistake. The cotton
may symbolize ``trust and a sense of confidence,'' he said. ``One
wouldn't want to tamper with that unless one has good reason to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Miniature trampolines are the latest in exercise equipment at
gyms, reports Men's Journal. The '90s name for using the things is
``Urban Rebounding.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Gar Smith &LR;  sends word of Wednesday's Restoration Fair at the
Palace of Fine Arts, which celebrates ecological restoration and
features a ``smudging'' ritual that sounds like Ash Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; 's butler,  &UR; Paul Burrell &LR; , whose book ``In the
Royal Manner'' is to be published in London on October 4, told the
Daily Mail that his boss wasn't the shy, soft-spoken doe she often
appeared to be in public. ``The princess demanded perfection, and
only the best would do,'' he said. ``When she shouted, you'd go
away with your tail between your legs and think about it. There's
only one boss in a situation, and she was the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   _ At a premiere party for the movie ``Stir of Echoes,''  &UR; Paul &LR; 
 &UR; Sorvino &LR;  told  &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  that he's created a film version of
``King Lear,'' in which he'll star with his daughter  &UR; Mira &LR; 
 &UR; Sorvino &LR;  as Cordelia. Lear will be a power broker, ``a mix of
 &UR; Donald Trump &LR;  and  &UR; Robert Moses &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I could write the lyrics but had no tape machine to record
melodies. So I would call home and sing into the answering machine.
I compiled everything that way. F _, there's nothing else to do!''
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roller Tommy Lee, telling E!Online how he used his time
in jail (for spousal abuse).
