<HEADER>
A9117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES21-COX     09-20 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mets-Braves series has teams 'ready to get it on'By Carroll
Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The National League East comfort zone the Braves have
lived in for the last four years is history. Here come the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   With a dozen games to play and only one game separating them
from second-place New York, the Braves open a three-game series
tonight at Turner Field against their greatest challenger since the
1993 Giants. John Smoltz and Rick Reed are the pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of all the talk,'' Braves third baseman Chipper
Jones said. ``Win or lose, I'm ready to get it on and see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny how similar the sentiment sounded coming from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get it on,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said after the
Mets' 8-6 win over the Phillies on Sunday. ``(The Braves) probably
watched the end of our game. They know where we are. They know
we're coming.''
</P>
<P>
   No joke. In the most anticipated Braves' regular-season series
in recent memory, Atlanta and the Mets face off in the first of six
games they will play in the next two weeks. The last three are
Sept. 28-30 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest surprise is that several thousand tickets
remain for each of the three games. As of Monday afternoon, 5,000
tickets were left for Tuesday night, 4,500 for Wednesday night and
2,500 were left for Thursday afternoon. But Braves ticket manager
Paul Adams said he expects all three games to sell out.
</P>
<P>
   No more than 4 1/2 games have separated the teams for the last
two months. The Braves have known for a while now their eighth
consecutive division title would have to come at the expense of the
Mets. So the so-called business-like Braves begin a gut-check
series, and it's not even October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our season is on the line, so of course there will be more
excitement,'' Tom Glavine said. ``I don't think that means we'll
play the game any differently. . . . I'd rather have a comfortable
lead, but it's still fun. Two of the most fun years were pennant
races in '91 and '93, but that's because you can look back and say
we won them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have won 13 of their last 18 games against the Mets
over the last two seasons, including taking two of three games
twice this year. Last season, with the Mets wild-card spot on the
line the last three games, the Braves swept them.
</P>
<P>
   But those victories were then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter,'' Smoltz said. ``We proved that, getting
beat by the Pirates year after year and then beating them in the
playoffs. Obviously, that gives you a little more confidence. But
that confidence gets shattered if you don't win right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams realize the importance of the first game or two of
this series, to see who can stake their claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the playoffs,'' Jones said. ``It's all about
momentum and who establishes it first. Usually the one who
establishes it first in the playoffs goes on and wins it.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, both teams are just glad the series is finally
going to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred and fifty games after spring training, we
anticipated this very moment,'' said Mets pitching Al Leiter, who
will start Thursday against Greg Maddux. ``It's exciting. This is
an opportunity few teams get. This is something we should
cherish.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
