<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO DEADLY U.S. DISASTERS; YELTSIN'S MISSING FINGERS; THE MOON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How many people died in the 1889 Johnstown flood and the 1900
Galveston hurricane?
</P>
<P>
   _ U.C., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: In the deadliest natural disaster in U.S. history, 6,000 to
8,000 people were killed when a hurricane struck Galveston on Sept.
8, 1900. The storm, which had winds of 125 mph, submerged the
island and destroyed 3,600 of the 5,200 buildings in the city.
</P>
<P>
   A book released this month, ``Isaac's Storm,'' by Erik Larson,
focuses on the role of National Weather Service meteorologist Isaac
Cline, who survived the storm by floating on the remains of his
house.
</P>
<P>
   There were 2,209 fatalities after the South Fork Dam broke
during a storm on May 31, 1889, pouring the 20-million-ton Lake
Conemaugh into a valley that included Johnstown, Pa., 12 miles
downriver.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnstown Flood National Memorial in St. Michael, Pa.,
includes the remains of the dam and portions of the lake bed. For
more information on the memorial, call (814) 495-4643 or visit the
World Wide Web site www.nps.gov/jofl.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is Boris Yeltsin missing a finger?
</P>
<P>
   _ G.T.K., Dallas
</P>
<P>
   A: The Russian president lost two fingers on his left hand in a
childhood accident involving a grenade.
</P>
<P>
   During the Nazi invasion of Russia, Yeltsin either stole a live
hand grenade from a weapons depot or found it in the woods,
according to press reports. He and a friend were trying to
dismantle the grenade when it exploded.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Communist Party presidential candidate Gennady Zyuganov
said Yeltsin's missing fingers and Mikhail Gorbachev's birthmark
were satanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's remember the prediction of the apocalypse,'' Zyuganov
said during a campaign speech. ``Two beasts sent by the devil are
coming out of the abyss. The first one has a mark on his head. The
second has a mark on his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Farmers and gardeners are told to plant vegetables such as
potatoes and carrots in the ``dark of the moon,'' and others in the
``light of the moon.'' What is meant by these phrases?
</P>
<P>
   _ H.D., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: The Old Farmer's Almanac defines them according to the dates
of the new moon and full moon.
</P>
<P>
   The dark of the moon occurs from the day of the new moon to the
day of the full moon, and everything else is considered the light
of the moon.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. To ask a question, contact him in care of the
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101, or e-mail him at
trivia(at)prefect.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
