<SLUG> BC-HEATHER-MATARAZZO-IN-NOW-AND-AGAIN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `NOW' GIRL: HEATHER MATARAZZO AND THE NEW FACE OF STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Heather Matarazzo in a scene from ``Now
and Again.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Every now and again, Heather Matarazzo wants to slap herself in
the face and scream, ``Oh, my God! I'm working!''
 &HT;    ``I really do,'' the young actress says. ``I'm somewhat
established in the industry and some people know who I am _ that's
a great feeling.
 &HT;    ``Ninety-nine percent of the actors in the United States are not
working, at least as actors,'' she adds, ``and I'm one of the few
who is. I have to keep reminding myself of that, otherwise I could
become very egotistical and not care and forget where I started.''
 &HT;    Few moviegoers can forget where Matarazzo started. The year was
1996, and the film was Todd Solondz's acidic black comedy ``Welcome
to the Dollhouse.'' Matarazzo stunned audiences with her
heartbreaking performance as dorky junior-high-school student Dawn
``Weiner Dog'' Weiner.
 &HT;    So convincing was Matarazzo that most people figured she had
been simply playing herself.
 &HT;    ``Everyone just assumed that I was Dawn and that Dawn was me,''
Matarazzo says with a shrug. ``It wasn't frustrating, though. It
wasn't. Really. I'm thrilled that people even recognized me. I'm
thankful that the movie went as far as it did.
 &HT;    ``People still recognize me,'' she adds, ``which is shocking
because I did that movie five years ago. They'll say, `Oh, you look
so different. I thought you were her, with the glasses.' I'm like,
`No, sorry to disappoint you.'
 &HT;    ``But it was great to get that response, to know that people had
this closeness to the character. And I love that people express
that to me.''
 &HT;    Matarazzo is now a self-assured 17-year-old and, as she says, a
working, even steadily working actress. Her post-``Dollhouse''
credits include such television programs as ``Roseanne,'' ``E.R.''
and ``Law and Order,'' as well as the films ``Devil's Advocate''
(1998) and ``54'' (1998).
 &HT;    At the moment, Matarazzo is sitting in a spartanly appointed
trailer parked on a street in Long Island City, N.Y., just a
stone's throw from the soundstages at Silvercup Studios, where
she's shooting the CBS television series ``Now and Again.''
 &HT;    Debuting on Sept. 24, ``Now and Again'' _ whose pilot was
written, produced and directed by ``Moonlighting'' impresario Glenn
Gordon Caron _ co-stars Matarazzo as Heather, the moody daughter of
Michael (John Goodman) and Lisa Wiseman (Margaret Colin), whose
life turns upside down when her father dies in a tragic subway
mishap.
 &HT;    Unbeknownst to Heather, however, the government implants
Michael's brain in a $3 billion, bioengineered body. Enter the new
and vastly improved Michael Wiseman (Eric Close), who can't contact
his grieving family and must complete assorted dangerous missions
assigned to him by Dr. Theodore Morris (Dennis Haysbert).
 &HT;    Matarazzo simply couldn't resist the project, she says.
 &HT;    ``It was an opportunity to work with Glenn Gordon Caron,'' the
actress says. ``It was a very interesting script, and I thought, if
the pilot could be that interesting, the rest of the scripts could
be even better.
 &HT;    ``Michael is going to be on his missions saving the world and
I'll be at home with mom, with my wit and my sarcasm. Occasionally
I'll be a teen-age brat,'' she says with a smile. ``She's a normal
teen who's suddenly dealing with this anger, frustration and
resentment toward her mother about her father's death. That's a
very real element.
 &HT;    ``We don't Hollywoodize it,'' she adds, ``and, even though we've
got the sci-fi stuff and even some comedy in the show, it's all
still grounded in the reality that everyone in this family is
trying to get on with their life.''
 &HT;    The prospect of a long run for ``Now and Again'' doesn't unnerve
Matarazzo. In fact, she welcomes the idea of maturing on screen, of
making the leap from teen-ager to young woman in the public eye.
 &HT;    ``That'll be pretty exciting,'' Matarazzo says, raising an
eyebrow and shooting a look at her mother, who's sitting quietly a
few feet away. ``That'll be pretty cool. I've never thought about
it that way.
 &HT;    ``I kind of think of `The Brady Bunch' and how they all grew up
on screen,'' she adds. ``I'm happier that I'll be a teen-ager
growing into a young adult, rather than a little child growing into
a teen-ager _ that's more embarrassing.''
 &HT;    Anyone who can't get enough of Matarazzo need not worry. Beyond
her weekly bits on ``Now and Again,'' she's recently completed four
independent features: ``Getting to Know You'' with Mary McCormack
and Chris Noth, ``Strike'' with Kirsten Dunst, ``Company Man'' with
Sigourney Weaver and Alan Cumming, and ``Cherry'' with supermodel
Shalom Harlow.
 &HT;    ``I don't know what's going to happen with those films,''
Matarazzo says. ```Getting to Know You' is on the festival circuit,
and they're trying to find a distributor.
 &HT;    ``I did `Company Man' more than a year ago, and `Strike' may go
straight to video,'' she adds. ```Cherry' is really cute, though. I
play an airhead waitress at a muffin shop, but she's not the kind
of airhead you just want to kick.''
 &HT;    Matarazzo clearly doesn't discriminate between studio films,
independent features and television shows. In fact, she thrives on
being able to jump around.
 &HT;    ``I'm at home wherever I'm acting, and I love a challenge,'' she
says. ``It's great if I can read a script and say, `Man, I can do
this,' and then get scared and think, `Oh, my God! I don't really
know if I can do this.'
 &HT;    ``Then I know I really have the bull by the horns.''
 &HT;    Truth be told, Matarazzo wants to do it all.
 &HT;    ``I want to produce, direct and write as well,'' says Matarazzo,
who lives with her family in Long Island, N.Y. ``I'm going to start
my own production company in the next two or three years.''
 &HT;    But those waiting for the second coming of Woody Allen will have
to wait a while, she adds.
 &HT;    ``I'm not even remotely close to setting it up,'' the
wannabe-mogul says, laughing at herself. ``One day I'll decide,
`Now,' and I'll stay up 24 hours a day and get everything in
motion.
 &HT;    ``I do that with everything, even cleaning my room,'' Matarazzo
admits. ``I won't clean it for months, and then I'll just do it
until it's spic and span.
 &HT;    ``But it's my ambition to produce, direct and screenwrite. I
might procrastinate a great deal, but I'll get it done.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Now and Again,'' consult the
