<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASHLEY-JUDD-IN-DOUBLE-JEOPARDY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHLEY JUDD, TENNESSEE'S ANSWER TO HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Ashley Judd with Tommy Lee Jones in a
scene from ``Double Jeopardy.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Before you go visit Ashley Judd, you'd better think twice.
 &HT;    ``You can't walk into my home without either singing a song or
doing a chore,'' the actress says.
 &HT;    Thank goodness this interview is taking place at Beverly Hills'
Four Seasons Hotel, far from her Tennessee home.
 &HT;    ``If we were at my house, you would be sent right to the sink to
rinse dishes,'' she says. ``Then you could shake out the throw rugs
on the sleeping porch.
 &HT;    ``You know the singer Billy Dean?'' Judd adds. ``Well, he came
over to my house for Christmas. And he's my favorite because he did
a chore and then he sang a song.''
 &HT;    Not the usual Hollywood approach, and indeed it's hard to
believe that the down-home-sounding Judd is a movie star.
Nonetheless, on Sept. 24 the 31-year-old actress will star in
``Double Jeopardy,'' the latest installment in what is rapidly
becoming a creditable career.
 &HT;    Judd's role, as a woman convicted of killing her husband only to
find that she's actually the patsy in his elaborate insurance scam,
was originally intended for Jodie Foster. But the three-time
Oscar-winner had to drop out when she learned that she was
pregnant.
 &HT;    Judd had been interested in the project from the beginning,
however, and was ideally situated when the role suddenly opened up.
 &HT;    ``She had her rep call my office every two weeks to say, `I know
you're meeting with Jodie Foster, but Ashley would still love to do
this role,''' producer Leonard Goldberg says in a separate
interview. ``Ashley really hung in there with it. She has this aura
about her that things are going to work out.''
 &HT;    ``If there is something I want,'' Judd says calmly, ``I will go
after it.''
 &HT;    That aggressiveness might surprise those who knew her when she
was a quiet, bookish girl growing up poor with her extroverted
mother and sister in rural Tennessee. Sometimes forced to live
without electricity, running water or a telephone, Judd recalls,
she and her sister would water down their soup to make dinner
stretch a little further.
 &HT;    ``We didn't have things,'' she says. ``But we had hope, which is
what mattered.''
 &HT;    Her father left the family when Ashley was a baby, leaving Naomi
Judd to raise Wynonna and Ashley on her own. The actress remembers
her mother being a strict disciplinarian.
 &HT;    ``I think she was tough because she was frightened, being a
single parent,'' Judd says. ``You knew when you were in trouble
because the cold, disapproving stare from her was worse than any
other punishment.''
 &HT;    Her sister knew how to finesse their mother, though.
 &HT;    ``Wy could crack her up,'' Judd recalls. ``She would be getting
into trouble, and Wy would put one of those Steve Martin arrows on
her head. Mom would start to laugh.
 &HT;    ``Unfortunately, I didn't have the same wily quality.''
 &HT;    When Judd was a teen-ager, her mother and sister took their
musical act on the road and, improbably, emerged as top-selling
country stars. That left the non-singing sister to be shuttled
between her father and a tour bus, spending a lot of time watching
television by herself.
 &HT;    ``I used to have a crush on David Letterman, until he did the
joke about the Judds,'' she says. ``He would say, `Did you hear
that the Judds have another girl, but she's so ugly they leave her
back home locked in the basement? Every once in a while they throw
her down a canned ham.'''
 &HT;    She winces at the memory. Being a Judd has its drawbacks,
including Naomi Judd's ``Love Can Build a Bridge'' (Fawcett Books,
1994), an autobiography _ later a television miniseries _ which her
daughters found more than a little inaccurate.
 &HT;    ``I'm reading my mom's book going, `This is dubious,''' she
recalls, laughing. ``And then I'm screaming, `Is this true?' But,
you know, mom had a deadline. I couldn't change the information.
 &HT;    ``So you sort of throw your hands up and say, `My reward is in
heaven.'''
 &HT;    But Judd has long since defined herself apart from her musical
relatives. Over the course of a short but star-studded film career
_ including roles in ``Ruby in Paradise'' (1993), ``Heat'' (1995),
``Smoke'' (1995), ``A Time to Kill'' (1996) and ``Kiss the Girls''
(1997) _ she's proven that she's her own woman.
 &HT;    She's also noted for her intelligence _ she graduated Phi Beta
Kappa from the University of Kentucky in Lexington _ an attribute
not always welcome in actresses in male-run Hollywood.
 &HT;    But Judd will have none of that.
 &HT;    ``What? Do I have to downplay my brain for the schmucks?'' she
says. ``Honestly, I think that being perceptive and having
interests is nothing but an asset.
 &HT;    ``I think what shocks people is that I have an urban side,'' she
adds. ``They're stunned that I'm well-rounded in ways they didn't
expect an actress or a Southerner to be. For instance, I walk into
someone's office, and after five minutes they go, `I expected you
to talk about corn bread and quilts.'''
 &HT;    Next up for the actress is a role as a killer in ``Eye of the
Beholder,'' a drama co-starring Ewan McGregor. Judd is outspoken in
her Christian views, but that doesn't stop her from playing evil
people, if she thinks it's dramatically effective.
 &HT;    ``Oh, this is interesting,'' she says, ``because when my sister
got pregnant with her son, she came to me one day and said,
`Ashley, tell me you would never take a role where you kill a
child.'
 &HT;    ``I was very silent,'' she recalls. ``And I finally said, `It
depends on where the script goes. It's drama, and tragedy is a
staple of drama.'''
 &HT;    Judd may not always agree with her sister, but they're clearly
on good terms. In 1993, after her Malibu home burned to the ground,
Judd packed her bags and headed for safer territory in Tennessee,
ending up half a mile away from her mother's driveway and down the
road from her sister's house.
 &HT;    ``My little five-acre fiefdom in the overall Judd kingdom,'' she
calls it. ``I think I appreciate my land more because I earned it.
Then there's the naturalist in me who just appreciates the land _ I
love the quote, `I have found there is nothing in this world that
nature cannot soothe.'''
 &HT;    After a moment, she adds that she had another reason for
relocating.
 &HT;    ``I also think the way I appreciate my house is often rooted in
fear,'' she admits. ``I'm afraid of recognition, which is why I
live in Tennessee.
 &HT;    ``I think I have a fear of fans, a fear of intrusiveness,'' the
actress says. ``That's the real reason this land is so sacred to me
now _ it protects me and buffers me against what we all call
celebrity.''
 &HT;    Judd, who has dated singer Michael Bolton and actor Matthew
McConaughey, among others, has had her share of problems with the
paparazzi. For now, she says, there's no one special in her life.
 &HT;    ``Yes, I think about family,'' she says. ``But something I've
always said, which I think remains true, is `For God to know and me
to find out.'
 &HT;    ``And, hopefully, the reporters a lot longer after that!''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
