A9132 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-THE-DAVE-MATTHEWS-BAN     09-20 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-DAVE-MATTHEWS-BAND-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVE MATTHEWS, MAKING MUSIC THE OLD-FASHIONED WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of the Dave Matthews Band, including Dave
Matthews, LeRoi Moore, Stefan Lessard, Carter Beauford and Boyd
Tinsley.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    After nearly 16 months of touring, Dave Matthews sounds like a
man with one thing on his mind _ and it isn't music.
 &HT;    ``I'm looking forward to stopping _ I want to go home,'' the
33-year-old Matthews says. ``I want to see what my house looks
like. I had a puppy _ it's a dog now, since I last got there. I'm
just looking forward to being home and putting my guitar down for a
month or so, stuffing it in a closet and trying to forget how to
play it.''
 &HT;    Matthews isn't complaining, mind you.
 &HT;    ``I'm not bored with my job yet,'' he adds with a chuckle.
 &HT;    But he does feel that, after two years of nearly constant work _
which included recording the Dave Matthews Band's last album,
``Before These Crowded Streets'' (1998), touring and guesting on
the new Santana album, ``Supernatural'' (1999) _ it's time to
recharge a bit before starting work on the group's next album.
 &HT;    ``What a bore I would be if my whole focus was making records,''
says Matthews, who lives in a 19th-century, hydropowered millhouse
near Charlottesville, Va. ``What a bore life would be if everything
was about what our next big thing will be.
 &HT;    ``You have to keep it in perspective.''
 &HT;    Matthews has certainly earned his break, having engineered one
of the decade's most successful rock careers since forming his band
in 1991.
 &HT;    Born in Johannesburg, South Africa, Matthews first came to the
United States in 1969, when his father, a physicist, took a job
with IBM. Matthews returned home to finish high school, then
settled in Charlottesville, where he played music and worked as a
bartender.
 &HT;    He eventually decided to form his own band and recruited some of
his favorite players from the local scene, including drummer Carter
Beauford, bassist Stefan Lessard, reeds player LeRoi Moore,
violinist Boyd Tinsley and occasionally guitarist Tim Reynolds,
with whom Matthews also sometimes tours as an acoustic duo.
 &HT;    Each of the band's five albums has sold platinum or better _
even ``Live at Red Rocks 8.15.95'' (1997), a low-key, unhyped
archival recording that still sold more than a million copies. More
recently, ``Before These Crowded Streets'' debuted on the Billboard
Top 200 album chart at No. 1, and has so far sold more than 2
million copies.
 &HT;    But the DMB's greatest success has come as a live act, one
generally regarded as the most consistent ticket-seller in the
business. During 1998 the band ranked No. 2 in the trade magazine
PollStar's annual survey, grossing $40.1 million in ticket sales
for 85 shows. Its first 61 concerts in 1999 sold nearly 1.5 million
tickets, and were marred only by parking-lot riots that resulted in
roughly 40 arrests Aug. 7-8 outside the Meadows Music Theater in
Hartford, Ct.
 &HT;    Those statistics are only half the story, however. The DMB has
built its success through the old-fashioned route of hard touring
and grassroots marketing _ with a few modern touches, of course.
 &HT;    At first the band paid its dues by playing 200 dates a year,
driving a battered red van to shows at clubs, beachfronts and
fraternity houses throughout the Southeast, winning fans with
heavily improvised performances that blended rock, jazz, soul and
world-music conventions.
 &HT;    Matthews and his cronies also encouraged their steadily growing
audience to record the shows, which, thanks to the tape-trading
underground, helped spread the band's reputation to college
campuses across the country.
 &HT;    Before long the group had an independent album, a burgeoning
telephone-order business and a Website that not only promoted the
band's appearances but also sold T-shirts, caps and other souvenirs
through the Bama Rags division of Dave Matthews, Inc.
 &HT;    As a result, by the time RCA Records signed the group in 1993,
it was getting an established, proven entity.
 &HT;    ``By no means had we anticipated that,'' Matthews says, adding
that he feels it's the group's music-first philosophy that has been
the primary lure for its fans.
 &HT;    ``I feel a connection to the audience,'' he says, ``but I can't
step outside myself and say why an audience likes it. I don't like
to spend much time thinking about what it is, either, for fear of
finding out and diluting it.
 &HT;    ``But I think that comes out of a happiness that they're
enjoying themselves,'' Matthews adds. ``There's a great connection
in the band with each other, and we love to play together. I can
say it's not something that was made in an office in Hollywood or
an office in New York _ it wasn't some plan from the 44th floor of
the BMG building or anything like that.
 &HT;    ``I can just say we enjoy playing.''
 &HT;    More than most concert acts, the Dave Matthews Band is a
constantly evolving institution, with a marked experimental streak
that many bands would be afraid to indulge.
 &HT;    ``Before These Crowded Streets'' was markedly different from its
predecessors, a dense, atmospheric collection that risked
alienating fans who were comfortable with the wiggly, buoyant
grooves of favorites such as ``Crash'' (1996), ``Too Much'' (1996),
``Ants Marching'' (1998) and ``What Would You Say'' (1998).
 &HT;    But as a musician, Matthews says, he craves change. And on
``Crowded Streets,'' which was co-produced by Steve Lillywhite, he
wanted to create more of a studio-generated work, unlike the
earlier albums that largely had been cooked up on the road.
 &HT;    ``I don't want to sound too much like I don't like those
albums,'' he says, ``but they were kind of like ... the collection
of holiday pictures, whereas this one was thinking about it as an
album, as a thing we had to finish, rather than saying `We have
five out of 10 songs done, we're halfway there.'
 &HT;    ``We were sort of continually sanding the whole thing,'' he
says. ``They were constantly changing and constantly developing.
There's a looser feel about the music, I think.''
 &HT;    Matthews _ who co-wrote and, along with drummer Beauford, played
on the song ``Love of My Life'' from the new Santana album _ says
that the band will release a live album later this fall, with its
next studio album due in 2000.
 &HT;    It's too early, he says, to say what might appear on that album.
But he does admit that, after the success of ``Before These Crowded
Streets,'' he feels a new license to experiment and tinker with
what the DMB is.
 &HT;    ``I think our sound is still changing and developing,'' he says.
``I think it's in a good space right now, and I feel pretty good
about it. I think maybe the only thing we don't want to do is
repeat ourselves.''
 &HT;    He doesn't have a sense of the band's future direction, Matthews
adds, but he doesn't mind that.
 &HT;    ``I don't really think that there's a line that we're traveling
along,'' he explains. ``I think it's more like looking for things,
boldly tromping on, you know? It's more of a search, more of a
waiting than it is a direction.
 &HT;    ``We're always writing,'' Matthews says, ``whether that means
it's just fooling around at sound check and our sound man happens
to be recording or it means we've got some new ideas, there's new
things coming all the time.
 &HT;    ``Whether or not any of them grow into tunes is a different
story, but I guess it means we're not bored with what we do yet.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website
