<HEADER>
A9136 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-20 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOTHES MAKE THE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service cliehnts.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here are a few men's fashion tips I picked up at
Macy's Passport fashion show last week:
</P>
<P>
   Create an image. Don't be yourself unless you're mostly naked
and your stomach ripples so tightly it looks quilted. The biggest
cheers at Passport didn't go to clothing, but to one particular
guy's stomach, designed and perfectly cut at a gym.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us will need clothes.
</P>
<P>
   When picking an image, mix and match senselessly, as long as you
use a lot of paisley, leather, shiny fabrics, puffy jackets and
items of clothing once associated with men with dirt under their
fingernails or flowers in their hair.
</P>
<P>
   Choose one part of your image from Column A: Carnaby Street,
Gasoline Alley, Easy Street or Mean Streets.
</P>
<P>
   Then choose from Column B: Skateboarder, Two Live Crew,
Audio-Visual Crew, Motocrosser, Mechanic, Oscar Wilde or the Wild
One.
</P>
<P>
   As far as I can tell, the idea of contemporary men's fashions is
to avoid being categorized except as cool.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Hilfiger even had one guy dressed in a midruff-baring
tight T-shirt (all the better to see his quilted tummy), a kilt in
the Hilfiger tartan and knee-high engineer boots.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. But it was a bit extreme, even for a show whose theme
was ``Extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's another thing I learned: If you're a guy who wants to be
noticed in San Francisco, wear a kilt, but not a dress. There is a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   The guy entering the show in front of me wore a backless evening
gown displaying the back of a linebacker. And here's one of the
great things about San Francisco: Nobody batted an eye. It must
have ticked him off.
</P>
<P>
   I attend Macy's Passport almost every year, not just because the
show has raised about $10 million for AIDS research and care since
1986. I also go to hang out with interesting people dressed to the
nines, and to learn how to raise my own sartorial standards,
perhaps to the fours.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting harder all the time.
</P>
<P>
   In his ``Devil's Dictionary,'' the great turn-of-the-century San
Francisco Examiner columnist Ambrose Bierce defined fashion as ``A
despot whom the wise ridicule and obey.''
</P>
<P>
   This year I obeyed the despot of fashion, who now rules from
SoHo and MTV instead of Milan and Vogue. I bought cargo pants, a
Shanghai Tang sweatshirt with Mandarin frog-fasteners and a khaki
bucket hat _ and now everybody's ridiculing me.
</P>
<P>
   They do it even though I have the sense not to wear all those
new items at the same time. I mix and match to create new images
ranging from a preppie in cargo pants to a preppie in a sweatshirt
that looks like it came from Jerry Brown's yard sale.
</P>
<P>
   If you're the kind of guy who hasn't worn jeans with rolled up
cuffs since fourth grade, it's hard to please the despot of
fashion. However, friends are always pleased to say, ``What in heck
are you wearing now?''
</P>
<P>
   My style is a lack of style, accessorized by inappropriate
impulse purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Men even have to create images for themselves at black-tie
events these days. You can't just check for soup stains and put on
the penguin suit.
</P>
<P>
   At Passport, men wore paisley tuxes, Lord Fauntleroy scarves,
Nehru jackets, Bat Masterson ties, and collars in every possible
style, including dog.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, men will be saying, ``But I wore this tux to last
year's show,'' and shopping for new ones before every event.
</P>
<P>
   At the dinner before Passport, I was sitting in my once-stylish
tuxedo next to a terrific young local designer named Julie Chaikin,
who described the line she was showing as ``urban preppie.''
</P>
<P>
   I said that sounded great, and indeed it turned out to be a
wonderful mix of debutante and Debby Harry. Women's fashions
involve image-splicing, too.
</P>
<P>
   When I said I was an urban preppie, Chaikin asked what I usually
wore. I said my average outfit was work boots, chinos and a leather
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like there was a long silence, then this engaging
woman said, ``As I was telling a journalist earlier, wear what
makes you feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   She was so nice I don't think she was being condescending. But
journalists should never be told to wear what makes them feel
comfortable. The world doesn't need to see all those elbow patches,
unpressed shirts and burrito-stained ties.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen the mechanic look, the hobo look, the glam rock look,
the army poncho look, the bike-messenger look, but there never,
ever will be a journalist look.
</P>
<P>
   Things were easier in the San Francisco of Ambrose Bierce's day,
when men of all professions only wore things that made them
uncomfortable _ dark wool suits distinguished only by the quality
of cut and tailoring, not Tommy and Diesel insignia.
</P>
<P>
   Bierce ended his career by disappearing in Mexico, and that was
easier then, too. How do you pack for disappearance nowadays?
Should I bring the battered-chic cowboy hat from the Sundance
catalog or that skateboarder bucket hat?
</P>
<P>
   You think a serape would make an OK kilt?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
