<SLUG> BC-EVERYBODY-LOVES-RAYMOND-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVERYBODY LOVES RAYMOND': RECIPE FOR A HIT SITCOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Ray Romano, Patricia Heaton, Brad
Garrett, Peter Boyle, Doris Roberts, Madylin Sweeten, Sullivan
Sweeten and Sawyer Sweeten in a scene from ``Everybody Loves
Raymond.'') 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the longest-standing, most widely accepted Hollywood
cliches is that prime-time-television programming is a crap shoot.
Every year, the networks offer up some three dozen new comedies and
dramas, and every year 80 per cent of them are labeled turkeys long
before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, how do some shows beat the odds? In search of
insight into the recipe for success, we talked to the people
responsible for one of television's biggest current hits, the CBS
sitcom ``Everybody Loves Raymond.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; 1. FIND A CHAMPION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Critics loved ``Raymond'' from the outset, but lots of rave
reviews have gone to great shows that disappeared with lightning
speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raymond's'' real hero was Les Moonves, president of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it all to Les,'' says Brad Garrett, who plays Ray's
neurotic older brother, Robert. ``When we started out on Friday
nights, we were getting eaten up by `Who's Cooking the Soup?' on
the Food Network. We really thought it was over. But Les said, `I'm
with you _ trust me, it's going to happen.'''
</P>
<P>
   Co-star Doris Roberts, who shines as Marie Barone, Ray's
ever-meddling mother, heartily agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Les' belief in us right from the beginning was so strong and
so supportive that it gave us the strength to keep going and not
worry about where we were in the ratings,'' she says. ``There was
never the fear of cancellation hanging over our heads, so we were
able to just go to work and enjoy it.''
 &UR; 2. GIVE IT TIME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most major hits _ including ``M*A*S*H,'' ``Cheers'' and
``Seinfeld'' _ struggled for a full season or longer to build a
decent following.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raymond'' is another classic example. Three years ago, it
debuted to dismal ratings on Friday nights, lost among a lot of
fluffy TGIF fare. But the network gave it time to blossom, and by
the end of its second season the show was a top-20 hit. Last year
it broke the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that first season turned out to be a blessing in
disguise,'' star Ray Romano says. ``We were still feeling our way
around and finding out who the characters were _ it was like
practice for us. By the time we got to Mondays, we were in a
groove.'' &QL; 
 &UR; 3. KEEP IT REAL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For all her crazy antics, Lucy was real. For all its show-biz
sophistication, so was ``The Dick Van Dyke Show.'' Likewise, head
writer/show runner Phil Rosenthal sees that ``Raymond'' almost
never rings a false note.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like best about our show,'' says Patricia Heaton,
who plays Ray's feisty wife, Debra, ``is that it doesn't have a
gimmick. It's not just line-line-joke, line-line-joke. The humor
comes out of genuine, believable relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil Rosenthal has an amazing ability to keep it honest,''
Garrett adds. ``He never pushes a joke, never does anything hokey.
He knows better than anyone how to tune into family dynamics.
That's really his thing _ he writes life.''
 &UR; 4. WRITE WHAT YOU KNOW &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carl Reiner began each script session for ``The Dick Van Dyke
Show'' by asking the writers what had happened at home the previous
weekend. Rosenthal calls that the greatest lesson he ever had in
running a sitcom: The best comedic moments are borne out of the
creators' own everyday lives.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ray Barone, Romano once toiled as a futon delivery man. He
and his wife, Anna, really do have twin sons and a daughter. His
real-life brother is a New York cop, his dad says ``Crap!'' just
the way Peter Boyle's Frank does, and Rosenthal's own mother is as
lovingly overbearing as Marie. &QL; 
 &UR; 5. KIDS SHOULD BE SEEN AND NOT HEARD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Newhart made a point of avoiding what he calls the ``Daddy
Stupid'' syndrome, realizing that sitcoms built around saucy kids
getting their hapless parents out of some weekly pickle have little
staying power.
</P>
<P>
   Like Newhart, Romano knows that adults tune in to watch other
adults in adult situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's a family show,'' he says, ``but it's not a `Full
House' kind of family show. It's a show about a family that's built
to appeal to adults by being a little edgy and a little quirky.''
 &UR; 6. PARK THE EGOS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nothing undoes a sitcom faster than a star who hogs the
spotlight _ just ask veterans of ``Roseanne,'' ``Cybill'' or
``Ellen.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, ``Frasier'' and ``Will &AMP; Grace'' work because
everybody _ producers, writers, actors, crew _ insists on pulling
together. ``Raymond,'' too, is blessed with tremendous team spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in having good hours and better food and a true
sense of friendship and family on the set,'' Rosenthal says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere on our show is so relaxed and generous that we
all appreciate what a tremendous thing we have,'' Heaton agrees.
 &UR; 7. LEARN FROM THE PROS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Transforming stand-up comics into solid sitcom actors isn't
easy, but it helps to surround them with seasoned professionals.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lesson Jerry Seinfeld learned well. Romano's still
learning _ but he's a crackerjack student, as is Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray and I both come from the world of stand-up,'' Garrett
says, ``where, if you don't hear laughs every 30 seconds, you think
you're dying out there. Watching and working with pros like Peter
and Doris has, I think, taught us to trust the silence. They've got
40 years in the business, so every week for us it's like going to
Comedy College.''
 &UR; 8. AVOID STEREOTYPES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sitcom songbook is filled with one-note sambas _ meddlesome
mothers, grumpy dads, stupid siblings, long-suffering wives.
They're all part of the ``Raymond'' mix, but there's a vital
difference: This ensemble has no second fiddles.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three seasons, Rosenthal, Romano and the other
writers have stretched real flesh over cardboard bones. A tender
vulnerability balances the brashness of Roberts' Marie. Beneath the
bluster of Boyle's Frank hides a caring grandpa who can't resist
sniffing his grandsons' heads. Garrett has transformed Robert from
a long-limbed loser into a sympathetic spokesman for all the
brothers and sisters who ever spent their lives coming in second.
</P>
<P>
   As for Heaton's Debra, Roberts is impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patricia's made her grow into the most full, deep, funny,
acerbic, edgy, fabulous, well-rounded human being,'' the veteran
actress says. ``And that's not easy to do. Most wives on TV are
just there to be a pretty little thing and feed the kids. But she's
done wonders with it.'HAVE A LIFE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Everybody on ``Raymond'' works hard, but they don't let
themselves become defined by their jobs or their celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a lot of personal drama on the show,'' Heaton
says, ``because we all respect the fact that we have other lives.
We come in, do our work, do our best and then everyone goes home to
their real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes for a very healthy set.''
 &UR; 10. MAKE IT TIMELESS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Topical humor is fine for ``Saturday Night Live'' and ``Mad
TV.'' But great sitcom writing transcends trendiness _ it's not
about haircuts or hemlines.
</P>
<P>
   An upcoming ``Raymond'' episode will focus on the Barones'
daughter getting burned in a ``Pokemon'' trading-card ripoff, but
such pop-culture references rarely surface on the show. Instead the
writers focus on slice-of-life situations that can stand the test
of time.
</P>
<P>
   That's why 30 years from now, when the average episode of
``Friends'' or ``Ally McBeal'' will look like little more than
retro chic, everybody will still love ``Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Everybody Loves Raymond,''
consult the CBS Website at www.cbs.com. And don't forget to visit
the New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
