<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9138 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-USAID-0921-C     09-20 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-USAID-0921-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH HIS COUNTRY IN TURMOIL, COLOMBIAN PRESIDENT STUMPS FOR AID
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ At the upscale Andino shopping center in this
capital's affluent northern district, you'd never know there's a
guerrilla war, a disturbing crime wave and a dire economic
recession gripping Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Giggling teenagers rush to the multi-screen cinema, where ``Ojos
Bien Cerrados'' _ ``Eyes Wide Shut'' _ is drawing heavy crowds.
Stylishly-dressed couples stroll the marbled hallways, dawdling at
European boutiques or grabbing a Wendy's hamburger in the sprawling
food court.
</P>
<P>
   But Colombia's troubles are visible just beneath the surface of
even this sheltered enclave. Armed security guards _ some with
German shepherds _ patrol the sidewalks, while hotel desk clerks
warn guests not to leave the exclusive district on foot.
</P>
<P>
   As Colombian President Andres Pastrana meets this week with U.N.
officials and U.S. President Bill Clinton in New York to discuss
strategies for salvaging his country, it's clear that 40 years of
guerrilla war, the endless battle against the drug lords, a crime
epidemic and the economic crisis have left many of this nation's of
38 million people exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana addressed the United Nations Monday, pushing a $3.5
billion plan of international aid _ including $500 million from the
United States _ to fight drugs and the leftist insurgency that have
left his nation reeling.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's middle class is fleeing the country, with hundreds
lining up each week at foreign embassies to apply for visas. Some
60,000 residents have emigrated legally so far this year, with U.S.
officials reporting 50,000 visa applications per month _ twice the
level of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate executives and the wealthy must hire bodyguards and
buy armored cars, as they have become kidnapping targets for both
guerrillas and criminals alike.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla war has uprooted hundreds of thousands of peasants
from the countryside, with many living in makeshift refugee camps.
Others flee to the cities, living in appalling slums and begging
for food.
</P>
<P>
   Residents here don't like to talk about the troubles, but some
admit the situation is extremely bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to find work here, and even if you can you may
not make enough to pay your rent,'' said Orlando Ordonez, 36, a
Bogota taxi driver. ``Many people want to leave. I know five or six
people who have left and more who want to but can't get papers.''
</P>
<P>
   An American who has lived here for four years with his Colombian
wife and young child plans to move to Florida. He likes the
country, but recently was robbed and beaten by six homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened in full view of a police station, and the police
did nothing,'' said the man, who insisted on anonymity out of fear
that kidnappers might target his relatives. ``Unemployment is so
high that people are desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   There is great frustration with the Colombian government.
Pastrana was elected last year after promising negotiations with
the leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, but no
substantive peace talks have begun. His approval ratings have
plummeted _ while a belief that the U.S. military will intervene
has grown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your government will send in troops,'' said Carlos Alzgate,
45, who was laid off recently from a government agency. ``I believe
you fear too much the conflict will spread to Panama and
Venezuela.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials adamantly deny the rumors, which have caused a
stir in the Latin American press. Only a few hundred U.S. troops
are currently in Colombia to help train police and soldiers, they
say.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, it seems clear that Colombia's future will be
filled with more uncertainty and probably more violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' said Ordonez. ``Our country is very beautiful.
But our situation is very complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
