<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9139 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     09-20 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDLIFE ROMANCE
</HEADLINE>
 
CREATOR OF `thirtysomething' AND `MY SO-CALLED LIFE' EXPLORES(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It could have come from some acerbic art film or romance novel,
or even from some Lionel Richie '80s pop tune about love, loss and
longing: ``How's it possible you might be who I need you to be?''
</P>
<P>
   But those words are uttered through sobs at the tail end of an
episode of ``Once and Again,'' as Lily Manning, harried mother and
divorcee played by the adorable Sela Ward, explains how she needs
the man she's falling for to provide a safe, soft landing.
</P>
<P>
   Scripted by writer/producer Marshall Herskovitz, that one line
is perhaps the sharpest example of the kind of unguarded
emotionalism at the heart of this new drama series. This show,
premiering on ABC Wednesday, prides itself on what TV usually feels
safer handling in sitcom form: the emotional ambivalence of new
love and fractured families.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why it's fair game to wonder whether ``Once and
Again,'' house-sitting for ``NYPD Blue'' until the cop drama
returns Nov. 9, stands a chance in a TV universe in which viewers
are more comfortable drawing life lessons from ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' wants to dissect modern life through the eyes
of single parents by focusing on a pair of 40-ish divorcees. On the
surface, they're incredibly good-looking and professionally
successful, but they're also terrified of considering their own
needs, of risking further upheaval in the lives of their children,
of throwing caution to the wind and pursuing a love do-over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're afraid,'' Rick, played by Billy Campbell, says to Lily
in Wednesday's opening episode, ``because you want more, not
because you deserve less.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick has been out of his marriage for three years, Lily
separated eight months from her husband of 16 years. They first eye
one another while behind the wheel of their respective SUVs,
sitting in the pick-up/drop-off lanes at their kids' high school. A
chance meeting leads to Rick calling Lily at her home, which
results in one of the many scenes that are subtle yet oh-so
significant.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the kitchen, Lily, phone in hand, is in the
crossfire of conversations among her two daughters and ex-husband,
her knees wobbling, her brow sweaty, her face pale. She literally
hangs up on Rick, only to call him moments later (and in private)
to accept a date.
</P>
<P>
   Ward and Campbell have turned in low-key but dead-on
performances modulated by their good looks, acting ability and
chemistry, and helped immensely by an understated tone, a delicate
pace, and writing that is thoughtful, witty and real.
</P>
<P>
   At a restaurant on their first date, Lily whips out a cell phone
connecting her to her kids at home. Smiling but slightly
embarrassed, she lays it on the table. ``I see you,'' Rick says,
bringing out his own, ``and I raise you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the kids. Lily's 9-year-old Zoe (Meredith Deane) hates the
possibility that her father, Jake (Jeffrey Nordling) can be
replaced. Fourteen-year-old Grace (Julia Whelan) is a bright,
sensitive girl with appearance issues: She fears she's overweight
(she isn't) and not pretty (she is). Lily's relationship doesn't
help her delicate psyche. Worse, she's hot for Rick's son,
16-year-old Eli (Shane West). ``Is he going to be, what, my
stepbrother?'' she wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   Rick and ex-wife Karen (Susanna Thompson) talk around Eli's
``problem'' of flunking courses. The problem is a learning
disability. Rick also has a 12-year-old daughter, Jessie, played by
Rachel Wood.
</P>
<P>
   This is enough for Lily, the more fearful of the two, to call
off their budding relationship, which leads to a climax that sets
up next week's episode. It's executed with such bittersweet
honesty, I would have been perfectly happy had the whole thing
simply ended right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' is the work of Herskovitz and partner Ed
Zwick, best known for their collaboration on ``thirtysomething''
and ``My So-Called Life.'' Both were powerfully subtle dramas
unafraid of showing characters as flawed, self-aware human beings,
and both were criticized profusely for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``thirtysomething,'' during its four-year run on ABC, was
branded as nothing more than an exploration of privileged,
narcissistic yuppies; ``My So-Called Life'' was hounded for its
overly dark treatment of the psyche of a teen-age girl.
</P>
<P>
   But despite its high media profile, ``thirtysomething'' never
achieved large-scale ratings success. ``My So-Called Life'' never
made it to a second season.
</P>
<P>
   Watching as ``Once and Again'' unfolds, you may get the sinking
feeling that this is simply too good to make it on network TV.
</P>
<P>
   I remember Herskovitz, after the death of ``Life,'' questioning
the sophistication of contemporary audiences _ wondering whether it
simply wasn't the right time for his series. Perhaps it is time,
particularly now that teen-age angst appears to be in.
</P>
<P>
   But my theory is that network programming has become so limited
and audiences so accustomed to not sitting up and paying attention
that a series asking you do so is doomed. Many viewers would rather
lean back and allow TV to wash over them with predictable
scenarios, to take them away from reality.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma for producers is to be authentic enough to
convincingly portray the perplexities of life, but not too
authentic, as that could undermine the entertainment element and
drive away viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Zwick and Herskovitz have a history of bravely taking on this
problem, and adding a degree of difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Once and Again,'' for instance, characters talk directly to
the camera, a technique that's being widely used this season but is
actually old hat for these guys. ``My So-Called Life's'' was
accompanied by a voice-over narration, a wonderful device that made
star Claire Danes a kind of on-the-scene analyst of her own life.
</P>
<P>
   The difference here is that Lily and Rick are shot separately in
black-and- white documentary format, explaining the emotions of the
current or previous scene.
</P>
<P>
   Laced with wry humor and heartfelt emotion, the device is
largely effective. One particularly apt interruption comes while
Rick is eyeing Lily from across the dinner table on their first
date. He's trying to be cool. To be calm. In control.
</P>
<P>
   Flash to Rick in black and white: ``Basically,'' he says,
giggling like a school boy, ``I spent the whole time trying NOT to
kiss her.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9140 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     09-20 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
