<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE SHOULD NEVER BE CLEMENCY FOR TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The series of apartment house bombings in Russia
terrorize the Russian people and alert Americans to the threats
facing them.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is quite stark: How can a democratic society
effectively combat terrorists while retaining the civil and
political rights that define its democracy? Russia and the United
States certainly differ in the quality, range and vitality of their
democratic institutions, but Russia is no longer the controlled
totalitarian society it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Having sustained bombings that have taken nearly 300 lives in a
small span of days, some Russians are waxing nostalgic for the good
old days of Soviet Communism, when a pervasive internal secret
police forestalled terrorists. Then it was doubtful that terrorists
would have even entertained blowing up apartment houses to kill
ordinary people in their sleep, given the forces of the state that
would be arrayed against them, unrestrained by legal niceties.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership of Russia today faces the awesome task of
reassuring its people and hunting down the terrorists, believed to
be Islamic fundamentalists from Chechnya in the Caucuses and their
Slav hirelings.
</P>
<P>
   Chechens living outside their homeland are beginning to pay the
price for the bloody depradations believed to have been committed
by their countrymen on behalf of winning independence for the
Islamic territories that are part of Russia. Police are examining
the residence permits of Chechens living in Moscow, using the
questionings as a form of harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Such police tactics invoke the notion of collective guilt, which
President Boris Yeltsin has warned against, and which is inimical
to the spirit of a working democracy.
</P>
<P>
   All this should be instructive to Americans, for we have faced
the same threat, now enhanced by the success of the terror
techniques in Russia. That terrorist accomplishment is likely to
inspire others with grievances against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Those who believe that America has been comparatively lucky so
far should keep in mind that the bombing of the federal building in
Oklahoma City killed 168 and injured nearly 700.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, the American people were confronted with two
terror acts committed by lone gunmen. In California, a terrorist
wanting to send ``a wake-up call to America to kill Jews'' wounded
three kids and two others at a Jewish community center before going
off to kill a postman because he was not white. In the Midwest,
another racist zealot murdered a black man and Korean man, and
wounded six Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1993 truck bomb assault on the World Trade Center, 1,000
were injured and five were killed, a small number compared to the
tens of thousands who worked or visited there and who could have
died had the circumstances of the explosion differed only a little.
Members of that conspiracy of Islamic militants were connected to a
foiled plot to blow up the United Nations among other targets and
assassinate an array of political personages.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the bombing of Fraunces Tavern in lower Manhattan by
the Puerto Rican FALN seeking to establish an independent socialist
regime killed four and injured 53.
</P>
<P>
   That is a sufficient, though far from complete, list of the
terrorist acts against Americans. We are especially mindful of the
Fraunces Tavern bombing a quarter of a century later because
President Clinton chose this, of all times, to give clemency to
convicted FALN members.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the massive difficulty a democratic government faces
overcoming terror, President Clinton's action was totally
wrongheaded. His rationale that the individuals involved were not
directly involved in an act that resulted in death is specious.
They were convicted of participating in the years' long conspiracy,
studded by repeated acts of violence, in which at least six people
died and nearly 200 were injured.
</P>
<P>
   If you are going to fight terrorists and retain democratic
norms, then the least you must do is punish the conspirators. In an
open society. the best possible dissuader available is the surety
of severe punishment. Tinker with that, and you go a long way
toward making the fight against terror even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Pardons or clemency should never be available to terrorists,
unless they were wrongfully convicted or they help to expose their
cohorts.
</P>
<P>
   The key threat to a democracy that wishes to remain one is
terrorists exploiting the legal protections of a system they are
striving to overthrow. To permit them to misuse these safeguards,
and thereby evade punishment, is to endanger democracy twice over.
</P>
<P>
   The FALN terrorized on behalf of Puerto Rican freedom, while the
people of Puerto Rico overwhelmingly rejected that notion at the
ballot box. Thus the FALN, a handful of zealots, was not merely
trying to bend the United States to its will. Through violence, it
also was trying to force the Puerto Rican people to support the
FALN program.
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeditor-at-large of the Albany, N.Y., Times
Union.)
</P>
</TEXT>
