<HEADER>
A9146 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DOCS-WAITING21-COX     09-20 1755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCS-WAITING21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The doctor is in .....so why are you still waiting? Why you
wait, and how long is too long
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Deborah Williams of Austell was already irritated by
the time she went to pay her doctor's receptionist for her annual
physical exam. She had spent more than two hours in the waiting
room. Then she sat in a paper gown in a cold examining room for
another half hour before actually seeing the doctor _ for a
20-minute checkup.
</P>
<P>
   But her irritation turned to rage when the receptionist casually
explained why Williams had waited so long: ``Oh, we forgot about
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 28, never went back. ``I didn't get my time's worth,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting is one of the top consumer complaints against doctors,
with many patients feeling medical offices are places Where Time
Stands Still.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors acknowledge that sometimes things get backed up. But
many say long waits are not their fault. Emergencies happen. And
most medical offices have to overbook _ like hairdressers, airlines
and auto mechanics _ to compensate for the many patients who are
woefully late or don't show up at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have a 20 percent no-show rate,'' said Dr. Bobby
Kaufmann, an Atlanta internist who works 12- hour days and will
personally apologize to a patient who's waited too long.
</P>
<P>
   But health-industry experts say that many problems could be
solved with minor changes in office procedures. In addition,
experts say patients can _ and should _ take steps themselves to
reduce waits, such as calling ahead to see if the doctor's running
late, scheduling appointments early in the day and complaining when
things go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem is many doctors are still incapable of
thinking of themselves as service providers,'' said Peter Gurney of
Service Intelligence, a Seattle-based firm that evaluates the
quality of customer service. ``Most of them want to explain to you
why things are the way they are, when they should be taking the
time to come up with creative solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Catherine Palmier, regional medical director for Aetna-US
Healthcare's Southeastern region, offered another explanation:
doctors often don't experience the problem first-hand when they
seek treatment. ``They're treated like celebrities'' by their own
doctors, she said. ``They rarely have to sit for long, so they have
no real life experience of what it's like for their own patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that this perennial sore point with patients is
increasingly getting doctors' attention _ because consumers are
more assertive and managed care companies are changing the way
doctors do business. HMOs and other managed care companies
typically bring in consultants, take patient surveys and make
covert field trips to determine patient satisfaction. And most
doctors now rely on managed care contracts for a t least half of
their business, according to the American Medical Association. So
physicians are more willing to learn new ways of business if it
means they can hold on to lucrative contracts with managed care
companies. In addition, some insurers offer bonuses to physicians
with high patient satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the time spent waiting is a key driver for
patient satisfaction,'' said Donna Deckard, director of health care
operations at the Georgia Region of Kaiser Permanente. ``So we have
put a lot of energy into this.''
</P>
<P>
   These trends are forcing changes in some pockets of medicine,
with waits being shorter, or at least, less painful.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, some medical clinics housed in malls equip their
patients with beepers so they can window-shop while they wait. In
Atlanta, a random survey of 20 physicians found about half of the
offices have recently re-arranged their waiting rooms, installed
aquariums and desks with dedicated phone lines, and stocked
children's waiting rooms with videos and new toys. At Atlanta
Plastic Surgery, for example, the waiting room is outfitted with
picture windows with a skyline view of Atlanta, an aviary and a
playhouse for children.
</P>
<P>
   Some offices have also restructured operations
behind-the-scenes. More office managers are now MBAs trained to
handle patient flow. Among strategies experts advise: attach
tickets to patient charts to track time snags, tie receptionist
bonuses to waiting-room management and offer long-waiting patients
vouchers for coffee, prescription discounts and parking.
</P>
<P>
   So how long should a patient have to wait? The answer depends on
whom you ask.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians see an average of about 25 patients a day, according
to one United Hospital Fund study _ a figure that's been rapidly
climbing in recent years also because of managed care. That allows
about 20 minutes per patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't wait any more than a half hour, '' said Mike
Donio of the People's Medical Society, a consumer advocacy group
based in Allentown, Penn. ``And if you've waited more than an hour,
you should walk out. And you should send them a bill for your
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Donio acknowledges there can be exceptions. Before a patient
storms out of an office, he or she should politely ask _ after 15
minutes _ for an explanation, Donio said. If the doctor was called
to an emergency, the patient should ask to be rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   But if delays are the result of a doctor ``running a cattle
chute,'' the patient has every right to be angry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Medical consultants agree. According to a 1997 survey in Medical
Economics, a trade journal for doctors, patients shouldn't have to
wait longer than 20 minutes. Similar results were found by the
American College of Family Physicians. But these recommendations
don't always match reality. And how much time patients spend
depends more on where they live in the United States and the type
of doctor they're seeing.
</P>
<P>
   One 1998 survey by National Research Corporation of Lincoln,
N.E. found women in Albany, N.Y., typically spend less than one
minute in their OB/GYN's waiting room. That compared with 25
minutes in Dayton, Ohio, and 10 minutes in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And consultants say surveys show patients can generally expect
to wait longer for specialists than general practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``A primary care physician tends to have more manageable
diseases, less stuff that's life-threatening,'' said Judy Bee, a
medical management consultant in Long Beach, Calif. ``Sometimes,
(specialists) are going to have to tell patients some pretty awful
news and answer a million questions, so time to time, you're going
to wait longer.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, it's unclear how long the average patient waits.
Kaiser reports that patient surveys show the average waiting time
for doctors in the company's regional network is 12 minutes in a
waiting room and no more than 8 minutes in an examining room.
</P>
<P>
   But variations between offices and clinics can be dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Washington, a 40-year-old father of two, said he has no
problem getting his children seen and treated within an hour. But
the East Point resident said when it comes to his own care, it's a
different story. Washington said he is so used to waiting, he
brings a book and a peanut butter-and-jelly sandwich to tide him
over.
</P>
<P>
   Also patients _ and insurance companies _ say they are seeing a
new trend of doctors shuffling customers out of the waiting room
quickly just to have them languish in an examining room.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Roberts, 39, said she waited with her husband, Jackie, in
an examining room last month for more than two hours. It was long
enough her husband had time to read all the magazines, get drinks
and ask the nurses (twice) what the hold-up was. In the end, the
physician apologized briefly for the wait and spent 10 minutes with
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was handled very badly,'' said Roberts of College
Park. ``It would have been much better if we had been informed
about what was going on and what choices we had.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   But waiting is often about more than time. What you're doing
while you're waiting may be more important than how long you wait,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Customer service consultants say no one does that better than
Disneyland where visitors may stand in hour-long lines for rides
that last for less than five minutes. The key, they say, is to keep
the customers busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can involve patients in something that distracts them,
the patients are a lot less aware of time and are far more
forgiving than if you just leave them there tapping their foot,''
said Shirley Miles-Watanab, who oversees the quality of customer
service at Virginia Mason Medical Center in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If patients are kept busy with something that interests them,
they tend to be much more, well, patient.
</P>
<P>
   And, they also are more satisfied with the visit if a medical
staff is a little proactive. For example, experts recommend staff
tell patients why the doctor is running late and offer to
reschedule. They also say the waiting room should be filled with
up-to-date magazines, television and even nooks with phones and
computer jacks so people can conduct business while they wait.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also recommend that patients who wait a long period of
time, ask the medical office to write off the cost of the visit,
complain to the doctor _ who might not be aware of the problem _ or
to the insurer. Or they can simply walk out and find another
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are getting more savvy about what they expect from a
doctor's office,'' said Marshall Franklin, administrator of Atlanta
Plastic Surgery, who once walked out himself after waiting more
than two hours for a physical exam. ``It used to be that the office
was run by the doctor's wife and scheduling problems were just a
fact of life. But those days are over.''
</P>
<P>
   TO AVOID WAITING
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Take the first appointment offered in the morning. That way,
you get to see the doctor before the day has become tangled with
problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Call before you leave home or your workplace for a doctor
visit _ like checking in on a traffic report _ to find out if the
doctor is running late. If so, reschedule or leave later.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Try to fill out any paperwork before you arrive, especially if
you're a new patient. Call and have the paperwork sent to your home
ahead of time. You don't want to miss your scheduled appointment
time because you're writing your health history or verifying health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
