<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ONCE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Once' an appealing look at love after 40
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I always had a map for my life,'' Rick Sammler (Billy
Campbell) says near the top of ``Once and Again,'' this season's
most affecting, most I-feel-your-pain new drama, which premieres
tonight at 10 on ABC. ``And now, it's like I walked off it
entirely. It's weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Masterfully navigating this off-the-map territory of divorced
40some-thing parents are creators Ed Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz,
who last guided us through the emotional, out-of-bounds landscapes
of suburban baby boomers in ``thirtysomething'' and ``My So-Called
Life.'' And while ``Once and Again'' will initially be thought of
as a kind of ``thirtysomething'' sequel, it's really more a
continuation of the too-brief ``My So-Called Life,'' with the focus
shifting slightly from the teens to the parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't they keep their private lives private, without
dragging innocent bystanders into it,'' the 14-year-old daughter of
Lily Manning (Sela Ward) says of her mother's maiden voyage into
post-separation dating.
</P>
<P>
   We soon learn that everyone's connected in today's family. The
parents are at the center of things here, but only as landmarks to
find our way through everyone else. Lily and Rick alternate between
the exhausting, super-adulthood of single parenthood, and the
giggly, bumbling second-adolescence of starting love lives all over
again.
</P>
<P>
   Lily has been separated for eight months and has yet to date;
Rick has been divorced three years, and started dating an
unsatisfying string of 25-year-olds almost from the moment he moved
into an apartment. Both carry the shell-shocked, hundred-yard stare
of that tribe out there connected by the trauma of failed
marriages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at me,'' Lily says to herself, in her SUV, as she waits
to pick up her kids. ``Other people seem safe. I look at their
faces and know that was once my face. I want to go back there.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no going back, of course, which gives this series the
sense of an adventure drama, an internal travelogue that's equal
parts discovery and hardship. These are people _ both the adults
and the kids _ who've been through enough to dispense with the
small talk; this isn't TV as escapism, but as a stark, often
unpretty mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' feels more accessible than Zwick and
Herskovitz's previous creations, which at times were overwhelmingly
dark or self-involved. Much of that has to do with the instant
likeability of Ward and Campbell. Their unloading on us feels less
like whining and more like the honest tribulations of old friends.
You want to pour them another cup of coffee; you don't have
anywhere better to go.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, especially, is virtually radiant with the inside-to-out
glow of a hard-won survivor. She's a beauty who barely notices her
surfaces anymore, which only makes them that much more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Her teenage daughter, Grace, is played by Julia Whelan with a
slightly frumpier intensity than Claire Danes portrayed the
teenaged Angela in ``My So-Called Life.'' Close your eyes, and her
voice is almost indistinguishable from Danes'.
</P>
<P>
   Other tricks that help open up this show, like the characters
talking in black-and-white to a therapist camera, indeed feel like
tricks _ like the overused conventions they are _ but their
familiarity also helps us get through the tough spots.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of those. This is a show about growing up,
whether you're already grown up or not. It asks us to grow up with
it. Tall order, but worth the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again''
</P>
<P>
   10 tonight on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
