<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LONG ARM OF THE TAX COLLECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The tax code has created more liars than the game
of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, your reward for effort, energy and thrift is
a big tax bill. That's your legacy if you're an American and,
especially, if you're a New Yorker _ that and the knowledge that
the only thing worse than paying taxes is the desperation of owning
nothing worth taxing. And, sure, it takes money to run a
government.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, though, the letter Don McKay received the other
day simply astonished him.
</P>
<P>
   It was from the New York State Deparment of Taxation and
Finance. It said that the department had reviewed a list of items
that Don McKay had declared at U.S. Customs as he'd reentered the
country from a trip abroad. It said that the State of New York knew
that he'd brought back a piece of jewelry for his wife and that the
value of the thing was $2,591.49. The letter informed Don McKay
that he owed the State of New York $207.31 in state use tax on the
purchase and $6.32 in interest for not coughing up the money within
20 days of his return from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   And, the letter said, Don McKay had better pay up _ right then
and there. Otherwise, the interest would shoot up to the level
charged on the Brooklyn docks by brawny guys named Lefty.
</P>
<P>
   Don McKay was astounded. It wasn't the $213.63 that troubled
him. He's chairman and CEO of Tougher Industries. That's a
mechanical construction business in suburban Albany that does
roughly $50 million a year and employs about 200 people. The
$213.63 tax payment represented more of an annoyance than a
hardship for him.
</P>
<P>
   What had Don McKay astounded was that he has railed for years
against the high taxes in New York, where he has lived for 31
years. He's right about that, too. New Yorkers rank No. 1 among
residents of the 50 states in combined per capita state and local
taxes, although New York is slightly below the middle of the pack
on state taxes alone. It's mainly the local taxes that kill New
Yorkers _ too many workers in too many tiny, outdated local
governments that suck our economic blood for no real purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But Don McKay has been going in and out of the country for
years, and he has been declaring overseas purchases at Customs for
years. Now he'd learned that, in addition to what you have to pay
the feds when you come back with stuff from abroad, the state also
can come and nail you for what amounts to a sales tax on stuff you
buy in, say, Greece.
</P>
<P>
   The letter Don McKay got explained that this tax dates back to
1965. It's imposed in addition to the duty imposed and paid to U.S.
Customs at the time of entry into the United States. The use tax is
payable within (20) twenty days.
</P>
<P>
   Don McKay sent New York state its check for $213.63. He also
sent a letter to the governor, the Assembly speaker and the State
Senate majority leader. He told them this story and said, ``You and
your legislature need to address concerns such as mine, enact a
responsible budget on time and make New York a desirable place to
live and work. You have a long way to go to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Don McKay is 68. He'll retire soon. He has to decide if he wants
to stay in New York, where tax collectors demand money on items on
which you already paid taxes somewhere else. One thing worries him
about moving out, though.
</P>
<P>
   New York might have an exit tax that nobody knows about.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Times Union, Box 15000,
Albany, N.Y. 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
