<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9153 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     09-20 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV22-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-FANGLED PROFANITY
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Wednesday, Sept. 22)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The subject of today's column is profanity, specifically such
words as %&AMP;(AT), !(NU)$&AMP;! and $&AMP;)!!.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, myself included, have noticed a lot of swearing
going on in the movies, on television and especially on the radio.
And it's not just football games or combat situations or lottery
drawings that provoke the bad language. Dirty words are flying out
of the mouths of men, women and children at a furious rate and for
no apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing, in a war movie, for a sergeant to order his men
to get their %&AMP;(AT) heads down. It is another thing, in a
lighthearted drama, for a kid to order his mom to pass the !(NU)$&AMP;!
salt.
</P>
<P>
   The result is not only a coarsening of the culture, but also a
devaluation of the swear words themselves. Cuss words, to be
effective, must be used sparingly, otherwise they lose their shock
value. If words like %&AMP;(AT), !(NU)$&AMP;! and $&AMP;)!! trip off peoples
tongues as lightly as words like ``bunny,'' ``cloud'' and
``rainbow,'' then what words are we to use when we whack ourselves
on the thumb with a hammer or three-putt from 5 feet?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, today's swear words and insults have lost their punch,
which is why I'm suggesting we replace our worn-out words with some
fresh and far more imaginative epitaphs found in the plays of the
world's most famous and talented potty-mouth, William Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   The Elizabethan style of profanity takes a little getting used
to, but with a little practice I think you'll find that it is as
fresh and lively as something can be that is 400 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, as you might expect, is a great help in generating
Shakespearean insults and tailoring them to your specific needs.
(Try http://www.randyworld.com/shakespeare/. There are lots of good
insults and there's even a wandering minstrel tootling in the
background.) For example, if your boss is giving you a hard time,
you might consider calling him or her a ``dankish, fat-kidneyed
horn-beast'' or, perhaps, a ``craven, hasty-witted hugger-mugger.''
</P>
<P>
   The boss, in turn, might respond by calling his or her employee
a ``saucy, rampallian foot-licker'' or (presumably) worse, an
``impertinent, pox-marked bum-bailey.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are plagued by unwanted house guests, as many of us in
Florida frequently are, you may drop this subtle hint from Henry V
the next time they ask to be driven to the beach: ``Thine face is
not worth sunburning.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempers often flare in restaurants, and Shakespeare thoughtfully
provides us with a variety of insults geared to the occasion. If
you are displeased with the service provided by your waiter or
waitress, you may wish to call him or her a ``mammering onion-eyed
ratsbane.''
</P>
<P>
   If, on the other hand, you have diligently served a customer
only to be stiffed on the tip, you would be perfectly within your
rights to refer to that customer as an ``artless, beef-witted
scut.''
</P>
<P>
   Fed up with double-talking politicians? Next time you feel like
sounding off, take a tip from Henry IV, part I and shout: ``You are
a shallow cowardly hind, and you lie!''
</P>
<P>
   Does the sight of an elderly person driving slow in the
left-hand lane drive you crazy? Don't insult your intelligence (or
ours) with a blast of the horn or a single-digit salute. Instead,
do what Hamlet would do. Roll down your window and shout: ``Thou
art open to incontinency!''
</P>
<P>
   If you happen to be the elderly person being insulted, then you
can respond with this line from Troilus and Cressida: ``Thou thing
of no bowels thou!'' though our highways would certainly be a lot
safer if everyone would just shut up and drive.
</P>
<P>
   If you disagree with the tone or content of this column, then
you might want to write me a nasty letter quoting Coriolanus: ``I
find the ass in compound with the major part of your syllables.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, be my guest. Just don't be surprised if I write back
and call you a ``weedy, guts-griping codpiece.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
