<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9155 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-20 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING TOO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-controlled Congress just can't leave
President Clinton alone.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan temptation to keep picking at him, as though he
were an ugly boil, is so overwhelming that GOP congressional
leaders have lost all sense of propriety and proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Their failure to impeach him should have beaten some common
sense into their heads, but instead it inflamed their frustration
and inflated their already overblown idea of their own power. Now
they are demanding that the president produce all White House
documents relating to his clemency for some aging, jailed Puerto
Rican militants and grovel before Congress for making the decision.
</P>
<P>
   This is pure politics, but it is stupid politics. And it is
definitely NOT the American way.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has no constitutional leg to stand on here. Article 2
of the Constitution clearly gives the president broad power ``to
grant reprieves and pardons for offenses against the United
States.'' This is solely the responsibility of the executive
branch. There's no mention of a legislative role at all, whether
oversight or authority to rescind or alter a presidential decision.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton quite properly responded by claiming executive
privilege and refusing to expose his confidential discussions on
the question to prying eyes on Capitol Hill. He said, in effect,
that the Republicans had no power to get into his head on this. It
is none of their business.
</P>
<P>
   Most presidents grant hundreds of pardons or other acts of
clemency during their terms of office, but only a few are
politically controversial. The most recent was President George
Bush's 1992 Christmas Eve pardon of former Secretary of Defense
Caspar Weinberger. He was about to stand trial on perjury charges
stemming from the covert arms-for-hostages swap with Iran and the
secret deal giving aid to the Nicaraguan contras.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had already lost his battle for re-election and could not
be punished again at the polls. So although some outraged
congressional Democrats threatened to hold hearings into the
Weinberger pardon, they never did. It was already old hat.
</P>
<P>
   The most politically unpalatable clemency decision of all time
was President Gerald Ford's 1974 blanket pardon of his disgraced
predecessor Richard Nixon two months after Nixon was forced from
office. Nixon thus escaped civil or criminal prosecution for his
role in the Watergate crimes, even though he had been named in
court as an ``unindicted co-conspirator'' and a contemporary Gallup
Poll showed that 56 percent of those surveyed felt Nixon should be
tried for possible criminal actions.
</P>
<P>
   The pardon contributed to Ford's defeat for re-election two
years later.
</P>
<P>
   The fierce political reaction was heightened by the fact that
Ford had indicated he would not pardon Nixon during the 1973 Senate
hearings on his nomination to become vice president. Ford's
credibility immediately plummeted in a swirl of speculation that he
had cut a secret deal with Nixon to get the second spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic-controlled Congress smelled an illegal bribe as
well as a hot issue since, with the vice presidency, then-Rep. Ford
got a bigger salary. Ford stonewalled House Judiciary Committee
requests for relevant records of his conversations with Nixon but
defused the criticism by volunteering to testify before his old
colleagues in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The committee was a pussycat, limiting Ford's time under
questioning and letting him testify without taking an oath. He
denied all, easily ducked the mostly soft-ball questions and left
bathed in a friendly glow. Bipartisanship was not entirely dead in
those days, as it is now.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley, running against Vice President Al Gore
for the 2000 Democratic presidential nomination, suggests wickedly
that Clinton should similarly testify on the Puerto Rican clemency
as ``the only way this is going to be put to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense. The politics of this comes nowhere near the high
stakes of the Nixon pardon. It has very short legs.
</P>
<P>
   The political issue is whether making a fuss over this will hurt
Hillary Clinton's New York Senate campaign. The idea is to make
Clinton appear soft toward terrorists. The jailed Puerto Rican
nationalists were members of FALN, a terrorist group, but as
individuals had not been convicted of any specific act harming
anyone. A large number of Puerto Rican voters live in Manhattan,
but they seem to be divided on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, is
huffing and puffing about sending subpoenas to Attorney General
Janet Reno and other administration officials to determine if any
laws were broken. He charges that proper administrative procedures
may have been sidestepped. What? Hatch is now the defender of
obscure bureaucratic rules?
</P>
<P>
   He is running for the Republican presidential nomination, which
makes this demand look even sillier than it would normally. Does he
want us to take him seriously or not?
</P>
<P>
   Hatch is down there in the dirty weeds with Rep. Dan Burton,
R-Ind., a House committee chairman who has vowed to get Clinton and
pursues the president without success for everything except getting
out of bed in the morning. Burton too is scattering subpoenas
everywhere, convinced that there is something wrong legally with
the clemency, if he could just figure out what.
</P>
<P>
   New York politicians may chew over the issue for a while. It's
their backyard. But Congress looks foolish (again), and President
Clinton will carry the day here (again.)
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
