<HEADER>
A9157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOOD-SCENE-COX     09-20 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-SCENE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Community pulls together as homes, lives devastated by flooding
 &HT;    By J. Eric Eckard and David Blount
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ When waters in Rocky Mount began to rise
this weekend, neighbor began helping neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard someone yelling for help, so I got up and saw the
water up to our house,'' said Moses Dickens, who stayed with his
72-year-old mother at Cowlick Creek behind the Weeks-Armstrong
public housing complex . ``I ran around and started banging on
people's doors, telling them to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite rising waters nearly 2 feet high in their yard, Dickens
and his mother, Carrie Dickens, managed to make it across the
street to a neighbor, whose home was on higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a river over here,'' Carrie Dickens said. ``Boats
came and got some people, but I walked out. It was up to my knees,
but I walked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Batts, another Overbrook Avenue resident, managed to
escape the rising creek before it came too far inside his home.
Batts, 73, and his 40-year-old son made their way through the
pouring rain and rushing floodwaters to a relative's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asleep, and the lady next door called me and said the
water was at my back door,'' Batts said. ``I got up and got out of
here. I'd never seen the water that close.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, James Taylor and his girlfriend escaped with their
7-month-old baby in tow just as floodwaters reached their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was banging on doors, trying to get people up and get people
out,'' Taylor said. ``We got our little baby and got out. We didn't
grab anything then, but we came back the next morning and got some
food, clothes and baby things.''
</P>
<P>
   The waters continued to rise though, and just about the entire
neighborhood was under water once the rains stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's ruined,'' Taylor said. ``The furniture's ruined;
the TV's blown; our clothes are ruined. We're calling around now,
trying to get some help.''
</P>
<P>
   Electricity remained off in that area until Monday, and many
people were trying to recover from their losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the people in here lost everything,'' said Moses Dickens.
``It's just a pitiful time.''
</P>
<P>
   As the waters continued to recede on Monday, the shock began to
sink in for the residents of the West Haven neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of trees now lie at the curb, toppled first by winds,
then cut by chain saws. Sawdust and pine straw covered the roads. A
tarp was placed across one roof damaged by a fallen pine. Some
lawns were immaculate as property owners carefully removed limbs
and other debris from their grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Power and tree removal crews delicately pulled electric poles
and trees away from one another. Streets were full of fallen
cables, and workers urged residents and bystanders to avoid the
downed lines.
</P>
<P>
   Deeper into the neighborhood, homes suffered more extensive
damage. The Tar River, once a scenic backdrop to the neighborhood,
became an intruder last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Judd Pierce, 16, waded into waist-deep water on Lafayette Circle
to retrieve what few possessions he could from his parents' home.
The family silverware was a top priority in the salvage mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty bad,'' Pierce said grimly. ``The floors are warped
out. Everything is still floating in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce and his parents were awakened by neighbors early Thursday
morning and warned of the rising waters. The family retreated to a
friend's home to ride out the worst of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's mother, Nancy, woke the rest of her family and threw on
clothes. Five minutes later, she took another look outside. Water
that had been in the yard minutes earlier already had found its way
into the sun room.
</P>
<P>
   Before the water began to recede, the Tar River was only 6
inches from the ceiling in the Pierces' home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like somebody has died,'' Nancy Pierce said, looking
back at the house. ``It's already started to lean, and I don't know
if we will ever be able to fix it. We might be bringing in a
bulldozer and just have it torn down.''
</P>
<P>
   George Valentine said the floods were unprecedented in West
Haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been here for 51 years,'' he said. ``The highest I had
ever seen it before was right after Hurricane Hazel. Even then, the
water never even got close to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charlie Godwin had to be evacuated by boat at 4 a.m. on
Thursday. ``The water was probably waist-deep,'' he said. ``I've
never seen anything like this. I'm not sure what we'll do now.''
</P>
<P>
   Families huddled at the edge of the receding waters and stared
at homes further down the street. Water lapped at the roof of a
home at the end of the block and some residents traveled the
streets in the only fitting means of transportation _ a bass boat.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Brewer offered what comfort she could to her friends.
Since Thursday, Brewer has washed several loads of laundry for
flood victims to provide clean clothes for those who lost their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone said they needed a little money, so I wrote them a
check. Someone else said they needed food, so I cooked them dinner.
I just wish someone else would tell me what I could do for them,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Don and Billie Stallings wandered through their home and
wondered when they would be able to move back in. While the power
was back on, the damage to their home was significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rode across that gate in a canoe,'' Don Stallings said,
pointing to a 6-foot gate at the back of his property. ``We got up
at 4 a.m. on Thursday, and the water was on the terrace. At 7 a.m.,
water was coming in the house. By 9 a.m., water was 2 feet high
inside. You read about it and hear about this kind of thing. Until
you actually see it, though, you can't be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Stallings tried to prepare for the flood. On Wednesday
afternoon, she was busy cooking food and making ice. But the floods
caught her by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready for everything except a flood,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pru Eatman was counting her blessings on Monday. Eatman's home
was just above the flooded area left by Floyd and became a
launching area for boats trying to rescue victims and survey
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary watching the water come up the street,'' she
said. ``All my friends down there are just devastated. I was so
lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Eric Eckard and David Blount write for The Daily Reflector,
Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
