<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETERMINED YOUNG GETS THE JOB DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Steve Young was a dead man walking. And throwing
touchdowns. And tossing out clever quips.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers quarterback looked up and down his body Sunday
evening, assessing the damage from a tumultuous 28-21 win over the
New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing is ... '' he said, glancing from torso to
toes, unable to choose from so many worthy, pain-filled candidates.
``... What is the worst thing?''
</P>
<P>
   He ultimately picked the welts and scratches all over him. He
blamed Candlestick's infield cutout and speculated that the rocky
surface helped Jeff Kent play second base a lot more than it helped
him play quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the Giants was a nice diversionary tactic. Young
would have done anything to obscure the fact that his
soon-to-be-38-year-old body had just been treated like a crash-test
dummy.
</P>
<P>
   To listen to him, you couldn't have guessed what he'd been
through. Actually, to watch him on the Niners' last drive, you
couldn't have guessed, either. It was as if there were two Steve
Youngs, the one who got no protection from his blockers, and the
one who wanted to protect them from the horrible truth and
consequences of their bad day at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Young No. 1 was the dead man.
</P>
<P>
   Young No. 2 was walking.
</P>
<P>
   Young No. 1 could barely stay dressed. He wore his shoulder pads
on his sleeve, because that's where the Saints put them.
</P>
<P>
   Young No. 2 had a bandage on his throwing hand after the game
and pretended it was routine.
</P>
<P>
   Young No. 1 was sacked five times and drilled to the ground 16
more. The TV crew started running the knockdown stats, as if this
were a boxing match.
</P>
<P>
   Young No. 2 said he'd had worse days. ``Let's look back,'' he
said with a grin that showed no pity for Young No. 1. Or, for that
matter, for the Young of 1996 and early 1997, the spindled and
mutilated years.
</P>
<P>
   Young No. 1 rushed plays all day, playing like a man in the face
of death. At the Saints' 3, he threw a pass to fullback Tommy
Vardell for a measly 1-yard gain while Terrell Owens stood
tantalizingly open in the end zone. The 49ers stalled at the 2 when
Young missed another open receiver and threw a quick, off-target
pass to Vardell.
</P>
<P>
   Young No. 2 was asked about that series, and didn't get annoyed
or defensive. He didn't point out that how distracting it was that
the Saints kept showing up in the backfield with him as if they
were invited guests. Or that they were always unfashionably early.
He just called neglecting Owens in the end zone ``a big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Young No. 1 took a helmet- to-helmet blow from blitzing New
Orleans safety Chris Hewitt and stayed prone for several long
seconds afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Young No. 2 stayed in the game, doubling over periodically, but
still driving the 49ers toward the tying touchdown with 2:03 left
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   After the touchdown, it was hard to tell which Young was
inhabiting his body. Maybe both personalities moved out. After all,
the accommodations had deteriorated dramatically in just a few
hours. The dilapidated quarterback went straight to the bench,
without even celebrating the touchdown. He slumped into a seat, his
head dangling forward. Trainer Lindsy McLean and team doctor James
Klint flanked him, talking, like contractors on a fixer-upper.
</P>
<P>
   Young finally got up and started walking, pacing, stretching his
arms. He pulled off his helmet, something he rarely does until he
is done playing for the day. He wiped off his head, then mopped up
the inside of the helmet. He had it back on when Lance Schulters
scored on a 64-yard interception return, giving the Niners the
lead. Young embraced Klint, leaning his fiberglass-encased head on
the doctor's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Young and Jerry Rice stood side by side on
the sideline, celebrating between themselves, the remains of a
dynasty watching a clock run down.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said that he praised Young's perseverance. The rest of the
conversation, he said, was largely unprintable. They were both
carried away. ``You can probably imagine,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't remember exactly what was said. But his memory, he
insisted, was intact. The hit by Hewitt had left him nauseated and
weary, but not concussed. ``Give me a test,'' he teased reporters
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   OK, were Klint and McLean giving him memory tests on the
sideline? ``No,'' he said. He raced over there only because he
needed to rest. ``I knew we might go into overtime,'' Young said,
``and I needed to build my energy back up.''
</P>
<P>
   That was No. 2, the determined denial-specialist talking. A week
ago, the same character emerged from a dreadful outing in
Jacksonville to promise better, to keep the Niners intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last week,'' Young said, ``I said: `Over my dead
body.''' And, even though he won't admit it, that's exactly how the
Niners won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
