<SLUG> BC-TV-ONCE-REVIEW-455&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORTYSOMETHING WITH SUV SEEKS SAME IN `ONCE AND AGAIN' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' feels like real life for someone in the big
four-oh range, though it features genetically enhanced actors.
</P>
<P>
   Sela Ward, who professes to being 43, and her co-star Billy
Campbell aren't exactly skirmishing with bulging waistlines,
thinning hair and wattling necks. Realism has its limits on
prime-time TV.
</P>
<P>
   But viewers who thought Marshall Herskovitz and Edward Zwick had
something to say to them with ``thirtysomething'' a decade ago
might experience the same flush of connection with ``Once and
Again.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABC romantic drama, produced by Herskovitz and Zwick,
premieres Tuesday in ``NYPD Blue's'' accustomed time slot. ABC's
game plan is a bit hazy, but ``Once and Again'' is supposed to
borrow the time period for seven weeks, then return to help fill
the ``Monday Night Football'' vacancy in January.
</P>
<P>
   But what if ``Once and Again'' clicks? Would ABC yank a budding
hit off the air?
</P>
<P>
   Network executives are paid huge sums to make decisions like
that. Then they're fired.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, ``Once and Again'' is my candidate for the year's best
new drama. It's quietly sexy. It's nuanced. It's well cast. It puts
genuine emotions on the table.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Once and Again'' has something most TV shows give up
without a fight: dignity.
</P>
<P>
   It's also very herskozwicky, meaning that maybe these people can
be too articulate and too self-reflective for the show's own good.
</P>
<P>
   Ward (``Sisters'') is Lily Manning, mother of two girls, 14 and
9. She's emphatically separated and well on her way to divorce.
Campbell (``The Rocketeer'') is Rick Sammler, the divorced father
of a boy and girl, 16 and 12. He's primed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a white suburban show, to be sure. She's a soccer mom; he's
a soccer dad. They meet when Lily's oldest daughter bruises herself
playing soccer.
</P>
<P>
   On their first date, their SUVs are parked side by side at the
restaurant. How perfect is that? On their second date, they're
close to being parked side by side themselves. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   This is the year of yapping to the camera, and ``Once and
Again'' is no exception. Sprinkled through the show are black and
white segments in which Lily and Rick talk about themselves, as if
being interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Am I happier now? I don't know. Ask me in another three
years. I always had a map for my life, where I was supposed to be
headed. And now it's like I've walked off it entirely. It's
weird.''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``I just don't know where I fit in my own life anymore, and
maybe I'm scared.''
</P>
<P>
   If I keep this up, I could talk myself into disliking ``Once and
Again.'' But the show plays better than it reads.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find yourself cheering for these two decent people to
take those revved-up sexual protons and build something lasting
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Also, to rip off their clothes and have sex like rutting
badgers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ Mike O'Malley has all the star power of sliced bologna, which
is one reason NBC's ``The Mike O'Malley Show,'' which also
premieres Tuesday, is one of the surer flops of the new season.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason deserves consideration: It's not funny.
</P>
<P>
   O`Malley, best known for his ultimate sports fan commercials on
ESPN, plays a 30-year-old bachelor in New Haven, Conn. He sets up
the show by sitting on his rooftop and talking directly to viewers
about life, love and the like.
</P>
<P>
   The show's main comic force is supposed to be Mark Rosenthal as
O'Malley's slacker roommate, Weasel. Ha ... ha.
</P>
<P>
   _ The other new series Tuesday night is ``Mission Hill,'' WB's
animated comedy from two former ``Simpsons'' producers, Bill Oakley
and Josh Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission Hill'' bills itself as the first animated show for and
about Gen-Xers. Who, frankly, deserve better.
</P>
<P>
   Andy French (voice of Wallace Langham) is a 24-year-old salesman
at Waterbed World. He'd rather be a cartoonist. He lives in a funky
inner-city loft with roomie Posie Tyler and his best friend Jim
Kuback.
</P>
<P>
   Two additions to the apartment propel Tuesday's pilot. They're
Andy's 17-year-old brother, Kevin, and the French family dog,
Stogie. The dog is alcoholic; the kid spends some time himself at
the porcelain throne.
</P>
<P>
   The animation style seems a throwback to the late '50s and early
'60s _ bright colors, geometric designs, a sort of ``Jetsons''
style to the human figures.
</P>
<P>
   But the animation is rarely used to advantage, to take stories
to the realm of the outlandish and even impossible, where live
action can't go.
</P>
<P>
   And the writing fizzles. I watched Tuesday's episode and tried
to contribute a giggle. No such luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
