<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ALCOHOL-FREE-WINE-750     09-20 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOL-FREE-WINE-750&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIPPERS DRINK UP ALCOHOL-FREE WINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TED APPEL   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Technology can perform modern miracles. It
can take the fat out of ice cream and potato chips. The caffeine
out of coffee. The calories out of Coca-Cola. And even the alcohol
out of wine.
</P>
<P>
   More and more health-conscious Americans are discovering the
technological marvel of alcohol-free wines, a small but growing
segment of the U.S. wine market.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol-free wines have been around for almost 25 years, but
many of the early brands were virtually undrinkable. Today, with
advances in winemaking techniques, vintners say they have
dramatically improved the quality of nonalcoholic wines.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake: Most wine lovers still won't confuse an
alcohol-free wine with the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't pretend to be a real wine. It doesn't have the body
and boldness, because the alcohol gives it that. But it has the
other characteristics of wine,'' said Lou Applebaum, brand manager
for Inglenook St. Regis, which introduced the first nonalcoholic
wine in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of alcohol-free wines are growing about 4 percent
annually, said Rob Celsi, brand manager for Sutter Home Fre, the
top-selling brand in the category. But the market is still a tiny
niche, accounting for less than 0.5 percent of the nation's wine
shipments. Last year, the Big Three makers of nonalcoholic wine _
Sutter Home, Ariel and Inglenook St. Regis _ sold a little over
500,000 cases.
</P>
<P>
   Demand is driven by affluent baby boomers, mostly women, who are
concerned about their health.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these consumers are wine drinkers who are temporarily
abstaining from alcohol for medical or social reasons, such as
pregnancy or being a designated driver. About half are people who
never drink alcohol, Applebaum said. Surveys by the Wine Market
Council estimate that 30 percent of U.S. adults _ or more than 43
million Americans _ do not drink any alcohol. However, some of
these people buy nonalcoholic wines to celebrate special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of alcohol-free wines spike over the holidays. Inglenook
St. Regis, for example, generates almost half of its annual sales
in the six-week period between Thanksgiving and New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The market for nonalcoholic wines did not start expanding until
the 1990s, when Mothers Against Drunk Driving and other groups
focused the nation's attention on alcohol-related problems in
society. Concerns about alcohol abuse created interest in
alternative beverages, prompting the beer industry to develop a new
line of alcohol-free beers. Noticing the trend, Sutter Home
introduced its nonalcoholic wine in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The problems of alcohol abuse may have driven consumers to
nonalcoholic wines in the early 1990s. But the opposite is true
today: Favorable publicity about the health benefits associated
with moderate consumption of wine is helping its clean and sober
cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of red wine soared in the United States after reports by
``60 Minutes'' on the ``French Paradox,'' which suggests that wine
is the reason the French have lower death rates from heart disease
than Americans, despite a similar diet of high-fat foods. Some
researchers believe that moderate consumption of alcohol _ whether
wine, beer or liquor _ leads to improved health. Other researchers
claim that antioxidants in wine _ with or without alcohol _ give it
an advantage over other alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have read about the French Paradox and the
heart-healthy aspects of wine,'' said Craig Rosser, marketing
director for Ariel Vineyards. Nonalcoholic wines provide a choice
for those who ``feel they are missing out because they don't drink
wine with alcohol,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, producers of alcohol-free wines still face hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in selling alcohol-free wines is not persuading
consumers to accept the concept, but rather teaching consumers to
find the products on store shelves, said Eileen Fredrikson, a San
Francisco wine industry analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The retailers don't know where to put it. Is it a wine? Does
it belong with juices? Does it belong with natural products? It's a
niche category, yes, but it is not one that has a uniform placement
in shops. So the consumer doesn't know where to look for it. There
is almost never anyone around to tell you where it is. You truly
have to know about the product and ask for it in many cases,''
Fredrikson said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, alcohol-free wines are more expensive than other
alternative beverages, such as sparkling water or apple cider.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And for good reason. It is not easy making alcohol-free wines.
</P>
<P>
   It all starts with wine made the traditional way: Grapes are
crushed to make juice and then fermented into wine, a process that
transforms sugar into alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, vintners cooked the wine until the alcohol
evaporated. ``It made for a nasty product,'' Celsi said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last decade, vintners have used technology to improve
the wines' complexity and mouth-feel.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel and Inglenook St. Regis remove the alcohol from their
wines through a process called ``reverse osmosis.'' Essentially,
the alcohol is filtered out by squeezing wine through a membrane
with tiny pores. Alcohol and water, which have the smallest
molecules, pass through the membrane and leave behind a syrupy wine
concentrate. Water is then added back to the concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter Home uses a different technology, created in Australia:
the ``spinning cone column,'' a 13-foot centrifugal chamber. Wine
is poured into the top of the chamber and flows over a series of
cones. In the first step, nitrogen is used to extract the aroma and
flavor components of wine. The process is then repeated at a higher
temperature to remove the alcohol. Finally, the aroma and flavor
components are reintroduced to the wine, and then the liquid is
blended with unfermented grape juice.
</P>
<P>
   All the nonalcoholic wines have less than 0.5 percent alcohol,
by volume. As a result, they have less than half the calories of a
regular glass of wine.
</P>
<P>
   How do they taste? A panel of wine experts assembled by The
Press Democrat gave mixed reviews to 16 alcohol-free wines.
</P>
<P>
   The panel awarded the highest marks to the most simple _ and
least expensive _ alcohol-free wines. Inglenook St. Regis White
Zinfandel, Ariel Blanc and Sutter Home Fre Premium White received
the best ratings for their respective brands. Most cost under $5 a
bottle, and all should be served ice-cold, the panelists said. Some
of the higher-priced wines _ which included vintage-dated,
appellation wines aged in oak barrels _ disappointed the panel.
</P>
<P>
   None of the alcohol-free wines, however, tasted like a
full-fledged varietal. Still, vintners say the quality of
alcohol-free wines has improved significantly in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat of Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
