u e BC-TV-ONCE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-20 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ONCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONCE AND AGAIN': HOW TO FIND NEW LOVE AND TROUBLE AFTER 40 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Once and Again,'' the upscale, divorced parents who fall
for each other with a few swoony glances while dropping their
children off at school seem to have ``insufferable navel-gazer''
written all over them. That may be what you expect from Edward
Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz, the creators of ``Thirtysomething''
and ``My So-Called Life.'' Once more they are determined to tap
into a generational moment, this time with people in their 40s in
their second go-round of looking for serious love.
</P>
<P>
   But in a rare instance of television reflecting life, here the
presence of children makes the parents less self-absorbed than they
might have been, whether they like it or not. Lily (Sela Ward) and
Rick (Billy Campbell) each have two children and a cranky
ex-spouse, characters who add a range and texture of realism
missing from the creators' previous shows. This ABC series is as
much about divorce and parents struggling with adolescent
children's sexuality as it is about their trying to find a love
life of their own. In a television landscape dominated by young
singles, ``Once and Again'' comes as a mature surprise. Sharply
written, with a bite, it is also one of the new season's most
polished, accomplished series.
</P>
<P>
   The lead actors help the series over the few patches that
threaten to become too cute or precious. Rick, an architect who has
been divorced for three years, has a teen-age son and a younger
daughter. Campbell is the lesser known of the stars. (He was in the
film ``The Rocketeer.'') He has an understated style that is
effective here, especially in the sequences that sound most
annoying: black-and-white segments in which the characters reveal
their thoughts to the camera.
</P>
<P>
   His first monologue sets the tone for the series, one that is
direct and free of self-pity. ``By the time you get divorced,
there's almost some relief in accepting that you've failed,'' he
says. ``You're worthless; you've destroyed your kids' lives. But
there they are, they still need you.'' And Rick is a believably
imperfect father, reluctant to acknowledge that his handsome
football hero son is failing two subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ward is better known (notably from the series ``Sisters'')
and has the tougher job. Lily is recently divorced, with a daughter
in high school and another in grammar school. She also owns a
bookstore with her sister, though that information doesn't creep in
until next week. Stereotypically, when Rick calls for a date, she
has a dish towel slung over her shoulder and can barely hear above
the noise of family squabbling in her kitchen. Sometimes Lily has a
single tear brimming. So far Ms. Ward has just managed to keep the
portrayal from becoming too mannered and the character from
crossing the line into cliche.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that is thanks to the series' most realistic and
compelling character, Lily's adolescent daughter, Grace (played
convincingly by Julia Whelan). In denial, Lily refuses to
acknowledge that her daughter is unpopular and has a weight
problem. Grace is distraught at the possibility that her mother
might have sex, especially with the father of a good-looking guy at
her school. When the children and their father return to Lily's
house, they find her energetically tangled with Rick on the couch.
``It's not OK,'' Grace screams, and runs to her room in horror.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue is often at its best and toughest when it involves
the teen-age characters. ``My mother has a date tonight,'' Grace
forlornly tells a girlfriend as they walk through the hall to
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom dates like six times a week,'' the friend says.
``They're all fat and gross.''
</P>
<P>
   Lily is saddled with too many strained speeches, including one
in which she tearfully tells Grace, ``Fear can be your friend.''
But however pompous or gaga about each other Rick and Lily become,
their former spouses add a bitter tone that cuts through a lot of
sweetness. Jake, Lily's ex-husband, says of their older daughter's
problems: ``She's fine when she's with me. Maybe it's you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' will run in its current time slot for seven
weeks, before ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' returns. If the show succeeds, the
plan is for it to disappear after that and return on Mondays in
January after football. That leaves plenty of time for viewers to
become engrossed in the complications of a love affair that ripples
realistically through two families.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ONCE AND AGAIN'
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Tuesday at 10 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Herskovitz and Edward Zwick, executive producers and
creators; directed by Herskovitz; Peter Schindler, producer; Debra
Petro-Lovatelli, co-producer. A production of the Bedford Falls
Company in association with Touchstone Television.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Sela Ward (Lily Manning), Billy Campbell (Rick Sammler),
Julia Whelan (Grace Manning), Shane West (Eli Sammler), Meredith
Deane (Zoe Manning), Evan Rachel Wood (Jessie Sammler) and Jeffrey
Nordling (Jake Manning).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
