<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9165 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      09-20 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Sept. 21 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan. (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ASSEMBLY (United Nations) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan
sounds a warning to a frequently paralyzed Security Council, saying
it must act faster and more effectively to meet the challenge of a
world engulfed in civil wars that quickly descend into the
slaughter of helpless civilian populations. Speaking to the General
Assembly the day before President Clinton is scheduled to address
world leaders here, Annan did not single out the United States or
any other major nation, but his unusually strong criticism of the
council's initial failures to deal with genocide in Rwanda and 1994
and to agree on responding to Serbian atrocities in Kosovo over the
last year pointed obliquely at U.S. policy decisions. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-RDP (Dili, East Timor) _ The vanguard of an international
peacekeeping force stakes its claim to this silent and broken town,
watched warily by clusters of refugees, sullen Indonesian troops
and small, angry groups of militiamen. There was no resistance _
but no welcome _ for the peacekeepers, who arrived with all the
firepower and high technology of modern war. There is no peace to
keep: East Timor's tiny capital is a dead city, burned, looted,
evacuated. By Seth Mydans. 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-CAROLINA (Tarboro, N.C.) _ There are 10,000 people in
shelters in North Carolina and two thousand of them are being
housed in a high school gymnasium here where there is no running
water. Most of the people are from tiny village of Princeville,
population 2,000. Princeville was the first town in America
chartered by feed slaves and now is completely underwater. Not even
rooftops can be seen from helicopters overhead and there is no way
in or out by road. Signs of devastation are everywhere in North
Carolina. But even more rain is expected Monday night and this may
worsen flooding on eastern North Carolina rivers. At least 23
people were confirmed dead after 20 inches of rain inundated North
Carolina's coastal plain. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-POLICE (Trenton, N.J.) _ After months of delays in her
attempt to address the racial discrimination problems plaguing the
New Jersey State Police, Gov. Christie Whitman nominates New York
FBI supervisor Carson Dunbar to become the next State Police
superintendent and reform the culture of a force with a long
pattern of mistreating minority motorists and black and Latino
troopers. Dunbar, who served briefly as a New Jersey trooper before
joining the FBI 22 years ago, is expected to win easy confirmation
in the state Senate. By David Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   JONES-PLAGIARISM (New York) _ Atlantic Monthly Press has halted
the October publication of a biography of John Paul Jones by the
prolific Scottish author James Mackay, pending resolution of
questions about similarities to the last major Jones biography,
published in 1959 by the eminent American historian Samuel Eliot
Morison. By Ralph Blumenthal. 2,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   Editors: at this time, the Times is using a wire story for the
earthquake in Taiwan.
</P>
