u a BC-FLOOD-CLINTON-COX     09-20 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-CLINTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton tours flood-ravaged towns in North Carolina
 &HT;    By Viola Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARBORO. N.C. _ Tears flowed down the face of Princeville
resident Patricia Woodard as she listened to remarks by President
Clinton during his visit to Edgecombe County Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard, like more than 4,000 other Edgecombe County residents,
stood near the corner of Main and Church streets as Clinton, Gov.
James B. Hunt and other state and federal officials toured the
flooded aftermath of Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all gone,'' Woodard said. ``I don't know what we'll do.
But I'm just happy we were able to get out. I'm glad (Clinton)
came, and I hope he does what he said he's going to do, especially
about getting housing. The shelter is filling up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton promised Edgecombe County residents the federal
government would stand by them until they got back on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been profoundly impressed by the family spirit of the
people of Edgecombe County,'' Clinton said. ``I hope all of you
will keep that attitude. I can only imagine how many of you feel,
spending the night in these shelters with small children. We have
to wait for waters to go down and make sure that the (drinking)
water is not contaminated. Keep up the good work. We're going to
stay with you as long as it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton toured the damaged areas of Tarboro, Princeville and
Greenville by air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much bigger than Grand Forks, South Dakota,'' he told
officials in remarks later released to the press. ``I bet when the
cost comes in, it will be as much as the Mississippi Flood. It was
beyond what we imagined. All of the stuff you see floating here and
on the video _ it was beyond the 500-year flood plain. This is
literally more than you would anticipate less than once every 500
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton outlined some of the initiatives going on
to help residents who have been devastated by the flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I flew over the town of Princeville and saw the houses and
businesses still buried under water, I'm just thankful that so many
lives were saved,'' Clinton said. ``I'll do my best to do what
Congresswoman Eva Clayton has asked for so I don't have to have her
camped out on the White House lawn. When she wants something for
you, she comes right to the White House and tells me about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by residents and downtown merchants, Clinton said,
``One thing I've learned is that no matter how much television
shows, it does not do justice to what's really happening because it
can't show what's going on inside the people. I know it's hard to
have to take your kids to a shelter. I know it's hard for folks who
have been farmers for 40 years to watch a crop totally destroyed
and wonder if they will be able to buy seed again.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has worked hard to build a good economy
and take care of health care needs, Clinton said. But once in a
while something happens that makes government officials understand
they are not in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it can happen to all of us,'' Clinton said. ``All of
our prayers and thoughts are with you, but we all have a
responsibility as part of the American family to help get you back
on your feet. Too many people have died, and there are still too
many unaccounted for. With all of the loss, we thank God people are
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noticed a minister in the audience wearing a shirt that
said, ``Too blessed to be stressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's keep that attitude,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Viola Harris writes for The Rocky Mount Telegram, Rocky Mount,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
