<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES FACE SCRUTINY OVER WHEELCHAIR POLICIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rights of disabled airline travelers under federal laws are
getting renewed attention from the Department of Transportation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In mid-August the department served Continental Airlines with a
complaint saying that the airline had treated three wheelchair
passengers illegally, and seeking fines of $250,000. Action against
other airlines is likely soon, according to Nancy E. McFadden,
general counsel in the department. The department has been looking
into the complaint letters it has received, she said, and is
preparing much broader moves against five airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McFadden would not identify the airlines, but the department
has begun breaking down by airline its monthly tabulation of
complaint letters from disabled passengers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The initial tabulation, covering January through June 1999,
showed that United led the list, with 37 letters. Then came US
Airways with 31, American and Delta with 23 each, and Northwest
with 19. The other domestic airlines, and foreign carriers, were in
single digits; Continental had 8. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McFadden said that Transportation Secretary Rodney E.
Slater, who took over the department on Feb. 14, 1997, has made
disability issues a priority. ``It is our strong belief that
complaints from the disabled are civil rights complaints and should
be treated differently from the others,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a separate step at the end of August, the department proposed
a new rule requiring that boarding lifts be provided for mid-sized
planes (those with 31 or more seats) if level-entry boarding or
ramps were not otherwise available. This would mean that wheelchair
users would not need to be carried up steps by airline employees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And under a new rule that recently took effect, airlines that
damage or lose wheelchairs may no longer limit their liability to
$2,500. The rule uncapping such damages became final on Aug. 2, the
department said. The previous limit was not high enough to cover
many electric wheelchairs.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The case against Continental began when Paul Tobin, Angelo
Bianco and Gerard M. Kelly reported that they were not able to get
their wheelchairs stored in cabins, as the law required, instead of
with the luggage, did not get seats in rows with movable armrests
and were bumped while being placed in seats with fixed armrests,
were stranded aboard long after other passengers had debarked or
were not able to get appropriate answers to their complaints.
</P>
<P>
   They were represented by the Eastern Paralyzed Veterans
Association, an advocacy group that has played a major role in
getting lift-equipped buses onto municipal routes. In 1998, it
filed formal charges for its three clients, saying Continental
violated the Air Carrier Access Act. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last month, after a preliminary investigation, Samuel
Podberesky, assistant general counsel for aviation enforcement at
the department, told the airline that his office found that the
complaints, and others it uncovered, were probably valid and that
it was asking an administrative law judge to hold a hearing and
levy fines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Continental, in response, unequivocally denies that it
discriminated against people with disabilities. Noting that the
department had found Continental's training of employees in dealing
with disabled passengers to be adequate, the airline said
``occasional inadvertent mistakes by an individual do not
constitute discrimination on the part of the corporation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In July the department's monthly summary of flight delays, the
Air Travel Consumer Report, added its breakout of disabled
passengers' complaint letters by airline. Ms. McFadden said that
this step was taken in response to a suggestion by the National
Council on Disability, an independent government agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the first six months of the year, the department received 192
such letters citing United States and foreign lines. The figures
for the month of July, published Sept. 8, showed 42 disability
complaints for the major domestic airlines, with US Airways getting
9, followed by United with 7, Delta with 6, American and Northwest
with 4 each, and the others with fewer or none. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The totals represent only complaints sent to the Department of
Transportation by consumers, unlike reports on lost baggage and
overbooking, data that the airlines are required to pass on to the
government. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Air Travel Consumer Report can be found at
www.dot.gov/airconsumer on the Web. Single copies of a monthly
report can be ordered at (202) 366-2220. Requests can also be sent
to Aviation Enforcement and Proceedings, Department of
Transportation, 400 Seventh Street S.W., C-75, Room 4107,
Washington, D.C. 20590. This address can also be used for
complaints.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern Paralyzed Veterans Association, 75-20 Astoria
Boulevard, Jackson Heights, N.Y. 11370, (718) 803-3782, has
published a free booklet, ``Accessible Air Travel,'' summarizing
provisions of the 1986 law; a laminated pocket summary is being
prepared. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its notice of proposed rule-making on provision of lifts for
medium-sized planes, the department said it would improve the
comfort, safety and dignity of disabled passengers because airlines
are now permitted to carry wheelchair passenger up steps if no jet
bridge is available.
</P>
<P>
   The department said that if airlines and airports cooperated,
the proposed rule would be inexpensive to enforce, since the lifts
now required for planes with 19 to 30 seats could be used. People
who want to comment on this proposal have until Nov. 26 to do so to
the address above. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
