<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 26) 
(jt) 
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paris Bike Tours
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it possible to sign up for a bicycle tour in and around
Paris in October, or is this only an option in the summer? _ Brian
M. Jameson, Columbus, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   A. Most of the companies that organize guided bicycle tours in
Paris offer them through Oct. 31, so you'll just make it. Here are
a few companies you might try:
</P>
<P>
   From its headquarters at 37 Boulevard Bourdon, near the
Bastille, Paris a Velo, C'est Sympa runs daily guided tours in
English from early March through the end of October and continues
throughout the year on a more limited basis. Most tours last about
three hours and vary in levels of difficulty, from the gentle
nine-mile Heart of Paris tour _ an exploration of the center of the
city from the Jewish quarter and the Louvre to the Ile de la Cite _
to the more intensive 16-mile Paris Contrast, which focuses on the
northern, hillier neighborhoods of the city. Dawn and early evening
tours are also available. Daytime tours cost $27 (calculated at the
rate of 6.2 francs to the dollar); evening tours are $31. Full-day
trips to Versailles or elsewhere in the surrounding countryside are
also options and cost $48. All prices include bike rental. Take
your own picnic for the full-day tour. Information: (33-1)
48.87.60.01.
</P>
<P>
   Maison Rue Libre, in the Forum des Halles, offers a variety of
tours through the end of October, after which it caters to groups
of at least three people by reservation only. The
one-and-a-half-hour Relaxed Visits tour explores the Latin Quarter,
the financial district, the Roman Baths of Cluny and the Place des
Vosges and other sites. Three-hour tours range in theme from
Mysterious Paris and Green Paris to Paris by Night. There's even a
Market Shopping Paris tour on Saturday and Sunday mornings.
Ninety-minute tours cost $17; the three-hour trips are $27, with a
discount for children under 12 and groups of more than 10 people.
Prices include bike rental. All reservations should be made at
least 24 hours before the tour and are available in several
languages, including English. Maison Rue Libre also rents bikes to
individuals throughout the year. On weekends from March 1 to Oct.
31, the company rents bicycles from buses situated throughout
Paris. For information call (33-1) 53.46.43.77. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Decathlon, a chain of sporting goods stores, rents bikes for $10
to $21 a day. Each additional day costs about half of the first
day's price. There are four stores in Paris and in major
metropolitan areas throughout France. The most centrally situated
Decathlon is at 17 Boulevard de la Madeleine in the first
arrondissement (33-1) 55.35.97.55.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller cycling stores in Paris, like Velo Bastille (33-1)
48.87.60.80; Paris Velo, (33-1) 43.37.59.22; and Maison du Velo
(33-1) 42.81.24.72; also rent out bikes for an average of $13 a
day.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking Portuguese in Rio
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where can I take Portuguese lessons in Rio? _ Hortense Bilow,
Harrisburg, Pa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your possibilities range from single classes to intensive,
multi-week courses. Here are three examples:
</P>
<P>
   Feedback, a language school with two branches _ one downtown at
74 Rua da Quitanda, the other at 35 Rua Farme de Amoedo in Ipanema
_ offers Portuguese lessons on an individual basis. Each one-hour
lesson costs $19 in the morning and $16 in the afternoon, and
students can start at any time of the year and choose the number of
days or weeks they want to attend. Information: (55-21) 552-0598
(Ipanema), (55-21) 221-1863 (downtown). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Copacabana, the Brazil-United States Institute offers
beginning, intermediate and advanced Portuguese classes. Each level
costs $233 and takes five weeks, with two hours of daily lessons
including conversation, grammar and reading. The classes are held
at 690 Avenida Copacabana. Information: (55-21) 548-8332. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic University, at 225 Rua Marques de Sao Vicente, in
Rio's Gavea district, offers a more extensive, five-level series of
classes of one semester each. Classes are held three times a week
and run from March to June or August to early December. Tuition for
a semester is $360. Information: (55-21) 529-9209.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's Eresma Valley Sites
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you tell me something about a historic monastery and some
other sites in the Eresma Valley near Segovia? I am finding very
little about this area in guidebooks. _ Elizabeth Wassman, San
Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. The Eresma River starts in the Sierra de Guadarrama, runs
downhill past La Granja and along the northern edge of Segovia, and
continues a long northwesterly route through pine forests and grain
fields before ending in the Duero River. Situated near the river,
and just outside the old walled section of Segovia but still within
city limits, are four notable sites within a 30-minute walk
starting from the Roman aqueduct along Santa Lucia Street.
</P>
<P>
   The first site is the Casa de la Moneda, the former Royal Mint
that began operations in the 16th century and continued for three
centuries, minting some of the gold and silver brought back from
Spain's New World colonies. The stone mint is closed and can be
seen only from the outside, but a restoration is planned for the
coming years.
</P>
<P>
   A bit farther down the road, which has now become a firm dirt
path, is the large El Parral Monastery, founded by King Enrique IV
in 1447, and paid for by the Marques de Villena, a 15th-century
noble who is buried there along with his wife and at least one
child. The monastery's principal stone church _ with richly carved
doors and Renaissance details _ celebrates Mass with Gregorian
chants every Sunday. It is open daily; hours vary.
</P>
<P>
   From there, return to the mint and turn onto a marked trail
along the Eresma River to reach the small San Marcos neighborhood
that contains La Vera Cruz Church, a 13th-century Romanesque
polygonal edifice, which is believed to have been built for the
Knights Templar. Open daily, except Monday; hours vary.
</P>
<P>
   In the same neighborhood, a few minutes away, is the Carmelitas
Descalzos Convent, whose principal church is from the 16th century.
Torquemada, of Inquisition notoriety, once was the prior there and
Pope John Paul II visited it in 1982. The tomb of St. John of the
Cross is at the site. It, too, is open daily.
</P>
<P>
   The Segovia Provincial Tourist Office, at 1 Plaza del Azoguejo,
has details about each site; (34 921) 462-906.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
