<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Egalite at Last On Paris Trains &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may have gone unnoticed by many tourists on their way to
Versailles, Fontainebleau or Disneyland Paris, but until Sept. 1
Paris' suburban trains still had first-class cars, eight years
after the Paris Metro had done away with its own class system. But
no longer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the Transport Ministry and several citizens'
rights groups, the Paris Metro company and the national railway
company, which together manage suburban train service, decided to
eliminate the first-class option this month. The change, which
transportation officials say affects less than 3 percent of
passengers, has increased the capacity of suburban trains by 10
percent. This is because the first-class cars were nearly empty,
with few people actually paying the more than 50 percent markup. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cartier Exhibition Goes to Chicago &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Cartier 1900-1939,'' an exhibition celebrating the jewelry
company's centennial, makes an appearance at the Field Museum in
Chicago this fall. More than 200 objects are included in the
exhibition, which was organized by the Metropolitan Museum of Art
and the British Museum. The examples of Cartier's work draw from
nature, architecture and such far-flung inspirations as maharajahs,
Tutankhamen's tomb, and the ornate trinkets of the czars. Several
pieces are on loan from museums in Paris and Geneva. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the art world embraced modernism, the young Louis Cartier, a
partner in his father's House of Cartier, developed techniques that
brought a new look to ornamentation. A dragonfly of jewels and
platinum, for example, appears to hover weightlessly above its
wearer; a diamond and ruby tiara, in contrast, gets texture and
dimension from a black steel setting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cartier is considered the first jeweler to have shifted the
focus on his craft from luxury to design, but the show is not
without opulence. No precious material goes unrepresented, and
several pieces _ made specifically for heiresses, movie stars and
other modern royals _ are unmistakably extravagant. Design sketches
and original plaster molds are also on view. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show opens Saturday, with two days of related activities,
and continues until Jan. 16 at the Field Museum, 1400 South Lake
Shore Drive, at Roosevelt Road. For details: (312) 922-9410 or
www.fmnh.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Caitlin Lovinger &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New Hotel Near the Forbidden City &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shangri-La Hotels and Resorts, a Hong Kong company, has opened
its fourth hotel in Beijing and its 15th in China: the 487-room
Kerry Center Hotel in the heart of the Chaoyang Commercial
District, near the Forbidden City, Tiananmen Square and the Great
Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel has a sports and recreation center with an outdoor
jogging and roller track, indoor tennis courts, a 114-foot heated
lap pool and full gym. Three restaurants offer Cantonese and
regional specialties and international fare. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Room rates begin at $210 a night, but through Nov. 30 all rooms
are 40 percent cheaper. The price includes Continental breakfast,
double miles with selected airlines. and free airport transfers.
Information: (800) 942-5050. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   French Artists Invade The West Coast &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 museums and galleries from Seattle to San Diego will
participate this fall in ``Cote Ouest: A Season of French
Contemporary Art.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Designed to showcase the current French art scene, the series of
nearly 50 solo shows, group exhibitions, screenings and
collaborations features the work of 70 emerging French artists
selected by curators of West Coast art institutions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the larger museums are the Seattle Art Museum, the
California Palace of the Legion of Honor in San Francisco, the
Portland Institute for Contemporary Art and the J. Paul Getty
Center in Los Angeles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Photography, video, painting, sculpture and installations will
be represented. At the Legion of Honor, for example, 10
forged-metal, terra cotta and bronze sculptures by Alain Kirili
will be ``in dialogue'' with Rodin works in the museum's collection
(Oct. 9 to Jan. 2), while the Santa Monica Museum of Art will
present a French video art program (through Nov. 27), and the
University of Washington's Henry Art Gallery, in Seattle, will
exhibit Gilles Barbier's ``Clones'' installations featuring eerie,
lifelike wax figures (Oct. 15 to Jan. 2). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few ``Cote Ouest'' shows have already opened. A list of
participating organizations is available from the French Consulate
in Los Angeles, (310) 235-3289. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Christopher Hall
</P>
<P>
   Where East Meets West in Berlin &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The historic Friedrichstrasse station, formerly the only border
crossing for rail passengers between East and West Berlin, is one
of the most famous Cold War frontiers, a classic rendezvous point
in espionage fact and fiction. Every day, about 110,000 commuters
and shoppers walk past the once terrifying police checkpoint that
adjoined the station, now a memorial _ called Traenenpalast, or
Palace of Tears _ to German families divided by the Wall and a
sometime setting for concerts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After four years of renovation, this 1882 landmark is well on
the way to being restored to its prewar glory. Even though work
will continue for another year and a half, on Sept. 2, the
refurbished Friedrichstrasse Bahnhof, representing an investment of
$106 million, was re-introduced to the Berlin public. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The restoration of the distinctive, 1920s-style bluish-brown
ceramic-brick facade required 5,000 handmade pieces of black terra
cotta trim. Inside, the last police barriers have long since been
swept aside to make room for a grand hall that houses 50 shops and
snack bars, plus ticketing and information booths. A formal
restaurant will open shortly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The restoration of the station complements recent architectural
projects in this rapidly gentrifying shopping district of East
Berlin, including a new Checkpoint-Charlie Business Center that
features an eight-story Philip Johnson office building at 200
Friedrichstrasse and the Galeries Lafayette department store with
its egg-shaped atrium at 23 Friedrichstrasse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Corinne Labalme &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
