<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9188 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-20 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT THE FUSS AND FLASH, GANNON JUST GET THE JOB DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Tim Brown's last memory this good is six years
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, this is the biggest road win I can remember since
we beat Buffalo in '93,'' the oldest living Raider without a ring
said Sunday, basking cheerily in the glow of, well, the biggest
road win the Raiders have had since they beat Buffalo in 1993 to
kick-start their last playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, though, Oakland's 22-17 win over Minnesota gave
the Raiders their first tangible proof that (a) they are not
destined to be Destiny's dust mites, (b) making plays doesn't
always have to mean making highlight film plays, and (c) that this
Rich Gannon fellow may be the perfect fit at the one position that
has pinched their feet since Jim Plunkett roamed the earth.
</P>
<P>
   There were enough big plays from Raiders great and small to
explain the upset, and Monday's film session will be the first
catered affair since the team moved back to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   But Gannon's play stood out because, well, it didn't stand out.
</P>
<P>
   It was brutally efficient, with enough clever improvisation to
make it seem that much better. He didn't throw the perfect 70-yard
spiral, but he did move the richly maligned Oakland offense as much
as he needed to, even if it wasn't as much as he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We left a lot of yards on the field,'' Gannon said, jumping
the line to take what little available blame there was. ``We left
the defense hanging a few times, and we have to get better. I'll
shoulder a lot of responsibility for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when confronted by the evidence of seven dropped balls that
could have turned 22-17 into 34-17, he stood shield in hand for his
guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, it's not the drops, it's the accuracy of the
throws,'' he said with jaw fully squared. ``Maybe if I put the ball
in there better . . . I have to make those throws better than I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   If this seems like a small thing to you, snap out of it. The
Raiders have known enough lousy times over the years that they have
developed complicated techniques for deflecting blame. To have a
quarterback who takes the hit for his mates after guiding them to
such a win speaks volumes about Rich Gannon.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, that whatever you think he doesn't have, he has much
more than you think.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon's numbers were good but not eye-popping; 21-of-33 for 248
yards and one score. But Gannon isn't a numbers guy, and never has
been. What he gave the Raiders was playmaking, with a lower-case
``p,'' the kind that doesn't have a soundtrack but has a point to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he ran for the winning score on a 5-yard
quarterback draw late in the third quarter. Look past the underhand
flip he delivered to tight end Rickey Dudley that turned a
potential drive killer into a 35-yard gain that set up his score.
Forget the 31-yard pea he threw to James Jett to get the Raiders
out of the shadow of their own end zone moments after Minnesota cut
the Oakland lead to five.
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK, don't forget them. They were huge plays, plays that
separated the Raiders from another gut-wrenching loss, plays that
make coach Jon Gruden describe Gannon as ``brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't forget the things he didn't do, things that Raider
quarterbacks have conjured up for years to ruin Sundays by the
crate-load and make Al Davis pull Al LoCasale's hair out in clumps.
</P>
<P>
   He threw no interceptions. He was sacked once, and seemed to
have a third eye out for pressuring Vikings, throwing the ball a
split second before getting popped. He escaped getting drilled a
good eight times, and the one time he fumbled, he recovered it
himself. He even made calling a timeout he didn't have seem
downright inspired.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders had a third-and-5 at the Minnesota 42 with 12
minutes and change left in the fourth quarter when Gannon came to
line and discovered old-time Raider chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the wrong formation out there, and to be honest, I
forgot we were out of timeouts,'' he said. ``But at the time, I
figured if we take the 5-yard penalty, it's not a big issue to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. The Raiders had to punt, but the defense, which had
prevented the Vikings from establishing their pace and tone on the
game stopped them each of the last three times they got the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Which, after all, is what a defense regarded as highly as
Oakland's is supposed to do, no matter how much Gannon wants to
fall on his own javelin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the beauty of it,'' he said. ``We have a great defense
that played well, even in the first half when I wasn't playing well
at all. I wanted to settle myself down because I didn't play well
at all in the first half. If I play well in the first half, it's
probably a different game.''
</P>
<P>
   But it already was a different game, different than the 28-24
loss at Green Bay last week, different than the standard close-
your-eyes-and-take-six-aspirin Raider game of the modern East Bay
era. It was the Raiders standing up until game's end, and winning
when nobody thought they could, in a place where few visiting teams
do.
</P>
<P>
   What it is, in words of tackle Lincoln Kennedy, is ``overdue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
