<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9192 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-COX     09-20 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves and Mets square off to decide which philosophy works
bestBy Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They both have power stashed at the corners, and they
both have stacked the defense up the middle. Both have production
at catcher too, or did, until Javy Lopez dismantled his knee.
</P>
<P>
   Both call out a flame-thrower for the ninth inning. Lately, the
Braves even have rediscovered the art of the stolen base.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves and New York Mets arrive at their 10 days of destiny
having followed the same kind of roster-building architecture that
has served general managers for decades now, if for only one huge
exception:
</P>
<P>
   The Mets view starting pitching as a vehicle to the seventh
inning; the Braves see starting pitching as a reason for living.
The two clubs not only will settle the NL East in these upcoming
six games, they also will further the late-century debate that
relievers have superseded starters in this era of biceps baseball.
</P>
<P>
   At Turner Field, the Mets find a club that is cinching its belt
around its rotation, wondering about Tom Glavine's 4.35 ERA and
John Smoltz's knuckleball almost as much as it wonders about Brian
Jordan. September, where philosophies clash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to get starters. I have all my life,'' Braves GM John
Schuerholz said. ``I'm just not saying that because you asked me
today. I've been doing it for 19 years _ trying to get starters and
guys that can catch the ball around them.''
</P>
<P>
   For two teams that stand just one game apart above the league,
the Braves and Mets arrive tonight via different routes. Since he
took the Mets' GM job in 1995, Steve Phillips gradually became
enamored of the Cleveland Indians, which had placed an effective
bullpen above stocking the rotation with proven stars. Even with
the midseason acquisition of Oakland starter Kenny Rogers (5-0),
Valentine's mandate for his starters remains the same: work six
innings while we get a lead and then get out of the way for the
bullpen to take it from there.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have thrown only three complete games this season,
second-fewest in the majors along with _ no surprise _ Cleveland.
The bullpen has worked 456 innings, an average of more than three
innings a game. New York relievers will earn some $11.2 million
this season, significantly higher than the $6.47 million Atlanta
relievers will earn. And that figure stood at just $3.5 million
until a bump from newcomer Terry Mulholland, also the fifth
starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bullpen is a lot more important over 162 games,''
Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   With Smoltz's elbow, Glavine's inconsistency and the departure
of Denny Neagle, Atlanta's starters' numbers are
uncharacteristically down. Their nine complete games ranks just
fifth in the league. Since Schuerholz's arrival in 1991, the Braves
had ranked first or second in complete games every year until now.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz has stood up to the criticism that the emphasis on
the starters _ $25.78 million or 35 percent of the Opening Day
payroll _ has mortgaged the bullpen. The fact that Atlanta
relievers enter the series with a slightly lower ERA (3.70) than
the Mets' (3.73) hardly ends the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the emergence of relief pitching in today's
baseball is evident, and it's very important,'' Schuerholz said.
``But given the choice if I would have starters or relievers, I'd
rather have starters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Indians are not alone in the revised thinking.
Contenders Cincinnati, San Francisco, Texas and Boston, working
around impaired rotations, all have been heavily reliant on their
bullpens all season. But the Mets have set a standard. They went
nearly two-thirds of the year before anyone went nine innings.
After Masato Yoshii and Rogers threw complete games on Aug. 15 and
18, the Mets have had just one more.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
