<HEADLINE>
RAISA GORBACHEV, WIFE OF LAST SOVIET LEADER, AT 67 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Raisa Gorbachev, the wife of former Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev, died in a German hospital Monday after an
eight-month battle with leukemia. She was 67.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gorbachev's husband and her daughter, Irina Virganskaya,
were by her side when she passed away at 3 a.m. local time at the
Muenster University Clinic in Germany, where she had been
undergoing treatment for leukemia since July 25.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gorbachev died in her sleep, doctors at the hospital
announced. She was scheduled to receive a bone marrow transplant
from her sister as soon as she recovered from complications caused
by chemotherapy and infection. Her condition deteriorated Sunday,
and she was transferred to the hospital's intensive care unit where
she remained unconscious until her death.
</P>
<P>
   The first spouse of a Soviet leader to be called ``first lady''
here, the outspoken, smart, and stylish Mrs. Gorbachev broke the
mold for Kremlin wives _ as Gorbachev opened up Soviet society and
tore down the Iron Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Gorbachevs moved into the Kremlin in 1985, the wives
of Soviet leaders hid in the shadows, rarely showing themselves in
public and never taking an active role in politics. But Mrs.
Gorbachev not only carved out a public role for herself in this
conservative society that still looks at female public figures with
suspicion, she blazed a new trail for women to enter public life.
Decked out in designer clothes, she traveled with Gorbachev,
advised him on policy, and was not afraid to speak her mind in
public.
</P>
<P>
   But while her bold style won praise in the West, it was
controversial at home, where Mrs. Gorbachev was scorned by many
Russians, who were put off by her flamboyance. Since her illness,
however, many here have inundated the Gorbachevs with veneration
and praise. In part, this may be that Russians, weary from a decade
of dashed hopes and unfulfilled expectations, long for the
boundless optimism of the Gorbachev years. Every major television
network here led the evening news Monday with somber reports on
Mrs. Gorbachev's death and footage of her and Mr. Gorbachev's
careers.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Mr. Gorbachev kept a lonely vigil by his wife's
side throughout her illness and, although deeply shaken, always
found time to brief reporters on her progress and to thank all
those who expressed their support and sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   It has also only now become widely known here that Mrs.
Gorbachev donated much of her wealth to charity and over the past
several years raised more than $8 million for children's leukemia
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Northeastern University in Boston bestowed an honorary
degree on Mrs. Gorbachev. The Gorbachev Foundation also opened a US
office at Northeastern, where the former Soviet president delivered
a commencement address in 1998. Raisa Gorbachev and Barbara Bush
delivered commencement addresses at Wellesley College in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gorbachev was born Raisa Maximova Titorenko on Jan. 5, 1932
in the Altai region of southern Siberia. The eldest daughter of a
railway construction worker and a housewife, she met Gorbachev, now
68, when both were students at the elite Moscow State University _
where she studied sociology and he studied law _ in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The two married in September 1953 and moved to Gorbachev's home
region of Stavropol in southern Russia after he graduated in 1955.
There she taught Marxist-Leninist philosophy at Stavropol State
University. She later took a teaching position at Moscow State
University when Gorbachev, a rising political star, moved his
family to the capital 1978. She gave up her academic career when
Gorbachev became Soviet leader in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In his memoirs, the former Soviet president wrote that his
mother did not approve of his outspoken wife. But Gorbachev never
let anybody doubt his deep love for the woman he called ``my
Raisa.''
</P>
<P>
   Grilled by reporters during her husband's unsuccessful 1996
presidential campaign about her tendency to accompany her husband
anywhere, Mrs. Gorbachev didn't miss a beat. ``You all wrote about
how I was always by his side when he was in power,'' she said then.
``But why don't you write that I never left his side after all of
you forgot about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from all over the world _ including Pope John Paul II,
President Clinton, and former British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher _ sent messages of condolence. Russian President Boris N.
Yeltsin, a bitter rival of Gorbachev's who forced him out of the
Kremlin in 1991, sent his as well. Yeltsin has also provided a
presidential aircraft to bring Mrs. Gorbachev's remains, and her
family, back to Moscow Tuesday. She is scheduled to be buried in
Moscow on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her husband and daughter Irina, Mrs. Gorbachev
leaves behind two granddaughters, Kseniya, 19 and Anastasia, 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
