<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAMA-AD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bockrath to resign at Alabama
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the first move in what could become a major shakeup
at Alabama, athletics director Bob Bockrath will resign this week.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Bockrath, who had been AD since June 1996,
does not bode well for the future of football coach Mike DuBose,
who has come under increasing fire since Saturday's stunning 29-28
loss to Louisiana Tech in Birmingham. DuBose was Bockrath's first
major hire, and his departure can only weaken DuBose's support,
which has been tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's rumor and speculation at this particular time, and I
wouldn't care to speculate on that,'' DuBose said Monday when asked
about the situation at his regular weekly news conference. ``I
understand the question, but until I know more that what I know,
I'd just as soon not speculate on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama is expected to name Finus Gaston, the school's senior
associate athletics director, to the job on an interim basis. Names
mentioned as possible candidates for the job include Mal Moore, a
former assistant coach now the associate athletics director for
football relations; former Crimson Tide All-American Lee Roy
Jordan, a businessman in Dallas; Florida State athletics director
Dave Hart, an Alabama graduate who played basketball for the
Crimson Tide; and former football coach Gene Stallings, whom DuBose
replaced in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bockrath, who could not be reached for comment, has been in
negotiations with university president Andrew Sorensen over his
severance package. The Birmingham Post-Herald reported Monday that
those negotiations had been completed over the weekend. Bockrath
had a five-year contract that paid him between $250,000 and
$300,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Bockrath, who came to Alabama from Texas Tech, was never very
popular with the Crimson Tide alumni or employees of the athletics
department, who disliked his impersonal management style. His
tenure was filled with controversy from start to finish:
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1998 Bockrath's former school, Texas Tech, was hit with
NCAA sanctions for rules violations and ``a lack of institutional
control'' during his time in Lubbock. Those problems did not sit
well with some Alabama alumni, as the school has just gone through
its own NCAA investigation.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a lawsuit that later was dismissed, an Alabama alumnus
charged that Bockrath had exchanged a premium skybox at
Bryant-Denny Stadium for a deep discount on a lot in a subdivision
in Tuscaloosa, Ala., where Bockrath owns a $750,000 home. Bockrath
recently put that home up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most recently, several members of the Alabama's Board of
Trustrees were critical of Bockrath's decision to keep DuBose as
coach after DuBose admitted to lying about an extra-marital affair.
Bockrath did not consult the trustees on the issue. If he had,
DuBose might have been fired.
</P>
<P>
   Bockrath's resignation also follows a decision by the trustees
to form a committee to oversee all personnel decisions in the
athletics department of the three schools in the university system.
That decision, in effect, rendered Bockrath powerless over major
hirings and firings.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation in Tuscloosa continues that Sorensen will be out as
the Alabama president before the end of the year. Sorensen
reportedlyis pursuing the opening for chancellor at Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
