<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9205 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-MAIN-COX     09-20 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love gets go-ahead for Ryder Cup actionBy Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Davis Love III has no way of knowing whether
The Country Club will be a spot to remember pleasantly _ in
contrast to the bitterness of Oak Hill and Valderrama.
</P>
<P>
   All that Love knew Monday, after arriving at the site of the
33rd Ryder Cup, was that his physical condition should not be a
factor. After a doctor-ordered, two-week break from golf, hunting
and fishing, Love said he no longer feels pain from a nerve in his
neck.
</P>
<P>
   Love worked on the practice range with teacher Jack Lumpkin of
Sea Island and later played nine holes. Love denied that two
matches a day might be too much of a load on Friday or Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the talk before,'' Love said, ``that I didn't want to
wear myself out for Sunday. Now, I feel like I could go the whole
way. I'm as rested as anyone on the team. My hip feels great. My
back feels great. I'm excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Bob Estes, the United States' first alternate,
is no longer on stand-by status. Not that Love ever seriously
considered missing the Ryder Cup, an event he respects so deeply.
Obviously, he longs to erase the gloominess of the 0-4 record he
took back from Spain two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed reading in the press how I wasn't going to play,
or how could I play after not playing for two or three weeks,'' he
said. ``Well, that's normal for me. I take time off a lot. . . . If
the only thing I could do the rest of the year was play the Ryder
Cup, I'd play that and take the rest of the year off.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest episode of back and shoulder pain was different in
that Love felt numbness in his left hand after hitting a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same thing Brian Jordan of the Braves has,'' Love
said. ``When he throws it, his hand goes numb. When I hit a ball,
my hand just kind of went numb. . . . I was just unsure of what I
was doing, because every time I hit it, it was like, `God, am I
tearing my shoulder and my arm up?' . . . I just aggravated the
nerve, and I had to let it calm down.''
</P>
<P>
   Love started hitting balls Friday, shortly after Hurricane Floyd
veered away from the Georgia coast and after he got permission from
orthopedic specialist Tom Boers of Columbus to ease back slowly. By
Sunday, Love, 35, was striking 3-woods and drivers with full
strength. And none too soon, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting away from golf was one thing,'' he said, ``but I
really couldn't do anything else, and that was a little boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Love's ``recovery'' was an uplifting development for the U.S.
squad, which held informal practice rounds Monday. Captain Ben
Crenshaw had begun the day with a wait-and-see approach about Love.
A few hours later, Love seemed available for as many matches as
necessary, probably with Justin Leonard as his partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Davis is one of the best players in the United
States,'' Jim Furyk said. ``Hopefully, he's very healthy, and he's
going to play very well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin and I want to play a lot together,'' Love said, ``and
if we're both playing good, I hope they play us a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Love has the longest consecutive Ryder Cup streak on the U.S.
squad, with this his fourth appearance in a row. He has a 5-8
record _ 2-1 in singles.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
