A9210 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-INNERWORKS-COX     09-20 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-INNERWORKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Third Millenium CEO announcement made, capital soughtBy Mark
Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It took two job offers and 15 years for Gerald
Eickhoff to land Michael Reene.
</P>
<P>
   Eickhoff, co-founder of Third Millenium Communications, an $8
million a year company that develops tools for corporate Web sites,
named Reene his new chief executive. Reene starts Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Eickhoff, 52, said he will work continue to work full-time, but
now he will focus on helping Third Millennium nail down a new
injection of investment capital. Eickhoff said he hopes to attract
about $16 million. He will also be talking to investment bankers
about a possible public offering of stock sometime in the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The pair first met in 1984. Reene was a consultant with Arthur
Andersen and Eickhoff ran his own consulting company, BEI Holdings.
Eickhoff was so impressed with Reene that he asked him to come work
for him. Reene turned him down. He wanted to test his mettle with a
big corporation.
</P>
<P>
   In May, after 17 years with Andersen and five years with IBM,
Reene was near the top when he stepped down. He ran the division
that served IBM's global telecommunications customers, selling
computer equipment and consulting services.
</P>
<P>
   But Reene, 43, also kept an eye on the smaller companies. He was
a founder of Consumer Financial Network, which was sold to iXL
Holdings in 1996. He sits on the board of Enrev, a battery
technology firm. And in 1996, when Eickhoff started his next
company, Third Millennium Communications, Reene was one of the
people who invested start-up money. In July, Reene took a seat on
Third Millennium's board and increased his stake. He now holds a 20
percent share of the Decatur, Ga.-based Web site developer.
</P>
<P>
   Third Millennium develops tools used on corporate Web sites,
including MVP.com, a new Web company being developed, in part, by
former football star John Elway. The firm also has a product,
expoexchange.com, a Web site that helps automate many of the
functions for trade shows, from booking plane tickets, to choosing
floor space to setting up itineraries.
</P>
<P>
   Reene will become president of the Technology Association of
Georgia on Jan. 1. He also sits on the board of the Georgia Center
for Advanced Telecommunications Technology, GCATT. He heads the
recruitment committee of the Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce's
Industries of the Mind program, an effort to attract attention to
the local high-tech community. Eickhoff has struck entrepreneurial
lightning once, with BEI Holdings. He also is a philanthropist
chairman of Honduras Outreach, which helps 25,000 Hondurans receive
a range of help, including health and planting advice.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Fleming, a partner with Alliance Technology Ventures,
has worked with Reene through the Industries of the Mind, GCATT and
Video Networks, a company Fleming's firm has invested in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have huge regard for him,'' Fleming said. ``I respect his
technology savvy and his business savvy and his understanding of
how to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT MICHAEL W. REENE
</P>
<P>
   _ Name: Michael W. Reene
</P>
<P>
   _ Age: 43
</P>
<P>
   _ Title: CEO Third Millennium Communications
</P>
<P>
   _ Tenure with company: Starts Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   _ Job responsibilities: Handles day-to-day operations._ Hobbies:
Playing tennis and spending time with his twin boys, his daughter
and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
