<HEADLINE>
BLOOD DONATIONS TRIPLE AFTER CHURCH SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Nearly 4,600 units of blood were donated by
North Texans in the four days after the shootings at Wedgwood
Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   It was two to three times the amount of blood normally donated,
said Jenny Nelson, a spokeswoman for Carter BloodCare, the primary
blood bank for 22 North Texas counties.
</P>
<P>
   The peak was Thursday when 1,900 units were drawn. The figure
fell to 1,364 on Friday, 821 on Saturday and 502 on Sunday.
Normally collections average about 500 a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the shooting happened last week we pulled in some units
from some of our outlying hospitals. Since we pulled from their
supplies last week, this week we'll be pulling from the blood
center inventory to get the hospital inventories built back up,''
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said that as of Monday, stocks of O-positive, B-positive
and AB-positive were at preferred levels. The supplies of
O-negative, A-positive and A-negative were at the minimum
acceptable level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep working hard to educate the community that we
need blood donors every day, not just following a crisis like
Wedgwood or the Oklahoma City bombing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the demand for blood has increased 8 percent to 10
percent this year, much of it due to aggressive cancer therapy and
surgeries that require more blood. She said donations are down
about 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that 60 percent of the general population can
give blood. In North Texas about 4.2 percent of eligible people
give. The national average is 4.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
