r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-BECKEL     09-20 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-BECKEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRISTI BECKEL REMEMBERED AT FILLED SANCTUARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALTOM CITY, Texas _ Bob and Debbie Beckel stood in the first
row, facing a portrait of their young daughter, as hundreds of
worshipers stood behind them, praying, singing and hugging their
own children especially tight.
</P>
<P>
   It was a beautiful tribute conducted on Monday because of an
ugly event: the murder of 14-year-old Kristi Kathleen Beckel, one
of seven people shot and killed last week in a rampage at Wedgwood
Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Kristi's funeral was at Bethesda Community Church in the Fort
Worth suburb of Haltom City, next door to Bethesda Christian
School, where she was a ninth-grader. Her mother is a teacher of
second-graders at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Al Meredith, pastor at Wedgwood Baptist, thanked the crowd of
mourners who nearly filled the 1,200-seat sanctuary at Bethesda.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an easy thing to come to,'' Meredith said. ``None
of us ever expect to bury our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said the doors at Wedgwood Baptist will remain open and
unguarded _ at least by police _ despite the horror last week that
stole Kristi's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen where some churches are hiring armed guards to
patrol the churches,'' the pastor said, adding: ``I respect their
concerns. But there are not enough armed guards in the world to
keep us from conflict and tribulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Debbie Beckel sat silently in the front pew, almost
close enough to touch their daughter's casket, with their other
daughter, Kim Marrillo, as Meredith preached that no one,
especially the young, is completely safe from someone like Larry
Gene Ashbrook, the killer at Wedgwood Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the protection of my children were up to me, I'd be a
basket case, I'd be in a mental ward,'' the preacher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be with them all the time, everywhere. I have to
release them to God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said Kristi was killed by a ``deranged gunman who was
in the power of the prince of darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has watched this community, this family of faith, in
amazement this week. ... The prince of darkness began in Wedgwood,
at my church,'' he said. ``Seven precious lives were snuffed out,
then the gunman turned the gun on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to pray for his family, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Vaughn, principal at Bethesda Christian School, said
Kristi was an inspiration to her classmates and to her teammates on
the school's vollyeball team, where she was described as an
``awesome server.''
</P>
<P>
   Every night, after school and after volleyball, Kristi would
stick her head into her parents' bedroom and wish them well, Vaughn
told the congregation. Then, she said, Kristi would ``leave their
room, go into her bedroom, and shout through the walls, `Good
night, I love you!' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
