<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-CLINTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS CONDOLENCES TO FORT WORTH IN CALL TO MAYOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KRISTIN N. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ President Clinton called to offer residents
condolences on Monday in the wake of Wednesday's church shooting
and volunteered his staff's help to develop a community response,
Mayor Kenneth Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed his frustration that these types of things are
happening in the country,'' Barr said of the 8:45 a.m. call. ``We
talked a little bit about the nature of them and a little bit about
what the country needs to do to figure out what to do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors have said that Larry Gene Ashbrook, a 47-year-old from
Forest Hill, was a social outcast who sent them irrational letters
before he killed seven people and himself Wednesday evening at
Wedgwood Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he told Clinton that he may convene a group of
religious leaders and mental health professionals to discuss what
help can be extended to people exhibiting deranged behavior in
hopes of preventing similar tragedies. Clinton offered to send a
staff member to help if Barr request.MDSD/.MDNM/s it, the mayor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, White House operators first tried to reach Barr
at City Hall, but patched Clinton through at Barr's family printing
business, The Barr Co., the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he spoke with Clinton for 10 or 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good conversation,'' Barr said. ``He said it was a
great puzzlement, there's some frustrated people in our society _
largely white males _ who seem to fall into this trap, this
conduct. He speculated a little about why.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the shooting tragedy, Clinton has publicly
advocated criminal background checks on would-be buyers at gun
shows similar to checks required for sales in gun shops.
</P>
<P>
   But on the telephone yesterday, Barr said, the two didn't
discuss additional restrictions on handguns or the general
availability of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him about the fact that Fort Worth is a safe city,
that our crime stats are down and that we had not had a homicide in
that council district in 1999'' until Wednesday, the mayor said.
``I said all of this adds to our bewilderment and inability to
understand what happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he also told the president about Safe City USA, a
program designed to reduce the number of gun-related crimes by
prosecuting criminals wielding weapons through the federal court
system which traditionally provides longer prison sentences. City
officials plan to launch the Safe City program Sept. 29. It was
planned before the church shootings, Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really appreciated his call,'' the mayor said. ``All of us
know how busy he is. It says a lot to me that he was concerned, and
he wanted us to know that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
