A9224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      09-20 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN GENERAL DISPUTES REPORTS OF WIDESPREAD DEATHS IN EAST
TIMOR
</HEADLINE>
   (With TIMOR-RDP) 
(nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Indonesia's top military commander,
disputing reports of thousands of deaths in East Timor, said Monday
that fewer than 100 people had been killed in the bloodshed in the
province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of victims that we have recorded since the
announcement of the result of the referendum is roughly in the
90s,'' said the commander, Gen. Wiranto. Widespread violence by
military-backed militias broke out last month after the people of
East Timor voted overwhelmingly to be independent of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the number we have recorded so far, but it is not the
tens of thousands or hundreds of thousands as reported by the
foreign media,'' he told the Indonesian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto's estimate is much less than those of pro-independence
groups, which put the death toll at anywhere from 900 to 7,000. And
it drew a skeptical response from the United Nations, which
sheltered hundreds of refugees in the capital, Dili, before leaving
its compound to a rampaging mob.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much hope he's right,'' said David Wimhurst, a
spokesman for the U.N. Mission in East Timor. ``However,
indications are that the situation is far more serious than he
suggests.''
</P>
<P>
   Wimhurst said the United Nations was particularly concerned
about refugees who had fled or were forcibly moved from East Timor
to neighboring West Timor. He said the United Nations would not
estimate the number of deaths without an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   With the first troops of an international military force landing
in Dili on Monday, such an investigation may soon be possible.
Wiranto's remarks seemed to anticipate that the Indonesian army
would soon come under harsh scrutiny for its role in the violence
over the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses have accused the military of helping anti-independence
militia groups kill people and loot and burn their homes.
</P>
<P>
   An uneasy calm hung over Jakarta on Monday, as Indonesia's
military and political leaders confronted the painful precedent of
foreign troops entering Indonesian territory for the first time
since independence. Sporadic small demonstrations broke out near
the parliament and in the business district.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 protesters gathered at the National Human Rights
Commission in Jakarta to demand a vote on independence for the
eastern province of Irian Jaya, which Indonesia took over from the
Netherlands in 1969. Political leaders here fear East Timor's
decision to break away from Indonesia will unleash separatist
passions throughout this archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   For Indonesia's president, B.J. Habibie, the decision to allow
soldiers into East Timor has thrown him on his heels during a
presidential campaign that already seemed to be turning against
him. An electoral assembly is to choose the next president this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Habibie will go to parliament to give an account of
why he acquiesced to demands for troops _ particularly a force led
by Indonesia's now unpopular neighbor, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Umar Juoro, an adviser to Habibie, said the president would
explain that the government had tried to restore order in East
Timor by imposing martial law. When that failed, Indonesia had
little choice but to accept outside help. Juoro said that Habibie
would note that Australia was the logical choice to lead a force
because of its resources and proximity to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Habibie's critics are using the fact that he allowed foreign
troops into Indonesia as a weapon against him,'' Juoro said.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on Habibie is not likely to subside. Monday, the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, Sadako Ogata, met with the
president to urge him to allow more emergency relief for the
estimated 200,000 refugees in West Timor. Earlier, Ms. Ogata
visited a refugee camp in Atambua, near the East Timorese border,
which is said to be under the grip of anti-independence gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ogata said Habibie had promised to allow more air drops of
food and other supplies. But she said it was too early to discuss
arrangements to move the displaced East Timorese back to their
shattered homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
