<HEADER>
A9235 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-20 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS WIN HAUNTED BY ERROR-PRONE WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Sunday's 31-28 comeback victory over the
Colts was a thriller, but Patriots coach Pete Carroll and his
players realize that if they continue to commit penalties at the
rate they did in that game, their chances of winning will be slim.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots set a team record with 15 penalties, including an
unsportsmanlike conduct call on Carroll, and they cost 135 yards.
In last week's 30-28 win over the Jets, they committed seven
penalties for 43 yards. Last season the Patriots committed 108
penalties, fourth-most in their history. The most penalized Patriot
team of all-time was the 1985 team, which committed 114 but went
11-5 and reached the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm most concerned about penalties _ we have to get that
cleaned up,'' said Carroll. ``And they aren't of the same type. We
didn't have a lot of motion penalties or holding penalties at the
line, we had aggressive-oriented penalties, we had a late hit, a
face mask, roughing the quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   And his own unsportsmanlike conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``That part we can handle,'' said Carroll. ``We can fix that up
in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   So concerned is Carroll that he's getting league officials to
come in during practice this week and call penalties during 7-on-7s
and 11-on-11s, ``just to do different things this week to create a
different emphasis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in these situations before. It's over-aggression at
times. They're hitting out there. I like the way we're chasing the
football. I like our aggressiveness, but the whole idea is we don't
want to make it easy on the opponent by giving them anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are a young team, but most of Sunday's penalties
were on guys who should know better. The breakdown:
</P>
<P>
   First quarter:
</P>
<P>
   1. Ed Ellis (three-year veteran), 5 yards for false start on
third and 7.
</P>
<P>
   2. Tony Carter (sixth year), 14 yards for unnecessary roughness
on second and 1. The Patriots wound up punting.
</P>
<P>
   3. Tebucky Jones (second year), 5 yards for an incidental face
mask on a punt.
</P>
<P>
   4. Lawyer Milloy (fourth year), 4 yards and automatic first down
for pass interference. The next play was a 42-yard touchdown pass
to Marvin Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   5. Larry Whigham (sixth year), 5 yards for illegal touch. This
nullified a 63-yard punt by Lee Johnson that had pinned the Colts
at the 3. Fortunately for Whigham and the Patriots, Johnson
followed with a 57-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   6. Ty Law (fifth year), 22 yards for pass interference.
</P>
<P>
   Second quarter:
</P>
<P>
   7. Law, 5 yards for illegal contact on second and 9 at the Colt
22.
</P>
<P>
   8. Carroll (26th year), 15 yards for unsportsmanlike conduct
when he kicks the flag thrown on Law and has heated words with the
official.
</P>
<P>
   9. Troy Brown (seventh year), 5 yards for encroachment on an
extra point.
</P>
<P>
   Third quarter:
</P>
<P>
   10. Tony Carter, 15 yards for unnecessary roughness on a punt.
</P>
<P>
   11. Ellis, 5 yards for illegal formation.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter:
</P>
<P>
   12. Harold Shaw (third year), 10 yards for holding on punt
return.
</P>
<P>
   13. Team, 5 yards for 12 men on the field.
</P>
<P>
   14. Team, 5 yards for delay of game, a penalty taken
deliberately to run the clock down as they were preparing for the
winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   15. Henry Thomas (13th year), 15 yards for roughing the passer
with 25 seconds left and the Colts desperately trying to get the
ball downfield into field goal range.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a problem that almost wrecked this game for us,'' said
Carroll. ``We come out of these two games with wins with a lot of
improvement to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to show improvement if we're to see good we are. To
execute so poorly _ and the execution had to do with the penalties
_ we weren't clean throwing the football. There are a number of
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Sunday's penalties will be reviewed by the league; in
some cases the league has said a penalty was unjust. One of Law's
interference calls was borderline, though he appeared to bump
Harrison as Harrison was going for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Carter's hit, the reason they threw it is not because is
was so late or overly aggressive,'' said Carroll. ``It's because he
hit his helmet on the other guy's helmet. Helmet-to-helmet contact
is very strict. Tony didn't realize what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   On the roughing-the-passer on Thomas at the end of the game,
Carroll said he never saw the roughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see that penalty,'' said the coach. ``Thomas hit him
higher and it was a vicious hit. It was so vicious that I think the
official thought it must have been a penalty. We'll turn it in and
see what they say about it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Whigham's illegal touch, Carroll said, ``That's a bad
mistake. He got jacked up about downing the ball at the 3-yard line
after he had gone out of bounds. He made a bad choice there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
