<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-8     09-20 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS RALLIES SEEK TO BRING ABOUT THE OUSTER OF MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.s News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The leader of a group of opposition
parties that will try to bring down President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia in a series of rallies and demonstrations beginning on
Tuesday says the outcome is really up to the Serbian people now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is poker with all the cards on the table,'' Zoran
Djindjic said in an interview on Monday. ``We don't have any
choice. We have to try to remove Milosevic by the end of the year,
and do it with people on the streets. We believe that the people
are stronger than Milosevic. But it depends on the people of Serbia
now, and I don't know what their reaction will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic's Democratic Party and the smaller opposition parties
in the Alliance for Change have made plans for simultaneous rallies
beginning on Tuesday evening in 32 Serbian cities and towns. They
have also tried to organize daytime events. Party workers will hand
out material from kiosks and canvass with petitions. Daily mock
trials of government officials will be presented on ``charges'' of
having failed the population or being corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a summer of intermittent rallies and disputes within
the broader opposition. The largest of the parties, the Serbian
Renewal Movement of Vuk Draskovic, will not take part in the new
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   But the Alliance politicians said it was time, as Djindjic
(pronounced jin-JITCH) said last month, at the biggest opposition
rally to date, ``to go to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally on Tuesday in Belgrade, the capital, will be in the
Square of the Republic, which will look full with 10,000 to 15,000
people, not in front of the Parliament, where the rally last month
drew an estimated 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rally posters show Milosevic and his wife, Mirjana Markovic,
with big red X's over their faces and with the slogan, ``The people
choose.'' That is an echo of a 1945 slogan the said, ``We want no
king, we want Tito _ the people choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic, appearing to use the time-honored tactic of lowering
expectations, said he expected that the rallies would start slowly
and peak at some point. Depending on the turnout, by the beginning
of next month the Alliance plans to concentrate on activities like
traffic blockades, some form of a general strike and naming an
alternative shadow government, to be led by a former Central Bank
governor, Dragoslav Avramovic.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition-run local governments of the main cities may then
make declarations of no confidence in the government and refuse to
obey it, Djindjic suggested. Or the opposition could on its own
hold informal elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``But by the end of October, Milosevic will respond in some
way,'' Djindjic said, ``with violence or counterdemonstrations or
new elections or his resignation,'' although Djindjic said he had
no great hopes for an easy or quick resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, the other main opposition leader, has been pushing
for early elections, and he is widely expected to wait to see how
the rallies fare before committing himself. If the turnouts are
large, he will have little choice but to join in some fashion. If
they are small, he is most likely to declare himself the leader of
the opposition and urge the others to unite behind him.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Draskovic said that he would join protests if the
opposition could agree on conditions for free, fair and early
elections and if Milosevic refused to schedule them.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear that Milosevic feels the need to have early
elections, in view of their risks to him, and he is also waiting to
see what turnouts the Alliance produces.
</P>
<P>
   So is the United States, which is backing Djindjic's efforts _
with more moral support than tangible help. A senior administration
official said in a telephone interview: ``We'll see if these
demonstrations go well, if they have a progression, plateau or even
decline. Then they can decide what comes next. They have four or
five weeks to mobilize people and see where that takes them.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a decline, he said, ``then the administration may
have to change its tune'' about whether this form of protest can be
effective.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic and Alliance officials are encouraged by opinion polls
that indicate that two-thirds of Serbs are unhappy with the
government, half believe that the political system is growing
worse, and nearly 40 percent have no confidence in Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But the polls, released last week by the Center for Studying
Alternatives, a research institute, from interviews with a random
sample of 1,600 representative Serbs, indicate deep and abiding
insecurity and fear of chaos and civil war. The government is
exploiting such fears through its propaganda, accusing the Alliance
of acting as NATO's cat's paw, of being in the pay of the United
States and trying to finish what the bombing started.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of the respondents said they feared a
lowering of their already poor living standards. Nearly as many
said they feared new inflation and being unable to find work.
Eighty percent said they feared civil war, and 70 percent mentioned
hunger. When asked whether they favored change even at the price of
violence, many respondents demanded that the word violence be
scratched out, pollsters said. Still, about a third said they
wanted change at any price.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the demonstrations is to turn those concerns into
collective action, to mobilize further Serbs who fear for their
future and to give them confidence, Djindjic said. If the rallies
build and the Alliance can achieve as many as two million
signatures on petitions, he added, he expects the government to
begin to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic said 30 people associated with the government and its
business interests had approached his party about making
contributions as a sort of bet on the future. They also want help
in having their names removed from a European Union ban on visas
and travel for 300 notables from the present administration.
</P>
<P>
   A senior aide to Djindjic, Cedomir Jovanovic, said Monday,
``Milosevic's power will disappear the day he no longer controls
the levers of power, when the police understand that there's no one
behind their backs but a little group of thieves, and in front of
them are the people.''
</P>
<P>
   But some party officials are also concerned that they are
attempting too much and opening too many fronts, that they have to
deal with the conflict with Draskovic, as well as internal
conflicts about strategy in the party and the Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The party's 5,000 active participants are already working 12
hours a day, officials said, and the canvassing that Djindjic plans
will take even more out of them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is party-building work _ obtaining signatures and
telephone numbers _ of the kind that the opposition has rarely
done, and it should help in elections should they come about.
</P>
<P>
   As for himself, Djindjic stepped back from an earlier pledge to
quit as party leader if Milosevic was still in power on Jan. 1,
2000. But if this new effort to unseat Milosevic fails, Djindjic
said, he will step down as a ``lightning rod'' for criticism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
