<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9277 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOOD-CREST-COX     09-20 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-CREST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    River threatens power, water; more rain could hamper efforts
further
 &HT;    By Dawn Bryant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The merciless Tar River, which just won't
scale back its soggy and destructive path, continued Monday to
threaten Greenville's power and water service.
</P>
<P>
   With the water rising, Greenville Utilities officials were
unsure whether their round-the-clock, creative battle with the
unforgiving river _ which has shattered the 24.5-foot 100-year
floodmark by more than six feet _ would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 p.m. Monday, fragile riggings at the submerged electric
substation and the water treatment plant were still holding up,
keeping electricity and water service to the city.
</P>
<P>
   But the slightest leak of a sandbag wall at the water treatment
plant, or an unstoppable piece of floating debris at the electric
substation could knock out those services.
</P>
<P>
   Roads to the plant and the substation are more like rivers. The
only way in and out is by boat or helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get anywhere,'' said Malcolm Green, GUC's general
manager/CEO. ``We are having to fly things everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   As the river continued to edge toward a crest Monday, water
reportedly was just a few inches from the only line bringing
electricity into the city.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers constructed that setup above the submerged substation
Saturday after floodwaters had knocked out power for nearly 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   If the river gets within nine inches of high-power lines there,
officials will have to shut off the power serving all of Greenville
and three-fourths of Pitt County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an adequate amount of breathing room for today,''
Green said Monday. ``I can't speak to tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the water treatment plant, crews have filled
thousands of sandbags to protect generators, transformers and
electrical panels, just as they did last week to protect the
electric substation.
</P>
<P>
   If water reaches that equipment, officials must take the plant
off line. The city would have to rely on its stored water supply,
which could last about four to five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's touch and go,'' said Ron Elks, GUC's water resources
director. ``Right now we are still doing fine. But if the water
continues to rise or hold at high levels for several more days, we
could find ourselves without enough raw water to treat.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of one to three inches of rain over the next
several days has everyone on edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what everybody is worrying about now,'' said Sharon
Daughtridge, an operator at the water treatment plant. ``If we get
any more water _ I just don't know. I don't know what else we can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   GUC crews have worked non-stop since Hurricane Floyd dumped 13
inches of rain on the area Wednesday and Thursday. Those downpours
fell on an already saturated ground from Hurricane Dennis' repeat
visits and other recent rains.
</P>
<P>
   That water has found places to go. It has submerged houses, the
Pitt-Greenville Airport and GUC's Operations Center, destroying
several trucks, the building's contents and employees' personal
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything over there is just ruined,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding forced GUC to relocate its emergency operations
center to its downtown office. The lobby has become a refreshment
station, with weary workers picking at tables of everything from
Pop Tarts and bread to chips and crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them are clinging to cellular telephones and hand-held
radios, the main means of communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prepare for disasters. That's a part of the business. This
is extreme,'' said Howard Corey, GUC's water resources engineering
coordinator. ``I've seen people do things, rise up and figure out
solutions where you don't think there are solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   After relying for several days on helicopters to cart workers,
generators, sandbags and food to the water plant, officials added
several boats to their arsenal Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Greensboro Fire Department and Forsyth Rescue Squad turned a
submerged bridge near the airport into a boat dock.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in wet-suits, crews made the eight-minute trip to the
plant more than a dozen times, once stopping to rescue two people
and some pets from a flooded house.
</P>
<P>
   After working three days with 1 1/2 hours sleep, one GUC
employee said the reason for the non-stop effort overrides his lack
of rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really think about it when you do it. It's the
company you work for. You just do what has to be done,'' he said,
sitting on the railing of the submerged bridge after being ferried
from the water treatment plant. ``We are going to beat it. We are
not going to let the floodwaters beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, George Fuller, a GUC crew leader, strapped on a
life jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some guys out there are tired. I've had plenty of rest.
I'm here to help serve,'' he said, returning for the second time in
three days to help fill sandbags.
</P>
<P>
   Like soldiers ready to enter battle, GUC workers armed with
waders and a change of clothes climbed into boats, anxious to see
what their workplace looks like. They've already heard warnings
about snakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see all kinds of Herculean efforts,'' Elks said.
</P>
<P>
   The water plant, sitting in the middle of what is now a lake,
resembled a war zone.
</P>
<P>
   A stalled front-end loader sat lopsided beside the
administration building; crews stood beside a wall of sandbags
monitoring the hum of the sump pumps, and workers waded through
waist-high river water. Nearby, soaked clothing was draped along a
railing. Overhead, President Clinton's convoy of choppers circled
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Daughtridge, a water plant operator, eyed the generator that
keeps the plant running, the one crews are trying to shield with
sandbags.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to keep that generator dry. If we don't, we can't
provide water,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To get from that generator to the operations building, which is
just feet away, workers have to stand in the scoop of an oversized
front-end loader and be carted to the other side of the building to
enter.
</P>
<P>
   The building's first floor is ankle-deep in water, Sandbags
protect electrical equipment. Pumps push the water through an open
window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is critical. Every little thing becomes a potential
dream killer,'' said Wayne Meads, a GUC water resources engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the chaos, GUC orchestrated a way to restore power to
Greenville on Saturday night and handle other minor emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The water) is hitting things nobody ever thought of,'' Green
said. ``It's pushed us, but we have been able to maintain service.
It's pushed us way up into our contingencies.''
</P>
<P>
   With a backpack of food and another holding dry clothes,
Daughtridge jumped off the front-end loader to start her 24-hour
shift. ``Home sweet home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Bryant writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
