<SLUG> BC-CMGI-ADFORCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI TO ACQUIRE ADFORCE IN $500M STOCK DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to improve the effectiveness of its on-line advertising,
CMGI Inc. said it plans to acquire a California Internet-promotions
company for about $500 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, the Andover, Mass. venture investment firm that
specializes in Internet companies, said it will buy AdForce Inc. of
Cupertino, Calif. and help it catch up to competitors by creating
synergies between AdForce and two other CMGI units.
</P>
<P>
   AdForce and the two CMGI units, AdSmart and Engage Technologies
Inc., are all involved in distributing commerical content over the
World Wide Web to users who, based on their demographic profile or
past selections, are judged to be more likely to respond.
</P>
<P>
   AdSmart, a wholly-owned division of CMGI, already applies this
theory to the distribution of ads from other companies. Engage, in
which CMGI owns a majority, creates software used for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
   AdForce's role is to function as a broker, assembling blocks of
material from 300 companies including America Online Inc. and the
World Wrestling Federation. It then distributes the material over
sites such as sports pages run by CBS.com.
</P>
<P>
   AdForce had already provided some material to Adsmart's network
under a previous partnership. Following the planned acquisition,
which still requires approvals from AdForce shareholders and the
Securities and Exchange Commission, AdForce will operate as an
independent unit within CMGI.
</P>
<P>
   AdForce's 160 employees will remain at offices in Cupertino and
Costa Mesa, Calif., and in New York. AdForce chief executive Chuck
Berger will continue to run the company.
</P>
<P>
   Engage has about 350 employees and Adsmart has about 150, none
of whom will likely be affected by the acquisition, said CMGI
marketing manager Bill White.
</P>
<P>
   First Albany electronic-commerce analyst Ullas Naik said the
deal should effectively expand CMGI's advertising network by giving
it access to a greater range of material with which to draw in
users. Eventually that should allow it to increase the rates it
charges ad producers to distribute such content.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more targetable the ads, the more valuable their
real-estate becomes,'' Naik said of CMGI's advertising operations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ends months of uncertainty for AdForce, whose shares
have declined to less than a third of their high of $62.73 since
May on concerns the company was losing ground to competitors such
as DoubleClick Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   However, Doubleclick gains much of its revenue through
ad-placement agreements with the AltaVista search engine, the
majority of which CMGI purchased in June for about $2.3 billion,
mostly in stock.
</P>
<P>
   While those agreements will remain in place, CMGI's White said
certain subdivisions of AltaVista might soon begin drawing ads from
the AdForce network instead.
</P>
<P>
   For the three months ended June 30, AdForce reported a loss of
$5.2 million on revenue of $4.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, CMGI will exchange 0.262 of
its shares for each of the 19.9 million oustanding shares in
AdForce. Based on Monday's closing prices the deal values each
AdForce share at $21.86, a 12 percent premium over AdForce's
closing price on Friday. Including outstanding warrants and other
obligations, AdForce has about 23.5 million shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in AdForce rose 3/4 to close at $20 1/4 in Nasdaq trading
Monday. Shares in CMGI rose 3 7/16 to close at $83 7/16 on the same
exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
