<HEADER>
A9296 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TIMOR-PEACEKEEPING-BO     09-20 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-PEACEKEEPING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACEKEEPING FORCE BRINGS QUICK ORDER IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ In less than 12 hours Monday, the first
elements of a multinational peacekeeping force took control of East
Timor's ravaged capital and began to disarm murderous
pro-Indonesian militias, achieving in one day what Indonesian
troops were unable or unwilling to do for the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen military flights and several ships carried
the first 1,190 heavily armed peacekeepers into Dili from northern
Australia before sunset, equipped with a UN mandate to restore
order and facilitate humanitarian relief in the devastated
territory.
</P>
<P>
   The troops, unlike UN peacekeepers in Bosnia several years ago,
have the right to use force to stop a rampage of one-sided
violence. Pro-Jakarta militias, apparently aided by Indonesian
security forces, unleashed a vicious backlash after 79 percent of
East Timorese voted to separate from Indonesia on Aug. 30. The
revenge campaign has claimed thousands of lives, destroyed
uncountable assets, and displaced 800,000 people _ nearly all of
East Timor's population, according to UN and Red Cross estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Two ships anchored off Dili were to dock early Tuesday, kicking
off a second day of deployment, with a total of 2,500 troops
expected to be in place by Tuesday night. The force is expected to
grow to 8,000 personnel from about 20 countries, and will remain in
East Timor until a longer-term UN force takes over to monitor the
territory's transition to independence.
</P>
<P>
   Dili was smoldering from fresh fires and destruction, but
otherwise quiet as the first Hercules C-130 cargo plane touched
down at dawn. It disgorged soldiers in jungle camouflage and flak
jackets who charged off to secure the airstrip, some squatting low
with their guns raised overhead. Squinting in the harsh sunlight,
commandos in full combat gear kicked their way through trash and
stepped over human waste littering the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The city was a ruined ghost town, devoid of cars or people on
the streets, and the smell of rot tainted the air.
</P>
<P>
   Feared civilian militiamen who had rampaged through Dili,
looting, burning, and shooting for the last two weeks, glowered
silently as the Australian-led troops secured the airport and
docks, unloading soldiers and supplies throughout the day. Radical
militia leaders had in recent days threatened to kill and ``eat the
hearts'' of foreign peacekeepers. But the force met no resistance
on its first day, and got help from the Indonesian military in the
form of vitally needed trucks. Peacekeepers also managed to disarm
at least two militiamen carrying homemade guns.
</P>
<P>
   Other men wearing red-and-white headbands in the colors of
Indonesia's flag crowded anxiously onto boats leaving the port;
many were joined by their families. Hundreds of other displaced
people who were sleeping at the port under tarpaulins seemed happy
to see the troops arriving, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town is a heap...but there is no animosity,'' said Bryson
Keenan, one of the first Australian officers to arrive Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Two fires raged in different sections of Dili, sending sparks
high in the air. It was unclear who set the fires, but organizers
of the UN-mandated force fear that embittered Jakarta supporters
and elements of the Indonesian military might try to sabotage the
peacekeeping operation or test its mettle.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment marks the first time foreign troops have set foot
on Indonesian-controlled territory since independence more than 50
years ago. It also marks a key transition for the disputed
territory of East Timor, a former Portuguese colony at the
southeastern end of the Indonesian island chain that Jakarta
invaded in 1975 and has occupied ever since.
</P>
<P>
   When pro-Jakarta gunmen wreaked havoc followed the Sept. 4
announcement of a landslide vote for independence, Indonesia at
first insisted that its military could control the situation. But
the government last week acknowledged that at least some ``rogue''
soldiers were participating in the revenge campaign, and buckled to
pressure to accept international peacekeepers, as long as
Indonesian soldiers served alongside foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, commander of the
multinational force, said the first troops ``met absolutely no
resistance...By and large, it has been a cordial reception.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Kiki Syahnakri, Indonesian military chief in East
Timor, said over the weekend he was withdrawing most of his troops
and would hand over command of East Timor _ and of six remaining
Indonesian batallions _ after the multinational force had fully
deployed.
</P>
<P>
   An advance team of US Marines entered East Timor with the first
wave of the multinational force, on a one-day mission to survey the
territory. The US has committed 200 support troops for
intelligence, communications, and transport.
</P>
<P>
   Just after midnight in Darwin Monday, a C-5 Galaxy transport
plane unloaded 18 US Navy personnel and satellite communications
equipment. It could be days or even weeks before US troops are
posted in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The first job of the UN mission dubbed ``Operation Stabilize''
is to secure Dili, and then to fan out to the hills where people
fled to escape violence and are now believed to be in danger of
starvation. A key challenge will be transporting humanitarian aid,
since there are few vehicles and very little gasoline left after
two weeks of looting and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor's rugged terrain also presents challenges; the
Ramelau mountain range has peaks rising above 9,000 feet, and in
the interior, unreliable passes snake along ridgelines. During the
rainy season, streams often cut off roads.
</P>
<P>
   In Darwin, UN humanitarian aid coordinator Abdulmejid Hussein
said he was ``cautiously optimistic that the situation will be
stabilized quickly'' and that aid can be delivered largely by land
and by sea.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein said relief work would begin in earnest ``as soon as the
security situation permits. We are very, very much ready. We could
have gone in even...a few days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   World Food Program spokeswoman Abby Spring said a $5.6 million
emergency program to feed 150,000 over the next two months could be
extended if necessary. ``These are people who didn't have a lot of
food to begin with,'' she said, raising the danger of quick
starvation from chronic malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   In Jakarta, Indonesia's military chief Gen. Wiranto told
parliament not to believe reports of war crimes or estimates that
thousands of people died in the recent violence, saying his
official death toll was under 100.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Armed Forces chief of territorial affairs Lt. Gen.
Bambang Yudhoyono told reporters: ``I am worried about opinion
being formed in the international community that what happened in
East Timor is a great human tragedy, ethnic cleansing or a
large-scale crime, when in reality it was not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
