<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOOD-NC-MAIN-COX     09-20 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-NC-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    While water recedes, Floyd's flood victims hope Harvey stays
away
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARBORO, N.C. _ Flood water from Hurricane Floyd remains
everywhere. A fetid cocktail of sewage and drowned hogs, turkeys
and chickens began receding Monday, leaving a brown stain on the
grass.
</P>
<P>
   More rain from Tropical Storm Harvey this week could make things
even worse.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Thelma Bridgers has been out of her home since
Thursday. She is one of more than 6,500 people still in North
Carolina shelters. Another 1,500 remain stranded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might find anything floating in your house _ snakes, rats,
dogs _ anything that has died in the water,'' Bridgers said Monday,
sitting in the shade of Tarboro High School. ``I left with what I
had on. I did not know the water was going to keep coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton toured the engulfed area Monday, offering
comfort and federal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a stage in downtown Tarboro, a few yards from the
receding flood waters, Clinton urged people in the 66 counties
declared national disaster areas to seek assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agencies are offering emergency Food Stamps,
low-interest loans, temporary housing and cash assistance. The U.S.
Labor Department authorized $12 million in emergency funds to
create temporary jobs to clean up North Carolina's worst natural
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who need it ought to take it,'' Clinton told several
hundred people during his tour of flood-ravaged areas east of
Raleigh. ``There is nothing to be ashamed of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Overflowing lagoons of animal waste and runoff from sewage
plants have deluged water treatment systems.
</P>
<P>
   In Jones County, the smell of rotting hogs filled the air. A
clean-up crew towed a pair of industrial-size incinerators to
dispose of the animal debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're telling us 100,000 hogs and a half million chickens,''
said Ronnie Jordan, a contractor hired to get rid of carcasses in
Jones County. He fears there may be many more.
</P>
<P>
   Contaminated water could be fatal for young children and the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a huge number of different risks out there right
now,'' said Johanna Reese from the North Carolina Division of
Environmental Health. ``The most immediate one we have is lack of
safe drinking water.''
</P>
<P>
   Flood waters have shut down the eastern third of North Carolina,
and the damage may exceed the $6 billion total from Fran in 1996,
the state's costliest natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100 campers have been hauled to Tarboro Park which will
become a center for evacuees, said Richard Moore, the state's
public safety director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of North Carolina will probably be the biggest
landlord in Edgecombe County within the next few days,'' Moore
said, adding that more than 1,000 campers and mobile homes for
displaced people may be needed.
</P>
<P>
   There are similar problems in Virginia, where Floyd washed fuel
oil, pesticides and untreated water into the streets of Franklin.
No smoking is permitted within 100 feet of roped-off roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the water catch on fire?'' one woman whose husband stayed
at their flooded home asked Mayor Jim Councill, whose business was
among those flooded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That I can't answer you,'' the mayor said. ``But it's
contaminated.''
</P>
<P>
   More rain is headed to Virginia, and that could keep downtown
underwater for days to come. Nearly 150 homes are under as much as
15 feet of contaminated water. Just outside town, the International
Paper Mill _ the area's largest employer _ remains closed.
</P>
<P>
   And Floyd spread his tarnish up the East Coast. As of Monday
evening, 62 deaths had been blamed on the storm and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   On the Raritan River town of Bound Brook, N.J., a layer of red
mud clogged streets. The National Guard stopped people from
returning home so inspectors could examine buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Damage in New Jersey could top $100 million, said Gov. Christie
Whitman. Evacuees pleaded for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in these clothes since Thursday,'' said Charnett
Hillireo. ``I have a 4-year-old here. He's going nuts. He didn't
fall asleep till 4 a.m. He just keeps crying, `Mommy, I want to go
home.' Who's going to help us?''
</P>
<P>
   Back in North Carolina, Gov. Jim Hunt pleaded for private
donations to bolster government aid coordinated by the Federal
Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President, tell the nation that we have tens and tens of
thousands of people without homes,'' said Hunt, adding that 1,500
people remain stranded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have suffered a terrible disaster in eastern North
Carolina,'' Hunt told Clinton, ``and you have seen it with your own
eyes. It is certainly the worst disaster we've ever had in North
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 300 roads remained closed in North Carolina, hampering
emergency crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge you to keep your spirits up and know we're going to be
with you every step of the way,'' Clinton told about 500 people in
Tarboro, an 11,000-resident historic town flanked by tobacco and
cotton fields.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Nightwolves'' air squadron from NAS Atlanta has helped
control North Carolina air space for the military helicopters in
rescue and relief missions. A combination of reserve and full-time
pilots from the Marietta, Ga., base could be in North Carolina for
up to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, helicopters from the National Guard, Air Force, Navy,
Marines, Army and Coast Guard shuttled food. In several towns,
grocery shelves are bare, the water undrinkable. Clinton said
federal, state and local rescue crews saved ``almost 1,000 lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The president urged people who remain in shelters to stay there
until flooding has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be safe'' before you return, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember there is a God of history; there is a God of
creation,'' said U.S. Rep. Eva Clayton (D-N.C.). ``A God of comfort
brings the best out in people.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 3,000 people crowded Tarboro High School, one of 18
area shelters opened after Floyd dumped 20 inches of rain on
eastern North Carolina . The region was still drying out from
Hurricane Dennis two weeks earlier. That storm dumped nearly 10
inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a new double-wide, and I never got to spend a night in
it,'' said Barbara Carr, 39, at Tarboro High with her six children.
'' We got out with the clothes on our backs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy is none of these damage claims are insured,'' said
Ed Roberson, 50, a Tarboro insurance agent who listened to
Clinton's speech. ''People do not have flood insurance because they
do not live in a flood plain.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson's business on Main Street was flooded. ``The water has
never come up this high before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials accompanying Clinton offered hope, made easier, they
said, by people helping one another.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said rescuers in boats heard people inside a house nearly
covered by water. They cut open the roof and found 11 people in the
attic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank all the heroes who have saved lives,'' Hunt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
