NYT-09-20-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9306 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-ONCE-SPI &LR;      09-20 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ONCE-SPI </SLUG>
  
 ABC's `ONCE &AMP; AGAIN' BEST OFFER OF THE NEW TV SEASON   
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Please watch ``Once &AMP; Again'' more often than once and again.
Please, please, please, please, please.
</P>
<P>
   If enough of us watch, ABC won't cancel ``Once &AMP; Again'' the way
it deep-sixed ``My So-Called Life'' and ``Relativity'' and
``Nothing Sacred'' and ``Maximum Bob'' and ``Murder One.''
</P>
<P>
   In this season's menu of new offerings, ``Once &AMP; Again'' is the
berries &AMP; cream: fresh and rich, sweet and pungent. With writing to
rival the best movies and camera work to match, it gives commercial
TV something to shout about. The performances of Sela Ward and
Billy Campbell are so full of truth that acting coaches will be
using the series in how-to seminars.
</P>
<P>
   Ward and Campbell play parents in their 40s, both divorced, both
with a couple of kids, both with a fear of what's lurking out
there, romance-wise, now that their marriages have failed.
</P>
<P>
   In the chatty style that drew millions of American baby boomers
to ``thirtysomething'' a decade ago, creators Edward Zwick and
Marshall Herskovitz are now exploring what's happening to many of
them as they hit their 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's character, Lily Manning, helps her sister run a bookstore
while doing the single-mom juggling act. Campbell plays Rick
Sammler, an architect who's a bit more aloof as a parent but
learning fast as he begins to see more of himself than he'd like in
his 16-year-old son, Eli (Shane West).
</P>
<P>
   The emotional tugging in ``Once &AMP; Again'' will test the stoutest
lines, the surest knots. Lily's older daughter, Grace (Julia
Whelan) is having self-esteem problems. Younger daughter Zoe
(Meredith Deane) isn't ready for a second dad. Putting her kids
first comes naturally to Lily, but does she do so at the peril of
her own well-being?
</P>
<P>
   Zwick and Herskovitz take the self-analysis that was the
hallmark of ``thirtysomething'' and extend it even further in
``Once &AMP; Again.'' By placing Lily and Rick in occasional
black-and-white segments separate from the main story, they set the
audience up as a sort of collective psychoanalyst. As Lily and Rick
pour out their hopes, their fears, their dreams, we get sucked into
their lives even more.
</P>
<P>
   It's a device sometimes used to mask bad scripts, but Zwick and
Herskovitz cleverly use it to advance the story.
</P>
<P>
   And don't worry. Lily and Rick aren't wacko. They're pretty
normal, in fact, with the usual insecurities of anyone who has
experienced a foundering relationship. As Rick says in one of his
``sessions'': ``If somebody knew that I didn't want them for them,
but basically because I was scared to death of being alone, I can't
imagine why they'd want me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once &AMP; Again'' is like that throughout: refreshingly real,
reflecting the thoughts of people who are uncompromisingly ordinary
in an age when TV characters aren't considered interesting unless
they're quirky.
</P>
<P>
   Once &AMP; Again. One-hour drama series about a budding romance
between two fortysomething single parents. Starring Sela Ward,
Billy Campbell, Julia Whelan, Shane West, Meredith Deane and Evan
Rachel Wood. Premieres Tuesday night on ABC. Parental guideline
rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
