<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9308 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-GRIFFI     09-20 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-GRIFFIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASKET SAYS IT ALL FOR CHURCH SHOOTING VICTIM CASSANDRA GRIFFIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By REBECA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The casket said it all.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, at the age of 14, Cassandra Griffin was laid to rest
in a bold blue casket with clouds painted on its lid.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting for a young woman so many describe as an angel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today some of you picked up the newspaper and you read the
obituary column, Cassie Griffin had died,'' said the Rev. Al
Meredith, pastor of Wedgwood Baptist Church, where the funeral took
place. ``Don't you believe it. This is not Cassie,'' he said,
pointing to her casket. ``Her soul and her spirit are with the
Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, a freshman at North Crowley High School, was one of
seven people shot to death on Wednesday at the church by a gunman
who then killed himself. They had gathered to pray, sing and
worship. But yesterday, in that fateful place, gunshots were
replaced by thunderous singing, screams were replaced by joyous
shouts to the Lord, and the gaping void left by the shooting was
filled with love and hope.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds gathered in the arc-shaped sanctuary, which seemed to
enclose the grieving family with loving arms. In the front row,
Cassie's parents David and Tralissa Griffin sat and held one
another. Cassie's brother, 11-year-old Chris, held a rainbow
colored Beanie Baby bear _ Peace.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding the casket was a brilliant sea of color _ pink
roses, yellow carnations, white lilies and orange and purple birds
of paradise. On either side of the casket floated lime-green
balloons in the shape of a frog, which represents a motto of the
church's youth: Fully Rely On God.
</P>
<P>
   People began filling the sanctuary an hour before the 2 p.m.
service. They lined up by the dozens to sign the casket with black
indelible markers. As they wrote, they hugged, cried and murmured
quiet words of comfort to one another.
</P>
<P>
   During the service, youth pastor Jay Fannin showed a homemade
video of young people praying at their school flag poles Wednesday
morning, part of a national See You at the Pole rally. The shooting
happened before the video could be shown at the church's evening
service.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the service, an emotional Meredith took the
podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many of you have been to the funeral of a martyr before?''
he asked those in the crowd. ``This is my fifth one in three
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Skinner, 14, and Robert DeBord, 17, were honorary
pallbearers and sat in the front row. Both were injured in the
shooting. Also attending were Mary Beth Talley and Jaynanne Brown,
who also were wounded, and Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr.
</P>
<P>
   As the service drew to a close, a clarinetist played ``Amazing
Grace'' while ushers opened Griffin's casket to allow people one
last glimpse of the young life that had touched so many.
</P>
<P>
   Some cried loudly and clutched Griffin's relatives in a tight
hug. One man dressed in a military uniform presented David Griffin
with an American flag, folded in a triangle, and saluted him.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fitting gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a Christian soldier, killed in the line of duty,''
said the Rev. Don Robertson of Plainview, who baptized Cassie
Griffin. ``Jesus died for her. She died for Him.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
