<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9313 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OLY-ATLANTAGAMES-COX     09-20 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTAGAMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta bid for Games is defended
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ U.S. Olympic Committee officials on Monday defended
attorney Griffin Bell's contention that the International Olympic
Committee had created a culture of corruption that exploited bid
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Griffin Bell) report does nothing to alter what we are
clear about,'' said Mike Moran, a USOC spokesman. ``This is much
wider than any American city.''
</P>
<P>
   The USOC forwarded a copy of Bell's report on the Atlanta
lobbying effort to the IOC late last week. In a cover letter, an
USOC attorney said the Colorado Springs, Colo., organization did
not plan any further investigation into the Atlanta bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned all the lessons to be learned in this,'' said
Scott Blackmon, deputy executive director and lead counsel of the
USOC. ``Based on what we've seen in the report, it looks like more
of the same culture. There's nothing different between what
happened in Atlanta and Salt Lake City.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC demanded last week the USOC explain why details of
Atlanta's gifts, travel payments and scholarship offers were not
included in an earlier report the USOC provided in an IOC inquiry
into improprieties in candidate cities.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said he believed the IOC had been seeking information
about its own members making improper requests of bid cities in its
February inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were looking for information about IOC members
approaching candidate cities. Atlanta informed us there was no
additional information, which we relayed to the IOC,'' Moran
offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe we have a problem with what they told us in
February,'' he said. ``It seems to be more weighted the other way''
with the bidders making improper offers.
</P>
<P>
   The report turned over to Congressional lawmakers last week
revealed that Atlanta bidders offered or considered lavish favors,
gifts and perks for IOC members and their families, including
college scholarships, free healthcare and job offers. The report
amended a previous accounting given to a U.S. House Commerce
committee investigation opened in the wake of the Salt Lake City
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Moran appears to corroborate the IOC's contention last week that
Atlanta bidders ``pushed'' the favors and gifts onto the IOC
members ``under the pretext of friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Moran said the USOC would not be drawn into a
finger-pointing spat. ``To affix blame here is not very helpful,''
he said. ``The question of whether cities are forcing something on
IOC members or whether IOC members are soliciting gifts is not the
point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our very own thorough look into this ... made it clear there
is a culture of this involving all bid cities and the IOC itself.
It has ebbed and flowed in various cities.''
</P>
<P>
   An ethics commission, headed by former Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell, investigated the Salt Lake City and determined the
IOC was an inbred, unethical group that fostered a ``culture of
improper gift giving.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten IOC members either resigned or were expelled in connection
with the Salt Lake City vote-buying scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Blackmon said the USOC couldn't afford another investigation.
``We have limited resources . We'd like to use those resources to
identify and train athletes.,'' he said. ``We spend an awful lot of
money in connection with Salt Lake. And we've already taken
corrective action.''
</P>
<P>
   Italian IOC member Mario Pescante, who led Rome's losing
campaign for the 2004 Games, accused the Americans of ducking
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't the Americans take the responsibility for the people
who organized this strategy of bribery and corruption? Who started
this? They did,'' Pescante told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are always against our movement. They don't have the
humility to criticize their own behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
