<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9317 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-F22-COX     09-20 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debate over F-22 Raptor turns to funding
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The debate over building the F-22 Raptor fighter
plane is shifting from whether it should be funded to a new fight
over how much money and how many planes will be built.
</P>
<P>
   That's a victory for the Georgia delegation, which has worked
hard to restore $1.8 billion in F-22 funding to the $266 billion
defense appropriations bill. That money would pay for the first
group of six fighters to be built at Lockheed Martin's Marietta,
Ga. plant.
</P>
<P>
   A special conference of House and Senate lawmakers will meet as
early as Wednesday to hash out a final figure. Congressional
supporters say that they are confident that the program will be
funded, but it is unclear how many planes will be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Their confidence comes from comments Appropriations Chairman
C.W. ``Bill'' Young, a Florida Republican, made to the St.
Petersburg Times over the weekend. Young told the paper that
Republican leaders from both the House and Senate had decided to
buy an unspecified number of the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Young's statement, coupled with the lift on budget caps, was
seen as a sign that the House was ready to work with the Senate to
fund the program. But some congressional staffers caution that no
deal is certain until the budget conference is finished.
</P>
<P>
   In Marietta, Lockheed Martin Aeronautical Systems issued a
statement saying it is ``encouraged by media reports concerning the
F-22 funding issue. At this time, however, we are not aware of any
specific details concerning how Congress may choose to resolve this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Cales, an Air Force spokeswoman at the Pentagon, said the
service ``doesn't have anything new on the issue. We're still
working with the congressional leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, both Lockheed Martin and the Air Force have
suggested that even a cut in the number of planes in the first
production lot would be counterproductive because it would disrupt
the supply chain and boost unit costs.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise move last summer, House budget leaders cut $1.8
billion from the $3.1 billion requested for the program in the next
fiscal year. The Senate approved the full amount, setting the stage
for a showdown between the House and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   By nixing the funding, the House put the $62 billion program
into limbo. Under current plans, Lockheed would build 339 aircraft
over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Cancellation of the F-22 program would be a severe blow to
Lockheed Martin and especially to the Marietta plant. Some analysts
believe the company would be forced to consolidate its aircraft
business, now split among Georgia, Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this indicates pretty clearly that the lights will
stay on the program,'' said Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) whose district
includes the plant. ``This is important for Georgia and our
national defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) agreed, but added he's frustrated that
the House put the F-22 program in jeopardy to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I don't like is the gamesmanship,'' Cleland said. ``The
entire program got ambushed by the House. They took the entire $1.8
billion and shifted it off to their own favorite programs, leaving
the F-22 high and dry. I think there are some people playing games
with national security. ``
</P>
<P>
   The attack was led by Rep. Jerry Lewis (R-Calif.), chairman of
the appropriations subcommittee. Lewis contends the Air Force
should re-examine its need for the F-22 when compared with upgrades
to pay and existing weapons systems. Ironically, the House version
of the defense budget includes money for extra C-130J cargo planes,
also built in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Sprecht, press secretary to Lewis, said if his boss had the
opportunity to address the Senate appropriations committee members,
``he could make them understand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But as a longtime appropriator, he's always willing to work
with Senate appropriators to pass the appropriations bills by the
end of the fiscal year,'' Sprecht said.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of the fiscal year fast approaching on Sept. 30,
congressional aides said, Lewis decided to work with the Senate
appropriators and not contest the program.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor influencing Lewis was his formidable opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Cleland and Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.)
gathered signatures from three-fifths of the Senate in support of
the program. Two of those signatures came from Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) and Minority Leader Tom Daschle
(D-S.D.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation's commitment to this program began some two decades
ago,'' Coverdell said. ``I simply cannot fathom why someone would
throw that investment away at this juncture.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the House, Speaker Dennis Hastert (R-Ill.) and Majority
Leader Dick Armey (R-Texas) have given their support for the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the chairman (Lewis) has had a lot of leadership
pressure put on him,'' said Rep. Jack Kingston (R-Ga.), a member of
the appropriations committee. ``There has been a barrage of support
on both sides of the aisle for the F-22. It has been an incessant
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Scott Thurston contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
