<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-TRIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND MAN TRIED IN DRAGING DEATH FOUND GUILTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ White supremacist Lawrence Russell Brewer, who
described himself in prison notes as a ``soaring eagle'' and ``hero
of the day,'' was brought down to earth on Monday when a jury found
him guilty of capital murder in the dragging death of a black man.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, 32, who has served time for house burglary, showed no
emotion when the jury of five women and seven men, including one
Hispanic, announced its verdict after four hours' deliberation in
the second trial to arise from the torture slaying of James Byrd
Jr. in Jasper, Texas, last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, so good,'' the victim's father, James Byrd Sr., said
after the punishment phase of the trial began. Brewer could be
sentenced to death, or life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution on Tuesday will call one more witness, a
psychiatrist, to testify about whether Brewer represents a future
threat to society. Defense lawyers declined to say how many
witnesses they plan to call, but the jury is expected to begin
deliberating Brewer's punishment on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second weight has been lifted from our shoulders,'' Byrd's
sister Mary Verrett told reporters. She said testimony showed
Brewer ``enjoyed what he did to my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was tortured, then he was killed and they got much
satisfaction out of that,'' Verrett said. ``And we the Byrd family
are satisfied right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray said he was
relieved at the verdict. The South Central Texas jury took 90
minutes longer to convict Brewer than a Jasper jury took find John
William King guilty in Jasper. King was sentenced to death. The
third man charged, Shawn Berry, 24, is expected to be tried in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 22 years, it doesn't get any easier,'' Gray said. ``It
scares you. Everyone was nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial was shifted from Jasper in East Texas, where the
killing occurred, 135 miles west to Bryan because of pretrial
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of Texas, particularly East Texas, is embarrassed by that
history (of racial violence) from 60 to 70 years ago,'' Gray said.
``When Jasper turned the case against Bill King, some people would
say they were just trying to protect themselves. When you move it
half way across the state of Texas and another jury returns a
guilty verdict, it kind of broadens the scope, speaks for the whole
state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said the DNA evidence placing Brewer at the scene where
Byrd was beaten and chained behind a pickup was the strongest
evidence. The case, he said, got a major boost when Brewer
testified, acknowledging he was at the scene and confirming he
smoked and drank there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The just punishment for this case in this set of circumstances
is death,'' Gray said. ``Will he be a danger in the future? I don't
see any answer to that but, yes, he will be a danger.''
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Brewer _ an exalted cyclops of a prison Ku
Klux Klan gang and self-described Aryan warrior _ intermittently
sobbed last week as he told the jury that he had no intention to
kill Byrd. He blamed Berry for slashing Byrd's throat, then
dragging him for three miles behind the pickup.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing argument, Gray said Brewer took the stand to
craft a scenario that put him at the scene _ which DNA evidence had
proven _ but made himself out to be a non-participant in Byrd's
kidnapping and slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He admitted enough to comply with the facts ... and just
staying short of the death penalty,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were three men in the truck, three men who smoked and
three men who had blood on their shoes,'' said Gray, who listed the
three different accounts Brewer gave of his actions to authorities
before the trial, in prison notes, and in his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a racist white supremacist like Bill King,'' the
prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Brewer blamed Byrd's kidnapping and murder on
Berry, who was the first suspect to give an account to
investigators. He said Brewer cut Byrd's throat before chaining him
behind the pickup.
</P>
<P>
   But in his closing statement, Gray said the dragging marks
started more than 60 feet from where Byrd was beaten, and there
wasn't enough blood at the scene or on Berry's clothes to
corroborate Brewer's account that Byrd's throat was cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lied when he told you he wasn't a racist and he lied when
he told you Shawn Berry cut James Byrd Jr.'s throat,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said that Byrd was alive and conscious before he
was chained to the bumper of Berry's pickup, and that, judging from
the black man's size, it took three men to subdue him long enough
to fasten the chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous amount of pressure for a conviction,''
Layne Walker, one of Brewer's defense attorneys, said in his
closing arguments. ``I know it. You know it. They know it,'' he
said, referring to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job of making you hate Russell Brewer.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0169 </DOCNO>
