<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-HACKED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE E-MAILS USER FIND THEIR PRIVACY VIOLATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: L0pht Heavy Industries in the penultimate graf is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As many as 4 million users of free electronic mail systems may
have been vulnerable to a gaping security hole that would let
anybody on the Internet read their mail. The incident is the latest
example of the risks involved in using free e-mail systems for
private communications.
</P>
<P>
   The problem affected free e-mail service on a number of major
Web sites including the E(asterisk)Trade on-line investment service
and Network Solutions Inc., the biggest provider of Internet
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   There was no evidence that anyone maliciously tampered with mail
at these sites. In addition, the e-mail system at E(asterisk)Trade
is entirely separate from that site's financial trading computers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the insecure mail system is run by Critical Path Inc.
of San Francisco, which sells e-mail service to other firms.
Companies like E(asterisk)Trade and Network Solutions offer
Critical Path e-mail as a free service to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions began offering free e-mail accounts last week,
and it was apparently some of these users who discovered the
problem. They found that by typing a certain address into a Web
browser and entering the name of a free e-mail user, they would be
registered as a ``new user'' of the system, but with full access to
the original user's mailbox. They could read the user's mail, or
send out phony messages that would appear to come from the actual
owner of the mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the problem was posted on the Internet's Hacker News
Network, and on a Web page run by 2600, a hacker magazine. The 2600
page described how to duplicate the bug. Soon the mailbox for
Network Solutions' own Web master was flooded with insulting
messages, mocking the lack of security at a site run by the company
that manages the ``.com'' Internet addresses used by most of the
world's major Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But Network Solutions wasn't to blame. Marcy Swenson, vice
president of engineering for Critical Path, conceded that the bug
resided on her firm's system and that it probably affected other
sites using Critical Path e-mail. Overall, Swenson said, about 4
million Internet users have free e-mail accounts running on the
Critical Path system.
</P>
<P>
   Swenson said Critical Path had shut down its system for allowing
the registration of new users, and expected to have the bug tracked
down and fixed by Tuesday. ``I can think of no other instance of
something like this,'' said Swenson. ``We're constantly working to
improve our security.''
</P>
<P>
   But Weld Pond, a security consultant with L0pht Heavy Industries
Inc., a Boston computer security firm, said systems such as
Critical Path's are rarely secure. ``This is not news to anyone in
the security industry,'' said Pond. ``These free, Web-based e-mail
systems are just riddled with security problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Microsoft Corp.'s Hotmail, which with 40 million
users is the world's largest free e-mail system, was beset by a
similar flaw that let anybody sneak into mailboxes belonging to
others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9330 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-APPLE-SETBACK-NYT &LR;      09-20 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SETBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE SAYS IT WILL NOT MEET EXPECTATIONS FOR QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the first setback for Apple Computer Inc.
since the return of the company's co-founder Steven Jobs two years
ago, the company said Monday that shipments, revenues and earnings
for the current quarter will fall short of expectations as a result
of smaller-than-expected deliveries of microprocessor chips from
Motorola Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Apple made the announcement after the market had closed. But the
warning sent Apple's share price down almost 10 points in
after-hours trading Monday evening. After rising 2 1/8 to 79 1/16,
within pennies of the all-time high, during regular NASDAQ trading,
it dropped quickly to 69 7/8 after the warning was issued.
</P>
<P>
   Since announcing its new PowerMac G4 line of desktop computers
on Aug. 31, Apple has received more than 150,000 orders. These
machines are based on the G4 version of the Power PC microprocessor
co-developed by Apple, Motorola and IBM Corp. Although both
Motorola and IBM manufactured previous generations of the Power PC
chip, Motorola is the sole source for the G4.
</P>
<P>
   ''They may be paying the price for the fact that IBM lost
interest in serving Apple a year ago,'' said Michael Slater, an
editor with the Microprocessor Report, an industry newsletter.
``Apple is stuck with one processor supplier, although they're not
worse off than anyone with a Pentium III system,'' he said,
referring to Intel Corp.'s most powerful chip. ``The thing that is
different is the one-to-one connection: There is one supplier and
one customer'' for the G4, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stock will get hit because they now have a picture for the
quarter that is less than perfect, but I think it will blow over
fairly rapidly,'' said Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P.
Morgan. ``Supply problems are fairly high-class problems. Demand
problems are more fundamental.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple said it would earn between $75 million and $85 million,
which is equivalent to 42 cents to 48 cents per share, in the
quarter ending Sept. 30. Analysts had expected 76 cents, according
to First Call. Apple will report its results on Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, Apple's interim chief executive, said in a telephone
interview Monday that the response to the new PowerMac models had
been extremely strong but that Apple was going to receive only
about 40 percent to 45 percent of the microprocessors it had
expected during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, after we'd announced the products, Motorola
informed us they're having problems ramping up the G4 production,''
Jobs said. ``If this had occurred earlier in the quarter, we would
have had time to recover from it. We've been told by Motorola we
will have the processors we need to catch up early next quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Wilke, Motorola's corporate vice president and general
manager of personal computer systems, said that there had been no
problems with G4 production but that Apple's demand had grown
faster than expected. ``Demand is high and naturally, the customer
would like more chips than we can supply,'' he said. ``The only
time you don't have these sorts of challenges is when you launch a
product nobody wants to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple introduced three models of the G4, distinguished by
processors of different speeds and other features. The 400 mhz
model, priced at $1,599, was available immediately, with a 450mhz,
$2,499 machine to follow this month, and a 500 mhz, $3,499 version
in October. As is often the case with new microprocessors, the
faster versions are not being produced in anticipated quantities.
The 450 mhz PowerMac is only now beginning to ship, and the 500 mhz
version will not ship until November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The December quarter will be affected because the design and
publishing crowd wants the 500,'' said Charles Wolf, an analyst
with Warburg Dillon Read. ``We ordered a 450, and the anticipated
delivery was a month out. That threw it into the next quarter in
any event.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wolf said he thought Apple's setback would prove temporary,
noting that the company has 160,000 advance orders for the new
iBook portable, which is not affected by the G4 issue, and is also
expected to introduce a more powerful version of the popular iMac
as early as next month. ``It's a hiccup,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs said the company might not always have a single source in
Motorola for the Power PC chip, but he declined to comment on
whether there were ongoing negotiations with IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the rest of the PC market is buying pretty much solely
from Intel, it's not that big an issue,'' Jobs said. ``At least
we're a much bigger fish in this particular pond.''
</P>
<P>
   The temporary shortage of Motorola chips has to be viewed in
light of the strong demand for Apple's new products and its ongoing
recovery, Jobs said. ``Given where Apple's come from in the past 24
months, having a quarter where we're going to miss and still being
able to report $75 to $85 million in earnings is progress,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
