<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9335 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOOD-MISSING-COX     09-20 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-MISSING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Families awaiting word on relatives
 &HT;    By Travis Fain
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Questions from family and friends continued
to flow into city and county emergency operators Monday as rescues
continued throughout flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the queries came from out of state as family members
unable to make contact with evacuees searched for information that,
in many cases, was difficult to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people are in shelters that we just can't put
our hands on,'' Pitt County Schools spokesman Barry Gaskins said.
</P>
<P>
   County officials were working Monday to compile an exhaustive
list of the almost 2,000 people in official shelters around the
county, Gaskins said. But many people are in ``ad hoc'' shelters
not being operated by the county, making it hard to track down
relatives who have generated a stack of missing persons reports,
sheriff's department Chief of Community Patrols Rick Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just can't make contact (with family members) ...
sometimes we know that they're at a shelter, sometimes we don't,''
Fisher said. ``A lot of these folks are in churches and homes
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The confirmed death count in the county remained at two Monday,
the two Hispanic men found dead after flood waters swept them away
near Grimesland on Friday, Fisher said. Their names have not been
released pending notification of the families.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville police have scaled back their search for a man swept
off an N.C. 33 bridge on Wednesday night. That investigation is
continuing, but dive teams have stopped searching the area,
according to Capt. K.M. Smeltzer of the Greenville Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue calls for the county had slowed Monday, but were still
heavy enough that rescue personnel, sheriff's deputies, National
Guardsmen and volunteers continued to throw available resources
into efforts, especially north of the Tar River. That area has been
cut off from Greenville except by air, Gaskins said. Rescuers
continued to use an unknown but large number of boats, Jet Skis,
hovercraft and helicopters in the search, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are locating people reported missing as fast as they
can, but evacuation of flooded areas remained the focus of
emergency operations Monday, Gaskins said.
</P>
<P>
   People can try to locate family members in shelters by calling
Red Cross hotlines at (252) 355-0532, (252) 355-0280, (252)
355-0344, (252) 355-1055, (252) 355-0794 or (252) 355-1620.
</P>
<P>
   In the city of Greenville, rescue requests had stopped coming
into the emergency center Monday afternoon, but officials continued
to monitor water levels and draft plans to renew rescue operations
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers and public employees alike have worked a lot of long
hours since Hurricane Floyd hit Thursday morning, Gaskins said.
More help is coming as national Red Cross and Federal Emergency
Management Agency support were expected to kick in by today.
</P>
<P>
   Already, volunteers from rescue departments across the state
have come to Pitt County and other points in eastern North Carolina
to help.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, a string of about six rescue vehicles sat along
Fifth Street in front of city hall, mobilizing for an operation.
Crews stood preparing equipment and waiting for orders from state
emergency management, not knowing where they'd be that night, or
where they would go tomorrow. That type of uncertainty is typical
of rescue operations that mobilize so many people, rescuers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just wait and see on each one,'' said Larry Pierson, a
volunteer fireman from the Asheville area. ``And adapt.''
</P>
<P>
   The crews spend their days, and most of their nights, in boats,
keeping to drainage ditches to avoid unseen mailboxes or anything
else that might be underwater, Pierson said. They sleep a few hours
each morning wherever they can. For Mike Soule, a 22-year-old
Asheville-area rescuer, that once meant on an airport runway
outside of Kinston.
</P>
<P>
   Their own homes are safe and dry, but Pierson said they couldn't
watch Floyd's disaster on television and not help.
</P>
<P>
   ``And our time will come,'' he said. ``It's a state-wide scratch
your back.''
</P>
<P>
   Flooded homes, ruined photographs and other irreplaceables are
the worst Pierson and his colleagues have seen during their
operations, he said
</P>
<P>
   But the material losses from Hurricane Floyd pale in comparison
to the pain of parents separated from their children.
</P>
<P>
   Larrie Ward's husband took their children back into Belvoir as
waters continued to rise on Friday, she said. That's the last she
heard of them because the phones are out. When she tried to go
looking for them, authorities had closed area roads, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm blaming myself, because I never should have let them go
back,'' Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ward has asked at shelters, called police and talked
to neighbors, looking anywhere she can for word of Brandon, 14, or
Samantha, 8. No one knows where they are and no one can tell her
how high the water is at her husband's home, Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trusting in the Lord,'' Ward said. ``And thinking that
they're fine. I'm trying not to think of the worst, but it keeps
popping into my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward's mobile home is under water and when, _ if _ the rest of
her family is found, they'll have nowhere to go, she said. But
that's less of a concern right now, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just devastated,'' Ward said. ``It's just like I'm in a
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Tina Child knows the same helpless feeling. Her 18-year-old son,
Aaron, has been missing since Thursday at 2 p.m.. A Greenville
detective has been assigned to the case, Smeltzer said.
</P>
<P>
   The last Tina Child heard, Aaron was at his brother Adam's
apartment, taking a nap. When Adam came home, his brother was gone
and his wallet and keys were left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be doing something real stupid right now, just hasn't
called,'' Child said. ``But that's not like him.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Aaron's East Carolina University roommates told Child he
thinks the freshman called on Friday, but that offered little
comfort and even less information, she said. She posted Aaron's
picture around campus and in student apartment complexes. Police
asked television stations to run pictures of missing people, but
they wouldn't, saying they've logged too many requests for that to
be feasible, Smeltzer said.
</P>
<P>
   The pain, both mothers said, comes from not knowing where their
children are or how they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone could just tell me that they're alright,'' Smeltzer
said, her voice faltering. ``Then I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis Fain writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
