<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9337 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CASSIDY-MERGER-BOS &LR;      09-20 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASSIDY-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON LOBBYING FIRM, PR GIANT SEEN NEAR MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cassidy &AMP; Associates, the lobbying firm that has
raked in millions in federal funds for Boston University and served
as a revolving door for influential political figures, is on the
verge of merging with a New York public relations giant to form one
of the largest unions on Capitol Hill, sources familiar with the
negotiation said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would combine the Cassidy Cos., an umbrella
organization that includes three separate service branches, with
Shandwick International, a public relations firm with offices in 54
countries. Two sources familiar with the talks said Cassidy would
sell for $70 to $80 million, and the merger could take effect as
soon as Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at both companies would confirm only that negotiations
are under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking to them. We're in negotiations. But there's no
final agreement,'' said Paul Costello, the Shandwick managing
director for national media.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy spokesman Dale Leibach said ``discussions are ongoing''
about the merger. ``But we don't have an agreement at this point,
and there is no guarantee that there will be an agreement,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sources on both sides of the deal, however, said it could happen
in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts said the impact of the arrangement should not
be underestimated. Like many recent mergers, a Cassidy-Shandwick
alliance could give both companies an instant boost in resources _
and would allow the conglomerate to provide ``one-stop shopping''
to clients who seek political and public relations advice all at
once.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of coordinated service makes a great deal of sense
for clients,'' said Nancy Sterling, vice president of public
relations for ML Strategies, which provides a similar service as
the consulting affiliate of the Boston law firm Mintz, Levin.
``They will be a significant lobbying and PR force, certainly
well-known on Capitol Hill. And they're going to have the backing
of Shandwick and the Interpublic Group.''
</P>
<P>
   The Interpublic Group is the international advertising and PR
holding company that owns Shandwick. Locally, Interpublic owns
advertising agencies Hill Holliday Connor Cosmopulos in Boston and
Mullen in Wenham, and the public relations firm Weber Public
Relations Worldwide in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Cassidy, a former congressional staffer who founded his
company in 1975 and turned it into a political powerhouse with
advisers from both parties, will remain CEO and chairman of the
Cassidy service units he now owns, a source said. The Cassidy
divisions would be folded into the Washington office of Shandwick
Public Affairs, but remain a distinct entity within the larger
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the Cassidy firms _ the public relations firm Powell
Tate _ might be fully merged with Shandwick, a source from each
company said, because it performs the same service as the New York
company.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy would receive about 20 percent of the profit from the
merger _ roughly the equivalent to his current stake in the holding
company that controls the Cassidy Cos., a source said. That company
is expected to earn approximately $45 million in revenue this year.
It currently has a staff of about 200, among them Jody Powell, who
once worked for Democratic President Jimmy Carter, Sheila Tate, who
worked for Republican President Ronald Reagan, and Barbara Sutton
and Jim Rowan, who worked for former Speaker of the House Tip
O'Neill, a Massachusetts Democrat. Powell is expected to be put in
charge of the Washington public relations part of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   The client list is equally impressive. Besides Boston
University, Boston College, and Tufts University, Cassidy and
Associates has lobbied for Boeing, Delta Airlines, General
Dynamics, Lockheed Martin, and Ocean Spray Cranberries within the
past two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
