u a BC-CAMPAIGN-MCCAIN-BOS &LR;      09-20 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MCCAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES HIT MCCAIN STANCE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ A group of conservative Washington lobbyists
touched down in New Hampshire Monday to denounce presidential
candidate John McCain's quest for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington group, which included Grover Norquist of
Americans for Tax Reform, Wayne LaPierre, executive vice president
of the National Rifle Association, David Keene, chairman of the
American Conservative Union, and Carol Tobias, political director
of the National Right to Life Committee, staged a news conference
at the Legislative Office Building to air their views.
</P>
<P>
   Norquist called the McCain-Feingold campaign finance reform bill
a ``threat to the first amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(McCain's) persistent sponsorship of legislation that would
stifle political speech in the name of reform is wrong, dangerous,
and, I believe unconstitutional,'' said Keene.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington group was met by protesters from groups
advocating campaign finance reform, holding signs that said ``New
Hampshire voters won't be silenced by big money'' and ``No more fat
cats.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, an Arizona senator, puts campaign finance reform high on
his political agenda. He has called the current system ``an
elaborate influence-peddling scheme'' and slammed those, even in
his own party, who defend it.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was not in New Hampshire Monday, but at a later press
conference his state supporters defended the senator's crusade to
rid politics of the often covert influence of big money.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Spaulding, a New Hampshire executive counselor and state
chairman of McCain's campaign, denounced the Washington lobbyists
for coming to New Hampshire to ``discredit campaign finance reform,
and to protect their six and seven-digit salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not here to attack John McCain for opposing the
common-sense pro-family positions that these organizations stand
for. John McCain has been their ally day in and day out for
common-sense conservative reforms and pro-family values they
profess to support,'' Spaulding said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain sponsored in the Senate the McCain-Feingold bill, which
has been scaled down since its original introduction.
</P>
<P>
   A more comprehensive bill, the Shays-Meehan bill, has passed the
House of Representatives and will be considered next month by the
Senate, where Republicans have filibustered campaign finance reform
efforts in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The groups appearing oppose both measures, but focused their
wrath on McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills seek to ban unlimited ``soft money'' contributions to
political parties. ``Soft money'' is the term for unlimited,
unregulated contributions to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   The bills do not change the regulations on individual citizens'
donations to candidates' campaigns, which are already limited.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain-Feingold bill was introduced in the Senate earlier
this year, but no longer includes limits on issue advertising
within 60 days of an election -- one provision McCain's critics
attacked, saying it could be put back into a bill in conference
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the `McCain Lite' version of the bill,
introduced this week, is simply a vehicle for amendments that
contain the speech-suppressive provisions...'' Tobias said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We firmly believe that if the ban on soft money is passed,
we're next.''
</P>
<P>
   These critics of the measure charge that it curtails freedom of
speech by preventing groups like the National Rifle Association and
National Right to Life from running ``issues'' advertisements
during the final stages of political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents -- such as Rep. Martin T. Meehan of Massachusetts who
sponsored the Shays-Meehan bill -- say that is simply not true.
They say the bill does not ban such advertising, it just forces
groups running such ads to disclose who paid for them. Currently,
they are not required to do so.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre said the NRA would fight such a law in court if it were
to pass.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's supporters said Monday's criticism will only help their
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I'd like to mention that, contrary to some rumors, we
did not pay the plane fare for our predecessors up here this
afternoon,'' Spaulding joked. ``But we are prepared to pay their
bus fare anytime they want to come back...their performance today
was probably one of the best arguments we could have for campaign
finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   While the average New Hampshire voter may not be well-versed in
the intricacies of the campaign finance reform debate, the issue
could play well here. Polls indicate that a majority of New
Hampshire voters want to reform the way elections are funded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
