r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-SCHOOL     09-20 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-SCHOOL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS AT SCHOOL ACROSS THE STREET FROM SHOOTING TRY TO GET BACK
TO NORMAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MARTHA DELLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Most of the students displaced from Bruce
Shulkey Elementary School last week were anxious to get back to
their school on Monday, arriving early with protective parents,
grandparents or neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But the youngest children, sheltered from details of the
Wedgwood Baptist Church shooting across the street, feared that the
``bad man'' who killed seven people would return to harm them.
</P>
<P>
   Soothing those fears kept kindergarten teacher Barbara Peters
busy on Monday, the first day back for 640 students who stayed home
or went to other schools Thursday and Friday after Shulkey became a
police command post.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought the bad man was still alive and hiding at the
church because they saw his picture on TV,'' she said. ``Some
thought bombs were still here. Some even thought the dead people
were buried at the church memorial.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters fielded her students' questions herself, although she
consulted with seven counselors and psychologists sent in to help
with more extreme fears.
</P>
<P>
   Older students were less fearful, said Principal Janet Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Like Peters, many teachers corrected misinformation, and assured
the students that an early morning sweep by bomb-sniffing dogs
showed their school free of bombs, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 30 students saw counselors, including about 20
Bosnian students who were counseled as a group because school staff
feared that their prior experiences might make the shooting more
traumatic for them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shulkey students are among several hundred counseled by school
district counselors and psychologists since the shooting, most at
schools where students were most affected by the shooting, said
Leslie James, director of special services.
</P>
<P>
   But most Shulkey students were glad to be back with their
friends. Classes followed the normal routine, just as their parents
hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Norvelle said her daughter, Annie, was confused about why
Shulkey was closed but was glad to be returning to her own
second-grade classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``She went to work with me on Thursday,'' Norvelle said. ``Then
she found out her friends were going to Westcreek and I let her go
there. It was a big adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think children need consistency. She needs to be back at
her own school.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-grade teacher Michelle Windsor said none of her students
seemed upset, including one girl who was in the church during the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of my students at the candlelight vigils. I think
that helped them,'' Windsor said. ``Their parents did a good job
explaining it to them, but most of them wanted to see their
friends. That's the best medicine now.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Sobczak, whose family knew one of the shooting victims,
agreed. She said her daughter Kathleen, a second grader, was a
little nervous but that her son Brendon missed his fourth-grade
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they were out of school two days, they saw everybody else
going about their normal lives,'' she said. ``I think it's good to
get them back into their routine and give them back the security
they had before.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason Stephanie Gaworski organized an impromptu
picnic at LeBlanc Park last Friday for her second- and fourth-grade
children and other Shulkey students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids needed to know that their friends were OK and the
school was OK,'' she said. ``My kids were not apprehensive about
coming back. They feel safe and loved here.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the feeling Walker and her staff were trying to impart
when they stood on corners outside the school early on Monday,
greeting parents, helping children out of cars and ushering them to
crossing guards and into the school.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard for parents such as Jeannie Johnson, whose
8-year-old daughter, Destiny, was inside the church and knew Sydney
Browning, the slain children's choir director.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's scared to go anywhere outside,'' Johnson said. ``They
had a counselor at church but she didn't open up. She keeps saying,
`Mommy, don't leave me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But even those children did fine once they got inside their
school, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were very few tears,'' Walker said. ``They were mostly
fidgety. The kids wanted to come back. Once they got inside, things
were pretty normal. We hope it will be even more so tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
