<HEADER>
A9350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HARVEY-COX     09-20 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State of emergency in place, Florida waits for Harvey's deluge
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Forget soccer practice today and keep
those yellow rain slickers handy. Never mind the umbrellas, it'll
be too windy.
</P>
<P>
   A week after Category 4 Hurricane Floyd threatened, much weaker
Tropical Storm Harvey is expected to bluster across central Florida
from the Gulf of Mexico, sloshing the county with 2 to 4 inches of
rain by tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The county was included in a tropical storm watch that included
all of Florida's east coast from south Miami-Dade County to Daytona
Beach, including Lake Okeechobee. Palm Beach County was included
because Harvey's tropical storm-force winds extend 150 miles on the
southeast side, putting the county on the fringe.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Lucie County, schools will be closed, but county and city
offices will be open.
</P>
<P>
   On the west coast, a hurricane watch is in effect from the
Suwannee River south to Bonita Beach and a tropical storm warning
from the Suwanee to east Cape Sable. Forecasters didn't expect
Harvey's winds to meet the 74 mph threshold for hurricane status,
but they declared the watch anyway as a precaution. They warned of
up to 10 inches of rain in the storm's path and low-lying areas
were voluntarily evacuated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters said Harvey could produce storm surge flooding of 3
to 6 feet above normal, up to 8 feet above normal at the heads of
bays on the west coast. They also advised that rains from the storm
could ease dry conditions in much of Florida as it sloshes across
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush declared a state of emergency in most of the state
except the Panhandle, thereby putting National Guard troops on
standby.
</P>
<P>
   A cruise ship with 1,701 passengers and crew labored in 12-foot
swells 100 miles southwest of Tampa. A tug boat was sent to pull
the liner Tropicale southwest, then swing around behind the storm
and follow it into port in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters warned that Harvey could spin off tornadoes as it
moves inland. Monday night, a possible tornado was blamed for
blowing a roof off a house near Naples.
</P>
<P>
   But forecasters expect Harvey to be more wet than windy in South
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be sufficient to cause some street flooding, that's
something we're all familiar with in South Florida,'' said National
Weather Service meteorologist Bob Pifer. The county also is under a
flood warning. The weather service is predicting southwest winds of
at least 20-25 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   A rather disorganized Harvey, which formed Sunday in the gulf,
is expected to wash ashore near Tampa Bay at midday with 60 mph
winds and quickly move northeast across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Water managers have been opening floodgates throughout the east
coast to prepare for any rain dropped by Harvey. Many canals were
already low because the district had drained them last week to
prepare for Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The district also is releasing water south from the sugar
farming region into the northern Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're watching and waiting,'' South Florida Water management
District spokeswoman Ann Overton said. The district's helicopters
are on standby to survey any damage.
</P>
<P>
   The South Florida Water Management District will take residents'
questions and complaints from 6 a.m. ``into the evening'' today at
(800) 544-2323, Overton said.
</P>
<P>
   The district can help residents figure out which of the region's
many drainage districts, local governments and homeowners'
associations control nearby floodgates, culverts and pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Florida Power &AMP; Light mobilized 700 workers from
Miami-Dade and Broward counties and dispatched them to the west
coast to join 500 others for help restore power as soon as Harvey's
winds subside to safer levels. FP&AMP;L urged customers who want to
report service problems to call (800) 468-8243.
</P>
<P>
   Once Harvey passes, a cold front will push south ``but it's
probably not going to make it to the southern part of the state,''
Pifer said. At best, it will bring drier air Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Tim O'Meilia writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Bill King and the Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
