<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BUCHANAN'S LONGEST DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan's presidential candidacy is looking swell. Within
the last few days he's made friends with Lenora Fulani and gotten
into an argument about whether it was a good idea to go to war
against Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's new book on foreign policy got a devastating critique
from that well-known scholar of world history, Donald Trump. As we
all know, Buchanan is pretty close to announcing that he wants to
be the Reform Party's presidential nominee, and Trump is enjoying
the speculation that he might try for the nomination, too. The
realtor is not much of a political deep thinker, but he does
definitely know that he favored American participation in World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Trump was apparently informed that Buchanan's book argues that
Hitler was not a threat to any vital American interests after 1940.
So the developer whipped off an indignant fax, in which he
misspelled ``Adolf.'' But no matter. Pat Buchanan, the master of
the red-meat quote, was left complaining on TV that his position
had been misinterpreted. Even in retreat, he didn't sound really
enthusiastic about our role in whipping the Nazis. (``Hitler
declared war on the United States. We had no alternative but to
fight him.'').
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Buchanan appeared to be heading toward an astonishing
detente with Lenora Fulani, a leader in the New York Reform
(Independence) Party who was once an ally of Louis Farrakhan. More
recently, she was Harlem coordinator for Abe Hirschfeld, the
eccentric parking garage developer who was then the Republican
candidate for Manhattan Borough president. Hirschfeld is about to
go on trial for allegedly hiring a hit man to knock off his
business partner. All this goes to show Ms. Fulani's talent for
both ideological consistency and picking a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has been courting Ms. Fulani because she controls a
number of votes in the Reform Party. And Ms. Fulani, who once
withdrew her support from Al Sharpton because she felt he was
getting too mainstream, is sounding very enthusiastic about
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go from Al Sharpton to Pat Buchanan would make a dead
person suspicious,'' said Sharpton Monday.
</P>
<P>
   What in the world brought them together? Like Buchanan, Ms.
Fulani has been accused of anti-Semitism, although that doesn't
seem a really great basis for finding common ground. Ms. Fulani's
political roots are with the New Alliance Party, a now-defunct
organization that was founded by Fred Newman, a psychotherapist and
playwright. In 1985, according to the Anti-Defamation League,
Newman told a party convention that Jews were becoming ``the storm
troopers of decadent capitalism against people of color the world
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman, Ms. Fulani and many of their old followers have now
migrated to the Reform Party, where they are valued for their
genius at getting people's names on the ballot. (This genius has
never translated into an actual victory in the polls. In my own
neighborhood in 1992, their candidate for Congress lost in a
landslide to a man who had died a week earlier.) Ms. Fulani says
they're building a non-ideological third party that is simply
focused on process issues, like term limits and campaign finance
reform.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of thinking presumes that American voters are so
intent on cleaning up the system that they don't care whether the
finished product looks like Pat Buchanan's idea of utopia or Lenora
Fulani's. The Reform Party is full of folks like this, inhabitants
of the political fringes who make Jesse Ventura look like Woodrow
Wilson, united only by their frustration over their inability to
make themselves heard.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fulani and Buchanan are angry on a higher plane _ not
because they can't get a hearing, but because they can't get
elected. Buchanan got plenty of attention when he ran for the
Republican presidential nomination, but his main achievement,
besides losing, was to scare moderate voters away from the party
altogether. Now the polls suggest that the vast majority of
Republican primary voters are planning to ignore him entirely. This
is driving Buchanan nuts, and sending him ricocheting into the arms
of the Reform Party and folks like Ms. Fulani. To tell the truth,
it does seem like the perfect place for him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
