<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9354 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-INQUIRY-940(2T     09-20 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INQUIRY-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION OFFICIALS SAY INVESTIGATION LOOKING AT PEOPLE CLOSE
TO YELTSIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal investigation of money laundering at
the Bank of New York is examining transactions with the bank by
people close to President Boris Yeltsin of Russia, according to
Clinton administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has found transactions involving Pavel Borodin, the
powerful head of Yeltsin's property management team, and Leonid
Dyachenko, the husband of Yeltsin's younger daughter, Tatyana, an
influential political adviser to her father, senior Clinton
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   One government official described the information that the FBI
had as ``credible'' but he declined to discuss it further because
the investigation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Yakushkin, the spokesman for Yeltsin, has previously
asserted that neither Yeltsin nor any members of the immediate
Yeltsin family has a foreign bank account. However, he said Monday
that that statement applied to Yeltsin and his two daughters. It
does not apply, he said, to their husbands: Dyachenko or Valery
Okulov, a senior executive at Aeroflot, the Russian national
airline, who is married to Yelena Okulova, the elder Yeltsin
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a Swiss prosecutor who has been investigating
corruption involving Russian officials said that money from
Borodin's accounts in Switzerland had been transferred to accounts
at American banks that are under federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to name the banks or the accounts. The entities that
have figured most prominently in the investigation in the United
States are the Bank of New York and a company called Benex, which
was related to several accounts at the bank in which billions of
dollars were funneled from Russia to other foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Yeltsin's son-in-law, federal authorities would
not say whether he had an account at the Bank of New York or
whether he had channeled money through the Benex accounts there.
However, officials said the amounts of money moving through the
Bank of New York by both men were ``substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials declined to discuss the nature of the evidence or
provide any details of the transactions. The Bank of New York
declined to comment on any specific accounts. American
investigators also say they have not determined the sources of the
funds moving through the bank nor their ultimate destination _
factors that have complicated the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has been the leading American bank in Moscow that
specialized in international services for Russian banks and
businesses. It was widely used to handle payments between Russian
companies and foreign suppliers and by individuals who wanted to
put money outside of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Many transactions could be legitimate and legal, but the bank
has been cooperating in a federal money laundering investigation
for a year. Neither the bank nor any individual has been formally
accused of any wrongdoing by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is safe to infer that it was parking and transfers,'' a
Clinton administration official said, referring to funds handled
for Borodin and Dyachenko by the bank. ``The investigation is
whether it was laundering.'' the official added, referring to a
series of banking transactions intended to hide the origin and
ultimate destination of money.
</P>
<P>
   Yakushkin, the spokesman for Yeltsin, was asked on Saturday to
help arrange comment from Dyachenko. But Monday he said that
Dyachenko was traveling abroad on business and could not be
reached. Yakushkin said no other aides or family friends could
speak on Dyachenko's behalf. He also said he could not provide
telephone or fax numbers or a business address for Dyachenko.
</P>
<P>
   Borodin has repeatedly denied any wrongdoing, and has dismissed
the allegations against him as politically motivated. In response
to whether he had an account at the Bank of New York, his spokesman
said, ``Mr. Borodin learned about the existence of the Bank of New
York from newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official said that after the
bank transactions by Borodin and Dyachenko were discovered last
week, the Justice Department immediately alerted the National
Security Council that administration officials should no longer
say, as they have since the investigation surfaced, that there is
no evidence of official Russian involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This changes the whole tenor of things,'' an official said
about the evidence that Borodin and Dyachenko used the Bank of New
York. Until now, he said, there had been only suspicions, and
rumors, that Russian officials were involved. ``Now U.S.
investigators are saying it,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the matter as ``very sensitive'' and known to only a
few people in the Clinton administration, the officials spoke only
on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty investigators will have in examining the banking
transactions are reflected in a message the American Embassy in
Moscow sent Washington earlier this month. The memo, which is
labeled ``sensitive'' and not for foreign distribution, outlines
the ``schemes'' used by Russians to get money out of the country.
The embassy notes that these have been used by people who merely
want money for travel or to help a relative abroad, by businesses
trying to avoid taxes by hiding their financial movements with
shell companies, and by criminal organizations laundering their
illegal proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government sent a delegation to meet with U.S. law
enforcement officials last week to discuss the Bank of New York
investigation. ``Fortunately, media reports of Russian money
laundering have not been confirmed,'' Prime Minister Vladimir Putin
said Monday after a meeting with Yeltsin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Swiss authorities have been investigating Mrs. Dyachenko, and
Borodin, on charges of money laundering and corruption. One
allegation is that Borodin and Mrs. Dyachenko received bribes from
Mabatex Project Engineering, a Swiss company based in Lugano that
performed extensive construction work on Yeltsin's residence and
other Kremlin properties.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts were awarded by Borodin's agency, which by his
estimate manages more than $600 million worth of property, palaces,
dachas, automobiles, aircraft, yachts, hospitals and spas. One of
the accusations against Borodin is that he his company provided
credit cards to Yeltsin and his two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, in a phone conversation, President Clinton
asked Yeltsin about the credit cards and Yeltsin denied those
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Dyachenko has not been as visible in Russian political circles
as his wife, Tatyana. They met while working at the Salyut Design
Bureau, which is part of the Russian space industry.
</P>
<P>
   His full first name is Leonid, but in the Yeltsin family he is
called Lyoshsa, which is also a diminutive for Alexsei.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when Tatyana was appointed an official adviser to her
father, a Moscow newspaper asked her in an interview what her
husband did. She appeared uncertain before answering that it was
``something connected with wood processing,'' the newspaper,
Obshchaya Gazeta, reported.
</P>
<P>
   Dyachenko later joined a company, Interural, that exported
metals from the Urals. It was a joint venture with a Swiss partner.
</P>
<P>
   An official in the personnel section of Interural, Irina
Nikolayevna, confirmed in a telephone interview that Leonid
Yuriyevich Dyachenko worked for the company several years ago,
though everybody addressed him as Alexsei. She said she did not
know his current whereabouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
