<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEVRON AND PHILLIPS DISCUSS JOINT VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Chevron and Phillips Petroleum have discussed forming a joint
venture in the petrochemical business, people close to both
companies said, but they added that a merger of the companies was
not imminent, despite a report in The Sunday Times of London that
sent Phillips shares up $2.8125, to $56.5625. Analysts said that
the recent recovery in crude oil prices meant oil companies were
under less pressure to merge.
</P>
<P>
   PRESSURE ON THE BANK OF JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan, which won independence last year, is under
intense pressure from international investors to ease monetary
policy to lift Japan's economy out of its decade-long slump.
Expectations of an announcement on monetary policy weakened the
strong yen in Tokyo trading and contributed to a surge in the Tokyo
stock market, where the main Nikkei 225 index rose 1.34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ COMPOSITE NEARS RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Big technology companies led by Sun Microsystems propelled the
Nasdaq composite index within a point of a new closing record. The
Nasdaq gained 16.53 points to close at 2,886.15. But other gauges
were little changed. The Dow Jones industrial average was up 20.27,
to 10,823.90, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index edged up
0.11 point, to 1,335.53.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices fell as traders grew pessimistic when the dollar
fell against the Japanese yen. The 30-year Treasury bond fell 1032
of a point to 1002632, sending its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, up to 6.07 percent.
</P>
<P>
   THE FUTURE OF E-COMMERCE
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's joint venture with Ford Motor to offer
built-to-order automobiles via the World Wide Web shows the
potentially wrenching changes that electronic commerce is bringing.
Ford's dealers are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ARRESTED EXECUTIVE LEAVES INFOSEEK
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Naughton, the Infoseek executive who has overseen Walt
Disney Co.'s online operation, the Go Network, has left the company
after his arrest on charges of soliciting sex from a minor on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   QUAKER OATS TO CUT 1,200 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Quaker Oats announced a three-year project to streamline its
North American operations, cutting nearly 1,200 jobs, or 10 percent
of the work force, closing plants and taking charges against
earnings. Some product lines are to be consolidated. But Quaker
plans to raise production capacity for its successful Gatorade
business.
</P>
<P>
   INQUIRY LEADS TO YELTSIN FRIENDS
</P>
<P>
   In its investigation of money laundering at the Bank of New
York, the FBI is examining transactions with the bank by people
close to President Boris Yeltsin of Russia, according to senior
Clinton administration officials, who named Pavel Borodin, the head
of Yeltsin's property management team, and Leonid Dyachenko, the
husband of Yeltsin's daughter, Tatyana.
</P>
<P>
   ROLLS ROYCE AGREES TO BUY VICKERS
</P>
<P>
   Rolls-Royce PLC has agreed to buy Vickers PLC for $933 million,
saying the deal will create a giant in the growing market for
engines and other ship propulsion systems.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA'S BIG CONGLOMERATES SURVIVE
</P>
<P>
   Korea's attempts to pare the size and power of big business
conglomerates are not working, a Korea Stock Exchange study found.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. URGES THIRD WORLD ROLE IN TRADE
</P>
<P>
   Industrial nations must relax trade barriers and open their
markets to the developing world, a U.N. agency said, urging a third
world focus in planned trade talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
