<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9359 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NJ-POLICE-(TRIMS)-NYT     09-20 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN NAMES FBI SUPERVISOR TO TAKE OVER N.J. STATE POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman announced Monday that her
nominee to head the state police is Carson Dunbar, an FBI
supervisor in New York, who promised to strengthen the force's
recruitment and disciplinary procedures and change its culture so
that racial bias is no longer tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   One of his first steps, Dunbar said, would be to make the
Internal Affairs Bureau more accountable to the public and to
review incentive programs for drug seizures that may have
encouraged racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   In surprisingly introspective comments for a news conference,
Dunbar, who was a N.J. state trooper in the early '70s, said Monday
that he had accepted the nomination to be superintendent of the New
Jersey State Police because of his mixed racial background. One of
his parents was black, and one was white, he said, adding that he
wanted a chance to build on the civil rights advances he has
witnessed during his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   He even revealed that several years ago, he was subjected to
racial profiling himself at a traffic stop by a New Jersey state
trooper.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Dunbar said he thought that the news media had
overstated the extent of the problem and assured officers that ``I
do not come with a chip on my shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Dunbar's status as a former state trooper and his
extensive experience as a federal law enforcement administrator,
however, some civil rights leaders questioned Monday whether he had
the leadership skills and vision to lead a deeply divided agency
through a politically charged overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fairness to him, we'll have to wait and see whether he's a
strong superintendent,'' said the Rev. Reginald T. Jackson,
director of the Black Ministers Council of New Jersey. ``But if
he's not a strong leader, we're going to end up in the same
situation two years from now that we're in now. Nothing this
administration has proposed will outlive the end of the governor's
term, and that is quickly drawing to a close.'' Whitman, who cannot
run for a third term, leaves office in January 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate is expected to hold public hearings on Dunbar's
nomination next week, and legislators from both parties say that he
is likely to be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   For Whitman, Dunbar's formal nomination ends seven months of
embarrassing fits and starts in an effort to address an issue that
has become the most persistent crisis of her five-and-a-half-year
tenure in office.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the governor fired the previous superintendent,
Col. Carl A. Williams, for making racially insensitive statements
in a newspaper interview. After years of insisting that the state
police did not engage in racial profiling, the governor made
history this spring when she became the first state official to
acknowledge that troopers discriminated against minority drivers
and harassed female and minority officers.
</P>
<P>
   But her attempt to replace Williams and enact change has been
fraught with miscalculations and political squabbles. The
governor's first choice for the top police job, a commander with
the Illinois State Police, withdrew from consideration after
encountering fierce resistance from state legislators who wanted
Whitman to choose someone from within the state police ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar's nomination was also stalled for months, as the governor
pressed Attorney General Janet Reno to approve an administrative
arrangement that would allow him to receive his full federal
pension.
</P>
<P>
   In naming Dunbar, the governor said she hoped his familiarity
with the protocol of the state police would allow him to enact
thorough reforms while being fair to the officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is going to be an advocate for the outstanding men and
women of the state police and someone who will ensure the
confidence in the public in the job that those men and women are
asked to do every day,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar seemed relieved that his wait for the nomination had
ended at last, and asked the news media and the public to be
patient as they measured his attempts to change the force.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in measured tones, Dunbar that his first priority would
be to bolster the department's internal affairs unit. That bureau
is now so autonomous that its commanders refuse to release any
information about discipline, even to citizens who file complaints
against officers.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar also said there were several other systemic changes he
would tackle, including recruitment and promotional policies, but
he cautioned that results might not come quickly. His job might
also be complicated if the U.S. Justice Departments Civil Rights
Division, which is now investigating the force, decides to appoint
an outside monitor.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the complexity of the task ahead of him, Dunbar, said he
looked forward to returning to the force where he worked as a
trooper from 1973 to 1977.
</P>
<P>
   As one of only a handful of minority troopers, Dunbar said he
had witnessed bias, but no real hostility, during his four years on
the force.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he said, he was not surprised to read reports that
many black and female troopers have been victims of discrimination
and harassment from their white colleagues and supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar rose quickly through the FBI, to his current position as
chief of administration in the bureau's New York office, but
co-workers and supervisors have given mixed reviews of his
performance. Lewis D. Schiliro, current head of the FBI's New York
office, said Dunbar was dedicated, experience and unfailingly
professional.
</P>
<P>
   But other FBI officials have criticized Dunbar's ill-fated
decision to end surveillance of a group of terrorists in 1992, six
months before they bombed the World Trade Center. One of those
critics, Oliver B. Revell, who was a deputy director of the FBI in
Washington during the early 1990s, said he had always viewed Dunbar
as a better administrator than an executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were the governor, I would want him to work for me
because he's honest and hard-working,'' said Revell, who is now
retired. ``But leadership isn't his strong suit, so I wouldn't want
to hire him for the superintendent's job.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar calmly rebutted questions about his leadership and his
role in the World Trade center case during Monday's news
conference, saying that he was an independent thinker who wasn't
afraid to make a tough decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy to come back and say, `Why didn't you do this?
Why did you do that?''' Dunbar said. ``It's a little bit more
difficult when you're making the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Dunbar's supporters argue that he will not have to
overhaul the force himself because the governor has already
appointed three members of the state attorney general's office, who
already have drawn up a detailed plan to improve the force.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But one brief exchange during the news conference suggested that
the racial politics of revamping the state police could make for
some tense moments. When the governor was asked whether Dunbar's
race was a factor in his nomination _ and she quickly responded
that he was chosen solely because of his professional
qualifications _ Dunbar jumped in before reporters could ask
another question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question that you just asked is just what I talked about
before,'' he said. ``There is no place that I can go, no matter
what I accomplish, without somebody asking that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why couldn't I just be the best possible candidate?'' Dunbar
said. ``Every time something happens and a minority happens to be
the person, then why is it that that question has to be raised?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
