<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-ENNIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH FILLS WITH YOUNG PEOPLE WHO CAME TO SAY GOODBYE TO JOEY
ENNIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By SARAH LUNDAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Enough young people to fill a small high
school attended Joseph ``Joey'' Ennis' funeral on Monday, and each
one's eyes were filled with sorrow and questions.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 mourners _ mostly teen-agers _ flowed into First
Baptist Church of suburban White Settlement to say goodbye to the
14-year-old Brewer High School freshman. They didn't know what to
do with their hands, their eyes, their hair.
</P>
<P>
   They fidgeted in the presence of death.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say that somehow gives the answer to all the
questions?'' the Rev. Jim Gatliff, First Baptist pastor, asked the
standing-room-only crowd. ``Why did this happen? I can say simply:
I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Ennis was one of seven victims killed Wednesday night when Larry
Gene Ashbrook walked into Wedgwood Baptist Church, where Ennis was
visiting, and sprayed bullets into the crowd of 150 youths.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Ennis' friends sat on the floors, stood in the
doorways, filled the sanctuary and several other rooms at First
Baptist. Many resorted to standing outside on the church steps.
</P>
<P>
   Ennis was too young to die, they whispered.
</P>
<P>
   Just four months ago, on May 25, 1999, Ennis wrote his mission
statement in life for a class assignment:
</P>
<P>
   ``My mission in life is to be kind and trustworthy with humor,
always keeping promises, especially as a friend, a son and a pet
owner. Don't let people get down in the dumps,'' Gatliff quoted
Ennis.
</P>
<P>
   Ennis had arrived early at First Baptist last Wednesday
afternoon. He wanted to play pool with his friends before going to
the youth rally at Wedgwood Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Hi, pastor,' '' Gatliff told the crowd. ``Little did
I know it would be the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Ennis, Donna Ennis' only child, loved playing basketball,
playing with his pet cats and spending ``family nights'' playing
board games at home.
</P>
<P>
   His cousin, 14-year-old Chris Belsher, had persuaded Ennis to
start going to the First Baptist youth group a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my cousin, my friend, and he felt like a brother,''
Belsher said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Belsher thanked the crowd for coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see people of different race, religion and color,'' Belsher
said as his voice trailed into tears. ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ennis' casket was closed, a basketball signed by friends
was at his feet. A Chicago Bulls jersey signed by friends was over
his chest. And pictures signed by friends sat at his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be missed!'' read one boy's T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
