<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-U.S.-1200(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIAN PRESIDENT SAYS U.S. WON'T BE DRAWN INTO STRIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIM GOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ President Andres Pastrana of Colombia insisted
Monday that despite his government's request for a huge new
infusion of aid from abroad, the United States would not be drawn
more deeply into Colombia's 40-year fight against leftist
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The times of intervention are over,'' Pastrana said in an
address to the United Nations on the opening day of the General
Assembly. ``These are times of cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Pastrana sought to reassure Americans about the
Clinton administration's deepening commitment to Colombia, saying
military aid and training would be channeled mainly to special
units like army battalions being created to fight guerrillas who
support the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana indicated that his government had decided not to ask
the United States for sophisticated attack or transport
helicopters. Instead, he said, Colombia will seek American
authorization to buy such aircraft with its own funds.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia will seek U.S. aid to strengthen its radar capabilities
and refurbish or replace many of its air force jets as part of a
stepped-up effort to intercept planes involved in the drug trade
flying into and out of the country, Pastrana said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that, for the first time, Colombia has joined Peru in
trying to shoot such planes out of the sky in order to deter the
traffickers. American officials confirmed that the new policy took
effect last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Pastrana administration is seeking at least $3.5 billion in
international aid over the next three years to carry out a
wide-ranging strategy to deal with leftist and rightist insurgents,
a surging drug trade and a faltering economy.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian officials hope that the brunt of that aid will come
from the United States, and they are using Pastrana's visit to New
York and Washington this week as a busy diplomatic sales tour that
will include meetings with President Clinton, congressional leaders
and others.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Colombian officials did not deny that their target
for American help is well above the $1.5 billion that Clinton
administration officials cited last week as the high end of what
they have considered providing to Colombia over the next three
years. The United States is giving Colombia $287 million in the
fiscal year that ends this month, according to State Department
figures.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Pastrana seemed to have no quarrel with the
notion, widespread in Washington, that his year-old government is
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a difficult year,'' he said wearily as he sat back
in an armchair in the midtown hotel suite where he is staying. In
the next room, a pile of Colombian newspapers announced darkly that
leftist guerrillas had decided once again to suspend their
participation in peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   But Pastrana pointedly challenged the American perception that
the most serious new turn in Colombia's troubles is the growing
alliance between drug producers in the south and the leftist
guerrillas there who tax the producers' crops or protect their
laboratories and fields.
</P>
<P>
   While the guerrillas may be growing stronger and the traffickers
are recovering from serious blows in the mid-1990s, Pastrana said,
their violence is not as serious as it was a few years ago when
rival drug cartels were still fighting ruthlessly against each
other and the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The security issue was much more serious in Colombia at the
end of the '80s and the beginning of the '90s,'' he said. ``What is
happening now is that the security problem is becoming mixed up
with the economic problem.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With the government's debt burden at a critical level, commodity
prices falling and unemployment on the rise, Pastrana said, the
country simply cannot afford to fight its battles alone,
particularly those against powerful cocaine and heroin traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colombia is ready to put up some cash, and we are putting it
up, but we need international aid,'' Pastrana said. ``This is a
partnership in which all of us must contribute _ the Americans, the
Colombians, the Europeans, the Asians.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials said the Pastrana administration hopes to get
at least $775 million in loans from international financial
institutions like the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund and that the total could rise to as much as $1.5 billion. But
despite talk of ``international cooperation,'' the officials said,
Colombia will turn to the United States for almost all of the
remainder.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While his aides said that about 55 percent of Colombia's
proposed aid would be spent to fight drug trafficking, the leftist
guerrillas and right-wing paramilitary groups, Pastrana also
sounded frustrated with the lack of emphasis in Washington on
social development, substituting other crops for drugs and trade
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, we are looking at not just the police part
of this. We are looking at the economic part,'' he said. ``This is
what we have to make people aware of in the United States and
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Discussing details of his military aid request for the first
time, Pastrana said he would not ask the United States to provide
the Colombian army with advanced UH-60 Blackhawk helicopters to use
as troop transports, as American officials expected. Instead, he
said he would seek American authorization to purchase as many as 15
aircraft and arm at least some of them for use against the
guerrillas. Such arms generally include small machine guns and
rocket launchers.
</P>
<P>
   The shift _ which officials said would also involve using
smaller UH-1N helicopters to transport a new American-trained
antidrug army battalion _ would probably mean less American
scrutiny on the Colombian military's use of the helicopters as
gunships against the guerrillas. The Colombians had previously
considered buying Apache and Cobra attack helicopters, officials
said, but had been discouraged in part by the difficulty they were
likely to have in getting American authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana also indicated that he would seek to expand a program
under which the United States is soon to refurbish 10 of the
Colombian air force's fleet of 14 A-37 fighter jets, installing
radar in five of them. In a telephone interview from Bogota, the
air force commander, Gen. Hector Fabio Velazco, confirmed that
Colombian jets have shot down four drug planes since late last
year, while hitting 11 others and forcing down 10.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Colombian defense minister, Luis Fernando Ramirez, said that
as part of the plan, Colombia hopes to create as many as four of
the new counternarcotics battalions over the next three years in
addition to the first such unit, which is expected to begin
operations at the end of the year. He also said the Colombian
military hopes to double its contingent of 2,500 navy and army
troops now fighting drug traffickers and their guerrilla allies
along the country's rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they were generally
pleased with Pastrana's plan, which Colombian officials presented
to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright last Thursday. But
administration officials are continuing to debate how they should
seek funding for the plan to keep congressional Republicans from
cutting other foreign aid programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
