<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9374 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUCHANAN-BOOK-NYT &LR;      09-20 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN'S VIEWS ON HITLER CREATE A REFORM PARTY STIR
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Minn.)  (nk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The shadow competition for the presidential
nomination of the Reform Party has become embroiled in Pat
Buchanan's views, expressed in his new book, that Hitler presented
no threat to the United States after Nazi Germany's initial
victories of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's thesis that Hitler offered ``no physical threat to
the United States'' as of late 1940 has been underlined for
criticism by Donald Trump, the real estate developer who, like
Buchanan, is considering seeking the Reform Party nomination next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The budding controversy was taken by one Reform Party official
as an early caution that Buchanan's history of such disputes should
offer the party some pause. ``A party takes on a lot of attitudes
and reflections of its standard bearer,'' said Dean M. Barkley, an
adviser to Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, the Reform leader who has
reservations about Buchanan's threat to quit the Republican Party
and campaign for the Reform nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Buchanan becomes the candidate, obviously if there's
negative baggage, that will affect the entire ticket,'' said
Barkley, noting Ventura's preference for a more ``centrist''
aspirant for the party line, Trump included.
</P>
<P>
   But Pat Choate, the party's 1996 vice-presidential nominee, who
is a strong Buchanan supporter, said Buchanan's stock was rising
positively within the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Critics are taking things in his book out of context and I
think he's explaining it well,'' said Choate, emphasizing that Ross
Perot, the party founder, was strictly neutral about any
competition for the nomination. ``Pat's doing very well. If he runs
for the nomination, he'll get the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book, ``A Republic, Not an Empire'' (Regnery Publishing),
Buchanan analyzes the history of American foreign policy and
questions whether Hitler sought war with the West or was driven to
it. ``Hitler made no overt move to threaten U.S vital interests,''
after his initial victories across Europe in 1939 and 1940,
Buchanan writes.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate chapter criticizing the power of numerous American
ethnic groups over foreign policy, Buchanan writes, ``After World
War II, Jewish influence over foreign policy became almost an
obsession with American leaders.'' Buchanan complained on CBS-TV's
``Face the Nation'' on Sunday that critics were lifting that
observation from a complex criticism directed at numerous groups.
``One paragraph discussing the power of the Israeli lobby is not
only legitimate, it is necessary,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   The book, which is a centerpiece of Buchanan's presidential run,
emphasizes the views of some historians that Hitler was primarily
interested in building a German empire to the east, not westward
toward the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Trump contends that Buchanan is denigrating the memory of
Americans who died fighting in an unavoidable war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat says Hitler had no malicious intent toward the United
States,'' Trump said in an interview. ``Well, Hitler killed 6
million Jews and millions of others. Don't you think it was only a
question of time before he got to us? He tackled Europe first and
we were next. Pat's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he had read the book, Trump said, ``I've seen the
phrases we're dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, complaining that he had been misrepresented, replied
that ``Mr. Trump's views reflect an almost paralyzing ignorance of
the history of World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Americans had no choice but to fight once Hitler
declared war on the United States, Buchanan said, while writing
that it was ``preposterous'' to suggest Germany had any real power
to threaten the United States after Hitler's air force was defeated
in the Battle of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The German invasion threat was history,'' he writes,
contending that the British and French declarations of war after
the German invasion of Poland served mainly to distract Hitler from
his strategy of attacking Russia and ``thus saved the Soviet Union
for Communism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Britain and France not given the war guarantees to
Poland,'' Buchanan writes, ``there might have been no Dunkirk, no
blitz, no Vichy, no destruction of the Jewish populations'' of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the excerpts being singled out, the overall thesis of
Buchanan's book is a warning against an ``unsustainable'' foreign
policy committing American forces in ``scores of nations in regions
where we have never fought before.''
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party officials said Buchanan, who promises a final
decision on whether he will switch parties next month, has
privately begun reaching out to key Reform officials, though not
yet to Ventura. Barkley, the adviser to Ventura, estimated that
Buchanan could stir enough excitement among some Reform Party
members to put together a serious organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's challenging to those of us who are not so excited to
provide a viable alternative,'' he said. ``If we can't, we've got
nothing to complain about because we always knew our party was
subject to an outside group coming in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
