09-20 -- John Horgan, a science journalist, at his home with his
parrot Zach. Horgan, who outraged countless scientists with his
book ``The End of Science: Facing the Limits of Knowledge in the
Twilight of the Scientific Age,'' now promises to make new enemies
with a new work, ``The Undiscovered Mind - How the Human Mind
Defies Replication, Medication and Explanation.'' (Susan Farley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- SCI-SPINE, 09-20 -- Tony
Scott, a spinal injury patient, trying to walk on a treadmill at
the UCLA Medical Center last week. An increasing number of studies
recently demonstrate that far from being a passive conduit,
slavishly ferrying information to and from the brain, the spinal
cord has its own contribution to make. Spinal cord neurons,
researchers are finding, are capable of learning in simple ways,
and show changes in response to environmental cues that many
investigators interpret as a form of memory. The research hopes to
offer better therapies for those recovering from spinal cord
injuries. (Michael Tweed/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- SCI-MARS-ORBITER, 09-20 --
An artist rendering of NASAUs Mars Climate Orbiter which arrives
just miles away from Mars in the early morning hours of September
23, 1999. The orbiter will fire its main engine to brake itself
into orbit around the planet. The orbiter will become the first
weather satellite around Mars, taking weather and climate
measurements during a two-year long mapping mission. (NASA/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
