<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 09/20/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) HOUSTON -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- BKL-COOPER-PROFILE-2, 09-20
-- Cynthia Cooper, the superstar point guard of the Houston Comets,
after defeating the New York Liberty in the finals of the Women's
National Basketball Association on September 5. Cooper, 36, has
written a new autobiography, ``She Got Game: My Personal Odyssey.''
``It's really about living life to the fullest,'' she says. ``I
want people to read this book and to be inspired by it.'' (Michelle
V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- BKL-COOPER-PROFILE-1,
09-20 -- Cynthia Cooper, the superstar point guard of the Houston
Comets of the Women's National Basketball Association, has written
a new autobiography, ``She Got Game: My Personal Odyssey.'' In it,
Cooper, 36, recounts a life shaped by personal lows and highs.
(Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- CONGRESS-SPEND-2, 09-20
-- Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, is seeking to protect
companies that drill on federal land. The issue could come to a
vote this week, and it appears as if the Senate might side with the
oil companies. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- CONGRESS-SPEND-1, 09-20
-- Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., says that companies drilling on
federal land are underpaying. ``We shouldn't have a double standard
just because an oil company is powerful, just because an oil
company can give millions of dollars in contributions,'' she says.
(Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- NY-FASHION-3, 09-20 --
DKNY's shrunken denim jacket and hip-hugging trousers with a python
detailing down one side, left; Calvin Klein's pale blue-gray belted
sheath in papery nylon. (Corina Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- NY-FASHION-2, 09-20 --
Bill Blass taking his bow on the runway, to an emotional standing
ovation. Blass came along in an age when everything in fashion was
personal. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- NY-FASHION-1, 09-20 --
From left, Randolph Duke's intricately beaded evening dress and
matching beret (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo); Calvin
Klein's silver ribbed jersey T-shirt with azure and tan python
skirt and matching sandals; from Richard Tyler, a raw silk
crocheted jacket and matching sea-green hot pants. (Corina
Lecca/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1999 --
OBIT-RAISA-GORBACHEV-2-B&AMP;W, 09-20 -- From left, former President
Ronald Reagan, Nancy Reagan, former Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev and Raisa Gorbachev during a 1992 celebration of Forbes
Magazine's 75th anniversary at Radio City Music Hall. Mrs.
Gorbachev died Monday in Muenster, Germany. She was 67. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1999 --
OBIT-RAISA-GORBACHEV-1-B&AMP;W, 09-20 -- Former President Ronald Reagan
kisses Raisa Gorbachev during a 1992 celebration of Forbes
Magazine's 75th anniversary at Radio City Music Hall. Mrs.
Gorbachev, who broke Kremlin tradition by sharing the spotlight
with her husband, the former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev,
and did so with bold self-assurance and flair, died Monday in
Muenster, Germany. She was 67. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- NY-SCHOOL-SEX-SCANDAL-B&AMP;W,
09-20 -- Biology teacher Richard Plass in his classroom in this
undated photo. Last month, Plass, an assistant principal and
biology teacher who in his 16 years at the school oversaw 250
finalists and two dozen winners in the prestigious Intel (formerly
Westinghouse) Science Talent Search, pleaded guilty to molesting a
15-year-old student last year in his office. Plass received three
years probation, retired and surrendered his teaching license.
(John Sotomayor/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BOUND BROOKE, N.J. -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- HURRICANE-NY-2,
09-20 --Residents remove debris from their homes on Monday which
were damaged from flood waters by Hurricane Floyd. Shopkeepers and
residents returned to Main St. on Monday to assess the damage after
the Raritan River rose to 12 feet above its banks on Thursday night
and Friday following heavy rains from the storm. (Dith Pran/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BOUND BROOKE, N.J. -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- HURRICANE-NY,
09-20 -- Sanitation workers remove debris from homes on Monday
which were left on the side of the street by residents returning to
their flood-damaged homes on Monday. Shopkeepers and residents
returned to Main St. on Monday to assess the damage after the
Raritan River rose to 12 feet above its banks on Thursday night and
Friday following heavy rains from Hurricane Floyd. (Dith Pran/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) TRENTON, N.J. -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- NJ-POLICE, 09-20 --
Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey, left, looks on as Carson
Dunbar talks to reporters on Monday. After months of bureaucratic
delay, Whitman on Monday announced the appointment of Dunbar, a
veteran FBI agent and administrator, as her choice to be the new
superintendent of the New Jersey State Police. If approved by the
state legislature, Dunbar would be charged with leading the
2,700-officer force which has been accused of using racial
profiling to stop motorists and discriminating against minority
troopers. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WALLACE, N.C -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- HURRICANE-CAROLINES-3,
09-20 -- Rain clouds loom over a field of crops and flooded homes
Monday afternoon near Wallance, in North Carolina's Duplin County.
More rain expected Monday night could worsen the North Carolina
flooding caused by Hurricane Floyd that already is blamed for
billions in damage. (Mark Courtney/Wilmington Star-News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PENDER COUNTY, N.C. -- Sept. 20, 1999 --
HURRICANE-CAROLINES-2, 09-20 -- Tobacco crops damaged by the wind
and rains from Hurricane Floyd on a field on Monday. More rain
expected tonight could worsen the North Carolina flooding caused by
Hurricane Floyd that already is blamed for billions in damage.
(Mark Courtney/Wilmington Star-News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BROOKLINE, Mass -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-3-BOS,
09-20 -- Payne Stewart and Justin Leonard of the U.S. team walk to
the 9th tee at the Country Club during their practice round on
Monday for the upcoming Ryder Cup. The U.S. will try and regain the
Ryder Cup from Europe in the three-day biennial matches that will
begin on Sept. 24. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BROOKLINE, Mass -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-2-BOS,
09-20 -- Tom Lehman, of the United States Ryder Cup team, during a
practice round on Monday at the Country Club, site of the upcoming
Ryder Cup. The U.S. will try and regain the cup from Europe in the
three-day biennial matches that will begin on Sept. 24. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NASH COUNTY, N.C. -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- FLOYD-COX, 09-20
-- Flood damage in Nash County near interstate I-95 last Saturday.
While flood waters decreased slightly, emergency crews here spent
Sunday trying to feed the homeless, rescue the still-stranded and
recover the dead left behind by Floyd. (David H. Weaver/Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- JONES-PLAGIARISM, 09-20 --
James Mackay's new work, ``I Have Not Yet Begun to Fight: A life of
John Paul Jones,'' right, is the first full-length biography of the
Scottish-born American naval hero in 40 years. After questions from
The New York Times, however, Mackay's publisher has halted the book
for a check on similarities to the last major Jones biography,
published in 1959 by the eminent American historian Samuel Eliot
Morison, left. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TARABORO, N.C. -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- HURRICANE-CAROLINAS,
09-20 --Brittney Bryant, 6, of Princeville, N.C. , plays on Monday
in the gymnasium at Tarboro High School, where some 3,000 people
are being shelter after their homes were flooded by Hurricane
Floyd. More rain was expected Monday night which authorities feared
may worsen flooding in the eastern North Carolina region, possibly
delaying the return of over 10,000 people to their homes. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- WALKMAN-REVOLUTION, 09-20 --
Emily Brady, 19, a student at Boston University, listens to the
``Beatles'' on her Sony Walkman while strolling up Massachusetts
Avenue last week. This month marks the 20th anniversary of the
introduction of the Sony Walkman, a device which revolutionized the
personal electronics industry. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-BOS, 09-20 --
United States Ryder Cup Team Captain Ben Crenshaw, left, and Europe
Team Captain Mark James pose with the Ryder Cup after the European
team's arrival at Logan Airport in Boston on Monday. The U.S. will
try and regain the cup from Europe in the three-day biennial
matches that will begin on Sept. 24 at The Country Club in
Brookline, Mass. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) GARRISON, N.Y. -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- SCI-HORGAN-MIND,
09-20 -- John Horgan, a science journalist, at his home with his
parrot Zach. Horgan, who outraged countless scientists with his
