<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1999 --
OBIT-RAISA-GORBACHEV-1-B&AMP;W, 09-20 -- Former President Ronald Reagan
kisses Raisa Gorbachev during a 1992 celebration of Forbes
Magazine's 75th anniversary at Radio City Music Hall. Mrs.
Gorbachev, who broke Kremlin tradition by sharing the spotlight
with her husband, the former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev,
and did so with bold self-assurance and flair, died Monday in
Muenster, Germany. She was 67. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- NY-SCHOOL-SEX-SCANDAL-B&AMP;W,
09-20 -- Biology teacher Richard Plass in his classroom in this
undated photo. Last month, Plass, an assistant principal and
biology teacher who in his 16 years at the school oversaw 250
finalists and two dozen winners in the prestigious Intel (formerly
Westinghouse) Science Talent Search, pleaded guilty to molesting a
15-year-old student last year in his office. Plass received three
years probation, retired and surrendered his teaching license.
(John Sotomayor/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BOUND BROOKE, N.J. -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- HURRICANE-NY-2,
09-20 --Residents remove debris from their homes on Monday which
were damaged from flood waters by Hurricane Floyd. Shopkeepers and
residents returned to Main St. on Monday to assess the damage after
the Raritan River rose to 12 feet above its banks on Thursday night
and Friday following heavy rains from the storm. (Dith Pran/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BOUND BROOKE, N.J. -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- HURRICANE-NY,
09-20 -- Sanitation workers remove debris from homes on Monday
which were left on the side of the street by residents returning to
their flood-damaged homes on Monday. Shopkeepers and residents
returned to Main St. on Monday to assess the damage after the
Raritan River rose to 12 feet above its banks on Thursday night and
Friday following heavy rains from Hurricane Floyd. (Dith Pran/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) TRENTON, N.J. -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- NJ-POLICE, 09-20 --
Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey, left, looks on as Carson
Dunbar talks to reporters on Monday. After months of bureaucratic
delay, Whitman on Monday announced the appointment of Dunbar, a
veteran FBI agent and administrator, as her choice to be the new
superintendent of the New Jersey State Police. If approved by the
state legislature, Dunbar would be charged with leading the
2,700-officer force which has been accused of using racial
profiling to stop motorists and discriminating against minority
troopers. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WALLACE, N.C -- Sept. 20, 1999 -- HURRICANE-CAROLINES-3,
09-20 -- Rain clouds loom over a field of crops and flooded homes
Monday afternoon near Wallance, in North Carolina's Duplin County.
More rain expected Monday night could worsen the North Carolina
flooding caused by Hurricane Floyd that already is blamed for
billions in damage. (Mark Courtney/Wilmington Star-News)
</P>
<P>
