<HEADER>
A9389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-STRATEGY-1STL     09-20 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-STRATEGY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(1,160)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVING THWARTED GORE'S RABBIT STRATEGY, BRADLEY PLAYS THE HARE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Changes `convince' to `persuade,' per style, in grafs 8 and 13;
clarifies in last graf, Floyd is one of the `few,' sted only,
Democrats ...) (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Riding a wave of favorable attention and strong
fund raising, Bill Bradley is adopting a campaign strategy that
mirrors his own meticulous manner: He is preparing for a grinding,
patient battle that could last into the summer, well beyond the
March primaries that many Democrats once thought would deliver the
nomination to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley game plan reflects the organizational strength of
Gore, who has built wide support among Democratic officials across
the nation and whose campaign seems capable of staying afloat even
if Bradley does extremely well in the early primaries.
</P>
<P>
   So while Bradley's advisers say he must win several early
primaries, New Hampshire, California and most important New York,
to build momentum, he must also be prepared to hunker down and
demonstrate that he can outlast Gore as the primary season drags
into April, May and June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are letting people know that we have the resources to see
this thing through for the long haul,'' said Gina Glantz, Bradley's
campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Under this strategy, Bradley and his advisers are doing
everything they can to delay the crowning of Gore as the Democratic
Party's consensus candidate. They have been aggressively wooing
undeclared elected officials and labor leaders. And they have been
urging a host of grass-roots organizations that represent core
Democratic voters _ including blacks, environmentalists,
abortion-rights advocates, gays and lesbians _ to stay neutral, if
not endorse Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   By their reasoning, if Bradley performs well early, he will buy
time to convey his message, establish beachheads in states where
Gore already has established organizations and make Gore appear
unelectable. Forcing the battle into the final June primaries would
also mean that New Jersey, which Bradley represented in the Senate
for 18 years, could tip the balance in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What one sees nationally, slowly, is movement toward Bill
Bradley,'' Douglas Berman, Bradley's campaign chairman, asserted.
``That's because as voters learn who Bill is and how he will
respond to the nation's problems, there is movement toward him.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, political analysts say, the Bradley strategy has worked
relatively well. He has stalled efforts by Gore to win the
AFL-CIO's endorsement, persuaded several abortion rights groups to
stay neutral, received the endorsement of a small environmental
group, Friends of the Earth, and won plaudits from gay and lesbian
groups by advocating broader civil rights protections for
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's eliminated Gore's quick-kill strategy,'' said Bill
Carrick, a Democratic consultant in California. ``It's beginning to
look like a war of attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Gore assert that once Bradley begins laying out the
specifics of his agenda, he is certain to upset some segments of
the Democratic base. They also argue that once centrist and
independent voters in New Hampshire voters see that Bradley has
taken more liberal positions than Gore on several issues, they will
reject him.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley faces a host of other obstacles, including having to
keep pace with the vice president's fund raising _ which, so far,
he has been able to do _ while also catching up to Gore's campaign
organization, which has a presence in most states. Gore, who
represented Tennessee in the Senate before being elected vice
president, seems particularly strong in the South as well as in
California, where he has won endorsements from almost every
Democratic state official.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley must also find a way to compensate for Gore's advantage
in so-called superdelegates _ members of Congress, party officials
and others who will automatically be sent to the Democratic
convention and who account for about 20 percent of all delegates.
Though neither candidate can say exactly how many superdelegates
they have, Gore clearly has a majority.
</P>
<P>
   That means Bradley will either have to win a larger percentage
of the primary vote in major states _ and thus a larger share of
the regular delegates _ or persuade Gore's superdelegates to switch
allegiances, which traditionally has been a difficult thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Bradley _ a Hall of Fame basketball player _
must win a few large states in the early going to prove that he is
more than a celebrity insurgent. Central to his calculations are
New York and California, which both hold primaries on March 7 and
together provide nearly a third of the 2,168.5 delegates needed to
win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a momentum point of view, our desire is to win New York
and California,'' said Gale Kaufman, senior adviser to the Bradley
campaign in California who has strong ties to the state's labor
unions.
</P>
<P>
   Though California has more delegates, New York is viewed by many
Democrats as a more crucial symbolic battleground for Bradley,
since he played with the New York Knicks for 10 years and is
probably better known there than in any other state except New
Jersey and Missouri, where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a must win for him,'' said former Mayor Ed Koch,
who is supporting Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Bradley has put together his most extensive
organization in the country, outside Iowa and New Hampshire.
Running the campaign is Michael DelGuidice, an investment banker
who was chief-of-staff to former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, and
Frank Sanzillo, a lobbyist and former aide in the state
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has also recruited several Democratic organizers,
including William Cunningham, a former chief of staff to Sen.Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., John LoCicero, a former top aide to Koch,
James L. LaRocca, a former transportation commissioner under Cuomo,
and New York City Councilwoman Ronnie Eldridge.
</P>
<P>
   Recent signs in New York have been encouraging for Bradley. Last
week, he won the endorsement of more than 20 Democratic officials
in Brooklyn, which has the most Democratic voters in the state. He
is also expected to pick up the endorsement of Moynihan in the
coming weeks. And last week, three separate polls _ by Zogby
International, Quinnipiac College and the Marist Institute for
Public Opinion _ all showed the race in New York to be a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of their growing concern about the state, Gore's
campaign has begun lowering expectations for their candidate. ``We
have always known that New York would be a tough fight,'' said Kiki
Moore, communications director for the Gore campaign. ``This is
Bill Bradley's back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore campaign is clearly not prepared to give up on New
York. In recent days, Gore has personally called politicians that
seemed to be tilting toward Bradley, including Rep. Jerrold Nadler,
a Manhattan Democrat, and Dominic Baranello, chairman of the
Suffolk County Democratic Committee. Gore was scheduled to meet
privately with Baranello this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to be talking about baseball,'' Baranello said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of how important he considers California,
Bradley has spent more days there this year, 31, than anywhere else
except Iowa. He is planning on delivering his first major policy
speech of the fall, on health care, in Los Angeles next week. He
has raised more money from California than anywhere. And his
campaign plans to open a state office with full-time staff in the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Though the vice president has sewn up the support of much of the
Democratic Party establishment, Bradley's supporters note that Al
Checchi also had endorsements from many California state officials
before he lost last year's gubernatorial primary to Gray Davis, who
went on to win in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because some politician endorses you don't mean his
friends will vote for you,'' said state Assemblyman Richard Floyd
of Carson, Calif., one of the few Democrats in the Legislature to
endorse Bradley. ``But you do get all his enemies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
