<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WALTON'S SCHOOL FOR THE BIG MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Ninety minutes of low-post tutelage
concluded, Bill Walton limped off in one direction and Gheorghe
Muresan walked stiffly in another. Fundamentals aside, the best
advice the most diversely talented center in pro basketball history
might have given the tallest man to ever play the game was what to
do to remain in one large, functional piece.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson one: don't take bold, unnecessary risks, and the minute
you feel sharp pain, by all means, sit down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very slow learner myself,'' Walton said Monday, the
start of three days of big-man workouts, Camp Cure-a-Klutz, at the
Nets' training facility. ``I played on a broken foot. Then you look
back 10 years later and say, `Maybe I shouldn't have done that.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the sore subject of play today, pay tomorrow, Walton opined
that Patrick Ewing should not have hobbled through the Knicks' wild
run on an aching Achilles' tendon. If you didn't hear him say that
on the network telecasts last spring, well, he was thinking it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to pay a huge price for that,'' Walton said,
suggesting Ewing faces the likelihood of pain until he quits.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about the Knicks, but Walton's assessment _ based on
his own unhealthy, unhappy experiences between championships in
Portland and Boston _ wasn't very good news for the metropolitan
area fan already heartsick about Vinny Testaverde's foot in
particular and the New York football season in general. Judging by
Sunday's results, the tender local sports psyche may, by November,
be raw, in need of a quick basketball fix. But the recent medical
word on Ewing and his backup, Chris Dudley (knee), as well as the
report that Jayson Williams won't play for the Nets until at least
January does not bode well for that.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what contingency plans the Knicks are making, as
Scott Layden, the latest in Madison Square Garden executives
schooled at the Pentagon, has reportedly issued a moratorium on
injury updates. The Nets, bless them, just continue to parade more
oversized bodies into their Champion Center. And in what amounts to
a minor managerial miracle, the players are actually coming to work
this week when they aren't legally bound.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no magic pill for the development of skills,'' Walton
said, after reviewing footwork and other basic concepts with Keith
Van Horn, Jim McIlvaine, Jamie Feick and Muresan, the most
intriguing class case.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot-7-inch Romanian import had three fairly productive
seasons in Washington, but in the summer of 1997, after Muresan
stood up tall as straight man for Billy Crystal while filming ``My
Giant,'' his aching foot was fitted for a cast and didn't get
better, and he didn't play for two years. According to John Nash,
the Nets' general manager, the misdiagnosed problem was a vertebra
in his back that was compressing a nerve, causing pain down below.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you feeling?'' Muresan was asked Monday, after
finishing a game of two-on-two _ he and someone named Peter Cornell
against Feick and Van Horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tired,'' Muresan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know much about Walton's career, his injuries?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear something.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Muresan is no threat to displace Walton at NBC, or
tower over him in the Hall of Fame. He did average 14.5 points, 9.6
rebounds and almost 3 blocks a game in 76 games in 1995-96. If
Muresan could somehow replicate those numbers, the Nets would thank
the playoff gods. The Knicks, in fact, would take that production
from Ewing, their giant, in a New York minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``George can be a force,'' Walton said. ``He's not a player who
can jump, who can run. He's got offensive skills. He's intelligent.
He thinks the game. His problem is getting his body to react to his
mental commands.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is what Walton tried to tell Muresan's body, by way of his
brain: Positioning is everything for a man his size. Watching from
the sideline, Dr. Jack Ramsay, Walton's championship Portland coach
in 1976-77, said no big man has commanded space in the paint,
without having to wrestle for it, better than Walton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran to his spot, turned, and his hands were up, calling for
the ball,'' Ramsay said. ``Across the board, no big man has ever
had Bill's variety of skills, when he was healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Always, the issue of health. Over one four-year stretch, Walton
played 14 games. He kept at it, though, until 1985, Boston, and
Larry Bird. He soon after left the sport a champion, limping tall
and proud, a great history lesson to be learned on perseverance and
patience through pain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
