<SLUG> BC-AUTO-LABOR-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL GM AND FORD FOLLOW IN FOOTSTEPS OF DAIMLERCHRYSLER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ DaimlerChrysler AG's tentative contract with the
United Automobile Workers contains company concessions that may
create problems when the union demands similar concessions next
from General Motors and Ford.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler agreed in the contract to hire more employees if
the work force at any factory complex falls by more than 5 percent
during the four-year contract for any reason except a downturn in
automobile sales.
</P>
<P>
   While DaimlerChrysler has a relatively young work force and has
been hiring more workers to keep up with demand for its sport
utility vehicles and pickup trucks, Ford Motor Co. and particularly
General Motors Corp. have large, older work forces that they have
been trying to reduce through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler also agreed to a so-called side letter that
contained a surprisingly categorical ban on any move to get rid of
unionized businesses. Over the years, the UAW has sometimes allowed
auto makers to have different side letters provided that they
accepted identical labor contracts. But the DaimlerChrysler side
letter represents a precedent for an effort by some in the union to
stop Ford's planned spin-off of its auto parts division, which has
$18 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the contract emerged in a compendium of contract
provisions prepared by the union as labor negotiations accelerated
in Canada and the United States Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Basil Hargrove, president of the Canadian Auto Workers union,
said Monday that the risk of a strike against Ford there on Tuesday
night was receding, but that a 35 percent chance of a walkout
remained. And Stephen P. Yokich, the UAW's president, said that
intensive talks with GM in the United States would start on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the current labor contract, DaimlerChrysler and GM had
proposed to guarantee the jobs of current UAW workers with at least
10 years of seniority. In exchange, both auto makers wanted relief
from a provision in the previous contract, which expired on Sept.
14. The controversial provision required DaimlerChrysler, GM and
Ford to hire more workers if employment in any region of the United
States fell by 5 percent or more from 1996 levels because work was
moved to other factories.
</P>
<P>
   But the UAW rejected that proposal. The compendium of contract
provisions released Monday showed that the union and
DaimlerChrysler did not agree on job guarantees for senior workers.
Instead, they retained the rule requiring new hiring and broadened
it to require that workers be hired if employment were to fall
sharply for any reason, and not just because work was transferred
to other factories. The rule also appears to require new hiring if
employment falls steeply at a single factory complex instead of in
a region.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract language is complicated, however, and has a few
small pieces of good news for the auto makers. For example, the
required drop in employment before new hiring occurs will relax
somewhat over the four years of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   A 10 percent drop in a factory complex's work force will be
required to trigger new hiring by the end of the contract in 2003.
The provision nonetheless could pose problems for GM and Ford. GM
had been hoping that up to 6 percent of its work force will retire
each year for the next several years and would not have to be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has been reducing employment at its older car factories in
Ohio while hiring workers at sport utility vehicle factories in
Kentucky, and has run afoul of the ``5-percent'' rule in Ohio.
Partly as a result, Ford has paid Ohio workers up to $45,000 apiece
to move to Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the 1996 agreement also turned out to have important
loopholes that still allowed GM in particular to continue shrinking
its work force, although not quite as quickly as executives had
hoped. Whether the current contract has such loopholes will not be
known for months, but Diane Swonk, the chief economist at the Bank
One Corp., predicted that the auto makers would be able to continue
downsizing somewhat under the new agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and GM declined to comment Monday on the DaimlerChrysler
contract.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler officials also refused to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the side letter, the union's summary said: ``The new
letter states that DaimlerChrysler will not close, nor partially or
wholly sell, spin-off, split-off, consolidate, or otherwise dispose
of in any form, any plant, asset or business unit of any type,
constituting a bargaining unit under the agreement,'' the summary
said.
</P>
<P>
   While the union has always demanded that each auto maker accept
virtually identical labor contracts, covering issues like wages and
benefits, side letters are tailored to each auto maker's
circumstances. DaimlerChrysler's side letter could nonetheless
create problems for Ford, which is making plans to spin off or sell
its auto parts division, Visteon Automotive Systems. The UAW has
left negotiations with Ford for last this year, and could ask Ford
for a similar side letter.
</P>
<P>
   While Ford has long enjoyed the best labor relations in the auto
industry, the union is divided on how to handle Visteon, union
officials said. While many want to prevent a spin-off of Visteon,
others note that GM spun off its auto-parts unit in May without
reaching an understanding with the union first. Because in-house
auto-parts divisions tend not to be competitive, stopping Ford from
following GM's example would result in the union's penalizing Ford
for having tried to negotiate the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW compendium of the contract also said that there had been
no changes in DaimlerChrysler's prescription drug plan. Complaining
of steeply rising costs, the auto makers had sought higher
co-payments for prescriptions, particularly for popular medicines
like Viagra, an impotence treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, UAW compendiums of labor agreements have tended
to be accurate because misrepresentations could result in
subsequent challenges to ratification votes.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, Hargrove, the Canadian union leader, said at a news
conference Monday afternoon that he saw only a 35 percent chance of
a strike when his union's current, three-year contract with Ford
expires at 11:59 p.m. on Tuesday. Ford's initial offer on Friday
had infuriated Canadian union officials, who dismissed it as
inadequate, but Ford revised its offer on Sunday and negotiations
since then have gone fairly well, Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus and energy is to try to do this without a shutdown
of production,'' he said, while cautioning, ``I'm reluctant to say
we can avoid a dispute here.''
</P>
<P>
   James Hartford, a Ford spokesman, said ``there are still a heck
of a lot of things that remain on the table.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
