<HEADLINE>
NO RESISTANCE, NO WELCOME FOR PEACEKEEPERS IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT number of troops to 1,000, sted 2,000,
and deleting British.) (With TIMOR-MILITARY) 
(nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ The vanguard of an international peacekeeping
force staked its claim to this silent and broken town Monday,
watched warily by clusters of refugees, sullen Indonesian troops
and small, angry groups of irregular militias.
</P>
<P>
   There was no resistance but no welcome for the peacekeepers, who
arrived with all the firepower and high technology of modern war.
There was no peace to keep; East Timor's tiny capital is a dead
city _ burned, looted and evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   Through the hot, still day, as dogs barked in the empty streets
and the leaves of banana trees rustled quietly, more than 1,000
Australian soldiers spread out through the city with their heavy
packs and weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Then as the sun went down, three large fires were set in
villages near the airport, their black smoke and bright orange
flames filling the sky, a sort of initiation for the invited but
unwelcome guests.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of a departing troop-transport plane mingled with the
popping sound of burning buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they are testing us,'' said an Australian trooper,
adjusting his night vision goggles as he stood beside an armored
vehicle, watching the flames. ``They want to make us do something
we don't want to do, but as long as we stick to our game plan we'll
be all right and we'll move them out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   Fires have been burning in Dili since the terror here began on
Sept. 4, the day the United Nations announced that the East
Timorese people had voted nearly 4-to-1 for independence from
Indonesia, which invaded and occupied the former Portuguese colony
in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, thousands of people have been reported killed and
hundreds of thousands have been forced to flee their homes by
civilian militias armed, supported and sometimes manned by the
Indonesian military. Indonesia's top military commander disputed
that estimate of deaths Monday, saying the military had recorded
fewer than 100 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was soldiers, men in green berets,'' a villager said of the
men who started one of the fires Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, the commander of the multinational
force _ which is to include some 8,000 troops from a dozen
countries _ praised the cooperation of the Indonesian military
Monday and said the initial deployment of troops had proceeded
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   He said that once the capital had been secured his troops would
begin moving through the territory _ where 800,000 people had lived
before the recent terror _ to neutralize any opposition and provide
support for a huge aid operation.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. Mark Evans, who commands the Australian troops who
make up the bulk of the forces here, said the first day had gone
``very smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased with the support we have had from the TNI
today,'' he said, using the initials for the Indonesian armed
forces. ``That augurs well.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Indonesian transport trucks, with armed
Indonesian escorts, helped ferry the foreign soldiers through town.
But only the foreigners returned the waves of onlookers; the
Indonesians stared back grimly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good reception by the TNI and had a guarded _ I would
call it guarded _ welcome by the local people,'' said Maj. Chip
Henriss-Anderssen, who arrived on the second aircraft Monday
morning in the first wave of Australian troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw men I would call militia,'' he said. ``They were
carrying homemade weapons and they were wearing a mixture of
camouflage and civilian uniforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kennedy, who coordinates relief efforts here for the
United Nations and has remained in Dili for the last two weeks,
said: ``I think the militias are taking flight or keeping a very
low profile. When we see them we stay in our cars and keep going.
We have armed TNI escorts. It's a yin and yang thing. They don't
press the TNI. Many of them are TNI.''
</P>
<P>
   As they drove through the town Monday, the newly arrived
soldiers passed block after block of burned, vandalized and
roofless buildings, their windows smashed, their contents looted.
The home of the Roman Catholic bishop, Carlos Filipe Ximenes Belo,
is a burned shell. So is the city's main hotel, the Mahkota. The
city's tiny shopping district disappeared in flames.
</P>
<P>
   As in the rest of Dili, the vandalism at the small airport _
where giant transport planes landed, unloaded and took off again
all day Monday without cutting their engines _ seemed to have been
an act of violent passion.
</P>
<P>
   In the departure lounge, people had picked up and flung here and
there the rows of molded plastic chairs, as if in a convulsion of
anger. The floor was smeared with feces.
</P>
<P>
   In the offices, the trash was ankle-deep. Computers and
telephones had been looted but someone had gone to the trouble of
dumping a can of blue paint over an old typewriter. A framed poster
of smiling flight attendants had been ripped from the wall and
smashed.
</P>
<P>
   Convoys of yellow civilian trucks rolled out of the city, filled
with refugees and their belongings, evacuating as the peacekeepers
arrived. They were native Indonesians or people who opposed
independence _ the families of militiamen or of civil servants
here, one resident said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are afraid of new fighting,'' said the resident, Misuar
Santos, as he watched them drive past.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier, a man with long hair, several strings of necklaces and
a black Che Guevara T-shirt said he expected that the militias
would withdraw for a while, wait their moment, then resume their
trouble-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they are waiting,'' he said. ``Maybe they still prepare
a bad plan. The militia will not stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, Julio das Dores Soares, 25, said he was a fighter for
independence _ an enemy of the militias _ who had left the city
after the referendum to go to Dare, a stronghold for the guerrillas
just south of here.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is back, he said, with seven of his friends, to assess
the situation. ``Now there is still panic in Dare,'' he said, where
relief officials say as many as 30,000 people have taken refuge.
``They want to come back to Dili but they are still afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   The people in Dare are not yet starving, Soares said, but they
are hungry. ``Many people need food,'' he said. ``Many children are
sick and some have already died.''
</P>
<P>
   Soares stopped abruptly. One hundred yards away two Indonesian
soldiers began slowly walking in his direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, excuse me,'' he said, disappearing quickly among
the banana trees of his village. ``Indonesian soldiers. I go now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
