<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brookline may mimic Brooklyn
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Get ready for the Brookline Stampede. By
mid-week, the U.S. and European players might think they're at the
Phoenix Open.
</P>
<P>
   Locals remember The Country Club, an traditional-style,
close-proximity course, as severely cramped in 1988, when it hosted
a U.S. Open and crowds were in the range of 22,000 to 25,000. From
best estimates, the 33rd Ryder Cup has been oversold by about
10,000 tickets per day.
</P>
<P>
   At least they won't all be out on the course at the same time.
There are 59 corporate tents and 200 tables on the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can be oblivious to it,'' said American Jim
Furyk, ``because half the course is white (tented) out there. With
the noise and that amount of people out there, I'm sure we'll start
noticing it tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadkins predicts rout
</P>
<P>
   Between now and Friday, when the matches begin, there will be
much talk about the strength of the U.S. team and the pressure on
it to produce after two straight losses to Europe. None of this
will matter to Lanny Wadkins, the 1995 U.S. captain at Oak Hill.
``I think our team is going to hammer 'em,'' Wadkins said. ``This
year I think is going to be the first rout in a while.'' . . .
European captain Mark James, who arrived with his team on the
Concorde from London, about the potential for fan rowdiness:
``Kiawah Island was an unfortunate chapter in the history of the
Ryder Cup. . . . Ben (Crenshaw) and I are very much keen to see
that various possible standards _ not only crowd behavior but
player behavior and sportsmanship _ are in every aspect this
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik-Garcia pairing?
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's Jesper Parnevik, who has been campaigning for a pairing
with 19-year-old Sergio Garcia, got some advance playing time with
the young man Sunday as the first players on site. Garcia birdied
four of his last six holes to beat Parnevik 1-up in an informal
match. ``He has that fire that Tiger Woods has,'' said Parnevik,
``so I think he's going to do great in match play.'' While some are
assuming Garcia will be teamed with Jose Maria Olazabal, a Miguel
Angel Jimenez-Olazabal pairing in best ball is more likely, largely
because of Ollie's erratic driving. Garcia can get a bit loose from
the teebox, too. Parnevik, on the other hand, is known for his
accuracy and solid ballstriking.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
