<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NO NEWS TURNS INTO BAD NEWS AT RETAILER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometimes the public shareholders are the last to
learn the really important things about companies they own.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, the J. Jill Group, a catalog and Internet
retailer of women's fashions aimed at affluent 35- to 55-year-olds,
announced that it would post a loss for the third quarter, which
ends on Saturday. It is ending one of its two catalogs, formerly
called Nicole Summers and lately called Nicole, only three months
after announcing that it had repositioned the catalog to aim for
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement came after the company asked NASDAQ to
halt trading, which it did at 2:07 p.m., with the share price down
$4.50, or 40 percent, to $6.875. Trading resumed at 3:22 p.m., and
the stock fell further, closing at $6.125.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a month ago, the shares were trading above $20. From
then through Monday, as the business was evidently deteriorating,
the company made no announcements. By the time it did talk, the
stock had fallen by two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   During the last couple of weeks, the share price had declined
slowly, on gradually increasing volume. Then, on Monday before the
announcement, the floodgates opened. By the time trading was
halted, volume came to 3.6 million shares, more than the total
traded over the preceding seven weeks and equal to more than a
third of the total shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear just how much of the bad news got out, or how it
did. But the heavy volume and the rapid decline of the stock Monday
morning made it appear that something had leaked over the weekend.
A company spokesman said that management would not discuss the
stock price, and Gordon Cooke, the company's chief executive, did
not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke, who took over the company at the end of 1995, had
developed a following on Wall Street as sales and profits grew
rapidly and the company announced plans both to sell on the
Internet and to open J. Jill stores in upscale malls. On Monday it
said that the Internet business, which began Sept. 1, was already
accounting for 5 percent of sales and that plans for the stores
were going well.
</P>
<P>
   But it also said that sales for the quarter would be about $46
million, roughly the same as in the quarter last year, and that the
company expected to lose about 11 cents a share in the quarter, in
contrast to a profit of 14 cents a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   While Cooke had been optimistic about both the Nicole catalog
and the J. Jill catalog in an interview with Bloomberg News on July
15, in Monday's announcement he was quoted as saying that ``the
inevitable slowdown of J. Jill's rapid growth has happened sooner
than we expected.'' The company blamed intensive competition and
the ``proliferation of e-commerce'' for its problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Nicole catalog was begun in mid-August to replace the former
Nicole Summers catalog. It was supposed to feature looser,
less-tailored clothing than Nicole Summers had emphasized. The fact
that it is being abandoned a month later presumably is an
indication that reaction to it was far worse than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The real losers here are those who read the company's press
releases and filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
and assumed that if anything important was going on, they would be
told.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pay Attention to Those Tender Offers
</P>
<P>
   The pros on Wall Street who owned stock in Comsat, the satellite
communications company, have made a lot of money at the expense of
the amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin completed its purchase of 49 percent of Comsat
on Saturday, paying an above-market price of $45.50 a share. If
Lockheed buys the rest of the company _ which it may not be allowed
to do _ it will pay considerably less for the remaining shares.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, it was in the interests of all shareholders to
tender their shares into the Lockheed offer. Yet only about 90
percent of the shares were actually tendered, Lockheed announced
over the weekend, and it will accept 54.26 percent of the shares
tendered.
</P>
<P>
   Those who did not tender passed up a significant profit
opportunity. While there is no way to know who they were precisely,
you can be sure that the vast majority were individual investors
who failed to understand what was going on. Many discount and
Internet brokerage firms feel no obligation to offer advice when
their customers are confronted with tender offers, and some
investors may not have brokers at all.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that those who did tender _ including many
professional traders and institutional investors _ are about $38
million richer than they would have been if all eligible shares had
been tendered. That is money lost by the ones who did not tender.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Comsat fell $5.56, to $30.44. If Lockheed is able to buy
the rest of the shares, it will exchange one of its shares _ which
closed Monday at $33.875 _ for each remaining Comsat share. That
purchase, however, is contingent on getting Congress to change the
law to approve such a deal, and so far the House has refused to do
so. Until it does, Comsat shares are likely to trade at a discount
to Lockheed shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
