<SLUG> BC-RAC-VALENZEULA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENZUELA GET ANOTHER CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Valenzuela, the oft-suspended jockey, is getting yet another
chance under a unique, one-year ``conditional'' license granted by
the California Horse Racing Board.
</P>
<P>
   The CHRB announced Monday that Valenzuela signed an agreement
over the weekend to submit to random drug and alcohol testing and
continue substance-abuse treatment. His new license, effective with
the Sept. 29 opening of the Oak Tree Racing Association season at
Santa Anita, can be revoked if he fails to meet those conditions.
</P>
<P>
   CHRB spokesman Mike Marten said executive director Roy Wood was
swayed by favorable reports on Valenzuela's battle with substance
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, 36, hasn't competed since October 1997, when Santa
Anita stewards barred him indefinitely for missing riding
assignments without being excused, his eighth suspension for
absence and drug-related infractions in a nine-year span.
</P>
<P>
   When Valenzuela shows up, he can be brilliant: He won the 1989
Kentucky Derby and Preakness aboard Sunday Silence, has ridden six
Breeders' Cup winners, and has been the leading jockey six times at
Southern California thoroughbred meets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
