<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-VALENZUELA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENZUELA CLEARED TO RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, Calif. _ The California Horse Racing Board cleared
jockey Patrick Valenzuela for a return to racing, according to a
press release issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The board, which regulates horse racing in the state, issued
Valenzuela, 36, a one-year conditional license. Valenzuela, who was
suspended from racing in October 1997 for missing too many mounts,
was unavailable for comment late Monday. His attorney Donald
Calabria, of Encino, did not return two phone calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela will return to the saddle on opening day at Santa
Anita's Oak Tree meet, which begins Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   `This has been an ongoing discussion for months,` said CHRB
spokesman Mike Marten. `As of Sept. 29 he's eligible as far as
we're concerned. There's no ta whole lot more to say.`
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year Valenzuela was arrested inside a Garvey Avenue
bar on suspicion of robbing a cab driver at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken to the Los Angeles County jail and bound over for
trial following a preliminary hearing dispute the fact that the
alleged victim couldn't identify Valenzuela as the man who robbed
him. The case was thrown out by a Superior Court `In the interest
of justice.`
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that, Valenzuela, who won the 1989 Kentucky Derby
aboard Sunday Silence, began to make his appeal for reinstatement .
In a May interview with Roy Firestone on ESPN, Valenzuela said he
had found religion and was living a sober lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   During hearings on his request, CHRB officials said they
received favorable information about Valenzuela's effort at
reforming from Calabria, other members of the horse racing industry
and Don Murray, executive director of the Winners Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, based at Santa Anita, is an assistance program
for people in the horse racing industry experiencing problems with
alcohol or drug abuse. Valenzuela is required to participate in the
program for the term of his conditional license, Marten said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement paving the way for his return, Valenzuela
agreed to submit to random drug and alcohol testing for one year.
His license can be revoked if he fails the test or quits the
program, Marten said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, Valenzuela was already at work. He took some
training rides at Hollywood Park in preparation for his return,
officials said. He is also working at getting his weight down from
120 to 117 pounds in time for the Oak Tree Meet.
</P>
<P>
   The rider, known affectionately as `P-Val,` has been suspended
from racing on eleven separate occasions for a variety of
violations, according to Marten. Nine of those suspensions were for
failure to show up for work.
</P>
<P>
   News of Valenzuela's return to racing was greeted with mixed
emotion Monday at Fairplex Park.
</P>
<P>
   `Pat Valenzuela is just like all the other athletes who have
been in this position, said trainer Barry Abrams. `He deserves the
chance. Drug addiction is a hard thing to fight. Hopefully, he will
see this as his last chance.`
</P>
<P>
   Privately, several jockeys expressed skepticism that Valenzuela
would be successful.
</P>
<P>
   `But, they'll give him the mounts, because he's that good,` said
one rider, who asked no to be identified. `He's like a cat -- nine
lives.`
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, who has had success with Valenzuela, said he wouldn't
hesitate using the jockey.
</P>
<P>
   `He's got the talent,` Abrams said. `He can ride with the best
of them. He ital on was ital off the best of them at one time.
</P>
<P>
   `The only way I wouldn't use him is if one of the owners didn't
want him,` Abrams continued. `But, it's not like he went and killed
someone.
</P>
<P>
   `If he can prove on the track he's as good as he was before,
he'll get the (mounts),` Abrams said. `I think a lot of trainers
feel the same way.`
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE,WEST COVINA, CA  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
