<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-ECON-600&AMP;ADD-NY     09-20 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JAPAN THESE DAYS, FEW SPEAK KINDLY OF CENTRAL BANK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Bank of Japan is under siege. At no time since the
central bank was granted independence from government control last
year as part of a sweeping reform of the nation's financial system
has it come under so much pressure.
</P>
<P>
   International experts ranging from the U.S. Treasury Department
to prominent private economists and investors want the central bank
to loosen what the bank already considers a loose monetary policy.
A looser monetary policy, they say, will help give the Japanese
economy the jolt needed to loft it, finally, out of a decade-long
slump.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the pressure is the unexpected strength of the yen,
which hit a three-year high against the dollar last week, setting
off concerns that it would derail the start of any economic
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, however, says it can do little more to spur the
economy _ having dropped interest rates practically to zero,
injected large sums into the money markets and yet produced little
in the way of increased demand for money to spend and invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large amounts of excess reserves currently exist in the
banking system,'' Kazuo Ueda, a policy board member, said in a
recent speech. ``Not a single bank has said that a further increase
in reserves would increase their lending.''
</P>
<P>
   The wrangling has evoked a sense of deja vu among economists
here. ``It's very, very reminiscent of the bad old days,'' said
Brian Rose, an economist at Warburg Dillon Read, ``when the Bank of
Japan had no independence and the press would announce its policy
changes ahead of its own announcements, the Ministry of Finance
ordered it around, and politicians felt free to weigh in as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank has resisted the appeals to do more, but on Tuesday,
the policy board will hold its regular meeting, where monetary
policy and the strength of the yen will undoubtedly be discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Currency traders, the country's leading financial daily
newspaper and others were betting Monday that the bank would
capitulate and announce plans to increase the money supply that
would work in tandem with some sort of foreign intervention to
suppress the yen's rise.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations of an announcement weakened the yen in Tokyo
trading and contributed to a surge in the Tokyo stock market, where
the benchmark Nikkei index of 225 issues rose 1.34 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese government officials also think that the bank will move
on Tuesday to ease monetary policy _ but in such a subtle way that
the markets may miss it at the outset, and foreign governments may
be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The officials are betting that while the bank would not reverse
any of its policies, it would begin increasing the money supply,
probably by adding to the 1 trillion yen pile of money _ $8.9
billion at current exchange rates _ it leaves in the market every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Such an increase would achieve the same effect as the
abandonment of Japan's ``sterilized'' currency interventions to
influence the yen's exchange rate. In such interventions, the
central bank offsets the surge in the money supply created by
selling yen with other actions in the money market.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and others who are concerned about the yen's
strength have said such interventions have only limited effect. But
the Bank of Japan does not want to be seen as caving in to the
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on the central bank over yen intervention
underscores the steadily rising tension between the central bank
and its former masters, the Ministry of Finance and ruling
political party. That tension has been simmering since April 1998,
when the bank was made independent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There also is a continuing confrontation over government bond
purchases, with the Finance Ministry and prominent politicians
urging the central bank to underwrite government bonds and the bank
refusing to take on that role.
</P>
<P>
   The bank contends that would give the government unfettered
ability to spend money at a time when the country's debt has
climbed precariously. Central bank officials are still resentful
that pressure to purchase government bonds was perceived as the
impetus behind its decision in February to reduce interest rates to
one-quarter of a percent.
</P>
<P>
   In its effort to defend its independence thereafter, the bank
has further compromised the perception that it makes monetary
policy solely on its own. ``The Bank of Japan seems always to be
driven into these untenable situations,'' a senior official said in
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, when it made moves to aid corporations with
financing, it was seen as responding to political pressure at home,
and in February, when it lowered interest rates, the bank was
accused of bowing to the dictates of Robert Rubin, then the
American secretary of the Treasury, who had inveighed upon the bank
to ease monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sympathetic to their rationale for doing what they do, but
markets and the political environment change rapidly and sometimes
it's better to act preemptively,'' said a senior Finance Ministry
official, who insisted that the ministry had not tried to
strong-arm the central bank. ``Unfortunately, they have tended to
wait until the last minute before taking action, and thus appear as
if they're being forced into it by those who have already advocated
it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the bank evidently feels as if it has been backed
into a corner. No one could have made that clearer than its
governor, Masaru Hayami, during comments after a meeting with
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa's remarks were those of the seasoned politician he is.
He said he had not discussed any specific issues regarding monetary
policy with Hayami. ``We had an important exchange of opinion,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he apparently angered Hayami by telling reporters that he
had arranged the meeting, thus suggesting that once again, the
Finance Ministry was trying to dictate to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Hayami subsequently declared that the bank had no intention of
changing its policy on ``sterilized intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The zero interest rate policy is already more than sufficient
as a monetary easing step,'' he said, forgoing the even more
nuanced language with which most Japanese officials speak.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps even more telling was the choice of venue for the
meeting. Apparently, neither man wanted to be seen on his
opposite's turf, and so they met in a hotel room in central Tokyo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
