<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW SAFE ARE THRILL RIDES?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, my husband and I took some grandchildren to watch a
tiny circus set up on a baseball field in Maine. We particularly
hoped to see the elephant put up the tent poles with her trunk. No
such luck. A backhoe was used.
</P>
<P>
   The elephant's owner shouted to bystanders that the elephant
could do the job better, but that animal-rights people usually
arrived as she started, and by the time all the documents and
veterinary certificates were inspected, the tent-pitching was
behind schedule, and it was easier to use a machine.
</P>
<P>
   True or not, the tale indicated that people had their eyes on
the elephant in her daily work life giving rides and lumbering
along in the parade.
</P>
<P>
   That memory returned while I was researching amusement park and
carnival safety in the light of the recent cluster of four roller
coaster deaths. Whose eyes are on the carnival rides, and what
powers do they have to protect the customers, especially young
ones?
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, that one-ring circus, which performed twice and
struck its tent, was inspected by the Maine Department of Public
Safety when it came into the state, and the rides were checked
after they were set up. But that show was also under the eye of the
federal government because the rides traveled from state to state.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the big rides in Ocean City, N.J., Santa Clara, Calif.,
and Doswell, Va., that brought four deaths last month, or those
involved in the two earlier reported deaths this year, in Coney
Island, and in Arlington, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Congress shifted jurisdiction over nonportable, or
``fixed,'' rides _ roller coasters, whirling devices, water rides
and the like _ to the individual states to inspect and regulate. At
this time, legislatures in 42 states have established some
oversight of amusement rides, according to the Federal Consumer
Product Safety Commission, and 8 states have none: Alabama, Kansas,
Missouri, Montana, North Dakota, South Dakota, Utah and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   The state laws have some relationship to the importance of
amusement parks to a state's economy. Florida, for example, home of
Disney World, Universal Studios Escape, Busch Gardens, Sea World
and Wet 'n Wild, has a law that exempts from inspection permanent
facilities with 1,000 full-time employees that maintain an
inspection staff approved by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Isadore Rommes, head of the Bureau of Fair Rides Inspections in
the Florida Department of Agriculture, says his bureau inspects 120
to 125 smaller parks twice a year, as well as mobile rides. ``We
think we have the most stringent law in the United States,'' he
said. Since 1987, there have been no recorded deaths on fixed rides
in Florida but two on mobile rides and two on rides whose status
was not known.
</P>
<P>
   California has 72 permanent theme parks and 48 roller coasters,
the most of any state. But although it has had 15 ride-related
deaths in 25 years, its law has remained as it was in 1968, with
mandatory inspections only for mobile rides and aerial tramways.
</P>
<P>
   However, this year the legislature was still in session in
August, when the four ride deaths occurred nationally, and on Aug.
25, when the Boomerang ride at Six Flags Marine World in Vallejo
stuck, stranding 28 people above the ground in 100-degree heat for
four hours.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators had before them since January a bill presented
by Tom Torlakson, a democratic assemblyman from Antioch, in the
East Bay area, to end the exemption for permanent rides. It was
Torlakson's second attempt with such a bill, and there had been
three other efforts since 1979, when there was a rash of accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week of the legislature, Torlakson's Assembly Bill
850 was approved. ``It was unfortunate that we had such a
mysterious rash of accidents,'' Torlakson said. ``But they raised
public awareness, and people began to ask why we were not
regulating this area. The bill was poised for passage this time,
but events clinched it.'' The assembly confirmation vote was 66 to
6.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis said he looked forward to signing a bill to
enhance consumer safety. His signature will mean that beginning
Jan. 1 all permanent amusement parks will be checked annually. Los
Angeles County, which performs its own inspections, is not covered
by this law.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency's summary also shows that six states with
regulations do not have government employees conduct inspections,
but assign this to insurance companies or other private
organizations. These are Arizona, Minnesota, Mississippi, New
Mexico, Tennessee and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The amusement park industry often describes its rides as less
hazardous than the automobile trip the family may take to get to
the park. Noting that there were 900 million rides taken in 1998,
John Graff, president of the International Association of Amusement
Parks and Attractions, said that the possibility of being injured
seriously enough to be hospitalized was 1 in 25 million and the
possibility of being killed was 1 in 450 million.
</P>
<P>
   It also compared 43 deaths listed by the government Consumer
Product Safety Commission since 1987 to the 141 people killed by
air bags in cars since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Although it does not regulate most of the rides, the safety
commission compiles data on ride-related deaths through death
certificates, hospital records and news reports. The injury
statistics are developed from the National Electronic Injury
Surveillance System, which sorts through hospital emergency room
data by codes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From Jan. 1, 1987, to June 30, 1999, the agency's list of 43
deaths linked to amusement rides _ deaths of employees are excluded
_ included 21 children under 16.
</P>
<P>
   The reports for 1998 and '99, the agency said, are still
incomplete, but the agency said the largest group of deaths, 11 in
the 1987-99 period, involved roller coasters. Whirling rides like
the one at Coney Island were involved in 10 deaths, water rides in
4, trains in 3 and Ferris wheels in 2.
</P>
<P>
   The agency noted a trend toward increased injuries from 1994 to
1998, which may be a result only of an increase in the number of
rides and riders, or may have additional causes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the agency estimated, there were 9,200 amusement-park
injuries treated in emergency rooms: 2,100 involving mobile rides,
4,500 fixed rides and 2,600 where the type of ride was not known.
The agency estimated that 0.8 percent of these injuries required a
hospital stay, a very low rate since the overall hospitalization
rate for all areas was about 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although the agency gathers and publishes amusement park injury
and death figures, as it does for other sorts of products, it has
no power to investigate or link injuries and deaths to four
potential causes: consumer behavior, operator behavior, mechanical
failure or design limitation.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Brown, chairwoman of the product safety commission,
describes herself as frustrated. A number of officials in the
industry, including a spokesman for the International Association
of Amusement Parks and Attractions and a spokesman for the Six
Flags theme park company, say that rider behavior _ ``horseplay,''
one spokesman called it _ is at fault in more than 75 percent of
the cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know if there is a pattern,'' Ms. Brown said.
``The industry can say something, and they may be right and they
may not be right. We need federal oversight of amusement park
rides. We need to do what we do in other areas. We need on-site
surveys, so we can come up with recommendations.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said her agency considered children a major concern.
``When a product is investigated,'' she said, ``we separate out the
cases involving children under 5 and work on what needs to be done,
and then at the next level and so on.'' In the cluster of four
deaths last month, there were two children, one 8, who died with
her mother in the roller coaster in New Jersey, and a disabled
12-year-old, who died on the Drop Zone, a ride at Paramount's Great
America in California.
</P>
<P>
   The amusement park trade organization has been fighting on
several fronts to avoid injuries and to improve its reputation.
Boyd F. Jensen, a lawyer who serves on the safety committee of the
amusement park group, said his group was pressing states to adopt
``patron safety laws'' and that 15 jurisdictions had. ``There are
three causes of injuries,'' he said, ``customer behavior, operator
behavior and mechanical safety. These last two are heavily
regulated but there aren't any laws that attempt to regulate the
behavior of patrons. We are just trying to even the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jensen's model laws provide civil penalties for patrons who
interfere with rides or do not comply with posted rules. ``People
need to know there will be a consequence if they cause accidents,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel L. Cliff, a spokesman for the amusement parks group, which
has a convention in Atlanta in November, said that guidelines for
safety signs were being worked on. One version adopts the three
shapes and colors used in skiing because, the literature said, it
is logical to have a uniform standard for all forms of recreation.
A ``mild thrill attraction'' would have a round green sign, a blue
square would indicate ``moderate thrills'' and a black diamond,
``high thrills.''
</P>
<P>
   One version of a black diamond sign had this text: ``High speeds
with extremely unusual and stressful physical forces. This ride
contains startling and unexpected thrills appropriate only for the
most healthy and physically able riders.''
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission's directory of state
amusement ride safety officials can be read on the commission's Web
site at www.cpsc.gov. Or a copy of the information for a particular
state may be obtained by sending a request and a stamped
self-addressed envelope to the commission, whose address is simply
Washington, D.C. 20207.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
