MORTON UPSTAGES McCULLOUGH FOR USC 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One of the pressing questions to emerge from USC's
narrow victory over San Diego State is what happened to freshman
tailback Sultan McCullough?
</P>
<P>
   After rushing for 83 yards in 17 carries against Hawaii,
McCullough carried the ball just three times for 10 yards against
the Aztecs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In (McCullough's) case, I felt like Chad Morton was having a
good game,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``Nothing against Sultan
at all. It was a close game.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton gained 91 yards in a career-high 30 carries against San
Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad's going to go as much as he can go. I never felt at any
time that he needed to rest,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Morton thought the Trojans had difficulty running because San
Diego State's defense had more players rushing than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the plays got messed up because they brought an extra
guy we couldn't block,'' Morton said. ``It was a great job by their
defensive coordinator. He knew when we were going to run the ball
and brought an extra guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes probably out: Wide receiver Windrell Hayes doesn't expect
to be available for Saturday's game against Oregon, but his first
thought after spraining his right ankle Saturday while delivering a
block was the fear that the injury was more serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to hold back the tears,'' Hayes said. ``I had all kinds
of stuff going through my mind. I'm just looking forward to
rehabilitation now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky call: One play that worked in USC's favor was a no-call on
an incomplete pass from Carson Palmer to Morton in the fourth
quarter, with the Trojans leading 17-14.
</P>
<P>
   Morton was behind the line of scrimmage, and the play was
technically a lateral, meaning it should have been a live ball with
two San Diego State players nearby. But the officials ruled the
play an incomplete pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they missed that,'' Hackett said. ``It looked like a
fairly quick whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   Right place, right time: Cornerback Kris Richard had two
interceptions against San Diego State, and was grateful for his
good fortune since both came on poorly thrown passes from
quarterback Jack Hawley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing my assignment, and it was like, `Oh look. A nice
gift. A gift from God,' '' Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State game time: Kickoff for the Oct. 2 game against
Oregon State at the Coliseum will be 3:30 p.m. The game will be
televised on Fox Sports West 2.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Hackett had this analysis of USC's performance
against San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked like a team playing its first game,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Palmer, Hackett felt the sophomore had a good game,
despite two interceptions that were not entirely his fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't play as crisp a game as the game before but it's
hard to,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer completed 14 of 16 passes in Hawaii, and 16 of 24 passes
against San Diego State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
