<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: 5 STARS FOR SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike the world's fanciest hotels and restaurants, car
dealerships are hardly the kinds of places people think of as
rating five stars, where how people are treated matters as much as
what they've come to buy.
</P>
<P>
   But DaimlerChrysler is spending big bucks _ more than $30
million _ on a new advertising campaign by Bozell Worldwide, a unit
of Bozell Inc., to try to change that perception, at least for its
4,500 dealers nationwide. More important, the ad campaign reflects
the company's response to the changing environment for car dealers,
who have come under pressure in recent years as auto superstores
like Car Max have come on the scene, and again as more people try
to buy cars on the Internet to avoid repeating bad experiences in
car dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler will try to harness its vast purchasing power to
offer dealerships that treat customers right the chance to save
money by buying goods and services through the auto company. The
savings could amount to $500 a vehicle, a collective $1 billion in
the first couple of years, according to James Holden,
DaimlerChrysler's executive vice president for sales and marketing.
``This can be huge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most automakers have been experimenting with dealer
relationships in the United States _ from buying up car dealerships
and grouping them together to create superstores to taking them
public to selling cars through the Internet. DaimlerChrysler
studied all of their attempts, and has finally settled on a
strategy. Instead of possibly angering its dealers by sidestepping
them with Internet sales and corporate ownership, it will hold out
several carrots to encourage them to provide better customer
service for new car buyers as well as those bringing cars in for
oil changes or repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Dealerships willing to spend time and money training employees
and spiffing up showrooms are given the so-called Five Star rating,
and only dealers with that rating qualify for a number of goodies.
Advertisements like those to be introduced this weekend will
encourage buyers to look for the Five Star signs; Internet
inquiries will be referred only to Five Star dealers, and most
important, Five Star dealers can cut their costs by buying supplies
_ from phone service to office supplies to health insurance _
through DaimlerChrysler. Other automakers have more of an
arm's-length relationships with dealers.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's American dealers spend $40 billion a year
buying goods and services, not including cars, nearly as much as
the $44 billion a year DaimlerChrysler spends in North America. All
dealers will initially be allowed to buy products and supplies
using negotiated discounts from the company's procurement team _
Chrysler was known for its ability to winnow costs from suppliers
before its merger with Daimler last year. But within two years,
dealers who want to use the service must be certified as Five Star
dealers or lose eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The new effort, called Five Star Market Centers, is now being
tested at 10 dealers in Indianapolis and will roll out nationwide
in the next 12 months. To illustrate the potential savings, Holden
told of an initial meeting with a national telephone-service
provider in which the phone company offered to drop its preferred
rate by 40 percent for affiliated car dealerships. ``We believe we
have the makings of a competitive advantage that is not readily
copyable,'' he said. Dealers selling former Chrysler company brands
_ Dodge, Chrysler, Plymouth and Jeep _ will be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler hopes that by promising to save dealers money,
they will buy in to the changes the company wants them to adopt.
``This is a change in the culture at our dealerships that must be
bought into,'' said M. John McDonald, DaimlerChrysler's senior vice
president for sales and service.
</P>
<P>
   To become Five Star certified, dealerships must follow 350
steps, including sending sellers to special training in customer
service and agreeing to follow certain processes for selling cars.
So far, after a two and a half year effort, 1,600 of the 4,500
dealers eligible have qualified, and 400 more are expected by
year's end. Ten have fallen off the wagon and been decertified,
Holden said.
</P>
<P>
   Television ads will start on Sunday during an NFL football game
and on ``60 Minutes,'' and will then be shown in a rotation that is
intended to reach 95 percent of the target market, 25- to
54-year-old heads of households. The ad campaign is so heavy that
the company calculates that each person in the target group will
see the ads 17 times. There are two TV ads now, and three will be
added soon.
</P>
<P>
   Print ads will follow in Time, Newsweek, Forbes, Fortune,
People, Architectural Digest and other magazines, as well as in 37
local newspapers for four Sundays later this year. Starting next
Tuesday, there will also be ads in The Wall Street Journal and USA
Today. And radio ads will run in 20 large markets.
</P>
<P>
   One television ad shows dealership employees working together to
get a customer's car ready quickly, and uses a motif of employees
tossing his keys to each other with impeccable timing.
``Introducing Five Star: a new approach to selling and servicing
cars and trucks,'' an announcer intones. The tagline is: ``Five
Star. It's better. We'll prove it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Marketing experts said the ads would probably speak to dealers
as much as to potential customers. ``It is going to make the
dealers feel pretty proud,'' said Jan Thompson, chief executive of
Designory Inc., a marketing firm based in Long Beach, Calif. that
specializes in building automotive brands. ``That would make me, if
I weren't one of those dealers, want to be one.''
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler said dealers should already want to be Five Star
dealers because the elite dealer group is more profitable. Five
Star dealers, on average, earn a 4.6 percent return on sales, while
other dealers for DaimlerChrysler and other companies typically
earn between 2 percent and 2.5 percent, Holden said.
</P>
<P>
   Creating the ads was a challenge because the Five Star
certification amounts to a business process. ``Advertising a
process is very, very difficult,'' said A.C. Liebler,
DaimlerChrysler's senior vice president for marketing. ``It can be
duller than dog food.'' In fact, one of Bozell's ad campaigns was
panned by dealers and was scrapped, Liebler said.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler said it would spend as much on these ads as it
spent on ads introducing a new car, and Liebler confirmed the
amount was well above $30 million. DaimlerChrysler spent $1.4
billion on advertising for all its brands in 1997 and 1998, and
spent $734 million in the first six months of this year, according
to Competitive Media Reporting, a unit of VNU that tracks
advertising spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Five Star name has been used by the company since the 1960s,
but was less widespread and did not refer to the same rigorous
customer satisfaction program. And of course Chrysler's corporate
symbol has been a pentastar since 1963.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
