<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KEY SERIES IN SEPTEMBER HAS THE FEEL OF OCTOBER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mets have been gazing at the scoreboard, staring at the
standings, watching the Braves on television and hearing more
questions about Tuesday night's series opener in Atlanta than a
17-year-old hears about prom night. This should be a memorable
experience, everyone tells the teen-ager. The Mets have heard that
same promise and should believe it, three times over.
</P>
<P>
   Some Mets were calm and some were giddy as they discussed their
enticing chance to finally overtake the Braves in the National
League East _ they are one game back, and Tuesday they begin a
three-game series in Atlanta _ a journey that officially began in
April. But, although many of the players have changed from last
season's fiasco of a finish and only John Franco has endured the
long stretch of exasperating seasons in Queens, the wait for this
chance started before 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have been the premier team in the league over the
past decade, so, in essence, the Mets, who have not advanced to the
post-season in 11 years, have been pursuing them in some way for
the entire period. The Mets have not been this close to the Braves
this late in the season since Atlanta was shifted to the NL East in
1995, more reasons for hyping these three games and the three that
will be played next week at Shea Stadium. The setting provides more
reasons for the Mets to hope they can reverse the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prudent approach is to not overestimate and overanalyze
these games because we still have a playoff spot to fall back on
with the wild card,'' Orel Hershiser said. ``But the secondary
thought is since the Mets' organization has been chasing Atlanta
for so long, that it sure would be nice to finish first.''
</P>
<P>
   First place would mean more to the Mets, who have the best
record in the major leagues since June 6, five games better than
the Braves. If the Braves faltered and ended their streak of seven
straight division titles, they could blame it on their shocking
spate of injuries and cite how their experience will help them in
the post-season, anyway, even if they are a wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets, first place is about grabbing respect and
eliminating any belief that they are similar to last season's team,
an 88-victory squad that gagged by losing five consecutive games to
botch a one-game lead for the wild-card berth. As much as these
Mets have proved to be much better and much different than that
team and are on a pace to win 99 games, that image of last season's
failure will linger in some fashion until they reach the
post-season. Finishing ahead of the Braves, who have won the NL
East by a whopping average of 14 games in the last four years,
would be a major achievement for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought process before every series is winning the
series,'' Al Leiter said. ``It's the same way with this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone in this clubhouse is thinking about winning
the division. I hope everyone is focused on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Softly, yet firmly, John Olerud said: ``This is our opportunity
to go down and win it. We're going head to head. If we play them
well, we can win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Manager Bobby Valentine, who had danced around questions
about the Braves like a hyper Rockette before Sunday, sounded like
the boxing referee Mills Lane when he declared, ``Let's get it
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Of course, this will not be an easy chore for the Mets
since the Braves have their rotation aligned imposingly with John
Smoltz, Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux, all Cy Young award winners,
expected to start the three games. The Mets will counter with Rick
Reed, Hershiser and Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious yet unspoken concern for the Mets is starting
Reed in the first game because, since being activated, he has
surrendered seven earned runs on 13 hits and six walks in 10
innings (6.30 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   Reed has escaped with two no-decisions, but he cannot continue
allowing two base runners in an inning and expect to beat Atlanta.
Especially since the Mets have lost four of six games to the Braves
this season and eight of nine at Turner Field in the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser said the Mets should treat the series ``like do-or-die
games,'' and compared the team to a high-wire act. But, instead of
walking on the wire without a net below, the Mets have a net in the
form of the wild card. But Mike Piazza warned that the Mets'
four-game bulge over the Reds is not invincible and said, ``If one
team comes out and takes the whole thing and Cincinnati is playing
good baseball, they could sneak up on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, besides one additional home game in the division
playoffs and possibly the League Championship Series, the Braves
and the Mets could also be fighting for a chance to face Randy
Johnson. If the post-season opened today, the Braves, as the
first-place team in the same division as the wild-card winner,
would oppose Arizona in a three-of-five-games series and face
Johnson twice. Yet, Leiter said: ``Randy can be dominant, but you
have to win a maximum amount of games. You can't try to map out
your post-season.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite appropriately, that has been done for the Mets and the
Braves in the regular season. The two finest teams in the NL East
will play six times in the next 10 days, giving September an
October feeling and giving the Mets the sweet chance that they have
pursued throughout the 1990s. For the Mets, a prom night of sorts
is finally here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure would be more fun to answer questions about catching
Atlanta and we can say, `Isn't that great?' instead of `Do you guys
feel like you're second fiddle again because you're getting in by
the wild card?''' Hershiser said. ``It would be nice to make our
day a little easier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
