<HEADER>
A9445 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      09-20 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND DEFENDANT GUILTY IN JASPER DRAGGING DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ A white supremacist who boasted that he was
``soaring like an eagle'' after the ``rush'' of chaining a disabled
black man to a pickup and dragging him to death near Jasper last
year was convicted of capital murder Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, which included no black members, deliberated for four
hours before delivering its verdict against Lawrence Russell Brewer
Jr., 32. Jurors then returned to the courtroom to begin the
punishment phase of the trial, which continues Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, the second white man to be convicted in the June 7,
1998, slaying of James Byrd Jr., showed no reaction as state
District Judge Monte Lawlis read the verdict before a packed
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's father, siblings and other relatives who had sat in the
front row of the courtroom through five days of testimony nodded in
agreement, and some cried silently. Lawlis had warned spectators
against any verbal outbursts in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, the family approached the courtroom rail
and hugged each of the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel as though a second weight has been lifted from our
shoulders,'' Byrd's sister, Mary Verrett, said outside the
courthouse. ``We knew from the beginning that the prosecution had a
very good case, a very strong case. It wasn't based on sympathy for
the Byrd family. It wasn't even based on the murder just alone by
itself. They had facts to show that this person enjoyed what he did
to my brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was tortured and then he was killed, and they got much
satisfaction out of that,'' she said. ``So needless to say, the
Byrd family, we too, are satisfied right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Verrett said that while she expects Brewer to get the death
penalty, she and her family will again put their faith in the jury
and will accept whatever punishment it gives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relieved, that's the word,'' Jasper County District Attorney
Guy James Gray said, adding that the prosecutors were getting
nervous awaiting the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jasper returned the case against (Brewer's co-defendant)
Bill King, some people would say they were just trying to protect
themselves,'' he said. ``When you move it half way across the state
of Texas, and another jury returns a guilty verdict, it kind of
broadens the scope. It speaks for all the state of Texas I think.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is we're long past those days that we were
embarrassed by. Race relations have improved a whole lot and we
don't want to see them slide backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's defense team, Doug Barlow and Layne Walker of Beaumont,
left the courthouse without commenting, as did Brewer's brother,
John.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is expected to begin deliberating Wednesday on the
sentence for Brewer, the former ``Exalted Cyclops'' of the
Confederate Knights of America, a small prison gang affiliated with
the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   He faces either death by injection or a life prison sentence,
for which he would have to serve at least 40 years before becoming
eligible for parole. Gray agreed with the Byrd family that a death
sentence would be appropriate. ``I don't like the death penalty,''
he said, ``but that's what he deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's former prison buddy and fellow racist, John William
``Bill'' King, 24, of Jasper, was convicted by a mostly white jury
in his hometown earlier this year and sent to death row. The third
defendant, 24-year-old Shawn Allen Berry of Jasper, will be tried
next month in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, whose trial was moved to Brazos County at lawyers'
request, spent more than four hours on the stand Friday in an
unsuccessful attempt to convince the jury that while he kicked Byrd
and spray-painted his face black, he did not kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said it was Berry who offered an intoxicated Byrd a ride
as he walked down Jasper's Martin Luther King Boulevard on his way
home from a friend's anniversary party.
</P>
<P>
   And, Brewer testified, it was Berry who killed the 49-year-old
father of three, slashing his throat with a knife, stripping him,
chaining him by his ankles to a pickup and dragging him more than
three miles through the East Texas woods.
</P>
<P>
   During closing arguments, Gray reminded jurors that Dr. Tommy
Brown, the pathologist who performed Byrd's autopsy, had testified
that Byrd's corpse showed no evidence of a knife wound.
</P>
<P>
   Brown had shown jurors more than a dozen color photos of Byrd's
remains and explained in graphic detail how Byrd had used his
elbows, knees and heels to shift his weight from side to side to
ease his pain and keep his head off the pavement as he was dragged
down a logging road and then a blacktop road east of Jasper. Byrd's
torture ended, Brown said, after two miles when his body slammed
into a concrete culvert, decapitating him.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's head, shoulder and right arm were found the next morning
in a ditch next to the culvert. The rest of his mutilated body was
found a mile down the road, outside the gates to a rural black
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was alive and he was conscious, and Shawn Berry didn't cut
his throat,'' Gray said. If he had, he said, Byrd's shirt and
undershirt would have been soaked with blood. There was no blood
found on either, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said Brewer's testimony was filled with lies and had a
recurring theme: ``Bad things happened to Russell and it wasn't his
fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn Berry is not exactly a powerhouse,'' he said. ``It took
all three of these men to subdue James Byrd. One of them had to
hold him down while they put chains on his feet. He's not going to
take that without fighting with all his energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said Brewer had concocted his story in an effort to
convince the jury that his involvement in the killing was minimal
so he could escape the death penalty. In his version, Brewer
insisted that Berry chained Byrd and King unchained him, and he
indicated that Byrd may already have been dead when he was chained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russell Brewer crafted his story to stay just short of a
capital offense,'' Gray said. ``He's not afraid of that
penitentiary. Out here on the street, he can't hold a job. He can't
do much of anything. But in that penitentiary, he's an officer,
he's a big shot. He's the Exalted Cyclops of a prison gang.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gray said his best evidence in the case was Brewer's DNA
found on a cigarette butt and beer bottle at the crime scene and
Byrd's blood on the defendant's tennis shoe. That evidence became
moot, however, when Brewer took the stand and admitted his
participation.
</P>
<P>
   And even before he testified, Brewer had written several
incriminating letters to friends and jailhouse notes to his
co-defendant, King. He called himself a ``star'' and said he was
``the hero of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   In one note, intercepted by jailers as the three defendants sat
in the Jasper County Jail, Brewer assured King that they would both
go free, just like O.J. Simpson, if they could agree on a story and
blame Berry. And he mentioned the logging chain, wondering if
authorities would be able to pull their fingerprints from it.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing argument, Barlow said Gray had ``a very vivid
imagination'' about what happened the night of Byrd's killing.
</P>
<P>
   Even if jurors decided that Brewer was lying, he said, the state
still did not prove its case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has proven that he was there, he has racist
tendencies and he popped off and bragged in his prison talk and
nothing more,'' Barlow said. ``You have to ask yourself, where is
the proof of who did what?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
