<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-WEB-BID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAN GROUP HOPING NFL WILL ACCEPT ITS BID FOR JETS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Internet investment group formed last month to acquire the
Jets from the Leon Hess estate said Monday that it had received
pledges totaling $17.5 million from about 8,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The group, BuytheJets.com, has also received local political
support from New York City Council Speaker Peter Vallone, state
Controller H. Carl McCall and three members of Congress to persuade
the National Football League to change its rules to permit its bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are starting to think this can happen,'' John
Crotty, a co-founder of the group, said. ``The demand is there. Our
numbers are real.''
</P>
<P>
   However, NFL rules bar partnerships of more than 25 individuals
to own a team, and require that the general partner own at least 30
percent of the team. ``Their interest is flattering, but their
structure doesn't comply with our rules,'' Greg Aiello, a league
spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the league waives its rule to permit BuytheJets.com to
enter the bidding process, it will not receive the confidential
sale prospectus that other potential buyers have received from
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., the investment bank handing the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Crotty has held one meeting with Goldman, Sachs and said that
``we are encouraged by the recognition and optimistic about the
bid's potential.'' Crotty said his group wants to emulate the
publicly owned corporation that runs the Green Bay Packers, a
structure that has been grandfathered by the league but is
prohibited for anyone else. If the BuytheJets.com bid succeeds, the
fan-owners would elect a board of managers and name a president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple idea and the response has been overwhelming,''
Crotty said. Since going on line on Aug. 17, the BuytheJets.com Web
site has received 500,000 hits. At least week's season opener for
the Jets, about 8,000 ``Let Us Bid'' signs were handed out to fans
by 30 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the game, people wanted to give us cash,'' said Crotty, who
first suggested the idea of buying the team to his friend Peter
Lyons during a golf game on Memorial Day. ``We didn't know if
people wanted to do it, but they've been enthusiastic.''
</P>
<P>
   With the price for the Jets expected to exceed $500 million,
Crotty said. his quixotic initiative must raise at least $180
million to become the majority owner of the team. He said the
fan-initiated bid would consider linking up with other bidders.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a letter to NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue, Vallone said:
``We only ask that the people of New York be afforded the
opportunity to coordinate a bid for the Jets, and not be summarily
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``If fans are able to have a vested interest in their team, it
can only extend and enhance the traditions that define the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   In his response to Vallone, Tagliabue rejected the online bid as
a structure that ``presents many serious issues and concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote: ``We have found that stable, locally based ownership
of the sort that the Giants and Jets have had for so many years is
a model most likely to result in successful club operations that
advance the interests of fans and communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six potential buyers have signed confidentiality
agreements with Goldman, Sachs to read the financial prospectus.
Among the suitors are Charles F. Dolan, Cablevision's chairman;
John McMullen, owner of the NHL's N.J. Devils; Fred Wilpon, the
Mets' co-owner; real estate developers Samuel LeFrak, Steve Ross,
Bill Mack and Sam Grossman; cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder; and Kirk
Kerkorian, the billionaire from Las Vegas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
