<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ATLANTA, IT'S CRUCIAL TO STAY ON TOP
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Forget unacceptable. For anyone associated with the
Atlanta Braves in the 1990s, anything less than a division title is
inconceivable. This is, after all, a team that has won an
unprecedented seven consecutive division crowns.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, events could be set in motion that force the
Braves to abdicate their throne. On Tuesday night at Turner Field,
the Braves open a three-game series with the Mets in what has
turned into Atlanta's most important series since 1993, the last
full season the Braves were in any real danger of finishing
anywhere but first place.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, despite a seasonlong succession of injuries that would
have finished off most other teams long ago, the Braves (93-57)
take both the best record in baseball and a one-game lead in the
National League East over the Mets (92-58) into the final two weeks
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Braves and the Mets have 12 games to play. Six of them
are head to head over the next 10 days, with the three in Atlanta
and three in New York, Sept. 28-30.
</P>
<P>
   Though both teams might qualify for the post-season anyway, that
is not assured, as Cincinnati began Tuesday night trailing the Mets
by four games in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   So how important is holding off the Mets, Atlanta's All-Star
third baseman, Chipper Jones, was asked last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important only in that we've got a string of them
going,'' he said, referring to all those division titles. ``The
main focus is to give ourselves a chance to win a World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have won only one World Series in Atlanta, in 1995,
despite their four NL pennants in the 1990s and the seven straight
division titles.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the Braves' legacy is on the line, too, these next
two weeks: as the team of the decade, over the Yankees, or as the
most underachieving team. It will probably take a second World
Series championship to assure the acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be validation,'' Atlanta General Manager John
Schuerholz said. ``And from a players' standpoint, it would be the
proper validation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said: ``I think it would be nicer to win it all this year
over any other year. People don't expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason this has been the Braves' most interesting
one season in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' said Atlanta's team president, Stan Kasten. ``But
the Chinese have a proverb, one that you might call a curse: `May
you live in interesting times.' And while it hasn't been good times
this season, it has been interesting and challenging. And you'd
have to say, the Braves have met every challenge thus far.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenges started with the loss of their best power hitter,
Andres Galarraga, to non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, and their closer,
Kerry Ligtenberg, to elbow surgery before the season began. It was
an ominous harbinger of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz went on the disabled list with a sore elbow on May
17 and again on July 5, and has changed his delivery, forsaken his
best pitch (his slider) and is experimenting with a knuckleball.
</P>
<P>
   Within two days in late July, Odalis Perez the rookie fifth
starter who injured his elbow, and Javy Lopez Atlanta's No. 1
catcher who hurt his knee, went down for the season because of
their injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, both Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine got off to
horrendous starts. Maddux (18-8, 3.35 ERA) has righted himself.
Glavine (11-11, 4.35 ERA), who won his second Cy Young award last
season, has not. Smoltz, meanwhile, is a mediocre 9-8, though he
has a 3.51 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are scheduled to face Smoltz, Glavine and Maddux this
week. As a result, this week the Mets will actually miss the
Braves' best starter _ Kevin Millwood, who is 18-7 with a 2.78 ERA
and who shut the Mets out on two hits over eight innings on July 3.
Millwood, however, is in line to pitch at Shea Stadium on Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets also might not see Brian Jordan, the slugging
outfielder who has a team-leading 106 RBIs. His season might be
over because of a nagging injury to his right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Millwood said, ``it's not like we haven't had to deal
with things like that all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have taken four of six games from the Mets this
season and swept the Mets in the final three games last season to
knock them out of the wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets have been the hottest team in baseball since June
6. For one day in July and eight in August, they were alone in
first place. Since Aug. 20, however, the lead has again belonged to
Atlanta, which has not finished out of first place since the
strike-shortened 1994 season. And there was no post-season play
that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of sit back and wonder how you are where you are,''
said Jones, who is hitting .320 with 41 homers and 98 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz said this season did not remind him of 1993, when the
Braves won 104 games and beat out the San Francisco Giants for the
NL West title by one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We added a player, Fred McGriff, of high quality that
season,'' Schuerholz said. ``This year has been the opposite. Our
roster has been depleted of those kind of players.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet we sit here talking with the best record in
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the next two weeks, the Braves will either have an
eighth straight division title, a first wild-card berth or an early
vacation. How they play the Mets will almost certainly determine
which one.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no matter how you cut it, we've played well for 10
years,'' Manager Bobby Cox said. ``And we're still playing well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
