<SLUG> BC-ROLLS-VICKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLS-ROYCE TO BUY VICKERS FOR $933 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Rolls-Royce PLC has agreed to acquire Vickers PLC for
$933 million, saying the deal will create a giant in the growing
market for engines and other propulsion systems to push ever-bigger
ships at ever-higher speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from making marine engines and power plants, Rolls-Royce
is the world's second-biggest manufacturer of aircraft engines, and
the chairman, Ralph Robins, told reporters the purchase of Vickers
was intended to achieve the same status in marine power systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is to get to No. 1 or 2 in the various markets in
which we operate,'' he said. ``We are up there in aerospace. This
will put us there is marine.'' Chris Springham, a Rolls- Royce
spokesman, said the two companies' combined sales in 1998 were some
$1.36 billion with combined operating profit of $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase brings together two of Britain's oldest engineering
companies. Vickers began in 1828 in the Sheffield steel business
and became nationally known as a shipbuilder, military contractor
and engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as part of a reshaping, Vickers sold Rolls-Royce
Motor Cars Ltd. _ which is not connected with the engine maker
Rolls-Royce PLC _ to Volkswagen for $790 million.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deal, finalized in secrecy over the weekend and signed
late Sunday night after less than a week of negotiations, came as
``a huge surprise,'' said Brian O'Keefe, an analyst with
Commerzbank here.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, investors appeared to be perplexed by the price
Rolls-Royce paid to buy a company that includes not just marine
propeller, diesel engine and turbine parts businesses but also a
land-based military business whose future is uncertain in the
post-Cold War era. Shares of Rolls- Royce fell 10.75 pence, to
close at 215.25 pence, in trading here.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest Vickers contract is a $2.4-billion order from the
British military for the Challenger II tank, which ends in 2001.
Vickers, which is credited with having invented the tank in World
War I, has already said that it will lay off 650 workers when it
closes one of its two Challenger II factories late this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marine business is a good fit, but the defense business is
not something that anyone would like to go out and buy,'' O'Keefe
said. Indeed, Rolls-Royce indicated in a statement that the Vickers
tank business would be spun off and that Rolls would ``examine its
options to participate'' in military industry consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   The main attraction of the deal, Rolls-Royce said in a
statement, was the Vickers marine businesses, which grew
significantly last year with the purchase of Ulstein Holding of
Norway, the world's second-biggest manufacturer of propellers and
other marine power equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The deal values Vickers stock at 250 pence, a 50 percent premium
on Friday's closing price of 165.5 pence. Additionally, the two
companies said, Vickers shareholders would keep a proposed interim
dividend of 2.85 pence, meaning a total premium of 53 percent on
Friday's close. Vickers shares surged 80.5 pence Monday, to 246
pence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
