<SLUG> BC-PLAYBOY-WRESTLERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN OPPOSITE CORNERS: THE WORLD WRESTLING FEDERATION AND PLAYBOY
MAGAZINE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ According to the lawsuit, it is a dispute over
``intellectual property rights.''
</P>
<P>
   That in itself would not be surprising, but the combatants in
this rarefied legal battle are the World Wrestling Federation and
Playboy magazine. And the intellectual property at issue is the
character Sable, described in the lawsuit as a ``sultry temptress''
in a skintight cat suit who, as wrestling fans well know, was once
the WWF's women's champion.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF, producer of the widely watched Wrestlemania and other
televised wrestling shows, Monday asked a federal district judge in
Manhattan to block Playboy from exploiting the WWF's trademarked
name Sable for a nude photo feature next month. Playboy is planning
to publish an issue sold only at newsstands, the suit said,
entirely devoted to Rena Mero, who wrestled as Sable.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF, a private entertainment company based in Stamford,
Conn., said in its suit that it had created Ms. Mero's Sable
character, who was also known for carrying a whip and ``gyrating
her hips and body in a highly suggestive, sexual manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said it gave Playboy permission to feature Ms. Mero
as Sable on its April cover and inside the magazine, but Playboy
then had published a second nude pictorial without permission in
September, billing it as: ``The Rematch. Sable Returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the suit contends, Playboy is preparing a special issue,
again without permission, with headlines like ``The Woman You Loved
as Sable in the Raw.''
</P>
<P>
   Playboy, the lawsuit says, is ``brazenly flaunting WWF's
valuable intellectual property rights.''
</P>
<P>
   A Playboy spokeswoman, Elizabeth Norris, had no comment, saying
the magazine's lawyers had not yet seen the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry S. McDevitt, a lawyer for the WWF, said Playboy's
continued use of nude photos of the Sable character was tantamount
to the wrestling federation's ``using the Playboy Bunny to sell our
goods.''
</P>
<P>
   In defending its legal claim on the Sable trademark, the
company's lawsuit also offers a revealing glimpse at how its
down-and-dirty matches are scripted, with preordained results.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says, for example, that Sable was introduced in April
1996, in a minor role, and ``gradually developed a personality and
character over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Sable was portrayed as a ``valet'' to escort a male
wrestler, Hunter Hearst Helmsley, into the ring, to hold his robe
and cheer for him, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, the suit said, ``the Sable character was
scripted to become, and did become, the WWF Women's Wrestling
Champion.''
</P>
<P>
   An initial hearing in the suit, which also seeks unspecified
monetary damages from Playboy, was set for Wednesday, McDevitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mero quit her role as Sable in June, and filed her own suit
against the World Wrestling Federation that month, charging breach
of contract, unfair trade practices and intentional infliction of
emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   McDevitt said the WWF had reached a settlement with Ms. Mero,
the financial terms of which were confidential. Her lawyer could
not be reached by phone Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
