<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC AND VODAPHONE DEAL SEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bell Atlantic Corp., the nation's largest local phone
company, and the international wireless giant Vodafone Airtouch PLC
could announce as early as Tuesday a joint venture to combine the
two companies' U.S. cellular telephone operations, valued between
$70 billion and $80 billion, people close to the companies said
</P>
<P>
   While negotiations could break down at any point, one person
said that the discussions were proceeding well and, at least as of
early Monday evening, both companies were committed to getting the
deal done. Executives and advisers from Vodafone and Bell Atlantic
spent much of last weekend in New York hammering out the details of
a coast-to-coast combination that would rival the national wireless
networks of the AT&AMP;T Corp. and the Sprint Corp., and comprise more
than 23.5 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone merged with Airtouch Communications, the largest United
States cellular company, this summer after snaring the company away
from Bell Atlantic. Executives from Vodafone and Bell Atlantic have
been discussing the joint venture since July.
</P>
</TEXT>
