<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9459 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      09-20 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PALER SHADE OF WHITENESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Normally, I wouldn't begin feeling guilty for being a
White man in America until April. Maybe even May.
</P>
<P>
   This year, my timetable for Caucasian self-reproach was pushed
forward by the folks at Arizona State University, who of fered for
the current semester a one-credit course titled ``Exploring Your
White / Euro American Roots.''
</P>
<P>
   The existence of this class caused a small controversy on
campus, which (nat urally) was blown all out of proportion by the
local papers and TV stations. This, in turn, jump-started my
otherwise dormant sense of pasty-faced remorse, regret and
recrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The course originated at the universi ty's Intergroup Relations
Center and was condemned last week by one ASU staff member for
``providing a space for Whites to navel-gaze without compelling
them to squarely face their role in perpet uating racial oppression
in this society.''
</P>
<P>
   It turns out, however, that facing our role in racial oppression
is exactly what students in the course are supposed to do _ while
gazing at their milky-white na vels.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the director of the center told a Republic reporter,
``It is not a course on Euro-American history. It is more about
looking at oppression, dis crimination, this concept of
Whiteness.''
</P>
<P>
   Kris Ewing, who is the center's assist ant director, told me she
is most inter ested in ``creating a dialogue'' in which people of
different races, sexes, ethnici ties and sexual orientations can
come to gether and mull over issues like, ``What does it mean to be
White?''
</P>
<P>
   Given the anxiety that question causes me, I always try to put
it off. &QL; 
Look at those legs
</P>
<P>
   Most years, I don't begin to contemplate my Whiteness until
early spring, and only then because I have no choice. That's the
time of year when temperatures rise, long trousers give way to
cutoff jeans and I'm forced to switch on the blindingly fluorescent
light bulbs known as my legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, are you white!'' I'll invariably be told, often in
public, forcing me to confront the heckler about how impolite it is
to mock another human being _ particularly if he's your father.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at ASU apparently didn't produce this course for me
and my kids, however.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ewing, ``We are raising a lot of good discussion
over issues that have challenged a lot of communities. This is a
dialogue course, a chance to bring students together and dialogue.
La tinos and Whites. Men and women. Afri can-Americans and Whites.
All with the goal to provide some level of understand ing through a
safe space.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing points out that ``there's some privilege to being White.''
She said her course is designed to ask, ``Whom does it advantage?
And, whom does it disad vantage?''
</P>
<P>
   While exploring my own personal White / Euro American roots,
back in Pittsburgh, I discovered that my two grandfathers had the
advantage of riding in steerage from Italy to the United States,
where they had the privilege of working in a steel mill.
</P>
<P>
   Along with African-Americans, Lati nos, Poles, Serbs, Irish and
so on.
</P>
<P>
   My father, my brother and I had the same privilege.
</P>
<P>
   And, while I've always considered my self pale-skinned, I didn't
know I was White _ with a capital ``W'' _ until I, too, attended a
university. &QL; 
Strange fixation
</P>
<P>
   Skin color is a lot more important to college professors than it
is to people of all shades slaving away in some industrial hellhole
to save the cash needed to provide their children the privilege of
attending a college. Such as ASU. Where students can waste their
time and their folks' money contemplating Whiteness.
</P>
<P>
   Or not.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, ASU had to cancel the class after only four people
(of unknown color or IQ) registered for it.
</P>
<P>
   The course will be available next se mester, though, and
everyone at the uni versity seems pleased and proud to offer it.
Which is enough to make your white, black, brown, red or yellow
skin crawl. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
