<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-SCHOLAR-NYT &LR;      09-20 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOLAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOICE OF CLINTON FOR HUMANITIES TALK MEETS RESISTANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Since 1972, the National Endowment for the
Humanities has selected a leading scholar to give its annual
Jefferson Lecture on the Humanities. Past recipients of the honor
have included Lionel Trilling, Robert Penn Warren, John Hope
Franklin, Sidney Hook, Toni Morrison, Gwendolyn Brooks, Gertrude
Himmelfarb and Barbara Tuchman.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the chairman of the endowment, William R. Ferris, said
the lecturer in 2000 would be President Clinton, and some scholars
are not happy.
</P>
<P>
   John Hammer, the director of the National Humanities Alliance,
said he was concerned that the choice of Clinton, who appointed
Ferris chairman, would politicize the endowment, a federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The list of lecturers until now has been very distinguished,
without regard to politics,'' Hammer said.
</P>
<P>
   John H. D'Arms, president of the American Council of Learned
Societies, told The Chronicle of Higher Education, which first
reported the selection of Clinton on its Web page Monday, that he
was also concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when one is very careful about trying to
depoliticize the humanities and the arts in the United States in
the eyes of Congress,'' D'Arms told The Chronicle, a ``speech by
President Clinton might have the reverse effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferris defended the choice. ``You take a little heat when you
make a change,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of inviting Clinton, he said, was to begin a
tradition in which all presidents would deliver a Jefferson
Lecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are expanding the endowment to reach the whole country,''
he said. ``We're opening all the doors and windows. Having the
president reflect on his or her relationship to the history of the
nation is part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Because history is one of the endowment's main components, the
endowment has helped to finance many presidential history projects,
Ferris said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if what he was doing would be considered an injection
of politics, Ferris replied: ``In a way it is. We're a political
reality. We depend on Congress and the White House for our very
existence.''
</P>
<P>
   But any politicizing, Ferris insisted, was bipartisan because
the Clinton invitation would set a precedent to be followed in
future administrations, regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   One former chairman of the endowment, William Bennett, said that
the invitation to Clinton was not only a politicization of the
endowment, but a partisan one as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is horrible, corrupt, but it fits the pattern of this
administration,'' said Bennett, a conservative Republican who
served in the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bipartisan?'' Bennett asked. ``I don't think so. The
Clinton-appointed chairman picks the guy who picks him to give the
lecture, a guy who has no qualifications, and calls it bipartisan
and broadening.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett added, ``Clinton has not only been corrupted; he has
corrupted all of those around him, and this is an example of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferris said of Bennett's criticism, ``It's short-sighted to
couch this as a partisan issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to create a historical record,'' he said. ``We
will have a bipartisan record.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferris said Clinton, a friend, had not answered the invitation
by Monday evening but that he expected the president to accept. The
White House did not respond to a call seeking comment. The lecture
is given in the spring in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how Clinton could be regarded as a scholar, Ferris
said: ``The endowment's founding language calls for bringing the
humanities to the American people. No matter how visible the
lecturer is, very few Americans have ever heard of the Jefferson
Lecture. This will bring it to every American. People will become
aware of what the humanities are. It will broaden the humanities
and touch the lives of all citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferris acknowledged that Clinton, whose advanced degree is in
law, was not a scholar in the traditional sense, adding, ``But he
is in the Jeffersonian sense that every citizen has the right to
express their thoughts about the nature of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the typical president would not simply assign the
speech writing task to an aide, Ferris said he thought each
president would write every humanities speech, seeing it as an
opportunity to express his philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer, the director of the National Humanities Alliance, said:
``I understand they are hoping it will provide more publicity. I
imagine that's true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990920.0243 </DOCNO>
