<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUKECRASH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
F-16 CRASH 7TH FOR LUKE PILOTS THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BARRETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A fighter jet crashed on Sept. 20 just north of Luke
Air Force Base, the seventh accident in the past year involving
pilots from the West Phoenix base.
</P>
<P>
   The F-16 jet appeared to have overrun the runway, after the
pilot was unable to stop and ejected safely. The jet then plunged
through a fence that surrounds the air base, crossed Northern
Avenue and hopped over an irrigation canal before coming to a rest
in a field owned by the Air Force, just south of a rural
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Thompson was out in his work shed tinkering with an old
car engine when he heard what he describes as ``a loud poof.'' He
guessed immediately it was the sound of another F-16 jet crashing
near his home _ the second jet from Luke to crash within a mile of
his property this year.
</P>
<P>
   This one landed in a field a few hundred meters south of his
home, in an area his neighbor calls ``The Kill Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Crashes) keep getting closer,'' said Thompson, who has
lived a half-mile north of the base for 17 years. ``They're getting
too close.''
</P>
<P>
   After witnessing two of the crashes, he said he's surprised no
one has been seriously hurt of killed. In each F-16 crash this
year, the pilots have been able to eject safely. However, this most
recent accident was the first in which the $20 mil lion jet was not
completely de stroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Air Force officials say there's no question the F-16D jet
involved in the Sept. 20 crash sus tained more than $1 million in
damage, making it a ``Class A'' mishap. That makes it the eighth
F-16 jet to crash in Arizona since fall, all but one involving Luke
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Four Luke crashes have been attributed to engine problems. Offi
cials say a landing gear malfunction caused another crash, and
pilot error was blamed for a sixth. The report hasn't yet been
released for the crash of an Air National Guard jet near Gila Bend
in June.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials say they don't know the cause of the Sept.
20 crash. They say it does not appear to be related to any past
crashes, nor was it likely an engine problem.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Maj. Sharon J. Preszler, had reported an electrical
malfunc tion about 10 minutes before she reached the base. The jet
was returning from training at Beale Air Force Base, near
Sacramento, Calif., with another Luke jet, which landed safely on a
parallel runway.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to stop her jet, Preszler, who was alone in the
two-seater jet, ejected from the ground about 1,000 feet from the
end of the runway, officials say. The 34-year-old pilot landed
safely in a grassy area just north of the runway. She was treated
and released from the base hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Base firefighters arrived at the scene within seconds and put
out a fire sparked by the crash. Maj. Derek Kaufman, a base
spokesman, said they likely saved the plane from total destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Preszler, an instructor pilot at Luke for almost two years, has
been in the Air Force about 13 years. She had more than 3,400 hours
of flight experience _ nearly one-third of it in the F-16 jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very well-qualified,'' said base spokesman Mary Jo
May.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the electrical mal function may have prevented Pre
szler from lowering the jet's hook, an alternate method of stopping
the aircraft. A cable was stretched across the north end of the
runway as a measure of last resort for pilots making emergency
landings, but Kaufman said the plane's hook was not lowered to
catch the cable.
</P>
<P>
   Though the jet crashed onto a field owned by the Air Force, it
came to rest just a dozen feet from the property's boundary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This underscores why we think it's vital that we don't develop
this area,'' Kaufman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has sent a team of investigators to the scene. It
will likely be two to three months before the accident report is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Luke is the largest F-16 training base in the world, flying
about 180 sorties a day. But all jets were grounded after today's
incident. Base commander, Brig. Gen. John L. Barry was out of town
Monday and unavailable for comment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
