<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-NY-ART-NYT &LR;      09-20 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-NY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 NO RELIEF FROM STORM PROBLEMS FOR N.Y. REGION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also HURRICANE-NY-SCOUTS, HURRICANE-CAROLINAS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the beginning of the workweek Monday, a day when
thousands of people throughout the New York region were hoping to
return to work, slide into a set of comforting routines and give
themselves a little more cushion from the jarring effects of
Tropical Storm Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in parts of New York and New Jersey, the day turned out
to be no better than Sunday, Saturday or Friday. Thousands remained
homeless. Thousands continued to scratch by without electricity or
telephone service. Schools stayed closed. Some automated teller
machines failed to spew money on demand.
</P>
<P>
   And the supply of water, all of a sudden, became a major concern
in a region still trying to wring itself dry, as thousands of
people were urged to stop using water for mundane chores, and
dozens of corporations, including some of the largest employers in
New Jersey, were urged to close because of low water pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after Floyd whipped through the area, many people were
still reeling from its aftereffects, even those who thought they
had escaped the worst of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water, you think it's always there,'' said Julie Capelo, a
housewife in Bridgewater, N.J., who was in line Monday for free,
potable water arranged by the township. ``But now, it's like you
can't do the wash. You can't bathe. You can't do the dishes. You
can't really cook, and all the restaurants are closed. It's
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Cranford police announced that on Saturday night, one of their
officers, Lt. Russell Scott Wilde Sr., 33, apparently killed
himself after working 48 hours nonstop on rescue and evacuation
efforts related to the flooding of the Rahway River.
</P>
<P>
   About 350 people in Cranford were evacuated from several hundred
flooded homes, and police received 750 flood-related calls, said
Capt. Eric Mason of the Cranford Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extensive hours that Lt. Wilde worked and the level of
responsibility that he had, we feel greatly contributed to this
tragedy,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the death toll from Floyd for the New York region now
stands at six. The damage has yet to be assessed, though officials
believe that the storm has caused hundreds of millions of dollars
in property damage. President Clinton has declared eight New Jersey
counties and four New York counties federal disaster areas,
enabling homeowners and businesses to seek federal disaster relief
in the form of housing, grants, loans and other assistance.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, more than 1,000 people, mostly in the center of
the state, in places like Bound Brook and Manville, remain
homeless, driven out first by raging rivers and later by the threat
of contamination. They sulk and pray in makeshift shelters at
schools, forlorn and disoriented, feeling as if life's rug has been
pulled out from beneath their feet.
</P>
<P>
   In New York state, more than 100 people remain dislocated,
including 17 or so who were evacuated from their homes in
Haverstraw Monday afternoon because of soil erosion, said Robert
Wingate, a spokesman for the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   And while those numbers have dwindled as cleanup efforts
continue and more people return to their water-logged homes, there
is a chance, as early as Tuesday night, that more rain and even
more flooding may come. An inch of rain is expected Tuesday, and
the National Weather Service has declared a flood watch advisory
for northeastern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly bears repeating that just because Floyd struck
the area several days ago, it doesn't mean that conditions can't
change on short notice in the days to come,'' Wingate said.
</P>
<P>
   There were some signs of improvement Monday, the fruit of
continuous efforts by emergency officials, volunteers and repair
crews.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic said the major telecommunications hub in Rochelle
Park, N.J., that was inundated by flood waters on Thursday night,
knocking out telephone service to a million customers, returned to
full operation Monday. New Jersey's major utility companies
reported that the number of customers without electricity had been
reduced to 30,000, mainly in the northern and central parts of the
state. By day's end, most of the region's transportation network
was back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, thousands of people around the country were finally able
to withdraw cash from automated teller machines. On Friday, flood
waters had forced the evacuation of the Rochelle Park data
processing center run by Electronic Data Systems Corp., one of the
country's largest operators of ATMs. By late Monday, 90 percent of
the machines affected around the country were back in order, said
Reed Byrum, a corporate spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, big problems remained Monday, related to the impurity
and inadequacy of the water supply.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, flood waters from the Raritan River roared
into the primary pumping and filtration plant of Elizabethtown
Water Co. in Bridgewater, N.J. Ever since, company officials have
urged its 550,000 customers in Union and Somerset Counties and
parts of Middlesex and Mercer Counties to boil water for three
minutes before using it. As a precaution, officials at other water
companies have asked customers to do the same, bringing the total
to 2 million around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabethtown officials have also been concerned about low water
pressure. So they have urged their largest customers, including
major corporations and the Bridgewater Commons mall, to remain
closed to conserve water for firefighting and other vital purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
