<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-20 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-NY-MANOR-NY     09-20 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-NY-MANOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBORS WADE IN TO SAVE OLD MANOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also HURRICANE-NY, HURRICANE-CAROLINAS) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLEEPY HOLLOW, N.Y. _ Philipsburg Manor, one of the oldest
historic sites in New York state, came close to being swept away in
the flood from Tropical Storm Floyd, but was saved when museum
curators and security guards, neighbors and history buffs and even
a local girls' soccer team all pitched in to divert the flow of a
furious river.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers returned Monday to shovel debris, clean colonial
knickknacks and carefully excavate antiques from the caked mud.
Burns Patterson, director of public relations for Historic Hudson
Valley, which operates the manor and five other historic sites,
said the support was gratifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people you sit side by side with at a computer desk
were hip deep in water getting their khakis wet,'' he said. ``I
sacrificed a pair of wingtips, but it was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble started Thursday night when uprooted trees and
debris caught on the supports of a 17th-century-style wooden
footbridge here and obstructed the flow of the Pocantico River, a
small tributary of the Hudson. Blocked from its course, the river
turned east and cut a wide swath through a hillside right between
the stone manor house built in 1685 and a 1960s reproduction of a
Colonial-era grist mill.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly five feet of water flooded the first floor of the manor
house, cracked the foundation and sent some antiques, including a
brass milk pitcher, floating downstream. A rare 18th-century Dutch
cupboard was bobbing in the kitchen when Geoffrey Carter, the
director of preservation, was summoned by security guards around 4
a.m. on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were huge trees coming down the Pocantico River, and
they were battering the side of the mill,'' Carter said Monday
afternoon. ``I thought for sure we were going to lose it. We
didn't, but we lost a retaining wall and a dock.''
</P>
<P>
   By 9 a.m. on Friday, nearly 70 employees of Historic Hudson
Valley were enlisted to don life jackets, loosen the logjam and
load sandbags in front of the manor house, which was once one of
the busiest commercial centers in New York and is now a living
museum of Colonial life popular with school groups. Later in the
day, museum volunteers and neighborhood residents arrived and
offered their services. By 3 p.m., a dozen girls from the Hackley
School, a private school in Tarrytown, gave up their soccer
practice to load sandbags.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good time,'' said Emily Cleveland, a junior. ``We
felt like we were helping people, and we were happy not to be at
practice for once.''
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts stemmed the tide until later that night when a
nearby company, County Asphalt, filled the river's channel with 12
truckloads of rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if this had been a computer factory, if people would
have chipped in like they did,'' Burns said. ``I think it shows
what history means to people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
