<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERSONAL VISION PROVES ELUSIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last Thursday morning, as rain beat against the
windows, Calvin Klein was in his office giving a reporter a preview
of the spring collection he planned to show the next day.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned Babe Paley, as a model appeared in the sort of
sheath she might have worn, except it was in trendy nylon. As Klein
went on, making a lot of hip references to the nerd style now in
vogue with London teen-agers, but blandly, without obvious personal
associations, it was hard not to notice a photograph leaning
against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   It was a portrait of Nicholas de Gunzberg _ Baron de Gunzberg, a
well-connected Vogue editor of the 1950s and '60s who knew Diana
Vreeland, Cecil Beaton; well, everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Was it true, Klein was asked, that Baron de Gunzberg had
discovered him?
</P>
<P>
   The designer brightened with that. ``Yes,'' Klein said, ``he was
my mentor.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, four blocks away, in Bryant Park, another of the
baron's proteges was getting ready for his final show. Bill Blass
had come along in an age when everything in fashion was personal.
The feuds, the glamour, the excitement. One felt something, and it
showed in the clothes. It was not for nothing that John Fairchild,
the former Women's Wear Daily editor, and a very personal tone,
once said that ``you can hear the sound of the traffic of New York
in Bill's clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   But today, who could you say that about? Someone like Tommy
Hilfiger may be a genius at marketing, but take away the rock
bands, the models, the videos of screaming teen-agers, and what do
you have but a graying businessman with no personal identification
with the clothes. This was the thing, more than any other, that was
noticed as the New York shows ended last week. And it wasn't
confined to middle-aged esthetes trying to project an air of hip
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Duke sent out a collection on Friday that didn't seem
especially personal _ broad-striped balmacaans, beaded slip dresses
and long shirt dresses that could have been designed by Oscar de la
Renta or Halston, and in fact probably were.
</P>
<P>
   Klein tends to say more through his sensational advertisements
than his fashion shows, which tells you how the focus has shifted.
On the runway, his clothes look drained of life and the emotions
consonant with it; one doesn't look at a pale gray sheath of papery
nylon or a silvery white suit of something called ``compact nylon
micro-check'' and think, Marvelous, let me at it. One thinks,
Sanitarium. It would have helped if Klein had injected into his
cold palette of white, nickel and pale blue a rebellious streak of
fuchsia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if one ignored the presentation, there was much to admire
in the collection, especially Klein's clever use of flagrantly
square men's-wear fabrics like tattersall and seersucker shirting
stripes. Before his show, Klein said the inspiration was the homey,
workaday fashion that one used to find at J.C. Penney's _
button-down shirts, skinny belts and shrunken vests over polo
shirts. It is also a look currently being revived by men's-wear
designers, including Klein: the nerd as a sexy individual.
</P>
<P>
   There were other familiar styles that modern-thinking women will
gravitate toward _ namely, shells and tops in paper-thin leather or
cotton worn with slim skirts or poplin trousers; shirt-waist
dresses in those almost invisible shirting stripes and checks;
georgette slips veiled with beaded tulle in a grid pattern, and a
singular python skirt in vivid azure. Given the sleek prettiness of
the clothes, it's hard to tell if Klein's hip nerdiness mattered or
simply gave the collection a with-it spin. Either way, women won't
care.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan had a doubleheader on Friday, showing her main
collection in the morning and her DKNY line at night in a tent
pitched in Central Park. Although both shows were something of a
no-brainer _ simple tops and bottoms at DKNY, variations of the
wrap shirt and scarf skirt in the main line _ Ms. Karan was so
firmly in familiar territory that one couldn't help but think the
day belonged to her.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, she rarely deviated from the idea of showing a
close-fitting top, whether in jersey or tightly wound chiffon or
crinkled cotton, worn with an asymmetrical skirt fluttering around
the knees. The look was a clean, intelligent update of her original
notion of pairing a bodysuit with a soft skirt. And though the show
was hardly more than a variation on a single theme _ now a stretch
chiffon wrap dress over a sheer navy slip, now an ivory jersey tank
with an ivory suede wrap skirt _ the upshot was a solid expression
of a designer's personal ideals. For too long she has dabbled in
the weird and Zen modern, when all anybody wants is the modern.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, with a klieg light ricocheting off the granite
front of Fifth Avenue, Ms. Karan sent out her DKNY collection.
Actually, it came pounding out as male and female models advanced
in columns of suede and skimpy leather. There were lacquered jeans,
bright sleeveless tops puckered with zigzag seams, tie-dyed
effects, and apron dresses with plastic stripes. It was young and
sexy, with no mental leaps.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the runways, Duke's perky knit hot pants and
popover tops looked warmed over. Ditto shiny trousers with a white
undershirt in the frisky sports style of Isaac Mizrahi. But then
too much in this otherwise colorful collection seemed a reprise of
other designers' greatest hits. The design team of Bruce continued
to perfect its idiosyncratic take on elegance, with raw denim
dresses, crochet knits and leather versions of the '80s blouson
top.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Richard Tyler seemed to come undone by his
under-the-sea theme. His show delayed by Floyd, he opened with
signature leather pants open at the sides with crochet insets.
There were sharply cut jackets, some looking slightly shrunken over
a bandeau top and hot pants hoisted up the rear. Things hit a snag
as the models, their heads plaited to resemble kelp, came out
dragging long skirts of misty chiffon, one overlayed with netting.
</P>
<P>
   So the collections, at least in New York, are over. The big
themes that stood out were a return (again) to pretty clothes, with
prints and sweet-pea tints like pink, lavender and pale blue offset
with flashes of peony, and some inventive uses of men's-wear
fabrics like glen plaid and tattersall.
</P>
<P>
   But if there was a moment when one felt something close to
emotion, even a sense of privilege, it was Bill Blass' show. Not
only were the clothes with-it, in a nonchalant way _ flared black
trousers with raffia fringe, jackets as casual as a windbreaker _
they evoked the unerring hand of Blass.
</P>
<P>
   As people poured backstage to greet him after a standing
ovation, Hila Ekelman, a buyer at Neiman Marcus, burst into tears.
Blass smiled, and what he told her could have served not only as a
balm, but as a warning to those who stray too far from what they
are and, in the deepest sense of the meaning, what they have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you dare,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
