<HEADLINE>
OWNERS OF SOUTH KOREAN CONGLOMERATES GAIN MORE CONTROL AFTER
ECONOMIC CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., name Ssangyong, 9th graf, is CQ) 
(af)  
 By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ The government has spent much of the last
two years trying to shrink the size and power of South Korea's big
business conglomerates, which are widely blamed for the reckless
expansion and heavy debts that helped cause the country's financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But in many cases, the owners of these big conglomerates, known
as chaebols, have become more powerful, making it increasingly
difficult for the government to force them to make changes.
</P>
<P>
   Some persuasive evidence of this trend was released last week by
the Korea Stock Exchange, which analyzed the stock ownership of 91
listed companies that are subsidiaries of South Korea's 10 biggest
chaebols.
</P>
<P>
   The stock exchange's analysis showed that the average stake of
one subsidiary held by another subsidiary within the same
conglomerate increased from 19.9 percent in January of last year to
28.7 percent at the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis also showed a record increase in the so-called
internal shareholding or the amount of shares of a chaebol's
affiliates that are held by its owners, their relatives and the
sister companies that they control.
</P>
<P>
   The average internal shareholding rose to 34.6 percent at the
end of last month, compared with 27.2 percent before the economic
crisis that battered South Korea in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The increased shareholdings do not result from rises in share
values that reflect the recent stock market boom in South Korea,
exchange officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened is quite the contrary,'' said Chung
Chul-hong, a spokesman for the exchange. ``Through capital
injections from one affiliate to another, chaebol group leaders
have increased their control over their lineup of subsidiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Ssangyong Group topped the list in terms of stockholdings by
owners or top executives. The founding family of the group held
6.52 percent of the group's total shares, followed by Daewoo with
5.2 percent and SK with 3.88 percent, the exchange said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federation of Korean Industries, a trade group that
represents the chaebols, declined to comment on the findings.
Representatives of the big chaebols also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers who have been pressing for changes in the chaebols
have called the exchange's analysis a telling reminder that South
Korea's business elite remains a powerful force. ``This is the
result of chaebol business owners continuing to prop up their
subsidiaries through capital injections from one affiliate to
another,'' said Lee Seok-hyun, a lawmaker of the ruling National
Congress for New Politics and member of a parliamentary committee
monitoring fair trade practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The control wielded by chaebol owners is still substantial,
achieved through one affiliate raising its shareholding of another
affiliate,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Chun at the stock exchange cited Hyundai Group, South Korea's
largest conglomerate, as a textbook example. In a bid to lower its
debt-to-equity ratio as required under South Korean economic
reforms, the Hyundai Electronics Co. required signficant capital
injections. But at the height of South Korea's economic recession
last year, the chip maker could not raise capital by issuing new
shares because few investors wanted to buy shares of risky
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than selling off its assets, Hyundai Group decided to
funnel cash from its construction unit, the Hyundai Engineering and
Construction Co. into the chip maker. The result was an increased
shareholding by the group's honorary chairman, Chung Ju-yung, who
was the largest shareholder of the construction unit. He
subsequently became the new majority shareholder of the chip maker
through the capital injection.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean government, however, has scored some victories
in its battle to strip some power from chaebol leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the government made chaebol leaders personally
accountable for losses from risky business investments. The
chairman of Samsung Group, Lee Kun-hee, was pressed to hand over
2.6 trillion won ($2.3 billion) of his personal wealth to cover
extensive losses incurred by the group's failed auto maker, Samsung
Motors Inc.
</P>
<P>
   And affiliates of South Korean business groups have been barred
from investing more than 25 percent of their assets into sister
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the government plans to strengthen the role of
outside directors by increasing their numbers at the boards of
chaebol companies, Lee said. He said the government also might form
an independent group of auditors composed of outside directors,
while allowing chaebol owners to exercise control in proportion to
their shareholding amount.
</P>
<P>
   But others are skeptical that chaebol leaders will easily
relinquish their control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The methods used by people running the chaebols should not be
underestimated,'' said Cho Dam, a professor of business
administration at Chonnam University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
