<HEADLINE>
SHOW FEEDS ON BOOMER INSECURITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It was bound to happen. &QL; 
The thirtysomething set has grown older if not up. Oh, sure,
Marshall Herskovitz and Edward Zwick, who created the baby-boomer
hit in the '80s, call their new show Once and Again, but
fortysomething would have been a perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon me while I gag.
</P>
<P>
   Once and Again is being touted by critics as a welcome, mature,
honest look at single parents learn ing to date again while raising
their children _ who are learning to date for the first time. It's
sensitive, it's so beautifully made it makes your teeth hurt, it
screams Big Monster Hit.
</P>
<P>
   It stinks.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand. A lot of people are going to love this
show. They all shop at the Pottery Barn, drive sport utility
vehicles and con sider it one of life's tragedies when Starbucks
closes early.
</P>
<P>
   The first line of the pilot sets the tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I ever wanted, I think, was to be safe,'' Sela Ward's
character says, moving into the overly arty, talking-to-the-camera,
black-and-white device that is just one of the show's irritants.
</P>
<P>
   If you like that line, you'll love the show. The rest of us can
only roll our eyes and watch as Once and Again's Nielsen numbers
rise. (At least temporarily. ABC is putting the show in NYPD Blue's
slot until November, then shelving it till Janu ary and moving it
to Mondays.)
</P>
<P>
   The show stars Ward and Billy Campbell (called Bill when he
starred in The Rocketeer). Ward's character is separated;
Campbell's divorced. They meet at their chil dren's school. Coy
phone calls are made, they arrange a date, they like each other and
. . . there are, of course, complications.
</P>
<P>
   They involve, naturally, those darn kids as well as the two main
characters' doubts and insecurities. It's the kind of show where,
at least in the first two episodes, they can do nothing _ really
nothing, not just big things like having sex but also things as
small as making phone calls _ without worrying about it out loud in
that stupid black-and-white stunt.
</P>
<P>
   It's life lived in an Eddie Bauer catalog. Beautiful people
moving through their difficult lives _ many, if not most, of the
difficulties are self-imposed _ with all the depth of a
long-distance phone-carrier commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz and Zwick specialize in just this type of
navel-gazing, having created not only thirtyso mething but also the
far-superior (and short-lived) My So-Called Life. Once and Again is
the inevitable, if logical, extension.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they fake depth with Big TV Issues: sex, divorce, the
ever-popu lar parenting. But it's all just win dow-dressing for
what is basically the adult version of Dawson's Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Teen shows, even the smart ones like Buffy the Vampire Slayer,
are often ridiculed for being nothing more than wish-fulfillment
fantasies played out by beautiful young peo ple. But Once and Again
is just an older version, something to make baby boomers feel good
about themselves. The difference is that these people are supposed
to be old enough to know better, and, more significantly, it's all
So Very Serious that it's difficult to care.
</P>
<P>
   This should come as no surprise. As the most self-centered
generation of the century begins to lose its grip on popular
culture, advertisers no longer find it the most desirable de
mographic. TV is lousy with beauti ful teens, wearing expensive
clothes and emoting. How is a baby boomer to fight back?
</P>
<P>
   Once and Again is a start. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Other new Tuesday night shows:
</P>
<P>
   Judging Amy: Amy Brenneman, late of NYPD Blue, based this story
of a judge and single mom moving back in with her mom on her own
mother. Man, they must have fought a lot. Still, if you wish NBC's
Provi dence was shown more than once a week, this should be a
sufficient fix to get you through till Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mike O'Malley Show: Did you know that Mike O'Malley _ ``The
Rick,'' the obsessive fan in ESPN commercials _ is a play wright in
real life? Or that he's star ring in his own sitcom? Did you care?
Didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Shasta McNasty: If you can't say something nice. . . . How about
this? Scheduling this opposite The Mike O'Malley Show is inspired,
giving cretins twice the choices.
</P>
<P>
   Angel: Buffy's vampire boyfriend is now in LA. No pilot was
avail able, but David Boreanaz will doubtless sink his teeth into
the role. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   The Strip: The lead character is named Elvis, and he lives in
Vegas. No pilot was available, but that should tell you all you
need to know. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
