<HEADLINE>
VIRGIN EXPRESS CHIEF QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Heading two public companies on two continents has
taken its toll on Phoenix executive Jonathan Ornstein, who resigned
as chairman of Virgin Express, a low-cost European airline.
</P>
<P>
   Ornstein, chairman, president and CEO of Phoenix-based Mesa Air
Group, will remain on the Virgin Express board.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a time when you just want to simplify your life,''
Ornstein said.
</P>
<P>
   He will turn more attention to running Mesa, a major regional
carrier that operates as America West Express in the Southwest and
as US Airways Express in the East.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement on Sept. 20 of Ornstein's decision to retire as
chairman coincides with other changes at Brussels, Belgium-based
Virgin Express.
</P>
<P>
   Board member David Hoare will replace Orn stein as executive
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   John Osborne, managing director of GB Airways, will join Virgin
Express as managing director.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne replaces Jim Swigart, a business partner of Ornstein's
who serves on the board of Mesa Air Group.
</P>
<P>
   GB Airways is a franchised airline linked to British Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Swigart and Ornstein are working on some airline-related
business opportunities, according to Ornstein, but he declined to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Virgin Express, patterned after U.S. low-cost carrier Southwest
Airlines, is owned by billionaire Richard Branson, whose business
empire includes airlines, travel, retail and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``John (Osborne) has had great success at GB Airways and I
believe that he and David (Hoare) will be great additions to the
Virgin team,'' Branson said in a prepared statement. ``I would also
like to thank both Jonathan and Jim for their contributions over
the past three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ornstein helped start Virgin Express in 1996 and served as CEO
until last year when he resigned to take the reins at Mesa. Virgin
went from five to 23 aircraft and now serves 10 European cities.
</P>
<P>
   Ornstein worked at Mesa before joining Conti nental Express in
1994 as president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Ornstein still has a strong interest in Virgin Express. He and
Swigart and their Barlow Partners, a private investment fund, own
about 5 or 6 percent of the airlines' stock, making them the
largest shareholders behind Branson, Ornstein said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-99 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
