<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ERVIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.) 
SAMUEL JAMES ERVIN 3RD, 73, FEDERAL JUDGE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Samuel James Ervin 3rd, who was the chief judge of the 4th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals from 1989 to 1996, died on Saturday in a
hospital in Morganton, N.C. He was 73 and lived in Morganton.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin continued to serve on the court after his retirement as
chief judge. At the time of his death, he was North Carolina's only
federal appellate judge in active service.
</P>
<P>
   The son of the late Sen. Sam J. Ervin Jr., chairman of the
Senate committee whose Watergate inquiry led President Richard M.
Nixon to resign, Ervin served as a part-time prosecutor in Burke
County from 1954 to 1956. He was elected to the state House of
Representatives in 1964 and 1966.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, he was appointed by Gov. Dan Moore to serve as a
Superior Court judge. He was named to the U.S. Court of Appeals in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin is survived by his wife, Elisabeth C. Ervin of Morganton;
and four children, Sam J. 4th, of Morganton; Elisabeth Fore Ervin
of Asheville, N.C.; Robert C., of Morganton; and Margaret Ervin
Bruder of Darmstadt, Germany, and seven grandchildren.
</P>
